  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: In the Beginning'
      title: In the Beginning
      number: 1
      content: 'When [[COMMENT(0)]] God  created  the heavens and the earth,   '
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: "  Although most translations view v.    as an independent sentence
          serving as a general heading, it is likely that the first phrase serves
          as a subordinate time clause, such as \u201CAt the beginning [of time],
          God created\u201D or \u201CWhen God began the creation of heaven and the
          earth.\u201D The first word in Hebrew is    and means \u201Cfirst,\u201D
          \u201Cchief,\u201D or \u201Cfirstfruits.\u201D Genesis gives us    of God\u2019s
          creation. The New Testament takes us into the new creation life of Christ
          until all things are made new.      This is the word  , the commonly used
          Hebrew term for God. It stresses his sovereignty and power and could be
          translated \u201CMighty God.\u201D    is the plural of    and occurs nearly
          2,600 times in the Bible.    is derived from the word  , which means \u201Cto
          worship\u201D or \u201Cto adore,\u201D and presents God as the one worthy
          of worship and adoration. After the word  , there is an untranslatable
          marking, which most scholars believe is a direct object marker with the
          first and last letters of the Hebrew alphabet. However, it is seen by some
          as the word known as  , which occurs over seven thousand times in the Hebrew
          text of the Old Testament. Some believe that this could be pointing to
          Jesus Christ who declared himself to be \u201Cthe Aleph and the Tav,\u201D
          or \u201Cthe Beginning and the End\u201D (,  ;  ;  ). The first verse of
          the Bible shouts out: \u201CGod is all powerful!\u201D      This is the
          word  , which is used in the Old Testament exclusively for God\u2019s creativity,
          things that only God can do. Creating is an integral part of God\u2019s
          nature.      Or \u201Cthe sky and the land.\u201D This is a merism (a figure
          of speech using two contrasting words to refer to an entirety) for the
          entire universe. See  ,  . The Hebrew word for \u201Cheaven\u201D appears
          seven times in this chapter (vv.  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ).    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "the earth was completely formless and empty, with nothing but darkness
        [[COMMENT(0)]] draped over the deep. God\u2019s Spirit hovered  over the
        face of the waters."
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: "  See  . Darkness is a frequent biblical metaphor for evil, misfortune,
          and death. It appears here as something more than an absence of light\u2014it
          is a distinct entity. See  .      Or \u201CGod\u2019s Spirit gently vibrated.\u201D
          The Syriac cognate word can mean \u201Cto incubate\u201D or \u201Cto brood.\u201D
          The Hebrew verb    means \u201Cto flutter,\u201D \u201Cto gently move,\u201D
          \u201Cto hover over with gentle wavering,\u201D or \u201Cto be relaxed
          [grow soft]\u201D and describes the utmost care and affection of a mother
          eagle caring for her young (see  ). This word is also used for a bridegroom
          hovering over his bride. This same Holy Spirit overshadowed (brooded over)
          a virgin named Mary to bring the perfect man into the world (see  ). God\u2019s
          Spirit danced over the waters on creation\u2019s morning.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "And then God announced, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CLet there be light,\u201D
        and light burst forth! <smallcaps>:</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  This is the Hebrew word  , which is most often translated \u201Csaid,\u201D
          but it can also mean \u201Cto think,\u201D \u201Cto imagine,\u201D or \u201Cto
          speak inside your heart.\u201D God imagined light and there was light.
          God spoke and shattered the cosmic silence to give birth to creation. God
          spoke ten times in the creation account\u2014the Ten Commandments of creation.
          See  ;  . God\u2019s thoughts had already imagined and shaped the largest
          galaxy and the smallest atom before he created them. With exquisite skill
          and creativity, God shaped all things by his word and spoke them into being
          with intricate detail and skill (see  ). A dimension separate from the
          being of God was birthed. No detail was too small for God as he prepared
          to unveil his masterpiece of wisdom, his dream come true. God spoke order
          and goodness into his creation.      Or \u201Cand there was light.\u201D
          God created light but did not create the sun until the fourth day. God
          himself filled the universe with the light of his presence and glory. The
          Hebrew verbs used with the phrases \u201CLet there be\u201D and \u201Cand
          there was\u201D are both related to the holy name      (\u201Clet there
          be\u201D) and    (\u201Cand there was\u201D). As he released this word
          of power, the universe began to expand and has been expanding ever since
          (see  ). God\u2019s kingdom operates according to the principle of endless
          increase (see  ), not of power that diminishes over time.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'And God saw the light as pleasing and beautiful; [[COMMENT(0)]] he
        used the light to dispel the darkness. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  The Hebrew word    can be translated \u201Cpleasing\u201D or
          \u201Cgood [beautiful]\u201D and is used seven times in this chapter (vv. 
          ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ,  ). God is mentioned 35 times (7 \xD7 5) and the earth
          21 times (7 \xD7 3) in the creation account. God\u2019s goodness was his
          intention in creation, and he embedded beauty within all he made.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "God called the light \u201CDay,\u201D and the darkness \u201CNight.\u201D
        And so, evening gave way to morning\u2014the first day. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: '  God begins in darkness and brings forth a new day. Chaos never
          hinders God from bringing forth light and order. It is not difficult for
          God to work where there is darkness, chaos, and confusion. See  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "And God said, \u201CLet there be a dome [[COMMENT(0)]] between the
        waters to separate the water above from the water below.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cvault\u201D or \u201Cexpanse [atmosphere].\u201D See 
          .    "
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: "He made the dome and called it \u201CSky,\u201D and separated the
        water above the dome from the water below the dome. Evening gave way to morning\u2014day
        two."
      comments: []
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: "He made the dome and called it \u201CSky,\u201D and separated the
        water above the dome from the water below the dome. Evening gave way to morning\u2014day
        two."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "And God said, \u201CLet the water beneath the sky be gathered into
        one place, and let the dry ground appear.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] And so it
        happened. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:9
        content: '  On the third day, the dry ground was raised up out of the waters
          (see  ), then God clothed it with vegetation. This can be compared to the
          new birth that comes to a believer, who is raised up and then clothed with
          the virtues of Christ. See  ;  . The progress of creation moves from the
          lower to the higher, from the darker to the brighter, from the evening
          to the morning. The Word of God put light into darkness, land in the midst
          of sea, air in the midst of water, and life in the midst of the uninhabited
          earth. In creation, God started with form and filled it with fullness.
          In nature, the seed sprouts: first the bud, then the blossom, and then
          the fruit. In human life the baby is first, then the child, and then the
          mature adult. So it is also in grace.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "God called the dry ground \u201CLand,\u201D and the gathered waters
        he called \u201CSeas.\u201D And God saw the beauty of his creation, and he
        was very pleased."
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet the land burst forth with growth: plants
        that bear seeds of their own kind, and every variety of fruit tree, each
        with power to multiply [[COMMENT(0)]] from its own seed.\u201D  And so it
        happened. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith seed within itself\u201D or \u201Cseeding seed.\u201D
          The work of God at creation involved three separations: (1) God separated
          the light from darkness (v.  ). (2) God separated the waters above from
          the waters beneath (vv.  ). (3) God separated the water from the land (v. 
          ). Out of this separated, resurrected land, God brought a variety of life.     
          Everything with life produces life after its own kind. Each species is
          able to reproduce itself. The Lord Jesus was the firstfruit of a new species
          of humanity. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The land flourished with grasses, every variety of seed-bearing plant,
        and trees bearing fruit with their seeds in them. And God loved what he saw,
        for it was beautiful. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Evening gave way to morning\u2014day three."
      comments: []
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "And God said, \u201CLet there be bright lights to shine in space
        to bathe the earth with their light. Let them serve as signs [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to separate the day from night, and signify the days, seasons,  and years.\u201D
        And so it happened. "
      comments:
      - number: "1:14\u201315"
        content: "  The heavens contain the embedded codes of God\u2019s glory, and
          are full of symbolic signs that testify to his greatness and wisdom. They
          are like huge billboards and advertisements in the sky telling people how
          good and great our Creator is. See  ;  .      Or \u201Cappointed times
          [feasts].\u201D See  . The stars are for signs, signals, and seasons.    "
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "And God said, \u201CLet there be bright lights to shine in space
        to bathe the earth with their light. Let them serve as signs [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to separate the day from night, and signify the days, seasons,  and years.\u201D
        And so it happened. "
      comments:
      - number: "1:14\u201315"
        content: "  The heavens contain the embedded codes of God\u2019s glory, and
          are full of symbolic signs that testify to his greatness and wisdom. They
          are like huge billboards and advertisements in the sky telling people how
          good and great our Creator is. See  ;  .      Or \u201Cappointed times
          [feasts].\u201D See  . The stars are for signs, signals, and seasons.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'God made two great lights: the brighter light to rule the day and
        the lesser light to rule the night. He also spread the tapestry of shining
        stars [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  Scripture often uses stars as a picture of believers or ministries
          who shine with supernatural light (see  ;  ;  ). We see from    that just
          as God named the \u201Csun\u201D and the \u201Cmoon,\u201D he also gave
          names to each of the stars. It is noted by numerous scholars that    never
          uses the names for sun () or moon () that were also Canaanite names of
          deities. This served a polemical purpose against the stories of the gods
          and other creation narratives in the ancient Near East.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'and set them all in the sky to illuminate the earth, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'to rule over the day and to rule over the night, and to separate
        the light from darkness. God loved what he saw, for it was beautiful. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Evening gave way to morning\u2014day four."
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "God said, \u201CLet there be life! Let the waters swarm with sea
        life, and let the sky be filled with soaring birds of every kind.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "God created huge sea creatures [[COMMENT(0)]] and every living creature
        that moves of every kind\u2014swarming in the water and flying in the sky,
        according to their species. God loved what he saw, for it was beautiful. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: "  Or \u201Csea monsters,\u201D \u201Cdragons,\u201D or \u201Cdinosaurs.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "God blessed [[COMMENT(0)]] them, saying, \u201CReproduce and be fruitful!
        Fill the waters of the sea with life, and the earth with flying birds!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:22
        content: "  This is the first mention of God\u2019s blessing in the Bible.
          On this day, God created life\u2014birds and sea life\u2014and blessed
          them. This blessing included being fruitful (reproduction) and multiplying
          (increasing in number).    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Evening gave way to morning\u2014day five."
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "God said, \u201CLet the earth produce every class and kind of living
        creature: livestock, crawling things, wild animals, each after its kind.\u201D
        And so it happened. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: Shaped by Love'
      title: Shaped by Love
      number: 25
      content: God made the wild animals according to their species, livestock according
        to their species, [[COMMENT(0)]] and all the creatures that creep along the
        ground according to their species. And God loved what he saw, for it was
        beautiful.
      comments:
      - number: 1:25
        content: "  God had a lamb before he had a man. Metaphorically, Jesus (God\u2019s
          Lamb) was slain before the foundation of the world (see  ). The print of
          the nails was upon him even as his hands formed the world. As the Creator
          shaped Adam from dust, redeeming mercy was stamped upon him.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet us [[COMMENT(0)]] make a man and a woman 
        in our image  to be like us.  Let them reign over the fish of the sea, the
        birds of the air, the livestock, over the creatures that creep along the
        ground,  and over the wild animals.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:26
        content: "  The plural form of the verb indicates there were more beings
          than Father God in the activities of creation. When taken as a whole, the
          Bible also points to the Holy Spirit and God the Son as participators in
          the glory of creation. See  ;  .      That is, humanity. The Hebrew word
          is simply  , which can be translated \u201Cman,\u201D but without a definite
          article it is used here as a collective term for man and woman. The definite
          article    does not occur before the word    until after God made woman,
          and together, they are  . According to the Talmud, the three Hebrew letters
          of Adam\u2019s name represent the initials of three men: Adam, David, and
          Messiah. The Hebrew word    means \u201Cto show [blood] red,\u201D and   
          means \u201Cto make.\u201D The statement to \u201Cmake [] Adam [ruddy]
          from [red] soil []\u201D is full of Hebrew puns that are lost in translation.     
          Or \u201Cas our image.\u201D \u201CImage\u201D can also be translated \u201Crepresentation\u201D
          or \u201Cresemblance.\u201D God created someone like himself to reflect
          who he is into all his creation. He created trees after their kind, birds
          after their kind, fish after their kind, and animals after their kind,
          but now he creates a God-kind of being. Christ is the image of God; man
          and woman will resemble him and bring his image into the created order
          (see  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ). The first man, Adam, was a type or figure of
          the Last Adam, Christ. See  ;  .      Or \u201Caccording to our likeness,\u201D
          or \u201Cto be like us [comparable to us].\u201D God is neither male nor
          female (see  ), but he has both male and female dimensions to his nature.
          What is this image given to each of us? It includes personality, the capacity
          for worship, the ability to make moral decisions (our conscience), and
          the ability to reflect God. Created as his image-bearers, all human beings
          bear the expression or image of God. As \u201Cphotographs\u201D of God,
          our characteristics are copies of his. Because he desired to give himself
          for you and to you, he took his own nature and likeness and fashioned a
          creature just like him\u2014one he could love with unlimited passion.     
          Man was meant to rule over all the things that creep along the ground,
          including the serpent and scorpion, which represent the powers of darkness
          (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: So God created man and womanand shaped them with his image inside
        them.In his own beautiful image, he created his masterpiece.Yes, male and
        female he created them.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "And God blessed them in his love, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CReproduce
        and be fruitful! Populate the earth and subdue it!  Reign over the fish of
        the sea, the birds of the air, and every creature that lives on earth.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:28
        content: "  God\u2019s blessing upon the human family implies love. God blesses
          both men and women, empowering them to live on this planet, infusing them
          with power and favor to succeed in life.      The word    means \u201Cto
          take dominion\u201D or \u201Cto control.\u201D This would imply harnessing
          natural resources in an appropriate fashion, caring for the earth, cultivating
          and harvesting its fields, mining its resources, and releasing its potential
          to benefit God\u2019s highest creation, humankind. See  .      Man and
          woman were both given the command to care for the earth and subdue all
          things. Man and woman are blessed by their Creator with authority to rule
          with him as co-regents. God\u2019s image is reflected in both men and women,
          and so is rulership.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "And God said, \u201CI give you every seed-bearing plant growing throughout
        the earth, vegetables, and every fruit-bearing tree with its seed within
        itself. They will be your food. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:29
        content: '  After the fall of Adam and Eve, meat was likely included in their
          diet. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "They will also be food for every animal and bird, and every creature
        that moves on the ground\u2014every creature with the breath of life.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]] And so it happened."
      comments:
      - number: 1:30
        content: '  A day will come when the carnivorous animals will become herbivorous
          again. See  ;  .    '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "God surveyed all he had made and said, \u201CI love it!\u201D For
        it pleased him greatly. Evening gave way to morning\u2014day six. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:31
        content: '  Because God created man on the sixth day, the number six is the
          biblical number of man.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Creation Details'
      title: Creation Details
      number: 1
      content: 'And so the creation of the heavens and the earth were completed in
        all their vast array. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: '  The seven days of creation hint at the seven stages through which
          one passes to become fully mature in Christ, complete in his image. Once,
          when we lived our sinful, empty lives in spiritual darkness (see  ), the
          Holy Spirit brooded over our souls to draw us to salvation (see  ). Then
          God spoke his Word of power, cascading revelation-light into our being
          (see  ), our Savior, Jesus the Word, the Light of salvation (see  ). Finally,
          we will cease from our own striving and enter into the Sabbath rest of
          completion and maturity (see  ).    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'By the seventh day, [[COMMENT(0)]] God had completed creating his
        masterpiece, so on the seventh day, he rested from all his work. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cday\u201D is    and can be translated
          in English into over fifty different words, such as \u201Ca twenty-four-hour
          day,\u201D \u201Ctoday,\u201D \u201Ctime,\u201D \u201Cforever,\u201D \u201Ccontinually,\u201D
          \u201Cage,\u201D \u201Clife,\u201D \u201Cseason,\u201D \u201Cperpetually,\u201D
          or \u201Ca period of time.\u201D The Hebraic mindset does not necessarily
          view    as a twenty-four-hour period. For example, the Scriptures speak
          frequently of the day of the Lord, which points to a time period of God\u2019s
          divine activity, not a day with a sunrise and sunset.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: So God blessed the seventh day and made it sacred, because on it,
        he paused to rest [[COMMENT(0)]] from all his work of creation.
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  God was not weary; he simply rejoiced in his masterpiece. God\u2019s
          work in us, for us, and through us continues through time. God\u2019s last
          day of creating (the sixth) was man\u2019s first day. As soon as man was
          created, he rested with God. In this way, he became one with God, dwelling
          with him and resting in his accomplishments. There is no mention of evening
          and morning completing the seventh day, for God\u2019s Sabbath rest endures
          forever and there is no night there. Our true Sabbath rest is found in
          the finished work of Christ (see  ;  ;  ;  ). Only one day of Creation
          was given a name: the seventh day, which was called \u201CShabbat.\u201D
          The Hebrew root word for \u201CSabbath\u201D contains two letters that
          mean \u201Cto return to a seat (rest) and learn.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "This is the account [[COMMENT(0)]] of the heavens and the earth after
        they were created. At the time   <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God <smallcaps>,
        or \u201Cthe God who is</smallcaps><smallcaps>,\u201D the God of mercy and
        power.</smallcaps> created earth and heaven, "
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  Or \u201CThese are the generations [genealogies].\u201D This
          phrase is used numerous times to begin a new section in the story line
          of Genesis.      This is the word  , which is used in the Old Testament
          exclusively for God\u2019s creativity, things that only God can do. However,
          here the Hebrew letter    is inserted into the word, which is incorrect
          grammatically. The letter    is the fifth letter in the Hebrew alphabet
          and is recognized by Jewish sages as the \u201Cdivine breath of God.\u201D
          Its occurrence here signifies that it was God\u2019s breath that gave birth
          to all that was created. See  .      See footnote on    on the Hebrew word 
          .      The Hebrew is        "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'there was yet no vegetation, grains of the field, or shrubs sprouting
        on the earth, for there was no one to cultivate the land, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God had not yet sent rain. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  Before the earth could flourish under God\u2019s blessing, there
          needed to be a man and woman to take dominion. The Lord created them to
          walk with him and to cultivate a garden. God made the earth to need a human
          touch. God and man were to work together to subdue, cultivate, and take
          dominion of the earth. See  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: In those days a mist [[COMMENT(0)]] arose from the soil and watered
        the whole face of the ground.
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cvapor\u201D or \u201Csubterranean spring.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God scooped up a lump of soil, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        sculpted a man, and blew into his nostrils the breath of life.  The man came
        alive\u2014a living soul! "
      comments:
      - number: 2:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cclay\u201D or \u201Cdust.\u201D The Hebrew contains
          an obvious play on words, a paronomasia, for the word for \u201Cman\u201D
          is  , and the Hebrew word for \u201Csoil [dust]\u201D is  . See  . Everything
          else was formed by an act of speech\u2014only man was sculpted by the hands
          of God (see  ). One day, Jesus picked up some earth, spat on it, and made
          clay; he touched the eyes of a blind man with it, and the blind man saw
          (see  ).      Or \u201Cthe breath of lives.\u201D To breathe into someone\u2019s
          nostrils is what happens when two people kiss. God kissed life into Adam.
          God\u2019s Word likewise is \u201CGod-breathed\u201D (). Jesus also blew
          his breath upon his beloved disciples (see  ). The lovers of God long for
          this \u201CSpirit-kiss\u201D (). See also  . Instantly, every portion of
          Adam\u2019s being was filled with life as Spirit-Wind poured into the man
          of clay lying in his Creator\u2019s arms. Adam\u2019s first sight was looking
          into the eyes of the Image-Maker. The dust of earth and the breath of Deity
          mingled as one, so that Adam could interact in both realms (physical and
          spiritual). This breath or \u201CSpirit of life\u201D was more than air;
          it brought intelligence, wisdom, light, and the image of God into Adam
          (see  ).      The Mishnah (a collection of oral law and rabbinical teachings)
          uses the word  , a synonym for    (soul), here.    is derived from the
          root  , a verb that means \u201Cto ask,\u201D \u201Cto seek,\u201D or \u201Cto
          request [as in prayer].\u201D In other words, the Talmud (an extensive
          commentary on the Mishnah) defines man as \u201Cthe creature that prays.\u201D
          Furthermore, the Talmud teaches that even  , the life-sustaining soul,
          is synonymous with prayer. A nuanced translation could be \u201Cand man
          was manifested as a praying being [one who could commune with God].\u201D
          In a sense, being human means moving in the direction of the divine design
          that God embedded within us. See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God planted [[COMMENT(0)]] a lush
        garden paradise  in the East,  in the Land of Delight,  and there he placed
        the man he had formed. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: "  The Lord wanted to plant himself in the dust of Adam and become
          life within him. In  , we see the pictures of both a tree planted in a
          garden and God planted in man. As the tree was to receive nourishment from
          the soil, so Adam was to draw life and sustenance from his Maker. Life
          for Adam depended on what he did with the Tree of the Knowledge of Good
          and Evil. Life for you and me depends on what we do with the tree on which
          Jesus died. Jesus Christ is now the Tree of Life to us and is accessible
          to all who come by faith (see  ;  ;  ;  ).      Man began in a garden,
          sinned in a garden, and was driven out of a garden (see  ). Then Jesus
          came. He went into a garden called Gethsemane as the perfect man and tasted
          the fruits of our suffering and pain (see  ). He was then laid in a garden
          tomb (see  ) that we might become the garden of his delight (see  ). God
          set man not in a factory to toil nor in a school to study, but in a garden\u2014a
          place where life grows.      That is, east of the land of Israel.     
          Or \u201CEden,\u201D a homonym that can mean \u201Ca plain [steppe],\u201D
          or \u201Cenjoyment,\u201D \u201Cbliss,\u201D \u201Cpleasure,\u201D or \u201Cdelight.\u201D
          A bliss-filled paradise became the home of Adam and Eve. Eden\u2019s very
          name reveals God\u2019s nature of love and grace. See  ;  ;  . Eden is
          the realm of glory and bliss that God wants to unveil to the believer.
          Ezekiel called it both the \u201Cgarden of God\u201D and the \u201Cmountain
          of God\u201D ().    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God made all kinds of beautiful trees
        to grow there\u2014fruitful trees to satisfy the taste. In the middle of
        the garden, [[COMMENT(0)]] he planted the Tree of Life  and the Tree of the
        Knowledge of Good and Evil. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:9
        content: "  Metaphorically, the garden of God is within the believer. In
          the middle of our \u201Cgarden,\u201D we are feeding on one of these two
          trees. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .      Or \u201Cthe Life-Giving Tree.\u201D
          For the believer, the Tree of Life is Jesus Christ, the Wisdom of God.
          See  ;  ;    and footnote;  ;  .      That is, the Tree that gives the
          knowledge of good and evil, a possible merism for \u201Cthe knowledge of
          everything.\u201D The great need of the human heart is life (relationship),
          not knowledge. God never intended for man to covet knowledge apart from
          a relationship with God. In the beginning, God didn\u2019t give Adam a
          list of commandments but offered him living food to sustain him. Jesus
          Christ is that Living Tree. He is meant to be the life and sustenance of
          all whom God has formed (see  ). By eating of the Living Tree, Adam would
          have shown his daily dependence on God. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Flowing from the Land of Delight was a river [[COMMENT(0)]] to water
        the garden, and from there, it divided into four branches.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  Eden is a preview of the New Jerusalem. See  .      Or \u201Cfour
          heads [headstreams].\u201D As the one river (God is the one River) flowed
          out of the garden, it separated into four heads. Four is the number of
          universality (four winds, four corners of the earth). These rivers refresh
          and water the whole world. Rivers are frequently used as metaphors for
          the Holy Spirit that Jesus gives us and the life-giving presence of God.
          See  ;  ;  ;  . The Hebrew word for \u201Criver\u201D () comes from a root
          word that means \u201Cto sparkle\u201D or \u201Cto be cheerful.\u201D The
          River of God will truly make his people sparkle with cheer!    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The first river, Overflowing Increase, [[COMMENT(0)]] encircles the
        gold-laden land of Havilah.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: "  Or \u201CPishon,\u201D which means \u201Coverflowing increase,\u201D
          \u201Cto leap forth,\u201D or \u201Cto spread out.\u201D        has a number
          of possible meanings: \u201Cto cause to grow,\u201D \u201Cto give birth
          out of pain,\u201D \u201Ca stretch of sandy land,\u201D \u201Cmud,\u201D
          \u201Cto twist or whirl in a circular or spiral manner,\u201D \u201Cto
          writhe or fall grievously in pain or fear,\u201D \u201Cto grieve,\u201D
          \u201Cbe sore pained,\u201D \u201Cto be sorrowful,\u201D \u201Cto tremble,\u201D
          or \u201Cto be wounded.\u201D All of the possible meanings seem to point
          to our human nature. The overflowing increase of God\u2019s River within
          us uncovers the gold hidden in the mud.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The gold of that land is pure, with many pearls and onyx [[COMMENT(0)]]
        found there.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: "  Onyx stones were mounted to the breastplate of the high priest
          and adorn the gates to the New Jerusalem. See  ;  .      The flowing river
          with its gold and precious stones points to the finding of treasure in
          the River of God, a beautiful metaphor for the life of Jesus flowing within
          us. God\u2019s loving generosity provided man with these garden treasures.
          See  ;  .    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The second river, Gushing, [[COMMENT(0)]] flows through the entire
        land of Cush.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:13
        content: "  Or \u201CGihon,\u201D which means \u201Cto gush [as a geyser]\u201D
          or \u201Cto give birth.\u201D        means \u201Cdarkened\u201D and refers
          to Nubia, one of the earliest civilizations of ancient Africa (present-day
          Ethiopia).    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'The third river, Swift Flowing, [[COMMENT(0)]] flows east of Assyria. 
        And the fourth is the river Fruitfulness. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  Or \u201CHiddekel\u201D (Tigris), which means \u201Cswift [flowing]\u201D
          or \u201Clike a swift arrow in flight.\u201D      Or \u201CAsshur,\u201D
          which comes from the Hebrew word for \u201Csuccessful.\u201D      Or \u201CEuphrates,\u201D
          which means \u201Cfruitfulness.\u201D When we interpret the names of the
          four rivers together, we read: \u201CThe River of God will bring overflowing
          increase, gush like a geyser, and swiftly bring God\u2019s people to success
          and fruitfulness.\u201D See  . It was a limitless land of freedom. God
          gave the entire paradise of Eden to earth\u2019s first pair\u2014a realm
          of endless pleasure without sin.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God took [[COMMENT(0)]] the man and
        placed him in the garden of Eden to work  and watch over it.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Ctook\u201D () can also mean \u201Cto
          marry\u201D or \u201Ctake a wife.\u201D      Or \u201Cserve.\u201D The
          Hebrew word for \u201Cwork\u201D () can also mean \u201Cworship.\u201D
          Our work is to be of service to God and an act of worship (see  ). God
          validates working for him, as Adam did by stewarding and tending the garden.     
          The Hebrew word used here is often translated as \u201Cwatchman\u201D in
          the Old Testament. Adam\u2019s role as the watchman over God\u2019s creation
          was to keep the garden (within him, see  ) and watch over it to keep the
          serpent out. Man\u2019s created role is protector, keeper, and watchman!
          God wants to redeem what was lost and nurture his sons and daughters, making
          them into strong \u201Ckeepers\u201D and \u201Cwatchmen\u201D over his
          work on earth.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God commanded him, \u201CYou may
        freely eat of every fruit [[COMMENT(0)]] of the garden. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:16
        content: "  Or \u201Ctree.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: Creation of Adam and Eve'
      title: Creation of Adam and Eve
      number: 17
      content: "But you must not eat of the Tree that gives the knowledge of good
        and evil, for when you eat from it you will most certainly die.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cdying you will die.\u201D God is neither unkind nor
          harsh; our tender Father God is gracious and generous to humanity. God
          alone knows what is good for us. To enjoy the good, we must trust and obey
          him. He knows that true freedom is in the loving shade of Eden. God knows
          that if we disobey, we will have decided for ourselves what is good and
          what is not good. We will have eaten the forbidden fruit and made ourselves
          our own gods. Death came into the world through Adam\u2019s sin (see  ).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God said, \u201CIt is not good
        [[COMMENT(0)]] for the man to be alone. Therefore, I will fashion a suitable
        partner to be his help and strength.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:18
        content: "  Or \u201Cpleasant,\u201D \u201Ccheerful,\u201D or \u201Cbeautiful.\u201D
          God\u2019s loving gifts can be seen in giving man his life-breath, a beautiful
          place of bliss (Eden) to work in, and now, a life-partner.      This is
          the Hebrew word  , a term frequently used for military help and ascribed
          to God himself fourteen times (e.g.,  ;  ). It could be translated \u201Cstrong
          rescuer.\u201D We would never say that God is inferior to man, nor should
          we say the woman is inferior to man, for both God and the woman are  .
          God\u2019s choice of the word    indicates that a man\u2019s wife is his
          first line of defense and an equal partner in the journey of life. The   
          is God\u2019s gift to the husband. The wife\u2019s role is more than that
          of an assistant to the man. She is the dynamic solution to man\u2019s loneliness
          as one who protects, reveals, and helps. Some see the ancient pictographic
          rendering of    as    (eye) -    (man) -    (weapon), to mean \u201Cthe
          revealer of the enemy.\u201D Both God and Adam wanted a partner. God wanted
          mankind to till and work the garden, accomplishing God\u2019s purpose for
          them\u2014to bring forth fruit. But Adam needed a bride, a partner for
          life who would be able to live and move and have her being in him. So God
          gave Adam a job and a wife. All of this was to be a picture to Adam of
          God\u2019s yearning for a forever partner who will not just work alongside
          of him but also love and cherish him.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'For <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God had formed from the soil every
        animal of the field and every bird of the air and brought them before the
        man to see what he would call them. So, whatever the man called the living
        creature, that was its name. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:19
        content: '  As he named each animal, Adam was expressing the authority God
          gave him to subdue and take dominion. With incredible intellectual abilities,
          Adam memorized the names of countless animals and all their subspecies.
          Adam was created with an organizational, administrative capacity which
          enabled him to identify and define the world around him.    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'He gave names to all the various cattle, birds, and wild animals,
        but Adam could not find a fitting companion that corresponded to him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God caused Adam to fall into a deep
        trance, and while he slept, he took a portion of Adam\u2019s side [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and closed its place with flesh. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cinner chamber.\u201D See v.    and  . The word that
          is usually translated \u201Cside\u201D or \u201Crib\u201D is an obscure
          one that can also mean a structural element essential to something\u2019s
          existence (like a beam for a house or hull for a boat). Eve was not taken
          from Adam\u2019s feet to dominate her, but from his side, near his heart,
          for him to cherish her.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God used the portion of Adam\u2019s
        side and skillfully crafted [[COMMENT(0)]] a woman and presented her to him.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:22
        content: '  This verb is not used for anything else in the creation account,
          only for the woman. It takes one verse to describe the creation of man,
          six verses to describe the creation of woman.      God instituted marriage
          by forming the man and the woman and bringing them to each other. Starting
          with the original genetics of man, the Lord fashioned a companion for Adam
          who powerfully expanded the expression of his own image. The great gift
          God gave to the woman was the ability to conceive and give birth. As the
          two came together, mankind would express a fuller, more complete picture
          of God. See  .    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then Adam said:\u201CAt last! One like me!Her bones were formed from
        my bones,and her flesh from my flesh!This one will be called \u2018Woman,\u2019for
        she was taken from man.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom her man [husband].\u201D Just as God reached into
          himself and took a portion of his being (image and likeness) to make man,
          he reached into man and took a portion of Adam to sculpt the woman. If
          Adam is dust refined, then the woman is double refined, for she was taken
          from man and shaped again by God\u2019s hand. There are many wordplays
          found in this portion of Scripture. The word for man is  , and the word
          for woman is  . The Son of Man also went into the deep sleep of death so
          that his beloved bride would come forth. Eve was in Adam before she became
          his bride; we were chosen in the Anointed One before we were born (see 
          ). Adam and Eve ruled together over this paradise; the bride of Christ
          will rule and reign with him over a restored creation. The Bridegroom-King
          and the bride are the counterparts to this story.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'For this reason, a man leaves his father and his mother to be unselfishly
        attached to [[COMMENT(0)]] his wife. They become one flesh as a new family! '
      comments:
      - number: 2:24
        content: "  Literally, \u201Cin his wife.\u201D This is the Hebrew word 
          , which means \u201Cto follow hard after\u201D or \u201Cattaching oneself
          to another as an act of unselfishness,\u201D the opposite of looking out
          only for yourself. See  . The Son of God likewise left his Father to join
          himself to (in) us, his bride.  "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: The man and his wife felt no shame, unaware that they were both naked.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Fall'
      title: The Fall
      number: 1
      content: "Now the snake [[COMMENT(0)]] was the most cunning  of all living
        beings that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God had made. He deviously asked
        the woman, \u201CDid God really tell you, \u2018You must not eat fruit from
        any tree of the garden\u2014?\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Csnake\u201D (serpent) is  , a very
          elastic term in Hebrew. It can function as a noun, a verb, or even as an
          adjective. When    functions as a noun, it means \u201Csnake\u201D; when   
          serves as a verb, it means \u201Cto practice divination [deception].\u201D
          When    has the definite article attached to it (as in this verse\u2014\u201Cthe
          snake\u201D) it can be translated \u201Cthe diviner [deceiver].\u201D When   
          serves as an adjective, its meaning is \u201Cshining\u201D or \u201Cpolished\u201D
          (i.e., \u201Cshiny\u201D). By adding the definite article to the word,   
          can then be rightly translated \u201Cthe shining one.\u201D Angelic or
          divine beings are described elsewhere in the Bible as \u201Cshining\u201D
          or \u201Cluminous,\u201D at times with this very word,  . \u201CThe shining
          one\u201D is the literal meaning of  . See  .      There is a wordplay
          here on the words    (in the previous verse) and  . They both come from
          the same triliteral Hebrew root.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "But the woman interrupted, \u201C\u2014We may eat the fruit of any
        tree in the garden, "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "except the tree in the center of the garden. God told us, \u2018Don\u2019t
        eat its fruit, or even touch it, [[COMMENT(0)]] or you\u2019ll die.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:3
        content: "  There is no mention of God forbidding touching the fruit tree;
          Eve was adding to God\u2019s command.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But the snake said to her, \u201CYou certainly won\u2019t die. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "God knows that the moment you eat it, your eyes will be opened, and
        you will be like God, [[COMMENT(0)]] knowing both good and evil.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 3:5
        content: "  Or \u201Clike gods [divine beings].\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When the woman saw that the tree produced delicious fruit, delightful
        to look upon, and desirable to give one insight, she took its fruit and ate
        it. [[COMMENT(0)]] She gave some to her husband, who was with her, and he
        also ate it.   '
      comments:
      - number: 3:6
        content: "  See  .      Man\u2019s sin began with a tree and ended on a tree.
          See  ,  .    "
    - name: '7: God Manifests in the Garden'
      title: God Manifests in the Garden
      number: 7
      content: Immediately, their eyes were opened, and they realized they were naked,
        vulnerable, and ashamed; so they sewed fig leaves [[COMMENT(0)]] together
        for coverings.
      comments:
      - number: 3:7
        content: '  The fig tree was the only thing Jesus cursed while on earth (see 
          ). Fig leaves are a picture for whatever we hide behind to cover our spiritual
          shame. This is the first attempt of man to cover his nakedness. Our works
          are never enough to cover our sinfulness. The robe of righteousness that
          Jesus clothes us in is perfect. See  .    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: Then Adam and his wife heard the sound [[COMMENT(0)]] of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God
        passing through  the garden in the breeze of the day.  So, they hid among
        the trees concealing themselves from the face of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God.
      comments:
      - number: 3:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cvoice.\u201D      Or \u201Cgoing [walking] back and
          forth repeatedly.\u201D That is, the sound or voice of God was heard from
          all directions. It was the voice that \u201Cwalked\u201D back and forth,
          back and forth, repeating the sound over and over. God has no feet, nor
          a body. His voice came into the garden as if it were everywhere at once.
          The Hebrew text could also be translated \u201CGod caused his voice to
          travel through the garden.\u201D      Or \u201Cwalking in the spirit of
          the day\u201D or \u201Cmoving in the breeze [breezy time] of the day.\u201D
          The implication is that God had been doing this daily, wanting friendship
          and intimacy with his newly created couple.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God called Adam\u2019s name and
        asked, \u201CWhere are you?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:9
        content: "  When Adam first sinned, he should have gone immediately to God
          to beg for mercy and forgiveness. Instead he did just what millions are
          doing today: he ran and hid from God so that God had to come and look for
          him. God knew where he was hiding but wanted Adam to admit his sin. The
          first question God asked in the Bible\u2014\u201CWhere are you?\u201D\u2014shows
          that we belong to God. He longs for each of us to examine our own lives,
          be honest with him, and come out of hiding. The first question of the New
          Testament is \u201CWhere is the child who is born king of the Jewish people?\u201D
          (). And the first question Jesus asked was \u201CWhat do you want?\u201D
          (). Our answers to these three questions hold the keys to understanding
          the need of our hearts, our life\u2019s passion, and God\u2019s plan for
          our lives. See  .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Adam answered, \u201CI heard your powerful presence moving in the
        garden, and I was afraid because I was naked; so I hid.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CWho told you that you were naked?\u201D God said. \u201CDid
        you eat the fruit of the tree that I commanded you not to eat?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Adam pointed to the woman and said,\u201CThe woman you placed alongside
        me\u2014she gave me fruit from the tree,and I ate it.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:12
        content: '  Blame shifting was the beginning of marital disharmony. Only
          the love of Christ can heal the wounds between men and women.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God said to the woman,\u201CWhat
        have you done?\u201DThe woman pointed to the snake and said,\u201CThe shining
        snake tricked me,and I ate.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God then said to the snake,\u201CBecause
        you have done this,you are cursed above every wild animal,condemned above
        every creature of the field!You will slither on your bellyand eat dust [[COMMENT(0)]]
        all the days of your life!"
      comments:
      - number: 3:14
        content: '  Adam was made from dust, and now the snake was cursed to feed
          on dust (see  ). Whatever we withhold from God becomes food for the enemy.
          We choose to make our dust-life the dwelling place for the demonic or the
          divine.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "And I will place great hostility between you and the woman,and between
        her seed [[COMMENT(0)]] and yours.He will crush your headas you crush his
        heel.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  Or \u201Coffspring.\u201D The seed of the woman is Jesus Christ.
          The male carries the seed, but Jesus Christ is the seed of the woman, for
          there was no human father to conceive him. See  ;  ;  ;  . Christ has sown
          himself as the seed into our hearts. We have been born again, not by a
          corrupting seed, but by an Incorruptible Seed, the living and abiding Word
          of God (see  ).      Or \u201CHe will batter your head, and you will batter
          his heel.\u201D However, the structure of the sentence (subject before
          the verb) implies a synchronic action, making the second clause concessive.
          This is the Protoevangelium, God\u2019s first announcement of a Savior,
          and presents a preview of Jesus Christ, who would be wounded by the snake/sin
          on his heel but bring a death blow to Satan by the power of his cross and
          resurrection. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then God said to the woman,\u201CI will cause your labor pains in
        childbirth to be intensified; [[COMMENT(0)]]with pain  you will give birth
        to children.You will desire   to dominate your husband,but he will want to
        dominate you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:16
        content: "  Or \u201CI will multiply your pain and your pregnancies,\u201D
          a likely hendiadys.      The Hebrew word for \u201Cpain\u201D () is a homophone
          that can also mean \u201Ccreativity.\u201D God will use our painful situations
          to birth and express his beautiful creativity through us. Many works of
          art, compositions of music, and powerful acts of kindness have been birthed
          through the \u201Clabor pains\u201D of our sometimes-troubled past. Pain
          can be the incubator of creativity and beauty.      Or \u201Cyour craving\u201D
          (noun). There is no verb in this clause; it is borrowed from the next.     
          Sin brought a painful conflict and power struggle into the home. This clause
          is not a statement of God\u2019s ideal (that either husband or wife dominate)
          but a result of the fall of humanity (arguing over who will be first place
          in the home). Husband and wife are both meant to reign and take dominion,
          for they are one. The thematic context is that of pain/conflict: conflict
          between the seed of the woman and the seed of the snake, conflict (pain)
          in childbirth and child rearing, and conflict in marriage. God\u2019s ideal
          for marriage is a mutual submission, deference, and sacrificial love that
          places the other above ourselves. See  ,  . See also Susan T. Foh, \u201CWhat
          is the Woman\u2019s Desire?\u201D    37 (1975): 376\u201383; Irvin Busenitz,
          \u201CWoman\u2019s Desire for Man: Genesis 3:16 Reconsidered.\u201D   
          7.2 (1986) 203\u201312.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "And to Adam he said,\u201CBecause you obeyed your wife instead of
        me,and you ate from the forbidden treewhen I had commanded you not to,the
        ground will be cursed because of you.You will eat of it through painful toil
        [[COMMENT(0)]] all the days of your life."
      comments:
      - number: 3:17
        content: "  The irony of the narrative is hard to miss. Because they ate
          what was forbidden, pain enters the world. The man will produce food to
          eat through \u201Cpainful toil,\u201D and the woman will experience \u201Cpains
          in childbirth.\u201D Additionally, the ground (and all creation) now labors
          with painful contractions waiting for the unveiling of God\u2019s sons
          and daughters (see  ).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: It will sprout weeds and thorns, [[COMMENT(0)]]and you will eat the
        plants of the field.
      comments:
      - number: 3:18
        content: '  Thorns are part of the curse brought about by the sin of man.
          Jesus wore a crown of thorns (see  ) because he took our curse and set
          us free. For the topic of thorns, see also the footnote on  ;  ,  ;  ; 
          .    '
    - name: '19: Eve'
      title: Eve
      number: 19
      content: "You will painfully toil [[COMMENT(0)]] and sweatto produce food to
        eat, until your body\u2014taken from the ground\u2014returns to the ground.For
        you are from dust,and to dust you will return.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:19
        content: "  This is the same word used for the woman having \u201Cpain\u201D
          in childbirth. The cause of pain in our human experience is sin.      Or
          \u201Ceat your bread.\u201D Work is not a part of the curse, for Adam was
          given responsibility for working and tending the garden before the fall
          (see  ). The punishment of the woman touches her identity as a wife and
          mother; the punishment of man touches his identity in his activity of work
          and being a provider.      See  ;  ;  ;  . Jesus experienced all the effects
          of the curse. He sweat and labored in prayer and in carrying the cross;
          he was crowned with thorns and left in the dust \u201Cfor dead\u201D ().
          It is true that our bodies will return to dust, but we have been lifted
          out of the dust and have been seated in the heavenly realm (see  ). Death
          no longer has victory over us because the resurrection of Christ is also
          our resurrection (see  ).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "The man named his wife Eve\u2014\u201CLife-Giver,\u201D  [[COMMENT(0)]]
        because she would become the mother of every human being."
      comments:
      - number: 3:20
        content: "  Adam changed her name from \u201CWoman\u201D to \u201CEve,\u201D
          the first of many name changes in the Bible. The Hebrew contains a pun,
          or paronomasia, with the name Eve, for her name    is very similar to the
          word for \u201Clife\u201D (, or \u201Cliving one\u201D). God gave the woman
          the ability to not only have babies but to also release life in a variety
          of expressions. Eve brought life into the structure of Adam\u2019s world.
          What does the Scripture tell us about the woman? First, she is God\u2019s
          chosen    (see  ), a protector, a provider, and a source of strength for
          a man. Second, she was taken from man, equally a partner under the Lord
          and perfectly matched for reunion as one. Third, she is the carrier of
          life for all humanity. A woman enfolds all three roles in one person.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God made garments [[COMMENT(0)]] from
        animal skins  to clothe  Adam and Eve. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:21
        content: "  This could also be translated \u201Ccoats,\u201D \u201Crobes,\u201D
          or \u201Ctunics.\u201D      Their first sight of death was an innocent
          sacrifice, killed for them.      Father God did what any good father will
          do when a child fails. He wrapped his love around them and did not degrade
          them. This verb (\u201Cto clothe\u201D) is mostly used for kings who clothe
          others with robes (see  ), or for priests who are clothed with sacred garments
          (see  ;  ;  ). When God clothed Adam and his wife, he did more than cover
          their nakedness. Moved by love, he clothed them to cover their shame. The
          role of Adam and Eve as rulers on the earth was not erased by their fall.
          They were still commissioned as a priest and priestess by God himself.
          God\u2019s love shines through this episode, for he was the One who, as
          an act of grace, caringly provided adequate covering for their bodies.
          For God to use bloodstained animal skins as royal robes to clothe his beloved
          Adam and Eve meant that animals had to be sacrificed to provide their covering.
          See  .    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God said, \u201CThe man has become
        like one of us, knowing good and evil. And now he might take in his hands
        fruit from the Tree of Life, and eat it, and live forever.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Therefore, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>-God expelled him from Eden\u2019s
        paradise to till the ground from which he was taken. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:23
        content: '  Taken from the earth, the man was now given the earth to till.
          Turning over the soil is a picture of how man must guard his heart, his
          life. We must become those who have been loosened and opened to the rain
          of God. The Tree of Life must be planted in the soil of the human heart.
          When God charged man to till the ground, it meant that the soil of his
          heart must be broken up and prepared for this beautiful Tree to come into
          him and branch out through him. See  .    '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'He drove them out of the garden, and placed [[COMMENT(0)]]  fearsome
        angelic sentries  east of the garden of Eden, with a turning fiery sword 
        to guard the way to the Tree of Life. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:24
        content: "  This is the Hebrew word from which we get \u201Cshekinah.\u201D     
          Or \u201Ccherubim,\u201D from the masculine word  , translated \u201Cone
          who intercedes\u201D or \u201Cone with knowledge,\u201D borrowed from the
          Assyrian language from a root word meaning \u201Cto be near.\u201D See 
          ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .      This is the first reference to the sword
          in the Bible. In    and  , the sword is a metaphor of God\u2019s Word as
          it judges the intentions of the heart. We still must pass through the ministry
          of the flaming sword to return to the place where God desires us to dwell.
          This sword was \u201Cawakened\u201D (see  ) against the Lord Jesus Christ
          as he paid the full price to redeem us to God. The cherubim embroidered
          into the fabric of the veil of the Holy of Holies were like sentries, guarding
          the way to the Life within. When the veil was torn in two from the top
          to the bottom, it was as though the cherubim parted and granted access
          within the veil for every believer to come and feast upon the Tree of Life,
          Jesus Christ. See  ;  ;  .      The way to the Tree of Life is Jesus Christ.
          See  ;  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Story of Cain and Abel'
      title: The Story of Cain and Abel
      number: 1
      content: "Now Adam had slept [[COMMENT(0)]] with his wife, and she conceived
        and bore a son named Cain. <smallcaps>  </smallcaps> She said, \u201CBy the
        grace of  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  <smallcaps>\u201D or \u201CBy the
        help of</smallcaps><smallcaps>\u201D; or literally, \u201CI gained a man-</smallcaps><smallcaps>\u201D
        or \u201CI brought him from</smallcaps><smallcaps>.\u201D This utterance
        by Eve is the first time anyone speaks the divine name in Scripture.</smallcaps>
        I have birthed a man!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cknew his wife.\u201D The Hebrew word for \u201Cknew\u201D
          is    and carries the implication of knowing intimately and experientially
          and implies a special relationship (i.e., sexually). It is possible that
          Eve\u2019s conception of Cain had taken place while they were still in
          the garden, which is also implied in  .        means \u201Cpossessed\u201D
          or \u201Csmith [fabricator].\u201D Some have surmised that since God prophesied
          a coming \u201Cseed\u201D of the woman, Eve believed that Cain was that
          promised deliverer. The triliteral root of the Hebrew verb    is the same
          root for the name  . Although the meaning of    is uncertain, some believe
          it could mean \u201Cacquired [one]\u201D or \u201Cpossession.\u201D Some
          Hebrew scholars believe a more accurate translation would read \u201CI
          have brought forth a man-[the God-man],\u201D meaning Eve believed the
          promise about her \u201Cseed\u201D () and presumed that Cain was the promised
          one. What a disappointment when Cain became a murderer!      Or \u201CTogether
          with          "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then later, she gave birth to Cain\u2019s brother Abel. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Abel grew up to be a shepherd, and Cain became a farmer, working the ground.   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:2
        content: "  Adam and Eve had many sons and daughters (see  ), but Cain and
          Abel seem to have been the two eldest. Jewish tradition holds that they
          were twins.    means \u201Cvanity,\u201D \u201Cpuff of air,\u201D or \u201Cfading
          away to nothingness.\u201D Perhaps this is because their hope for the Messiah
          had faded. Or maybe they saw from the thorns and thistles and hard ground
          that life was much more difficult outside the garden than inside, and their
          joy faded away. Paul tells us in    that the world was made subject to
          vanity (or \u201Cfutility\u201D). Adam and Eve saw this vanity firsthand
          and named their son Abel. The Syriac name for Abel means \u201Cherdsman.\u201D     
          Cain chose to work the ground, which was under the curse.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'After some time passed, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> Cain
        presented an offering to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> from the produce of
        the land. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:3
        content: "  Or literally, \u201CFrom the end days.\u201D In contrast, Abel
          brought the firstfruits (firstborn), while Cain brought the leftovers.
          He gave  his leftovers after he had satisfied himself. This is one reason
          why his offering was rejected.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Abel also brought his offering, from among the finest [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of the firstborn of his flocks. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> was very pleased 
        with Abel and accepted his offering, '
      comments:
      - number: 4:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cfattest.\u201D Many Jewish scholars believe it was a
          lamb that Abel sacrificed to God. Sheep were not used for food prior to
          the flood (see  ), only for sacrifice.      Or \u201Cto gaze upon [with
          favor and devotion].\u201D It is possible that fire from heaven consumed
          Abel\u2019s offering as a sign that God was pleased and accepted Abel\u2019s
          blood sacrifice (see  ;  ). God also gazed upon Abel\u2019s heart and saw
          his longings and was pleased, for Abel offered a sacrifice to God with
          faith. See  .    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'but with Cain and his offering, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> was
        not pleased, [[COMMENT(0)]] making Cain very furious and resentful.   '
      comments:
      - number: 4:5
        content: "  Cain\u2019s heart and character were not right with God (see
          footnote on  ). Some believe Cain picked inferior portions of produce (no
          mention of firstfruits) to offer to God, much like trying to please God
          with good works without faith. The curse could not be broken by a product
          of the curse. See  ;  .      Or \u201Chis face [countenance] fell,\u201D
          a Hebrew idiom.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Cain,\u201CWhy are you so
        angry and bothered?"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "If you offer what is right, won\u2019t you be accepted? [[COMMENT(0)]]But
        if you refuse to offer what is right,sin, the predator, is crouching in wait 
        outside the door of your heart.It desires to have you, yet you must be its
        master.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:7
        content: "  Or literally, \u201CIf you do well, uplifting?\u201D Scholars
          consider this verse to be one of the more difficult verses in Genesis to
          translate. The implication is that God would lift up Cain with favor (forgiveness)
          and accept Cain if he did well by bringing an acceptable offering. This
          is not condemnation, but an invitation for Cain to change his ways. The
          Hebrew word for \u201Cuplifting\u201D is taken from the root word  , which
          means \u201Cto carry away,\u201D \u201Cto take away,\u201D \u201Cto lift
          up,\u201D \u201Cto bear [iniquity],\u201D or \u201Cto forgive.\u201D Abel\u2019s
          works were righteous, and Cain\u2019s works were evil. See  .      Or \u201Ccrouching\u201D
          or \u201Cresting outside the portal.\u201D The Akkadian word for \u201Ccrouching\u201D
          () is frequently associated with a demon. Sin is seen as a demon-beast
          crouching at the door of Cain\u2019s heart. However, the word for \u201Csin\u201D
          can also mean \u201Csin offering.\u201D God could be telling Cain that
          there is a sin offering, as a resting lamb, lying outside his door to be
          the acceptable sacrifice. They were opening a portal to the presence of
          God. If the sacrifice was accepted, the portal (Hb.  ) to God\u2019s presence
          would open. Both sin and Jesus are knocking on our hearts\u2019 doors waiting
          to come in. See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "One day Cain said to his brother, \u201CLet\u2019s go out into the
        field.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] When they arrived at the field, Cain rose and
        attacked and killed his brother Abel."
      comments:
      - number: 4:8
        content: '  The words of Cain are missing from most Hebrew manuscripts but
          are found in the Samaritan Pentateuch, Septuagint, Vulgate, and Syriac.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Cain, \u201CWhere is your
        brother Abel?\u201DHe answered, \u201CHow do I know? Am I my brother\u2019s
        keeper?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cguardian.\u201D In a sense, Cain was saying about his
          shepherd-brother, \u201CAm I the shepherd\u2019s shepherd?\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said, \u201CListen\u2014the voice of
        your brother\u2019s blood [[COMMENT(0)]] is crying out to me from the ground!
        What have you done? "
      comments:
      - number: 4:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cbloods\u201D or \u201Cdrops of blood.\u201D Blood crying
          is a symbol of the soul crying out for the right to live, demanding for
          the punishment of the murderer. Bloodguilt calls for justice, even from
          the ground. It is as if the face of the earth blushes as it becomes stained
          by blood. Blood (spilled) outside the body is always plural in Hebrew,
          \u201CYour brother\u2019s bloods.\u201D This speaks of his descendants
          that could have lived\u2014their blood, too, cried out against Cain. The
          blood of Abel cried out for vengeance, but the blood of Christ cries out
          for mercy and pardon. Therefore the blood of Christ speaks a better word
          than the blood of Abel (see  ).    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Now you are banished [[COMMENT(0)]] from the land, from the very
        ground that drank your brother\u2019s blood from your hand!   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:11
        content: "  Or \u201Ccursed [punished].\u201D      Bloodguilt not only stains
          the conscience but also defiles the ground. See  . We are told to avoid
          the way of Cain (), which would include (1) offering God what is cursed,
          (2) jealous anger toward another, (3) refusing to repent, (4) murder, and
          (5) wandering away from God\u2019s presence.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "When you try to cultivate the ground it will no longer produce crops
        [[COMMENT(0)]] for you; and you will be a fugitive, a homeless wanderer!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cyield its strength.\u201D      Or \u201Cyou will be
          a totterer and a wanderer.\u201D Alienation from God is the ultimate consequence
          of sin.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Cain said to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, \u201CMy punishment is
        more than I can bear! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:13
        content: "  Or \u201CIs my sin too great to be forgiven?\u201D (LXX). The
          Hebrew word    refers to sin and its punishment. The Hebrew can be translated
          \u201CMy sin [or \u201Cmy punishment\u201D] is too great to bear.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Look\u2014you\u2019ve thrown me off the land today, and now I must
        hide from your presence. As a fugitive and wanderer on the earth, anyone
        who meets me may choose to kill me!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> responded, \u201CNot so! If anyone
        kills you, I promise the seven-fold [[COMMENT(0)]] vengeance of Cain will
        be released upon him!\u201D So, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> put an identifying
        sign  on Cain as a warning so that no one would dare kill him. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:15
        content: "  That is, seven times over\u2014seven lives will be taken to avenge
          Cain\u2019s death. Or it could mean seven generations will be avenged.
          The next murderer we find in Scripture is Lamech, the seventh generation
          from Cain. Jewish sages believe it was Lamech who killed his ancestor Cain.     
          Or \u201Cmark.\u201D It could have been a visible mark upon Cain as a warning
          that he was under divine protection. See  ,  . However, it is also possible
          that God showed a supernatural, authenticating sign to confirm to Cain
          that he would not be harmed. Ancient rabbis taught that the mark of Cain
          was a horn that grew on his head.    "
    - name: '16: The Family Line of Cain'
      title: The Family Line of Cain
      number: 16
      content: Then Cain left the presence of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and journeyed
        to the Land of Wandering, [[COMMENT(0)]] east of Eden.
      comments:
      - number: 4:16
        content: "  Or \u201CNod,\u201D the Hebrew word for \u201Cwandering,\u201D
          likely a symbolic place. There was a span of 130 years from the creation
          of Adam to the murder of Abel, which would have allowed for other sons
          and daughters of Adam to have spread over the earth. Some have calculated
          there could have been over half a million people alive at that time. See 
          ;  . Scripture does not mention the line of Cain after this chapter nor
          mention Cain\u2019s death. Within Jewish tradition there is a reference
          to Cain marrying his sister. See    4:9; Sanhedrin 58b.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Cain slept with his wife and she conceived and bore Enoch. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Cain was building a city  at the time, so he named it the Village of Enoch,
        after his son. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:17
        content: "    means \u201Cdedicated,\u201D \u201Cteacher,\u201D or \u201Cinitiated.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cwalled village.\u201D God banished Cain to wander as a fugitive,
          but instead he built a city in rebellion to God.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Enoch\u2019s son was Irad, [[COMMENT(0)]] and Irad\u2019s son was
        Mehujael,  and Mehujael\u2019s son was Methushael,  and Methushael\u2019s
        son was Lamech. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:18
        content: "    means \u201Ccity of witness,\u201D \u201Cwild donkey,\u201D
          or \u201Cfugitive.\u201D        means \u201CGod is combatting\u201D or
          \u201Csmitten by God.\u201D The Akkadian word    means \u201Cecstatic (seer).\u201D       
          means \u201Cmy god is husband\u201D or \u201Cman of god.\u201D Some suggest
          it is taken from a word in Ugaritic,  , which means \u201Cman of Baal.\u201D
          Others view it as \u201Cman of Shael\u201D or \u201Cman of Sheol,\u201D
          the underworld.        means \u201Coverthrower\u201D or \u201Cone who brings
          low.\u201D The Arabic meaning of    is \u201Cstrongman.\u201D Lamech, the
          first polygamist, was the seventh from Adam in the line of Cain. He denotes
          the antichrist spirit with his prideful boasting.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Lamech married two women, Dawn [[COMMENT(0)]] and Dusk.   '
      comments:
      - number: 4:19
        content: "  Or \u201CAdah,\u201D which means \u201Cdawn,\u201D possibly related
          to the Hebrew word  , meaning \u201Cjewel.\u201D      Or \u201CZillah,\u201D
          which means \u201Cdusk\u201D or \u201Cshadow.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Dawn gave birth to Jabal, [[COMMENT(0)]] the first  of those who
        lived in tents and raised livestock. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:20
        content: "    means \u201Cnomad\u201D or \u201Cflowing.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe
          father,\u201D used also in v.  .    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Jabal\u2019s brother was Jubal, [[COMMENT(0)]] the first of musicians
        who played instruments.   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:21
        content: "    means \u201Cjoyful sound.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe harp [stringed
          instrument] and flute [wind instrument].\u201D The Hebrew word for    means
          \u201Cto hold\u201D or \u201Cto handle\u201D and later became associated
          with \u201Cto play skillfully.\u201D Jubal invented musical instruments
          and taught others to play them. See  ;  . Musicians today should dedicate
          their gifts and talents to God for him to be glorified.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Dusk gave birth to Tubalcain, [[COMMENT(0)]] the first of blacksmiths
        who forged all kinds of bronze and iron tools. His sister was Naamah. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:22
        content: "    means \u201Cflowing from Cain.\u201D He invented and taught
          others metallurgy.        means \u201Cpleasant\u201D or \u201Cgracious.\u201D
          The triliteral root,    can also mean \u201Cto sing.\u201D At least one
          Targum reference describes her as a professional singer. Ancient Jewish
          writings suggest that Naamah became Noah\u2019s wife.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Lamech boasted to his wives: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CListen to me, Dawn
        and Dusk!Mark my words, O&nbsp;wives of Lamech!I have killed a man for wounding
        me,and a young man for bruising me. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:23
        content: "  The form of v.    is the first example of poetry in the Bible,
          known as parallelism. Many Jewish scholars view this \u201CSong of Lamech\u201D
          as a summary of a larger poetic composition describing the exploits of
          Lamech.      Or \u201CI would kill a man for my wounding, in fact a boy
          for a bruise.\u201D There is a Jewish legend that states that Lamech killed
          Cain. If Lamech was boasting that killing others will be his practice,
          he became the world\u2019s first terrorist.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "If killing Cain costs seven lives,for Lamech, it will cost seventy-seven!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:24
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Adam slept with his wife again and she bore a son whom she named
        Seth, meaning \u201Cappointed,\u201D for she declared, \u201CGod has appointed
        for me another son [[COMMENT(0)]] to replace Abel, because Cain killed him.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:25
        content: "  Or \u201Cseed.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: After many years Seth had a son named Enosh. [[COMMENT(0)]] During
        his lifetime, people  began to worship  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and
        pray to him. <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: 4:26
        content: "    means \u201Cmortal\u201D or \u201Cfrail [man].\u201D Seth humbly
          named his son Enosh, emphasizing the frailty of man.      Or \u201Che [Enosh].\u201D
          With Enosh and his family line, we see the restoration of a longing to
          commune with God.      Or \u201Ccall upon his name,\u201D a biblical description
          of prayer that includes praise and worship. The name  expresses his personality,
          \u201CHe who Is and Causes to Be,\u201D and reveals his desire to commune
          with human beings.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: Family History of Adam and Eve'
      title: Family History of Adam and Eve
      number: 1-2
      content: "When God created human beings he made them in the likeness of God
        and created them as male and female. After he had created them, he lovingly 
        [[COMMENT(0)]] blessed them and named them \u201Chumanity.\u201D So here
        is the family history  of Adam and Eve: "
      comments:
      - number: "5:1\u20132"
        content: "  Love is implied in God\u2019s blessing upon the human family.
          God\u2019s blessing was upon man and woman, empowering them to live on
          this planet. Inherent in this \u201Cblessing\u201D was being infused with
          power and favor to succeed in life and to multiply. Father God loves to
          bless his people.      Or \u201CAdam.\u201D No stronger statement could
          be made that male and female are coequal before their Creator. There is
          really only one man in the Old Testament, and that is Adam. There is really
          only one man in the New Testament, and that is Jesus. There are really
          only two men who have represented the human race: the first Adam and the
          Last Adam, Jesus Christ. The books of Genesis and Matthew are both introduced
          with the record of the generations of Adam and Christ.      Or \u201Cbook\u201D
          or \u201Cwritten record.\u201D What follows is a genealogy. God included
          so many genealogies in the Bible because he loves families and they are
          important to God. Each name represents a family.      See  ;  .    "
