    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Hadoram, [[COMMENT(0)]] Uzal,  Diklah,   '
      comments:
      - number: 10:27
        content: "  Hadoram, which means \u201Cthe god Hadad is exalted,\u201D was
          the possible ancestor of the Yemenite people (the Sabeans).      Uzal (or
          \u201CAzal\u201D) was the ancient name of Sanaa, capital of Yemen.       
          means \u201Cdate palm.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Obal, [[COMMENT(0)]] Abimael,  Sheba,   '
      comments:
      - number: 10:28
        content: "    means \u201Cstripped bare.\u201D There are a number of possible
          locations in Yemen of a city once named Obal.        means \u201Ca father
          sent by God\u201D or \u201Ctruly, God is my father.\u201D Abimael was an
          ancestor of Arabian tribes.      Descendants of Sheba settled in southern
          Arabia. Sheba is sometimes identified with the entire Arabian Peninsula.
          See  .    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Ophir, [[COMMENT(0)]] Havilah,  and Jobab.  All the descendants of
        Joktan '
      comments:
      - number: 10:29
        content: "  Ophir is known as the east coast of Arabia and is frequently
          connected to gold, i.e., \u201Cthe gold of Ophir.\u201D      This Havilah
          is not believed to be the same Havilah mentioned in  . This region of Havilah
          was in Arabia toward the Red Sea.      Jobab, which means \u201Cdesert,\u201D
          is an unknown region likely located in Arabia.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'lived in the territory that extends all the way from Mesha [[COMMENT(0)]]
        toward the eastern hills of Sephar.   '
      comments:
      - number: 10:30
        content: "  Mesha, which means \u201Cfreedom,\u201D is the region on the
          east coast of the Red Sea.      Sephar, which means \u201Ca numbering,\u201D
          is the hilly region near the Red Sea.  "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'These were the families of Shem according to their genealogies, by
        their families, lands, languages, and nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "After the flood, Noah\u2019s descendants formed nations as the people
        spread throughout the earth."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Tower of Babel'
      title: The Tower of Babel
      number: 1
      content: 'Now everyone at that time spoke a single language [[COMMENT(0)]]
        with one vocabulary. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cone lip.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'As people migrated eastward, [[COMMENT(0)]] they found a large plain
        in the land of Shinar and settled there. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom the east.\u201D The Hebrew is ambiguous.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "They said to one another, \u201CCome, let\u2019s unite together and
        make bricks of clay  [[COMMENT(0)]] and burn them until they become hard.\u201D
        So, they piled up the bricks they made to serve as stones and collected tar
        for mortar. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:3
        content: "  God\u2019s building never includes bricks, only stones. Man makes
          bricks; God is the Maker of stones. The New Jerusalem will not be made
          from bricks but from precious stones (see  ). Pharaoh made his treasure
          cities out of bricks; God raises up his temple using living stones (see 
          ).    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then they said, \u201CCome, let\u2019s begin work to build ourselves
        a city with a lofty tower that rises into the heavens. We\u2019ll make a
        name for ourselves, a monument to us, [[COMMENT(0)]] instead of being scattered
        all over the earth.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 11:4
        content: '  An ancient historian, Philo Judaeus, says that each worker engraved
          their names on the bricks to memorialize themselves. Today their names
          are forgotten, and the Name of God stands as a High Tower. Seeking to make
          a name for ourselves is self-worship. We are to lay aside our reputations
          to make the Name of Jesus famous (see  ). Jesus emptied himself of his
          outward glory.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'But when <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> came down to see the city
        and the tower which mortals had started building, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "he said, \u201CIf they have begun this as one people sharing a common
        language, then nothing they plan to do will be impossible for them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Come, let us [[COMMENT(0)]] go down and confuse their language and
        prevent them from understanding each other.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 11:7
        content: '  In the plural pronoun many theologians see the three members
          of the Godhead.      Some linguists believe there are nearly seven thousand
          languages in the world. Although God confused the language of earth, he
          will one day purify (clarify) the language so that people will serve him
          in unity. See  .    is the reversal of Babel, for God gave men unlearned
          languages as they spoke in tongues.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> scattered them over the entire earth,
        and they stopped building their city. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:8
        content: "  The Bible ends with two figurative cities, Babylon and the New
          Jerusalem. Babylon-builders will always seek to make a name for themselves.
          Those who are a part of the New Jerusalem long to see only the name of
          Jesus exalted. The overcomer\u2019s name will be engraved forever on a
          stone in the City of our God where he makes his dwelling with man (see 
          ).    "
    - name: '9: Genealogy of Shem'
      title: Genealogy of Shem
      number: 9
      content: "That is why the city was called Babel\u2014because it was there that
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> confused [[COMMENT(0)]] the language of the
        whole world and from there the people were scattered over the face of the
        earth."
      comments:
      - number: 11:9
        content: "    comes from the Hebrew word \u201Cto confuse.\u201D However,
          in the Babylonian language, the city was called Bab-ilu, \u201Cthe gate
          of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'These are the descendants of Shem. [[COMMENT(0)]]Two years after
        the flood, at the age of one hundred, Shem had a son named Arphaxad.   '
      comments:
      - number: 11:10
        content: '  See  ;  .      See  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: And after Arphaxad was born, Shem lived another five hundred years
        and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'When Arphaxad was thirty-five, he had a son named Shelah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:12
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: And after Shelah was born Arphaxad lived another four hundred and
        three years and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When Shelah was thirty, he had a son named Eber. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:14
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: And after Eber was born, Shelah lived another four hundred and three
        years and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'When Eber was thirty-four, he had a son named Peleg. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:16
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: And after Peleg was born, Eber lived another four hundred and thirty
        years and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'When Peleg was thirty, he had a son named Reu. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: And after Reu was born, Peleg lived another two hundred and nine years
        and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'When Reu was thirty-two, [[COMMENT(0)]] he had a son named Serug. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cone hundred and thirty-two\u201D (LXX, Sam. Pent.).
          It is Jewish tradition that Reu was born when the Tower of Babel had begun
          to be built.    means \u201Cfriend\u201D or \u201Cshepherd.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: And after Serug was born, Reu lived another two hundred and seven
        years and had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'When Serug was thirty, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> he
        had a son named Nahor. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cone hundred and thirty\u201D (LXX, Sam. Pent.).    means
          \u201Cinterwoven\u201D or \u201Cstrength.\u201D According to the  , Serug
          was the first one of Shem\u2019s descendants to turn from  to worship idols.
          It is said he taught sorcery to his son Nahor.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: And after Nahor was born, Serug lived another two hundred years and
        had other sons and daughters.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'When Nahor was twenty-nine, he had a son named Terah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:24
        content: "    means \u201Cwild goat\u201D or \u201Cwanderer.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: And after Terah was born, Nahor [[COMMENT(0)]] lived another one hundred
        and nineteen years and had other sons and daughters.
      comments:
      - number: 11:25
        content: "  Jewish tradition states that Nahor lived in Ur, on the Euphrates
          in lower Mesopotamia, the place where God appeared to Abram.    means \u201Cangry,\u201D
          \u201Cpassionate.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: The Story of Terah'
      title: The Story of Terah
      number: 26
      content: 'When Terah was seventy, he had sons named Abram, [[COMMENT(0)]] Nahor,
        and Haran. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:26
        content: "  This was the Patriarch who would later have his name changed
          to Abraham.    means \u201Cexalted father.\u201D    means \u201Cfather
          of a multitude.\u201D There were ten generations from Adam to Noah and
          ten generations from Shem to Abram.        means \u201Cliving in the high
          place\u201D or \u201Cmountaineer.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Here are the descendants of Terah. Terah was the father of Abram,
        Nahor, and Haran, and Haran was the father of Lot. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Haran preceded his father, Terah, in death in the land of his birth,
        in the Chaldean city of Ur. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:28
        content: "  The word    means \u201Cdemonic;\u201D    means \u201Cflame.\u201D
          Ur was an ancient city-state in Mesopotamia (modern Iraq), which was approximately
          fifty miles south of Babylon. The ruins of Ur can still be seen at modern
          Tell el-Muqayyar. In 2000 BC, Ur was perhaps one of the largest cities
          of the world. It is clear that Abram and his father served foreign gods.
          Ur was named after the moon goddess and was her center of worship. The
          Chaldeans were astrologers, occultists, and idol worshipers. Ancient traditions
          state that Terah was an idol-maker until his death. The Jewish writers
          have a tradition that Abram and his father were cast into a fiery furnace
          for refusing to worship idols and were miraculously delivered. See  .    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The brothers, Abram and Nahor, were both married. Abram\u2019s wife
        was Sarai. [[COMMENT(0)]] Nahor married the daughter of his deceased brother
        Haran; her name was Milcah,  and her sister was Iscah.   "
      comments:
      - number: 11:29
        content: "    means \u201Cruler\u201D or \u201Cmy princess.\u201D God would
          later change her name to \u201CSarah.\u201D      Nahor married his orphaned
          niece.    means \u201Cqueen.\u201D        means \u201Cdiscerner\u201D or
          \u201Cone who scans abroad.\u201D Iscah is Jessica in English.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: Now Sarai was barren and childless.
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Terah took his son Abram, his grandson Lot, [[COMMENT(0)]] the son
        of Haran, and his daughter-in-law Sarai, his son Abram\u2019s wife, and they
        all departed together from the Chaldean city of Ur to go into the land of
        Canaan.  But when they journeyed as far as Haran,  they settled there. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:31
        content: "    means \u201Cto wrap a covering\u201D or \u201Cto envelop.\u201D     
          The land of Canaan takes its name from the son of Ham, Canaan. The land
          of Canaan is mentioned sixty-six times in the Old Testament but not found
          in the New Testament.      Most scholars identify Haran with a city in
          Turkey, now in ruins, called Harran, which is approximately six hundred
          miles from Ur. It is the city that Jacob fled to (see  ;  ) and, later,
          that the Assyrians destroyed in the days of Hezekiah (see  ;  ).  "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: Terah lived two hundred and five years and died in Haran.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: God Appears to Abram'
      title: God Appears to Abram
      number: 1
      content: "Now <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Abram, [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CLeave
        it all behind  \u2014your native land, your people,your father\u2019s household,
        and go to the land that I will show you. "
      comments:
      - number: 12:1
        content: "  The God of glory appeared to Abram and spoke with him (see  ).
          God\u2019s appearance to Abram was sudden and without warning. The same
          voice of creation now proclaims a message of hope and blessing to all the
          world. Abram had no burning bush to inspire him, no tablets of stone to
          guide him, and no ark of the covenant as a centerpiece of worship. Neither
          did Abram have a temple to worship in, a Bible to read, or a priest to
          counsel him. Nor did Abram have a pastor to pray for him, or a prophet
          to prophesy to him. But Abram had a divine encounter.      Or \u201CGo
          yourself,\u201D from  , which is a Hebrew play on words. The implication
          is that although Abram must undergo a traumatic departure from his native
          land, he was actually traveling to find his more authentic self. Perhaps
          \u201CGo and find yourself\u201D conveys the meaning.      The Hebrew word   
          is etymologically linked to the Canaanite word  , which means \u201Cfirmness
          of will\u201D or \u201Cstubbornness.\u201D God was saying to Abram, with
          double meaning, leave your country but also leave your own will behind
          in order to enter God\u2019s plan. We need to leave it all behind, including
          our ideas of how God will work.      God was calling Abram out from more
          than just his relatives. He was calling Abram out from specific deity worship
          connected to nations, clans, and ancestors.      Leaving all that is familiar
          was an incredible act of faith on Abram\u2019s part (see  ). He was told
          to go into an unknown land, but it would result in the seven-fold blessing
          of vv.  .    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: Follow me,and I will make you into a great nation. [[COMMENT(0)]]I
        will exceedingly bless and prosper you,and I will make you famous, so that
        you will be a tremendous source of blessing for others.
      comments:
      - number: 12:2
        content: "  This would take a miracle, for Sarai was barren. This would have
          greatly stretched Abram\u2019s faith, yet he believed. Because he had left
          his nation, God would make Abram into a great nation. God gave creative
          ability to Abram, not only to produce offspring, but also to apply creative
          ability to form lasting enterprises that would shape a nation. God gave
          the ability to create community to Abram and his seed.      Or \u201CI
          will make your name great,\u201D which in the ancient Near East also implied
          being highly esteemed for his character. The building of the Tower of Babel
          was so that men could \u201Cmake a name\u201D for themselves. This was
          intended to be the gift of God and not something to be seized for oneself.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "I will bless all who bless youand curse all who curse you. [[COMMENT(0)]]And
        through you all the families of the earth will be blessed.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 12:3
        content: "  Or \u201Call who cause you harm I will punish.\u201D See  .     
          Or \u201CAnd by you all the families of the earth will bless themselves\u201D
          or \u201CEvery nation will long for me to bless them as I have blessed
          you.\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'So Abram obeyed <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and left; and Lot went
        with him.Now Abram was seventy-five years old when he departed from Haran
        after his father died. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 12:4
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'He took his wife Sarai, his nephew Lot, and all the possessions and
        people [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, the true God. Also, Abram was wealthy before
        Pharaoh gave him gifts (see</smallcaps> he had acquired in Haran; and they
        departed for the land of Canaan. When they arrived in the land of Canaan, '
      comments:
      - number: 12:5
        content: "  Or \u201Csouls.\u201D Jewish tradition states that Abram preached
          the revelation of    ).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: Abram passed through the land and stopped at the sacred site of Shechem,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] famous for the great oak tree of Moreh. <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        At that time, the Canaanites were also in the land.
      comments:
      - number: 12:6
        content: "  The Hebrew word    (a generic place) is never used to describe
          a city. In this context it is likely linked to the Arabic word  , which
          means \u201Csacred site.\u201D The word    means \u201Cbetween the shoulders.\u201D
          The shoulder represents all power and authority (see  ;  ;  ). The site
          of Shechem was the physical center of modern Israel and is mentioned as
          a sacred place (see  ;  ;  ,  ).      Or \u201Cthe oak [cluster of oaks]
          of Moreh [oracle giver, instruction].\u201D Undoubtedly, this was a place
          of mystery, and it was so famous that people used the tree as a landmark.
          See  . At the great tree of Moreh,  taught Abram to walk by faith, not
          by sight. God will lead us to a place of true strength (Shechem) and instruct
          our hearts (Moreh) to trust in him alone.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> appeared [[COMMENT(0)]] before
        Abram and said, \u201CThis is the land I will personally deliver to your
        seed.\u201D  So Abram erected an altar there to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        who had appeared before him. "
      comments:
      - number: 12:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cmade himself visible.\u201D Scripture records at least
          nine appearances of God (theophanies) to Abraham (see  ). The first was
          while he was still in Ur (see  ). See also  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ,  .      Or
          \u201Cto your future descendants.\u201D God\u2019s divine declaration assigned
          the land of Israel to Abram and his descendants. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "From there, he journeyed on toward the hill country east of Bethel
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and pitched his tent  with Bethel
        on the west and Ai  on the east. And there he built another altar to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        where he prayed and worshiped <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. <smallcaps>,\u201D
        which implies both prayer and offering a sacrifice.</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 12:8
        content: "    means \u201CHouse of God.\u201D This is modern Beitin, a city
          about eleven miles north of Jerusalem. It is clear Abram adored  and was
          faithful to his voice.      While Abram lived in a tent without foundations,
          he was looking and waiting for a city with unshakable foundations (see 
          ). Likewise, we are living in the \u201Ctent\u201D of church life today,
          waiting for its ultimate consummation\u2014the New Jerusalem, the City
          of God with foundations. Paul, the Abraham of the New Testament, was a
          tentmaker.        means \u201Cthe heap of ruins.\u201D It is often identified
          as et-Tell, which was about a mile from ancient Bethel. See  . Bethel is
          the House of God; Ai (the world) is a heap of ruins. The House of God is
          drawing us in. We must turn our backs forever on the old creation life,
          which is nothing more than a heap of ruins!      Or \u201Cand he called
          upon the name of      "
    - name: '9: Abram Detours to Egypt'
      title: Abram Detours to Egypt
      number: 9
      content: Then Abram journeyed from there by stages through the southern desert
        region. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 12:9
        content: '  That is, the Negev. Abram had traversed the entire length of
          Israel from north to south.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'At that time, a severe famine struck the land of Canaan, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        forcing Abram to travel down to Egypt and live there as a foreigner. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:10
        content: "  Although the promised land was a land flowing (flourishing) with
          milk and honey (), all three patriarchs (Abraham, Isaac, Jacob) and Joseph
          experienced a famine (see  ;  ;  ;  ). Faith will always be tested. This
          famine tested Abram\u2019s faith. So often when we set out for our promised
          land, we encounter a famine. You can be right where God wants you to be
          and still be faced with severe trials. It is better to suffer in God\u2019s
          path than to be at ease in Satan\u2019s.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "When he drew near to Egypt, he said to his wife Sarai, \u201CLook,
        I\u2019m worried because I know that you are a beautiful, gorgeous woman. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "When the Egyptian men take one look at you, they will say, \u2018She
        is his wife.\u2019 Then they will kill me in order to have you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Just tell them you are my sister [[COMMENT(0)]] so that they will
        treat me well for your sake and spare my life.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 12:13
        content: "  In fact, Sarai was his half sister (see  ). If the Egyptians
          were to kill Abram, it would leave Sarai vulnerable to the men of Egypt.
          This was, in fact, a troubling moral dilemma for Abram. By calling her
          his \u201Csister,\u201D any interaction with her culturally required a
          negotiation with her \u201Cbrother.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When Abram entered Egypt, everyone noticed Sarai\u2019s stunning
        beauty. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 12:14
        content: '  Sarai was at least sixty-five at this time, ten years younger
          than Abram.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When Pharaoh\u2019s dignitaries spotted her, they went to Pharaoh
        and raved about her beauty. Then they took Sarai into the palace and made
        her part of Pharaoh\u2019s harem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Because she pleased Pharaoh, Abram got along very well in Egypt and
        received royal treatment: he was given sheep, cattle, male and female donkeys,
        camels, and male and female slaves. [[COMMENT(0)]]'
      comments:
      - number: 12:16
        content: "  All of Pharaoh\u2019s gifts were signs of great wealth imparted
          to Abram by the king. It was the great wealth and many possessions that
          caused Lot to want to separate from Abram (see  ). There were many people
          who accompanied Abram both into Egypt and back into Canaan. He had the
          converts he acquired in Haran (see  ), plus 318 trained soldiers who were
          born under Abram\u2019s care (see  ) who also had wives and children. It
          is possible that Abram had several thousand people who accompanied him.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> struck Pharaoh and his household
        with terrible diseases because he had taken Abram\u2019s wife, Sarai. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "So Pharaoh sent for Abram and said, \u201CHow could you do this to
        me? Why didn\u2019t you tell me she was your wife? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 12:18
        content: '  Somehow, perhaps by a dream, God showed Pharaoh his sin.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "And why did you lie to me by saying, \u2018She\u2019s my sister,\u2019
        so that I took her as my wife? Now, here\u2019s your wife back; take her
        and begone!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: Then Pharaoh gave strict orders to his men to escort them out of Egypt
        along with everything they had. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 12:20
        content: '  Besides great possessions, Abram also acquired servants in Egypt,
          and Hagar was one of them (see  ).  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Abram Had a Lot to Lose'
      title: Abram Had a Lot to Lose
      number: 1
      content: Abram took his wife and all that he owned, and left Egypt. They returned
        to the southern desert region, and Lot went with them.
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Now Abram had become very rich [[COMMENT(0)]] in livestock, silver,
        and gold. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cweighty\u201D or \u201Cheavy.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'And he journeyed on from place to place as far as the hill country
        region of Bethel. He returned to the place between Bethel and Ai where he
        had pitched his tent at the beginning. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "This was the place he had first built an altar to pray and worship
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D Abram went
        back to the first altar he had built to commune with this God who had made
        promises to him. There are times we, too, need to go back to our beginnings
        in order to recapture our \u201Cfirst love\u201D for Jesus before we can
        move forward. See</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 13:4
        content: "  Or \u201Che called on the name of    .    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Now Lot, who accompanied Abram, was also rich and had accumulated
        flocks, herds, family, and servants. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:5
        content: "  Or, literally, \u201Ctents,\u201D meaning those who camped with
          Lot.    "
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: "Arguments erupted between Abram\u2019s herdsmen and Lot\u2019s herdsmen
        because the land could not support both living together, for their animals
        and possessions were too numerous. At that time, Canaanites and Perizzites
        were also in the land. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "13:6\u20137"
        content: '  The implication is that grazing rights were in dispute between
          all four parties (Abraham, Lot, the Canaanites, and the Perizzites).    '
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: "Arguments erupted between Abram\u2019s herdsmen and Lot\u2019s herdsmen
        because the land could not support both living together, for their animals
        and possessions were too numerous. At that time, Canaanites and Perizzites
        were also in the land. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "13:6\u20137"
        content: '  The implication is that grazing rights were in dispute between
          all four parties (Abraham, Lot, the Canaanites, and the Perizzites).    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "So Abram said to Lot, \u201CLet\u2019s not quarrel with each other,
        or between our herdsmen, since we are relatives. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Look at the vast land that is in front of you! Let\u2019s settle
        in different regions. If you choose the land on the left, then I\u2019ll
        go right, and if you want land on the right, then I\u2019ll go left.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Lot lifted his eyes and carefully surveyed the land around him [[COMMENT(0)]]
        all the way to Zoar. He noticed that the Jordan Valley was fertile and well-watered
        (this was before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah).
        It looked beautiful, like the garden of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, or
        like Egypt. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:10
        content: "  Or \u201CLot lifted up his eyes.\u201D When Abram offered the
          choice to Lot, he should have said, \u201CUncle, I choose you. God is with
          you. My choice is your choice.\u201D Every young person likes to be separated
          from the older generation. Lot missed the will of God by separating from
          the called one, Abram. There is protection, covering, and anointing when
          we walk with those who walk with God. Our flesh would rather \u201Cdo it
          on our own,\u201D but God\u2019s way is to walk in fellowship with called
          ones. The meaning of    is \u201Ccovert,\u201D \u201Csecret,\u201D or \u201Cconcealed.\u201D
          Everything about Lot was hidden away in his heart. Compromise was a way
          of life for him. The secret tug of the world drew him away from the place
          of blessing. He had never really left Ur; he was still an idolater at heart.
          When he chose the rich plains, he was looking for the closest thing that
          resembled Egypt. He chose what would please him without considering the
          consequences. Lot\u2019s possessions were eventually burned in the fires
          of judgment, and he ended up living in a cave.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'So Lot chose to settle in the Jordan Valley. He departed toward the
        east, and the family split up and separated from each other. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Abram settled in the land of Canaan while Lot settled in the cities
        of the lowlands, at a place [[COMMENT(0)]] near Sodom. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cpitched his tent.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: God Speaks Promises to Abram'
      title: God Speaks Promises to Abram
      number: 13
      content: Now, the people of Sodom were extremely wicked and rebelled against
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "After Lot separated from him, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> 
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> spoke to Abram, \u201CLift up your eyes and
        look around you to the north, the south, the east, and the west. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:14
        content: "  Although the New Testament describes Lot as \u201Crighteous\u201D
          (), Scripture portrays him as an object lesson of one who compromised his
          faith by wanting both to follow  and to love this present world. See  .
          It appears that God waited until Abram and Lot finally separated before
          giving Abram further blessings. Through the life of Abram, we learn that
          separation brings revelation. Abram separated from (1) his country, (2)
          his relatives, (3) Egypt, (4) Lot, (5) his desire to get wealth (see  ),
          (6) Ishmael (see  ), and (7) from his beloved son, Isaac (see  ). These
          seven separations brought revelation, encounters, blessings, miracles,
          and inheritance.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "As far as you can see in every direction is the land that I will
        give to you forever\u2014to you and your seed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'I will multiply them until they are as numerous as the specks of
        dust on the earth. If anyone could count the dust of the earth, then your
        offspring could also be counted. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Now, get up and walk through the land\u2014its length and its breadth.
        All the land you walk upon will be my gift to you!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 13:17
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: Abram moved his camp and settled by the oaks of Mamre, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> which are at Hebron,  and there he built another altar to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.
      comments:
      - number: 13:18
        content: "    means \u201Cfatness.\u201D It is a picture of the strength
          of God\u2019s anointing and the weighty glory of the Lord. Mamre was located
          about three miles north of Hebron. It was the site of a pagan shrine, but
          Abram reclaimed it for  and erected an altar there to the true God.       
          means \u201Cto unite [in fellowship].\u201D The modern Arabic name for
          Hebron is al-Halil er-Rahman, meaning \u201Cfriend of the Merciful One,\u201D
          a reference to Abraham, the friend of God.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Abram Rescues Lot'
      title: Abram Rescues Lot
      number: 1
      content: 'During the reign of Amraphel [[COMMENT(0)]] king of Babylon,  he
        allied with three other kings: Arioch  king of Ellasar,  Kedorlaomer  king
        of Elam,  and Tidal  king of Goyim.   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:1
        content: "    most likely means \u201Cspeaker of dark secrets.\u201D Some
          Assyriologists and scholars identify him as the famous King Hammurabi of
          Babylon.      Or \u201CShinar,\u201D which means \u201Ccountry of two rivers.\u201D       
          means \u201Cfierce lion.\u201D      Or \u201CLarsa,\u201D a city-state
          of lower Chaldea. It was the center of the cult of the sun-god Utu. It
          is recognized as modern Tell Senkereh in Iraq.    means \u201CGod is chastener.\u201D       
          means \u201Cthe servant of the goddess Lagamar [no mercy].\u201D       
          means \u201Chidden\u201D and was an ancient pre-Iranian kingdom in Persia.
          Susa was its principal city.        means \u201Cgreat son.\u201D He was
          a chief (king) of various nomadic tribes in Mesopotamia.      Goyim was
          likely a country east of the Tigris in the lowlands of Mesopotamia called
          Gutium.    is also the Hebrew word for \u201Cnations\u201D or \u201Cpeoples.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'These four kings went to war against five kings: Bera [[COMMENT(0)]]
        king of Sodom,  Birsha  king of Gomorrah,  Shinab  king of Admah,  Shemeber 
        king of Zeboiim,  and the king of Bela,  which is Zoar.   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:2
        content: "    means \u201Cwith evil.\u201D        means \u201Cburning.\u201D       
          means \u201Cwith wickedness.\u201D        means \u201Csubmersion.\u201D     
          Although some believe    means \u201Csplendor of the father,\u201D the
          Midrash (Ber. Rab. 42) explains Shinab as  , \u201Cone who draws money
          [wherever he can].\u201D        means \u201Cearth fortress.\u201D       
          likely means \u201Cknown for being strong.\u201D        means \u201Cgathering
          of troops\u201D or \u201Cgazelles [beautiful ones]\u201D and is recognized
          as modern Tsvoyim.        means \u201Cdestruction.\u201D        means \u201Cinsignificant\u201D
          or \u201Csmall.\u201D    "
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: Kedorlaomer had oppressed these five kings for twelve years until
        they rebelled against him in the thirteenth year. They all became regional
        allies in the valley of Siddim, [[COMMENT(0)]] which is now the Dead Sea.
      comments:
      - number: "14:3\u20134"
        content: "    means \u201Cdivision\u201D or \u201Cdemons.\u201D    "
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: Kedorlaomer had oppressed these five kings for twelve years until
        they rebelled against him in the thirteenth year. They all became regional
        allies in the valley of Siddim, [[COMMENT(0)]] which is now the Dead Sea.
      comments:
      - number: "14:3\u20134"
        content: "    means \u201Cdivision\u201D or \u201Cdemons.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'In the fourteenth year, Kedorlaomer went to war with his allied kings.
        They defeated the Rephaites [[COMMENT(0)]] in Ashteroth-karnaim,  the Zuzites 
        in Ham,  the Emites  in Shavah-kiriathaim,   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cgiants.\u201D See  . The Hebrew word    also means \u201Cshades
          [ghosts]\u201D or \u201Cspirits of the dead.\u201D See  ;  ,  .       
          was a Canaanite goddess of fertility and coupled with    means \u201Cgoddess
          of two horns.\u201D Ashteroth-karnaim was the likely capital city of Og,
          king of Bashan, east of Lake Galilee.      Or \u201CZuzim.\u201D    means
          \u201Croving creatures.\u201D      The city of Ham may be the ancient name
          of the Ammonite capital Rabboth-Ammon.      Or \u201CEmim.\u201D    means
          \u201Cterrors.\u201D    is the Moabite name of a people of giants who once
          occupied Moab. See  .        means \u201Cthe plain of the two cities.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'and the Horites [[COMMENT(0)]] in the hill country of Seir,  as far
        as El Paran  near the desert.   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:6
        content: "    means \u201Ccave dwellers.\u201D Mt. Hor is the location where
          the first high priest, Aaron, was buried. Mt. Hor is near Petra in Jordan.
          See  .        means \u201Chairy\u201D or \u201Cshaggy\u201D and refers
          to the mountainous area south of the Dead Sea located in Edom.        means
          \u201Cbeautiful oaks.\u201D      The invasion route began east of the Jordan,
          moved southward, and returned northward toward the Dead Sea, conquering
          as they went, finally defeating the five kings.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then they turned back and attacked En-mishpat [[COMMENT(0)]] (that
        is, Kadesh) and subdued all the country of the Amalekites  and the Amorites 
        who lived in Hazazon-tamar. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:7
        content: "    means \u201Cthe spring of decision\u201D or \u201Cspring of
          judgment.\u201D    means \u201Csacred.\u201D En-mishpat is identified as
          modern \u2018Ayn Qadeis, fifty miles south of Beersheba.        means \u201Cwarlike\u201D
          or \u201Cvalley dwellers.\u201D        means \u201Csayers\u201D or \u201Cmountain
          dwellers.\u201D        means \u201Cdividing the date palm\u201D and is
          identified in    as En-gedi, a town on the western shore of the Dead Sea.
          The tribes mentioned in vv.    were likely some of the \u201Cgiants\u201D
          that were in the land. See  ,  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then the king of Sodom, the king of Gomorrah, the king of Admah,
        the king of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar), marched out in
        battle formation in the valley of Siddim. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "There they faced off against Kedorlaomer, king of Elam; Tidal, king
        of Goyim; Amraphel, king of Babylon; [[COMMENT(0)]] and Arioch, king of Ellasar\u2014four
        kings against five. "
      comments:
      - number: 14:9
        content: "  Or \u201CShinar,\u201D a name for ancient Babylon.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Now the valley of Siddim was full of tar pits, and as the kings of
        Sodom and Gomorrah and their armies retreated from the battle and fled, some
        of them fell into the tar pits, and the rest fled to the hill country. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The four victorious kings captured all the possessions and all the
        food of Sodom and Gomorrah and left. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "They captured Lot, Abram\u2019s nephew who had been living in Sodom,
        and took him and all his possessions."
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'One who escaped came to Abram the Hebrew and told him what had happened
        to Lot. Abram was living by the oaks of Mamre the Amorite. Mamre had two
        brothers, Eshcol [[COMMENT(0)]] and Aner, who were allied by treaty with
        Abram. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:13
        content: "    means \u201Ccluster.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When Abram heard that his nephew Lot had been taken captive by the
        four kings, he mobilized all the men in his camp, [[COMMENT(0)]] 318 in all
        who had been born and trained in his own household, and he pursued the invaders
        as far north as Dan. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:14
        content: "  These were not only warriors but also disciples (Hb.  , \u201Ctrained
          ones\u201D) of Abram. It was God who supernaturally won this battle, for
          Abram was facing numerous fierce tribal warriors. Abram realized that the
          battle would be won with God\u2019s help. Abram was a noble man, for he
          could have easily left Lot, who chose to live in Sodom, in the hands of
          his captors.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then, during the night, Abram strategically divided his forces and
        defeated them. His forces attacked them and routed them as far as Hobah,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] north of Damascus. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:15
        content: "    means \u201Chiding place.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: Abram Blessed by Melchizedek'
      title: Abram Blessed by Melchizedek
      number: 16
      content: He recovered all the stolen possessions and brought back his nephew
        Lot, together with the women and all the prisoners.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "After Abram returned from defeating Kedorlaomer and the kings who
        were with him, the king of Sodom went out to meet Abram at the valley of
        the Shaveh [[COMMENT(0)]] (known as the King\u2019s Valley).   "
      comments:
      - number: 14:17
        content: "    means \u201Clevel\u201D or \u201Cequal [equalize].\u201D     
          The King\u2019s Valley later became known as the Kidron Valley. But the
          events of this chapter happened in the King\u2019s Valley\u2014the low
          place where we meet the King.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'And Melchizedek, [[COMMENT(0)]] who was both a priest of the Most
        High God and the king of Salem,  brought out to Abram bread and wine.   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:18
        content: "  There are varying viewpoints on the identity of Melchizedek;
          some scholars view Melchizedek as merely a type or picture of Christ or
          a Canaanite royal priest. Others believe that he was a Christophany, a
          pre-incarnate appearance of Christ as both a priest of the Most High God
          and the King of Salem (peace). He appeared out of nowhere, with no genealogy
          or pedigree other than being a king-priest. Two Dead Sea scrolls dating
          back to at least the first century BC found in Cave 11 at Qumran (11Q13,
          11QMelch), state that Melchizedek was a divine being, and was given the
          Hebrew title  . According to this text, Melchizedek proclaimed the Day
          of Atonement as a day coming when one will atone for the sins of the people
          and will be their supernatural deliverer and their judge (see Wise, Abegg,
          Cook [1996].  ). See also footnote on  ;  ;  ,  ;  ;  . In  , Jesus said
          that \u201CAbraham&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. foresaw me coming and was filled
          with delight!\u201D Abraham saw the day of Jesus as Melchizedek came out
          to meet him with bread and wine.      Salem is the name of ancient Jerusalem.
          See  . Melchizedek was a priest on behalf of whom? Not the Jews, for Abram
          was yet to have a son. Rather, it was on behalf of the gentiles. God established
          a priesthood over the    before he brought forth a priesthood over the
          Jews. Melchizedek was a gentile king over a gentile city. Gentiles have
          been in the heart of God from the beginning.      Bread and wine is the
          substance of the Lord\u2019s Table. Melchizedek brought a Communion service
          to Abram.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He spoke over him a special blessing, saying,\u201CBlessed is Abram
        by God Most High, [[COMMENT(0)]]Creator  of heaven and earth."
      comments:
      - number: 14:19
        content: "  Or \u201CEl Elyon.\u201D      Or \u201CPossessor.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And blessed be God Most High,whose power delivered your enemies into
        your hands!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]Abram gave Melchizedek a tenth of all he
        possessed.   "
      comments:
      - number: 14:20
        content: "  Abram was not a warrior; he was a prophet. Yet with God\u2019s
          power behind him, he became a conqueror and won a battle against great
          odds. Only God gets the glory with every victory we experience.      See 
          .    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then the king of Sodom said to Abram, \u201CJust give me the people
        you rescued; keep all the spoils for yourself.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "But Abram said to the king of Sodom, \u201CI raised my hand to <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        God Most High, and I pledged a solemn oath to the Possessor of heaven and
        earth "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "that I would keep nothing for myself that belongs to you, not even
        a thread of a garment or sandal strap. That way, you will never be able to
        say, \u2018I was the one that made Abram rich.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 14:23
        content: '  Abram resisted the temptation for acquiring wealth apart from
          a relationship with God. He wanted God to be his boast and his true wealth.
          See  ;  ;  .  '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "I will take nothing except what my young men have eaten, and the
        share of those who went with me\u2014Aner, Eshcol, and Mamre. Let them take
        their share.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: God\u2019s Covenant with Abram"
      title: "God\u2019s Covenant with Abram"
      number: 1
      content: "Afterwards, the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> came to Abram
        in a vision [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> and said, \u201CAbram, don\u2019t yield to fear, for I am your
        Faithful Shield <smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s shield rather
        than to take refuge in what the world could give him. See</smallcaps> and
        your Abundant Reward.\u201D <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 15:1
        content: "  The phrase \u201Cthe word of  came\u201D is found 245 times in
          the Old Testament. In this instance, the word of  came  . It is possible
          that  appeared again before Abram (see  ).      was assuring Abram that
          he would now be a Shield to protect Abram from any retaliation by the kings
          he had conquered. He chose to be hidden behind    ;  ;  ;  . Each of us
          may claim this promise to have God himself as our Faithful Shield.     
          Because of what Abram had done by rescuing Lot and refusing to take financial
          reward for his noble acts,  himself would become Abram\u2019s reward. This
          new, intimate relationship with God exceeded any financial loss Abram experienced.
          A new intimacy with God always emerges when we choose him over the world\u2019s
          pleasures.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "But Abram replied, \u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, what
        good is your reward [[COMMENT(0)]] if I remain childless? I\u2019m about
        to die without a son, and my servant, Eliezer of Damascus, will inherit all
        my wealth. "
      comments:
      - number: 15:2
        content: "  Or \u201CWhat can you give me?\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "A servant in my household will end up with everything because you
        have not given me any children.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Immediately, the word of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> came to him:
        \u201CNo! Eliezer will not be your heir. [[COMMENT(0)]] I will give you a
        son from your own body to be your heir.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 15:4
        content: "  Or \u201CThis man will not inherit you.\u201D      Or \u201CWhoever
          comes out of your body will inherit you.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> brought him outside his tent [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and said, \u201CGaze into the night sky. Go ahead and try to count the stars.\u201D
        He continued, \u201CYour seed will be as numerous as the stars!\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 15:5
        content: "  God wants to take us outside of our \u201Ctents,\u201D our limitations
          and opinions of how God can do a miracle. Paul, the tentmaker, was taken
          outside of the natural world and shown the mysteries of God, much like
          his ancestor Abram. See  .      See  . The seed of Abraham is now both
          earthly (as many as the grains of sand) and heavenly (as many as the stars, 
          ;  ;  ;  ;  ). The heavenly stars point to the heaven-born church of Jesus;
          the grains of sand point to the earthly seed of Abram, the Jews who inherit
          Abram\u2019s promises. See  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: And Abram trusted every word <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had spoken!
        And because of his faith, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> credited it to him
        as righteousness. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 15:6
        content: '  That is, God accepted Abram and made him righteous by his faith.
          See  ,  ,  ,  ;  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then he said to him, \u201CI am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, who
        brought you out of the Babylonian city of Ur, to give you all this land to
        possess.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But Abram said, \u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, how can
        I be sure that I can possess this land for myself?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 15:8
        content: '  Abram was asking God for a sign to assure him that he had legal
          standing to stake a claim to the land and possess it.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to him, \u201CBring me a heifer,
        a female goat, and a ram, each three years old, [[COMMENT(0)]] also a turtledove
        and a young pigeon.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 15:9
        content: "  Or possibly, \u201Ceach three-fold,\u201D that is, three of each
          animal. However, the verb form used here seems to indicate the years (though
          the term for \u201Cyears\u201D is not included), as there are other normal
          ways to say \u201Cthree.\u201D The number three points to the three years
          of Jesus\u2019 ministry and to his resurrection on the third day. The death
          of the animals shows that suffering precedes inheritance. See  ;  ;  ; 
          .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So, Abram brought the animals to him and killed them. He cut them
        in two (except the birds) and laid each half opposite the other in two rows. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: Vultures [[COMMENT(0)]] swooped down upon the carcasses, but Abram
        stood there and drove the vultures away.
      comments:
      - number: 15:11
        content: "  Or \u201CBirds of prey.\u201D Some expositors see the vultures
          as symbolic of evil powers attempting to interfere with this covenant ritual.
          When we step into covenant with God, it is important to stand on the promise
          and to drive away our own fears and doubts that rise up in our own souls.
          See  ,  ;  .    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'As the heavy veil of night fell, Abram went into a deep state of
        sleep, [[COMMENT(0)]] and suddenly a great dreadful darkness surrounded him
        and he was filled with fear.   '
      comments:
      - number: 15:12
        content: "  Or \u201Ca trance-like state,\u201D the same words used in  .     
          For those of us with prophetic promises yet to be fulfilled, we must contend
          with our doubts and wait on God with faith and patience. Even in our dreadful
          darkness, our Faithful God will not disappoint us.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Abram, \u201CKnow this:
        your descendants will live as strangers in a foreign country. They will be
        enslaved and mistreated for four hundred years. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 15:13
        content: '  This was a prophecy that the Israelites would be enslaved in
          Egypt. See  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Afterward I will punish that nation for enslaving them, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> and your descendants will come out of slavery with untold wealth.   '
      comments:
      - number: 15:14
        content: '  punished Egypt with ten plagues. See  .      At the time of their
          exodus, God would give the Israelites the back wages for four hundred years
          which they deserved. As they departed, the Egyptians gave great riches
          to the Israelites (). It was an extraordinary transfer of wealth. The riches
          of Egypt funded the building of the tabernacle in the wilderness, including
          the ark of the covenant and all the golden furnishings.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'You, however, will go to your ancestors in peace and live a full
        life. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:15
        content: '  Abraham lived one hundred and seventy-five years (see  ).    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And after the fourth generation, your descendants will return here;
        for then the sin of the Amorites will be ripe for judgment.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 15:16
        content: "  One reason why the Israelites were kept in Egypt for four hundred
          years was the justice of God. He had to wait until the sin of the Amorites
          was fully deserving of God\u2019s judgment so that he could righteously
          destroy them from the land.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'When the sun had set, and it was very dark, there suddenly appeared
        [[COMMENT(0)]] a smoking firepot and a blazing torch that passed between
        the split carcasses. <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith a flash of fire there appeared\u201D (LXX).     
          God\u2019s manifest presence appeared as a smoking firepot and a blazing
          torch. The smoking firepot points to the Father (;  ) and the blazing torch
          speaks of the Son, the Lord Jesus (see  ;  ;  ;  ). It was the custom in
          the ancient Near East to light a torch (lamp) when making a covenant, symbolizing
          the fire of destruction that would come if the covenant were to be broken.
          See  . God\u2019s promise to Abram, spoken that mysterious night, became
          the \u201Ctitle deed\u201D to the land.  gave Abram the boundaries of the
          expanse of the land of promise. Rivers and land would be part of the inheritance\u2014land
          occupied by the enemy. Powerful princes would be dethroned as the Israelites
          marched into the fullness of their inheritance. The God that walked between
          the sacrifices would walk through the promised land and conquer their foes
          (see  ).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "On that day, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> entered into covenant
        [[COMMENT(0)]] with Abram: \u201CI have given this land to your descendants,
        from the Egyptian border  to the great river Euphrates, "
      comments:
      - number: 15:18
        content: "  Or \u201Ccut a covenant.\u201D      Or \u201Criver of Egypt,\u201D
          possibly the brook (wadi) in eastern Sinai known today as Wadi el-\u2018Arish.  "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'the entire land of the Kenites, the Kenizzites, the Kadmonites, '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Rephaites, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "the Amorites, the Canaanites, the Girgashites, and the Jebusites.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Hagar and Ishmael'
      title: Hagar and Ishmael
      number: 1
      content: 'Now Sarai had borne no children for Abram. She had an Egyptian slave
        girl named Hagar, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 16:1
        content: "  There is a Jewish tradition that Hagar was the daughter of Pharaoh,
          who after seeing the miracles that accompanied Abram and Sarai, gave the
          Egyptian princess to be Abram\u2019s servant (Midrash by Rashi).    can
          be translated \u201Censnaring.\u201D It is also related to the word for
          \u201Cstranger.\u201D In Arabic, it could mean \u201Cfugitive.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "so Sarai said to Abram, \u201CPlease listen. Since <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has kept me childless, go sleep with my maidservant. Perhaps through her
        I can build [[COMMENT(0)]] you a family.\u201D Abram listened and did what
        Sarai asked."
      comments:
      - number: 16:2
        content: "  That is, give Abram a son. This is an obvious wordplay in Hebrew.
          The words for \u201Cbuild\u201D () and \u201Cson\u201D () are quite similar.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Abram had already lived ten years in the land of Canaan when his
        wife Sarai took her Egyptian slave girl Hagar and gave her to Abram to be
        his second wife. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He slept with Hagar, and she conceived. Once Hagar realized she was
        pregnant, she belittled Sarai and despised her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So Sarai went to Abram and said, \u201CIt\u2019s totally your fault
        that Hagar despises me\u2014and you\u2019re not standing up for me!  [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I gave my slave girl to your embrace, and when she found out she was pregnant,
        she despised me. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> judge between us who is
        in the right!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 16:5
        content: '  In the honor/shame culture of the ancient Near East, barrenness
          was a disgrace. The shame that Hagar heaped on Sarai was culturally and
          emotionally more than she could bear.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Abram responded, \u201CShe\u2019s your slave girl under your authority,
        so do with her whatever you think best.\u201D Then Sarai cruelly mistreated
        Hagar, who then ran away from her."
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The angel of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u201D
        in v.</smallcaps><smallcaps>\u201D refers to an appearance of</smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> encountered Hagar by a spring in the wilderness, the spring
        on the way to Shur.   "
      comments:
      - number: 16:7
        content: "  This is likely a preincarnate appearance of Christ (called a
          Christophany), for the angel is called \u201C  . \u201CThe angel of   
          in human form. This is the first mention of an angel in Scripture.       
          means \u201Cwall\u201D and is identified with a wilderness near the Egyptian-Israeli
          border.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "He asked her, \u201CHagar, servant of Sarai, where have you come
        from and what are you doing here?\u201DShe replied, \u201CI\u2019m running
        away from Sarai, my mistress.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The angel of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> told her, \u201CYou have
        to go back to your mistress and humbly submit to her.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The angel added, \u201CI will greatly multiply your descendants until
        no one can count them.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 16:10
        content: "  Only God could multiply Hagar\u2019s descendants. We see the
          kindness of God revealed by his promise to Hagar. God is the guardian of
          the weak and the suffering. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s angel continued, \u201CYou are
        now pregnant, and soon you will give birth to a son. You will name him Ishmael,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has heard your cries of
        distress. "
      comments:
      - number: 16:11
        content: "    means \u201CGod hears\u201D or \u201CMay God hear!\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Your son will have a wild nature that no one can tame. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He will be hostile toward everyone, and everyone will be hostile toward him;
        and he will live at odds with all his kinsmen.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 16:12
        content: "  Or \u201CHe will be a wild donkey of a man.\u201D This was not
          necessarily a crude insult, but a figure of speech indicating that Ishmael
          would live a solitary existence. Like a wild donkey left in the desert,
          he would be wild and untamed. This is the \u201Cbeastly\u201D nature of
          fallen man, the wild Adam, the flesh.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "After her encounter with <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, Hagar called
        him by a special name, \u201CYou are the God of My Seeing,\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for she said, \u201COh my, did I just see God and live to talk about it?\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 16:13
        content: "  Or \u201CYou are the God who sees me\u201D or \u201CYou are the
          God whom I See.\u201D This encounter at the well reminds us of a later
          time when Jesus would journey to a well to meet a woman who had a history
          of running from God. At this well of Jacob, the Living One again saw into
          the heart of a woman and spoke mercy to her. At Jesus\u2019 encounter with
          the woman at Jacob\u2019s well, God saw into her heart, and she saw into
          God\u2019s. See  .      Or \u201CHave I not gone on seeing after he saw
          me?\u201D The exact meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'That is why the well is called Spring of the Living One Who Watches
        Over Me. [[COMMENT(0)]] The well is still there, between Kadesh and Bered.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:14
        content: "  Or \u201CBeer-Lahai-Roi.\u201D The Hebrew word for \u201Cspring\u201D
          has a homophone that can be translated \u201Ceye.\u201D        means \u201Csacred\u201D;   
          means \u201Chail.\u201D A place known as \u201CLittle Petra\u201D appears
          on maps today as Siq al-Barid. It lies about four miles north of Petra
          and is situated in a short canyon. About halfway between Ein Kadesh (also
          known as Ein Musa) and Siq al-Barid are the ruins of a small Turkish village
          named Chai, and its spring is called Ein el-Chai. This site seems to match
          the description of Beer-Lahai-Roi with its spring-fed well.  "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Hagar returned and bore Abram a son, whom Abram named Ishmael. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Abram was eighty-six years old when Hagar gave birth to Ishmael.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Covenant of Circumcision'
      title: The Covenant of Circumcision
      number: 1
      content: "When Abram was ninety-nine years old, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        appeared to him again and said, \u201CI am the God who is more than enough. 
        Live your life in my presence  and be blameless.   "
      comments:
      - number: 17:1
        content: "  Thirteen years elapsed between chs.    and  . Abram and Sarai
          were incapable of conceiving a child. See  .      Or \u201CI am El Shaddai.\u201D
          This is the most frequently used name for God prior to the Law being given
          at Sinai.    is one of the words for God.    () is taken from a Hebrew
          root word that carries multiple expressive meanings. It can mean \u201CGod
          of the Holy Mountain,\u201D \u201CGod of the Wilderness,\u201D \u201CGod
          the Destroyer of Enemies,\u201D \u201CGod the All-Sufficient One,\u201D
          \u201CGod the Nurturer of Babies [the Breasted One],\u201D \u201CGod the
          Almighty,\u201D \u201Cthe Sovereign God,\u201D or \u201Cthe God who is
          more than enough.\u201D The combination of    (Almighty) with    describes
          the tender heart of God, one who cares for his beloved ones. To a man ninety-nine
          years of age, God All-Sufficient was a revelation that would sustain Abraham.     
          Or \u201Cbefore me.\u201D Living consciously before God frees us from the
          false self that lives only before others.      The Hebrew word    can also
          mean \u201Cperfect,\u201D \u201Ccomplete,\u201D \u201Cwhole,\u201D or \u201Cfull.\u201D
          The more-than-enough God is telling Abram to walk continuously in the fullness
          of God\u2019s presence, which will make him perfect and complete. A new
          revelation of God\u2019s goodness (The God of more than enough) will always
          be followed by a new challenge (walk blameless before God). Because he
          is Almighty, we can live in holiness, following his ways.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "I will confirm my covenant between me and you, and I will greatly
        multiply your descendants.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then Abram fell on his face in awe before God, [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        God said to him, '
      comments:
      - number: 17:3
        content: "  When man bows in the dust, God will speak in grace. Abram\u2019s
          posture is a picture of his humility as he ponders this revelation in the
          presence of God.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CI establish my covenant with you:\u201CYou will become a father
        of many nations."
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: You will no longer be named Abrambecause I am changing your name to
        Abraham, [[COMMENT(0)]]for I have made you a father of many nations.
      comments:
      - number: 17:5
        content: "    means \u201Cexalted father\u201D;    means \u201Cfather of
          a multitude.\u201D The church today does not need exalted fathers; we need
          fathers who will multiply themselves in their sons and daughters. Generational
          transfer is in the heart of God and was here revealed to Abraham.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: I will make you abundantly fruitful, more than you expect.I will make
        nations out of you,and kings will trace their lineage back to you. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 17:6
        content: "  David, Solomon, and Hezekiah, for example, were kings and leaders
          who came forth from Abraham\u2019s blessed relationship with God. He has
          likewise made us kings and priests! See  ;  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Yes, I will establish my eternal covenant of love between me and
        you,and it will extend to your descendants throughout their generations.I
        will be your children\u2019s [[COMMENT(0)]] God, just as I am your God."
      comments:
      - number: 17:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cdescendants\u2019.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "I will give to you and your seedthe land to which you have migrated.The
        entire land of Canaan will be yours and your descendants\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]as
        an everlasting possession.And I will be their God forever!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 17:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cseed.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "God explained to Abraham, \u201CYour part of the covenant is to obey
        its terms, you and your descendants throughout the ages. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So here is the sign of the covenant that you are to keep, so that
        it will endure between you and me and your descendants: circumcise [[COMMENT(0)]]
        every male among you. '
      comments:
      - number: 17:10
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Ccircumcision\u201D () means \u201Cto
          cut short,\u201D \u201Ccurtail,\u201D \u201Cto blunt,\u201D \u201Cto cut
          off,\u201D or \u201Cto destroy.\u201D With a new name, Abraham was to perform
          circumcision on the eighth (number of new beginning) day. This external
          sign of circumcision would set the Israelites apart for God. The New Testament
          truth of heart-circumcision is the cutting away of our flesh (our rights
          to ourselves), in dedication to God (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'You must undergo cutting off the flesh of your foreskin as a special
        sign of the covenant between me and you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Throughout your generations, each male child must be circumcised
        eight days after his birth. This includes those not of your descendants\u2014those
        born in your household and foreign-born servants whom you have purchased; "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'they must be circumcised, homeborn and purchased alike. In this way,
        you will carry in your flesh the sign of my everlasting covenant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Any uncircumcised male who does not have the foreskin of his flesh
        cut off will be cut off from his people, for he has broken my covenant.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "God also said to Abraham:\u201CConcerning your wife Sarai,you are
        not to call her Sarai anymore, but Sarah, [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2018My Princess,\u2019
        will be her name."
      comments:
      - number: 17:15
        content: "  The names Sarai and Sarah appear to be dialectical variations
          of the word for \u201Cprincess\u201D or \u201Cqueen.\u201D God was emphasizing
          to Abraham and Sarah that the past, with its season of waiting, was over.
          Their new names signified a new era, a new fulfillment of promises, and
          a new destiny calling them forward.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "I will wonderfully bless her,and I will certainly give you a son
        through her.Yes, I will bless her greatly,and she will become a mother of
        nations;kings of nations will arise among her children!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Abraham laughed so hard he fell to the ground, saying to himself,
        \u201CHow in the world can a hundred-year-old man become a father? How can
        my wife Sarah get pregnant at ninety?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "And then he spoke out loud: \u201CO, that Ishmael might prosper with
        your blessing!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 17:18
        content: "  Or \u201CO, that Ishmael might live in your sight!\u201D a metaphoric
          way of saying that he longed for Ishmael to prosper and live under God\u2019s
          favor. Ishmael was Abraham\u2019s \u201Cplan B,\u201D and Abraham is still
          hoping that the promises God had given to him could transfer over to Ishmael.
          God, however, has no \u201Cplan B.\u201D He will always accomplish his
          original, perfect plan.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "God said, \u201CListen to me. I promise that you and Sarah will have
        a son, and you will call him Isaac. [[COMMENT(0)]] I will confirm my everlasting
        covenant of love with him and his seed. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:19
        content: "    means \u201Che laughs.\u201D It can mean \u201Che [God] laughs\u201D
          or \u201Che [Abraham] laughs.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'And regarding Ishmael, I have heard your cry and I will indeed bless
        him. I will cause him to have many, many descendants. He will father twelve
        rulers, [[COMMENT(0)]] and I will make him into a great nation. '
      comments:
      - number: 17:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cprinces.\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But my everlasting covenant relationship is with Isaac, who will
        be born to you and Sarah about this time next year.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: When he had finished speaking with Abraham, God ascended up to heaven.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 17:22
        content: "  Or \u201CGod rose from upon\u201D (lit. Hb.) or \u201CGod went
          up from Abraham.\u201D The implication is that God ascended, returning
          to heaven after coming down to meet with Abraham.  "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'So without delay Abraham obeyed God and took his son Ishmael and
        every male in his household (whether born in his house or foreign-born servants)
        and circumcised them that very same day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Abraham was already ninety-nine years old when he was circumcised, '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'and his son Ishmael was thirteen. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'They were both circumcised on the same day, '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: along with all the men of his household (whether born in his house
        or foreign-born servants).
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Appears Again to Abraham'
      title: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Appears Again to Abraham
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> appeared once again to Abraham while
        he lived by the oak grove of Mamre. During the hottest part of the day, as
        Abraham sat at his tent door, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'he looked up and suddenly saw three men standing nearby. As soon
        as he saw them, he ran from his tent to welcome them. He bowed down to the
        ground [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 18:2
        content: "  This is the first place the Hebrew word    is found in the Hebrew
          Bible. It is most often translated \u201Cbow down in worship.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "and said, \u201CMy Lord, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        if I have found favor in your sight, don\u2019t pass me by. Stay for a while
        with your servant. "
      comments:
      - number: 18:3
        content: "  This is the word    (Lord), a name used over five hundred times
          for God. Abraham was waiting for his day of visitation at his tent (tabernacle)
          door. The tent or tabernacle is frequently used as a metaphor for our bodies,
          our lives on this earth. Abraham was prepared and ready for this supernatural
          day of visitation. We have to get outside of our tents (limitations, flesh
          life) if we are to believe the promises of God (see  ). Jesus said that
          Abraham saw him (see  ). When Abraham saw the men, he knew it was the Lord
          coming to visit him. Verse    makes it clear that it was  who appeared
          in human form (a theophany). The two other \u201Cmen\u201D were angels
          in human form. See  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I\u2019ll have some water brought to you all so that you can wash
        your feet. [[COMMENT(0)]] Rest here a while under the tree. "
      comments:
      - number: 18:4
        content: "  What sweet intimacy we see in this chapter! Three times Scripture
          tells us that God made Abraham his friend. In  , God gave the land to Abraham,
          his friend. In  , God called Abraham his friend. And in    (see footnote),
          because Abraham believed, he was called God\u2019s friend. You, too, have
          been given an inheritance since you believed. You are now God\u2019s chosen
          friend.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Since you\u2019ve stopped by your servant\u2019s home and honored
        me with your presence, I\u2019ll have food prepared for you so that you can
        be refreshed; then you can go on your way.\u201D\u201CVery well,\u201D they
        responded, \u201Cgo ahead and do as you have said.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Abraham hurried back into the tent and said to Sarah, \u201CQuick,
        we have guests! Get three measures [[COMMENT(0)]] of fine flour, knead it,
        and bake some bread.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 18:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cseahs.\u201D A seah is over at least seven liters of
          dry measurement. Orthodox Judaism measures a seah at over fourteen liters.
          This would have made a very large batch of bread. Abraham prepared much
          more food than needed for three hungry men. It is always good to be extravagant
          when we give to God and others.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then Abraham ran to the herd, selected a tender choice calf, and
        told his servant, \u201CHurry\u2014prepare this calf for my guests!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then he brought the meal they had prepared\u2014roasted meat, bread,
        curds, and milk\u2014and set it before his guests. Abraham stood by them
        under the tree while they ate."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "They asked him, \u201CWhere is your wife Sarah?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]He
        answered, \u201COver there\u2014in the tent.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:9
        content: "  This was a statement of revelation-knowledge, for how did he
          know that Abraham was married and that his wife\u2019s name was Sarah?    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then one spoke up and said, \u201CI will return about this time next
        year, when your wife Sarah will certainly have a son.\u201D Sarah overheard
        it, for she was at the tent door not far behind him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: Now, both Abraham and Sarah were already very old, and Sarah was past
        the age of childbearing. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 18:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cit had ceased to be with Sarah after the manner of women.\u201D
          In other words, she was past menopause.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Sarah laughed to herself with disbelief, saying, \u201CA woman my
        age\u2014have a baby? After I\u2019m worn out [[COMMENT(0)]] will I now enjoy
        marital bliss and conceive\u2014and with my aged husband?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cwithered\u201D or \u201Cdried up.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  knew her thoughts and asked Abraham,
        \u201CWhy is Sarah laughing, saying, \u2018How can a woman my age have a
        baby?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Do you think there is anything too marvelous [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s
        question remained unanswered for three thousand years until Jeremiah the
        prophet responded, \u201CThere is nothing too hard for you!\u201D (</smallcaps>
        for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>? I will appear to you at the appointed
        time next year and Sarah will have a son!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:14
        content: "  This same Hebrew word is used as a title of the Lord Jesus in   
          (\u201CThe Wonderful One\u201D). Nothing is too extraordinary for God!
          He is Wonderful!  ). He delights in doing what is impossible to man. See 
          .    "
    - name: '15: Abraham the Intercessor'
      title: Abraham the Intercessor
      number: 15
      content: "Sarah was afraid, so she denied it, saying, \u201CI wasn\u2019t laughing.\u201DBut
        he said, \u201CYes, you were!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Afterward, the three men departed and walked toward Sodom, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and Abraham went off with them to see them on their way. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:16
        content: "  Or \u201Clooked toward the face of Sodom.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "As they walked, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said, \u201CShould
        I really hide from Abraham what I intend to do? "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'After all, he will become a great and powerful nation, and every
        nation on earth will seek bliss like his. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 18:18
        content: "  Or \u201Call nations on earth will [long to] be blessed as he
          is blessed.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "It is true; I have singled him out as my own, [[COMMENT(0)]] so that
        he will lead  his family and household to follow my ways <smallcaps>, an
        idea found over fifty times in the Old Testament and twelve times in the
        New Testament (i.e., \u201Cway of the Lord\u201D).</smallcaps> and live by
        what is right and just. I will fulfill all the promises that I have spoken
        to him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:19
        content: "  Or \u201CI have known (Hb.  ) him.\u201D The Hebrew word    has
          a universe of meaning that includes \u201Cintimacy,\u201D \u201Cchoosing,\u201D
          \u201Cknowing fully,\u201D \u201Cacting justly,\u201D \u201Csharing love,\u201D
          \u201Cto take someone into your heart,\u201D and more.      Or \u201Cinstruct\u201D
          or \u201Cenjoin after him.\u201D      This is the first reference to the
          \u201Cways\u201D of      "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> explained to Abraham, \u201CThe outcry
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  for justice against Sodom and Gomorrah is so great and their
        sin so blatant "
      comments:
      - number: 18:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cshriek,\u201D \u201Clament,\u201D \u201Cwail,\u201D
          \u201Cshout,\u201D or \u201Coutrage.\u201D The Septuagint reads \u201Ctheir
          outcry,\u201D i.e., the outcry against the people of Sodom and the indictment
          against them. The sin of Sodom was blatant and outrageous. See  ;  . The
          voices that cried out would have included those of the people suffering
          the abuses of those in power in their homes and cities. Sin has a voice
          that cries out for justice, but the blood of Jesus has a greater voice!    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "that I must go down and see if their wicked actions are as great
        as the outrage [[COMMENT(0)]] that has come to me, and if not, then I will
        know.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 18:21
        content: "  Or \u201Caccording to the outrage that has come to me they have
          completed.\u201D The Hebrew word for completed is  , meaning \u201Cfinished\u201D
          or \u201Ccompleted.\u201D God already knew the extent of their wickedness.
          He was searching to see if there is still a reason to withhold judgment.     
          This is the word  , the same word God used in v.  : \u201Cto know Abraham
          [fully, intimately, firsthand knowledge].\u201D The \u201Cif\u201D God
          used in this verse sparked hope in Abraham that God might relent of his
          judgment.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "As <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s two companions went on toward
        Sodom, Abraham remained there, as <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> paused before
        Abraham. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 18:22
        content: "  This verse is listed as a rare instance of Masoretic interference
          with the text known as    or \u201Cscribal corrections.\u201D The implication
          is that the text needed to be amended to read \u201CAbraham still stood
          before the Lord.\u201D This translation has left this phrase in its original
          state, as translated from the oldest manuscripts and ancient external sources.
          God paused before Abraham, giving him time to ponder and ask for mercy
          for the city. God waits for our intercession. God wants us to plead for
          mercy even when judgment is imminent.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "So Abraham came forward to present his case before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        and said, \u201CAre you really going to sweep away the righteous while you
        judge the wicked? "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "What if you find fifty righteous people in Sodom? Isn\u2019t your
        mercy great enough to forgive? Why judge the entire city at the cost of the
        fifty righteous who live there? "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "That\u2019s not who you are\u2014one who would slay the righteous
        with the wicked, treating them both the same way! Wouldn\u2019t the Merciful
        Judge of all the earth always do what is right?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s character, not the character of the people
        of Sodom, was on the line. Abraham stood alone before</smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 18:25
        content: "  Or \u201Cact justly?\u201D Abraham appeals to  not only to spare
          the righteous but also to express his merciful heart.    and plead for
          the lives of wicked people to be spared. This moved God\u2019s heart, and
          he granted each request Abraham made\u2014until Abraham stopped asking.
          Abraham asked six times. What would have happened if Abraham had asked
          the seventh time? Abraham did not change the mind of God; he demonstrated
          what was already on God\u2019s heart.  "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said, \u201CAlright. If I find
        fifty righteous in Sodom, I will spare the whole city for their sake.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Abraham spoke up again and said, \u201CI am just a man formed from
        earth\u2019s dust and ashes but allow me to be so bold as to ask you, my
        Lord. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "What if there are only five lacking, and you only find forty-five
        righteous in Sodom? It\u2019s not who you are to destroy the entire city
        for lack of five righteous people.\u201DAnd <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        said, \u201CAlright. If I find forty-five righteous in Sodom, I will spare
        the whole city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CBut what if there are only forty?\u201D Abraham asked further.<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        answered, \u201CAlright. If I only find forty, I will spare the city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Abraham paused\u2014then he said, \u201CLord, please don\u2019t be
        offended with me, and let me speak&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. What if there are
        only thirty?\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> answered, \u201CAlright.
        If I find only thirty, I will spare the city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Abraham ventured even further, asking, \u201CAllow me to dare speak
        this way to you, my Lord. But what if you find there only twenty righteous?\u201D<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        answered, \u201CAlright. For the sake of the twenty I will not destroy the
        city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Then Abraham took a deep breath and asked, \u201COnce more, please
        don\u2019t let my Lord be angry with me if I make but one more request. What
        if you find only ten righteous?\u201DAnd <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> answered,
        \u201CAlright. I will extend my mercy and not destroy the city for the sake
        of ten righteous.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> finished speaking with Abraham. He immediately
        went on his way, and Abraham returned home.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Wickedness of Sodom'
      title: The Wickedness of Sodom
      number: 1
      content: "That evening, the two angels came to Sodom [[COMMENT(0)]] while Lot
        was sitting at the city\u2019s gateway.  When Lot saw them, he got up to
        meet them and bowed with his face to the ground. "
      comments:
      - number: 19:1
        content: "    means \u201Cscorched\u201D or \u201Cburnt region.\u201D     
          A city gateway usually consisted of towers, guardrooms, and a meeting area
          where people could sit. Often, the city leadership would conduct meetings
          there (see  ). Recent archeological discoveries at Tel-Dan revealed a stone
          bench that was fifteen feet long connected to the wall of one of its towers.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He said, \u201CPlease, my lords, come to your servant\u2019s house
        to spend the night and wash your feet; then you can rise early and go on
        your way.\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D they answered. \u201CWe will be fine to spend
        the night in the town square.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'But Lot was so insistent they finally agreed to go to his house.
        Lot had unleavened bread baked for them and prepared a feast, and they ate. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'But before they retired for the night, the men of the city, men young
        and old, from every part of the city of Sodom, to the last man, surrounded
        the house. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "They shouted out to Lot, \u201CWhere are the men who came to your
        house tonight? Bring them out to us so that we can have sex with them!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 19:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat we may know [] them.\u201D This word is used frequently
          for sexual relations. They surrounded the house, not simply to introduce
          themselves to the men, but to sexually abuse them. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ; 
          ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Lot went outside, shutting the door behind him, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "and said to them, \u201CNo! My brothers, I beg you, don\u2019t sink
        to such depravity! "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Look, I have two virgin daughters; I\u2019ll bring them out to you,
        and you can do with them as you please. Only don\u2019t do anything to these
        men, for they are guests in my house.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 19:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey have come under the shadow of my roof.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CGet out of our way,\u201D they replied. \u201CThis guy comes
        as a foreigner to live among us, and now he dares to judge us! We\u2019ll
        inflict more harm on you than on them!\u201D Just then they lunged at Lot
        and tried to break down the door, "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'but the two angels reached out and pulled Lot safely back into the
        house and bolted the door. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: They struck the men outside the house, young and old, with one blazing
        flash of light [[COMMENT(0)]] so that they could not find the door!
      comments:
      - number: 19:11
        content: "  The Hebrew word    is found only here and in  . The word indicates
          more than sightlessness (Hb.  ), but a sudden immobilizing and dazzling
          flash of light. See the Aramaic Targums; Yoma 22b.; H. M. Orlinsky,   
          (Philadelphia: Jewish Publication Society, 1969), 93ff.; E. A. Speiser,
          \u201CThe \u2018Elative\u2019 in West-Semitic and Akkadian,\u201D    (1952):
          81ff.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then the visitors said to Lot, \u201CWho else lives here? Do you
        have any other family here\u2014sons or daughters, sons-in-law or daughters-in-law
        who live in Sodom? Get them all out of the city, "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "because we are about to destroy this place. A tremendous outcry against
        the people has come before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, and he has sent
        us here to destroy it!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "So Lot went out to find the two men who were pledged to marry his
        daughters and told them, \u201CHurry, leave the city, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        is about to destroy it!\u201D But they thought he was only joking and paid
        him no attention."
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "At dawn, the angels urged Lot, saying, \u201CGo! Take your wife and
        your two daughters and leave or you will be consumed in the judgment about
        to come to the city!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'But Lot hesitated, so the angels grabbed his hands and the hands
        of his wife and daughters and brought them outside the city, because <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        was merciful to them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Once they were safely outside the city, the angels said to them,
        \u201CRun for your lives! Don\u2019t stop anywhere in the plain until you\u2019ve
        reached the mountains. And don\u2019t even look back, or you\u2019ll die!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Lot replied, \u201COh no, my lords. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "You\u2019ve been so gracious to your servant, and you\u2019ve been
        so kind to save our lives, but I can\u2019t make it to the mountains. It\u2019s
        so far from here; disaster will overtake me, and I\u2019ll die! "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Look, over there is a village close enough to run to, and it\u2019s
        a small one. [[COMMENT(0)]] Let me escape there instead. You can see that
        it\u2019s such a small village. Let my life be spared!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 19:20
        content: "  Or \u201CZoar,\u201D a wordplay in Hebrew. The word for \u201Csmall\u201D
          sounds like  .    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D he replied. \u201CI will grant this request
        too. [[COMMENT(0)]] I will not destroy that village. "
      comments:
      - number: 19:21
        content: "  Or \u201CI have lifted up your face,\u201D a figure of speech
          for showing favor.    "
    - name: '22: The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah'
      title: The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah
      number: 22
      content: "Now, you must hurry. Run to that village, for I can\u2019t do anything
        until you are there.\u201D (That is why the village was called Zoar.)"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'By mid-morning, [[COMMENT(0)]] Lot arrived at the small village of
        Zoar, '
      comments:
      - number: 19:23
        content: "  Or \u201CWhen the sun had risen upon the earth.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s fire from heaven fell upon
        Sodom and Gomorrah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'He completely destroyed the cities of the plain, and all their inhabitants
        and whatever grew in the valley. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 19:25
        content: '  Jesus made it clear that if the miracles he did in Israel had
          been seen in Sodom, the people of Sodom would have repented. Therefore,
          it will be more tolerable for them in the Day of Judgment than for the
          cities of Galilee (see  ). Knowing that God will soon judge the corrupt
          world, it is vital that we live holy lives (see  ).    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "But Lot\u2019s wife turned and gazed longingly on the city and turned
        into a pillar of salt. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 19:26
        content: "  See  ;  . Perhaps there really was a salt-pillar that resembled
          a human. In the book the  , which was included in the Septuagint, it says,
          \u201CA pillar of salt stands as a memorial to an unbelieving soul,\u201D
          and Josephus claimed to have seen it in his day (  1.203).    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'That morning, [[COMMENT(0)]] Abraham hurried back to the place where
        he had stood before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.   '
      comments:
      - number: 19:27
        content: "  Or \u201CThe next morning.\u201D It is unclear whether Abraham
          saw the moment of the destruction of the cities or if he viewed the smoke
          rising the next day.      See  . The implication from    and    is that
          this high point may have been some distance from Abraham\u2019s camp.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Looking down toward all the land of the plain, he saw columns of
        smoke billowing up from Sodom and Gomorrah [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014like the smoke
        of a furnace!"
      comments:
      - number: 19:28
        content: "    means \u201Ca ruined heap\u201D or \u201Cto chastise.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: Lot and His Daughters'
      title: Lot and His Daughters
      number: 29
      content: So before God destroyed the cities of the plain where Lot had settled,
        he remembered his affection for Abraham [[COMMENT(0)]] and spared Lot from
        all the destruction.
      comments:
      - number: 19:29
        content: "  That is, he honored Abraham\u2019s request. God had not forgotten
          Abraham and then suddenly remembered him, but rather showed his affection
          for Abraham by fulfilling his request to spare the righteous.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Afraid to remain in Zoar, Lot left there and settled in the hill
        country and lived in a cave with his two daughters. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "One day, his firstborn suggested to the younger, \u201COur father
        is getting old, and there isn\u2019t a man anywhere who could impregnate
        us in the normal way. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Come, let\u2019s get our father drunk with wine and have sex with
        him. That way we can at least have children through our father.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "That night, they got their father drunk with wine, and the firstborn
        went in and slept with him. Lot was so drunk he didn\u2019t have a clue about
        what had happened. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 19:33
        content: "  Or \u201Che did not know when she lay down and when she arose.\u201D
          See v.  . This chapter opens with Lot sitting at the gate of Sodom, the
          seat of authority, and ends with him drunk in a cave\u2014from councilman
          to caveman! Lot could have returned to his uncle, Abraham, but instead
          he fled to a cave.    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "The next day, the firstborn said to the younger, \u201CI slept with
        my father last night. Tonight, it\u2019s your turn. We\u2019ll get him drunk
        with wine, and you can sleep with him and we can preserve our family line
        through our father.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'So they got their father drunk the second time; and the younger went
        in and slept with him. He was once again so drunk he had no clue what had
        happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "As a result, both Lot\u2019s daughters became pregnant by their father. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'The older daughter had a son named Moab, [[COMMENT(0)]] who is the
        ancestor of the Moabites of today.   '
      comments:
      - number: 19:37
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom my father,\u201D a wordplay which in Hebrew sounds
          like \u201C[conceived] from my father.\u201D      Jewish tradition views
          these two daughters as righteous women whose motives were noble. Perhaps
          they presumed the entire world had been destroyed and that Zoar was spared
          only while they were there, leaving no other living male except their father.
          Regardless, one day a descendant of Moab, Ruth, would be included in the
          roots of the Jewish monarchy as David\u2019s great-grandmother (see  )
          and listed in the genealogy of Jesus Christ (see  ). There is no sin or
          evil that can hinder God\u2019s grace from shining through even the darkest
          cloud of human failure.    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: The younger also had a son named Ben-Ammi, [[COMMENT(0)]] the ancestor
        of the Ammonites of today.
      comments:
      - number: 19:38
        content: "  Or \u201Cson of my relative,\u201D a wordplay which in Hebrew
          sounds like \u201Cson of my [paternal] relative.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Sarah Taken into the King\u2019s Harem"
      title: "Sarah Taken into the King\u2019s Harem"
      number: 1
      content: 'Abraham journeyed from the oaks of Mamre to the southern region of
        Canaan [[COMMENT(0)]] and settled between Kadesh and Shur, to live as a temporary
        resident in Gerar.   '
      comments:
      - number: 20:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe land of the Negev.\u201D      This would have been
          an arduous journey as Abraham was a very wealthy man with hundreds of servants
          and many flocks and herds of livestock.    means \u201Clodging place\u201D
          and was a Philistine city-kingdom south of Gaza.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Now Abraham had said about his wife Sarah, \u201CShe\u2019s my sister.\u201D
        So Abimelech, [[COMMENT(0)]] king of Gerar, sent for her and took her into
        his harem.   "
      comments:
      - number: 20:2
        content: "    has two possible meanings: \u201CMelech [Molech] is my father\u201D
          or \u201Cmy father is king.\u201D      Sarah was ninety years old. God
          had supernaturally rejuvenated her and made her attractive to a king. According
          to Jewish tradition, \u201Cher flesh was rejuvenated, her wrinkles smoothed
          out, and her original beauty was restored\u201D (Bava Metzi\u2019a 87a).
          The Dead Sea Scrolls likewise comment on Sarah\u2019s miraculous restoration
          due to her faith in the promise of God with these words: \u201CFair indeed
          are her eyes&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. and all the radiance of her face&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.
          and her hands how perfect. Her legs how beautiful and without blemish her
          thighs&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. And when the king heard the words of [his three
          officials], he desired her exceedingly, and he sent [them] at once to bring
          her to him, and he looked upon her and marveled at all her loveliness&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.
          and he [God] sought to slay me.\u201D See  , Simon &amp; Schuster, 1957.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "One night, God appeared to Abimelech in a dream [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        said to him, \u201CYou\u2019re as good as dead, for you have taken into your
        harem a married woman!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 20:3
        content: '  We see from this not only that God speaks in dreams to the righteous,
          but that he will also come to the lost and share his heart with them (see 
          ). Dreams are powerful avenues into the human spirit. God may speak to
          you in dreams, if you will listen.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Now Abimelech had not touched Sarah, so he said to the Lord, \u201CWould
        you really destroy people who are innocent? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:4
        content: "  Or \u201CWould you really slaughter an innocent nation?\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Didn\u2019t the man tell me, \u2018She is my sister\u2019? And didn\u2019t
        she agree and say, \u2018Yes, he\u2019s my brother\u2019? I\u2019ve done
        this with clean hands and a clear conscience.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then God answered him in the dream, \u201CYes, I know you did this
        with a clear conscience. Furthermore, it was I who kept you from sinning
        and kept you from touching her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Now return the man\u2019s wife, and because he is a prophet, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        he will intercede on your behalf that you may live. But if you don\u2019t
        give her back\u2014you will certainly die, you and your entire household.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 20:7
        content: "  This is the first time the word \u201Cprophet\u201D is found
          in the Bible. The Hebrew word    means \u201Cto bubble up,\u201D referring
          to the stirring of the Holy Spirit that bubbles up through the prophet
          with divine utterance.    is the most common word used for \u201Cprophet\u201D
          and can also be translated \u201Cto declare\u201D or \u201Cone who declares.\u201D
          However, some etymologists connect it with Akkadian word  , \u201Cto call.\u201D
          Assyrian kings had the title of \u201Cthe one called,\u201D that is, called
          by the gods. The form    in Hebrew could also signify \u201Cone who receives
          the [divine] call.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So Abimelech rose early in the morning and gathered all his servants.
        When he told them about his dream, they were terrified! '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Abimelech summoned Abraham and asked him, \u201CWhat is this trick
        you have played on us? I did nothing wrong to you. Why would you bring such
        great guilt upon me and my kingdom? You have done to me what no one should
        ever do to another.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then Abimelech asked, \u201CWhat is your purpose in doing this?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Abraham answered, \u201CBecause I thought, \u2018There\u2019s no
        one here that fears God. They will kill me to get to my wife.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cover the matter of my wife.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Besides, she really is my half sister. She\u2019s my father\u2019s
        daughter, but not my mother\u2019s, so I married her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When God sent me out to wander from my father\u2019s house, I said
        to her, \u2018Here is how you can show your love for me. Everywhere we go,
        you must say about me, \u201CHe\u2019s my brother.\u201D&nbsp;\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then Abimelech gave Abraham\u2019s wife Sarah back to him. In addition,
        he gave him sheep, cattle, and both male and female servants. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Abimelech told him, \u201CLook, my land is now before you; feel free
        to settle wherever you please.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then he turned to Sarah and said, \u201CI am giving your brother
        a thousand pieces of silver [[COMMENT(0)]] as compensation to settle any
        claim against me, to exonerate you in the eyes of all who are with you, 
        and to clear your reputation.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 20:16
        content: "  Or \u201Ca thousand shekels,\u201D which would amount to about
          twenty-five pounds of silver.      Or \u201Ca covering of eyes.\u201D The
          Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Abraham prayed to God; and God healed Abimelech! He also healed
        Abimelech\u2019s wife and female servants of their infertility and they began
        to have babies again. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:17
        content: "  Considering that Abraham\u2019s wife had never given him a child,
          it was an amazing miracle for Abraham to pray for someone else to give
          birth! The very first healing in the Bible was through the prayer of a
          childless man, Abraham. He had no confidence in himself as he prayed this
          prayer of faith. However, he could pray in total confidence that it had
          to be God doing the miracle. He prayed for the very thing he had not yet
          received. When the last two verses of    are read together with the first
          two verses of  , we see that Isaac\u2019s conception occurred as a result
          of Abraham\u2019s prayer for another person with an identical need.  "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "For <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had shut all the wombs of the women
        of Abimelech\u2019s household because he took Sarah, Abraham\u2019s wife."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Birth of Isaac'
      title: Birth of Isaac
      number: 1
      content: '<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> visited Sarah, [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> just as he said he would, and fulfilled his promise to her. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:1
        content: '  We are not told if the Lord appeared to Sarah or visited her
          in a dream, but it is clear that  came to her to confirm his promise.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'And Sarah conceived and bore Abraham a son in his old age, at the
        exact time God had promised them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Abraham named his son Isaac, the miracle son, whom Sarah bore him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When Isaac was eight days old, Abraham circumcised him, as God had
        commanded him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Abraham was one hundred years old when his son Isaac was born. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Sarah said, \u201CGod has brought me laughter, and everyone who hears
        about this will laugh [[COMMENT(0)]] with me.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 21:6
        content: "  This verse contains a double allusion to the name  , which means
          \u201Che laughed.\u201D Every time Abraham and Sarah spoke Isaac\u2019s
          name, they acknowledged the miracle of God. The name    (Isaac) is the
          word for \u201Claughter\u201D but in the past tense. It could be translated
          \u201Cdelayed laughter.\u201D If you had a baby after turning one hundred,
          you might laugh too! Notice the details of Isaac\u2019s birth and how they
          foreshadow the birth of our Lord Jesus: (1) Both sons were the promised
          seed\u2014;  . (2) Both were long awaited\u2014;  ;  . (3) Both had mothers
          who asked questions\u2014;  . (4) Both had names given before birth\u2014; 
          . (5) Both births were miraculous\u2014;  . (6) Both sons were a delight
          to their father\u2014;  .    "
    - name: '7: Hagar and Ishmael Sent Away'
      title: Hagar and Ishmael Sent Away
      number: 7
      content: "And she added,\u201CWho would ever have told Abrahamthat Sarah would
        one day nurse children!Even though Abraham is an old man,look\u2014I have
        given him a son!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Isaac grew and was weaned; and on the day Sarah weaned him, Abraham
        prepared a great feast. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But Sarah noticed the son of Hagar, the Egyptian, was mocking [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        her son Isaac.   '
      comments:
      - number: 21:9
        content: "  The Hebrew word used here is built on the root stem from the
          name  . It is possible to translate it \u201Cjesting,\u201D \u201Cplaying,\u201D
          or \u201Cmaking fun of [Isaac].\u201D Regardless, Sarah saw it as a threat
          to her son. See  .      The italicized words are found in both the Septuagint
          and the Latin Vulgate.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So she said to Abraham, \u201CGet rid of this slave woman and her
        son. Banish them, for the son of that slave woman must not become a coheir
        with my son Isaac!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Abraham was very upset over Sarah\u2019s demand, for Ishmael was
        his son too. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "God spoke to Abraham, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CDon\u2019t be distressed
        over the slave woman and her son. Listen to every word Sarah says to you,
        and do it, for it will be through Isaac your promise of descendants will
        be fulfilled.   "
      comments:
      - number: 21:12
        content: "  Perhaps God spoke to Abraham in a night vision or dream. God
          still speaks to his prophets today, as he spoke to Abraham.      Or \u201Cthrough
          Isaac your seed will be counted.\u201D See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Rest assured, I will make the son of your slave woman into a nation
        too, because he is your son.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Abraham rose up early the next morning, bundled up some food and
        a skin of water, and strapped them to Hagar\u2019s shoulders. Then he gave
        her his son and sent them away. So, Hagar and her son Ishmael departed and
        wandered off into the wilderness of Beersheba."
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'When the water was gone, she grew desperate, so she left her son
        [[COMMENT(0)]] under a bush. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:15
        content: '  Ishmael was not an infant, for he had been circumcised at thirteen
          (see  ), and Isaac was born a year afterwards. It was common to wean children
          at the age of four or five, so Ishmael was at least a teenager when Hagar
          was sent away.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then she walked about the distance of a bowshot and sat down, for
        she thought, \u201CI can\u2019t bear to watch my son die.\u201D As she sat
        nearby, she broke into tears and sobbed uncontrollably."
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "And God heard the voice of the boy. The angel of God called out to
        Hagar from the heavenly realm [[COMMENT(0)]] and said, \u201CWhat\u2019s
        the matter, Hagar? Don\u2019t be afraid, for God has heard the voice of your
        son crying as he lies there. "
      comments:
      - number: 21:17
        content: '  Both Ishmael and Isaac were saved by a voice from heaven (see 
          ).    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Get up! Help the boy up and hold him by the hand, for I will make
        him into a great nation.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: Then God opened her eyes to reveal a well of water. She went over
        to the well and filled the skin with water and gave the boy a long, cool
        drink.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'God was with Ishmael as he grew up in the wilderness of Paran. He
        became an expert archer, '
      comments: []
    - name: "21: Abraham\u2019s Oath to Abimelech"
      title: "Abraham\u2019s Oath to Abimelech"
      number: 21
      content: and his mother, Hagar, arranged a marriage for him with an Egyptian
        woman.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "At that time, King Abimelech and Phicol, [[COMMENT(0)]] his army
        commander, came to Abraham and said, \u201CIt is obvious that God is with
        you and blesses everything you do.   "
      comments:
      - number: 21:22
        content: "    means \u201Cstrong.\u201D      It was not simply the wealth
          of Abraham that impressed them; it was also the supernatural healings that
          took place when Abraham prayed.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Now swear to me here before God that you will not deceive me, my
        children, or my descendants, but as I have shown you loyal friendship, so
        you will treat me\u2014and the land in which you live as a foreigner\u2014with
        loyal friendship.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CI give you my oath,\u201D Abraham answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "But Abraham voiced a complaint about a well of water which Abimelech\u2019s
        servants had seized by force. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Abimelech responded, \u201CThis is the first time I\u2019ve heard
        about this; you never told me before now. I don\u2019t know who has done
        this.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: So Abraham took sheep and cattle, gave them to Abimelech, and the
        two men made a covenant.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Then Abraham set apart from his flock seven ewe lambs, '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "and Abimelech asked him, \u201CWhat are you doing with these seven
        ewe lambs you have set apart?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "He replied, \u201CI am giving them to you, and by accepting these
        seven ewe lambs, you acknowledge the proof that I dug this well and it belongs
        to me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: That place was called Beersheba, [[COMMENT(0)]] because it was there
        that both men swore an oath to one another.
      comments:
      - number: 21:31
        content: "    can be translated either \u201Cwell of seven [lambs]\u201D
          or \u201Cwell of the oath.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'After completing their pact at Beersheba, King Abimelech and Phicol,
        his army commander, departed and returned to Philistine country. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Abraham planted a tamarisk tree [[COMMENT(0)]] in Beersheba, and
        there he worshiped <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the everlasting God.   '
      comments:
      - number: 21:33
        content: "  A tamarisk tree is a type of evergreen that can grow up to fifty
          feet. Abraham did not plant the tamarisk tree for landscaping; it was a
          statement proclaiming his faith. Planting the tree revealed Abraham\u2019s
          faith and endurance until the time of fruitfulness (see  ).      Or \u201CEl
          Olam,\u201D which means \u201CGod Eternal,\u201D \u201Cthe Hidden God,\u201D
          or \u201Cthe Always God\u201D (see  ). This name proclaims that God is
          God over Eternity and God over eternal things. Abraham\u2019s heart and
          focus were turning to the God of Eternity. The things of the earth were
          growing meaningless to him (see  ). El Olam was preparing Abraham to yield
          his greatest treasure, his son. Only one whose heart is fixed on eternity
          can ever make sacrifices pleasing to God (see  ;  ). When we see the Eternal
          One, we can let go of temporary things. Abraham touched eternal life as
          he dwelt by the tamarisk tree and the well. This was his true preparation
          for giving up Isaac.  "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: And Abraham lived many years in peace as a foreigner in Philistine
        country.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: God Tests Abraham\u2019s Faith"
      title: "God Tests Abraham\u2019s Faith"
      number: 1
      content: "Some time later, God tested Abraham. [[COMMENT(0)]]He said, \u201CAbraham!\u201D
        \u201CYes, I\u2019m here,\u201D Abraham answered."
      comments:
      - number: 22:1
        content: "  See  . A new revelation (seeing God as El Olam) will always bring
          a new test. There is no indication that Abraham knew he was being tested.
          The word for \u201Ctested\u201D is most commonly translated \u201Cproved.\u201D
          The purpose of God\u2019s tests are not so that we will fail, but that
          he will prove that we are faithful. The Midrash shows the word for \u201Ctested\u201D
          is derived etymologically from a word that means \u201C[elevated] banner,\u201D
          like a flag flying high above a ship or a victory banner elevated over
          an army. This means that God elevated Abraham and made him great by testing\u2014test
          upon test, greatness after greatness. He does the same thing today with
          the spiritual seed of Abraham. We all want Abraham\u2019s faith, but do
          we want Abraham\u2019s trial to perfect our faith? Tests are God\u2019s
          vote of confidence in our future. The budding qualities of Christlikeness
          are brought forth in every test of our faith. Someday, you may call a \u201Cblessing\u201D
          what you once called a \u201Cburden.\u201D      God had spoken many, many
          times to Abraham. Perhaps this time he spoke by an audible voice or by
          a dream.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "God said, \u201CPlease [[COMMENT(0)]] take your son, your only son,
        Isaac, whom I know you dearly love,  and go to the land of Moriah. <smallcaps>\u201D
        and comes from a root word meaning \u201Csight\u201D or \u201Cvision.\u201D
        Abraham was told to go to the mountain of Clear Vision. Moriah is inside
        the city walls of modern Jerusalem and is part of the historic site of the
        Temple Mount. The temple of the Lord will always be built at the place of
        sacrifice.</smallcaps> Offer him up to me as a burnt offering on one of the
        mountains which I will show you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 22:2
        content: "  \u201CPlease (Hb.  ) take your son.\u201D God\u2019s merciful,
          understanding heart is seen by the word \u201Cplease.\u201D      As every
          detail of God\u2019s instruction was revealed, Abraham\u2019s task became
          more and more challenging. Ishmael was his only son with Hagar, but when
          God spoke Isaac\u2019s name, Abraham\u2019s heart sank. Then, God added
          \u201Cwhom I know you dearly love.\u201D What a test this was of our father
          of faith, Abraham! Early Jewish tradition holds that Abraham concealed
          this encounter with God from Sarah so that she would not hinder him from
          doing as God commanded. See Josephus,    1.12.2.        means \u201Cchosen
          by      "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Early the next morning, Abraham cut the wood for the burnt offering,
        loaded it on his donkey, and set out for the distant place God had shown
        him. He took with him two of his servants, and his son Isaac.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'On the third day, [[COMMENT(0)]] Abraham looked up and saw the place
        in the distance. '
      comments:
      - number: 22:4
        content: "  So many wonderful things happen \u201Con the third day.\u201D
          See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . Keep in mind, a journey like this would have been difficult
          for an aged man. Think about what heart-breaking agony he must have endured
          for these three days. Truly, Abraham is \u201Cthe father of faith\u201D
          ().    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CStay here with the donkey,\u201D Abraham told the young men.
        \u201CIsaac [[COMMENT(0)]] and I will go up and worship;  then we  will return
        to you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 22:5
        content: "  Or \u201CThe boy,\u201D a noun that encompasses a wide age range
          from infancy to young adulthood. Scholars speculate Isaac\u2019s age at
          this time as around twenty; however, Josephus, the Jewish historian, has
          his age at twenty-five (  1.13.2), while others calculate he was thirty-seven.     
          This is the first use of the Hebrew word for worship () in the Bible. Abraham
          freely offered his beloved son to God and called it worship. True worship
          always involves a sacrifice. The first reference in the New Testament to
          worship is found with men bowing down before a child and offering sacrificial
          gifts to Jesus\u2014gold, frankincense, and myrrh. The biblical concept
          of worship includes freely bowing down before God, bringing our gifts (sacrifices
          of praise) to honor and adore him. The Hebrew language has meaning attached
          to every letter, not just every word. Often, the meaning of the word is
          the combination of the meaning of each individual letter. For example,
          the Hebrew word for \u201Cworship\u201D () means \u201Cto bow down in adoration.\u201D
          It\u2019s the combination of only three letters in Hebrew:  .    = \u201Cfiery
          passion.\u201D    = \u201Cjoining with God in a secret place or bridal
          chamber.\u201D    = \u201Cin the presence of God.\u201D Thus, worship could
          be defined as \u201Cexperiencing God\u2019s fiery passion as we come into
          his presence in the bridal chamber.\u201D See Scherman, Nosson/Zlotowitz,
          Meir, Rabbis: Wisdom in the Hebrew Alphabet, 1988, p. 88.      Notice the
          faith of Abraham. He knew that God, if he had to, would resurrect Isaac
          so that both Isaac and his father would return to where they left the servants.
          See  ;  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So Abraham took the wood for the burnt offering and placed it on
        Isaac\u2019s back. [[COMMENT(0)]] Abraham carried the knife and the fire, 
        and the two of them walked up the mountain together."
      comments:
      - number: 22:6
        content: "  Isaac carrying the wood foreshadowed Christ carrying his cross.
          See  ;  .      That is, a \u201Cfire [stone],\u201D most likely a flint
          rock to strike and build a fire.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CFather?\u201D Isaac broke the silence.\u201CYes, my son,\u201D
        Abraham replied.\u201CWe have the wood and the fire,\u201D Isaac said, \u201Cbut
        where is the lamb for the burnt offering?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Abraham answered, \u201CMy son, God himself will provide [[COMMENT(0)]]
        the lamb for an offering.\u201D So they went on together."
      comments:
      - number: 22:8
        content: "  Or \u201CGod will see for himself.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'When they arrived at the place on Mount Moriah that God had shown
        him, Abraham built an altar and stacked the wood on it. He tied up his son
        Isaac and laid him on top of the wood on the altar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then Abraham took the knife in his hand to plunge it into his son, '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "but the angel of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> called to him from
        heaven, saying, \u201CAbraham! Abraham!\u201D\u201CYes, I\u2019m here,\u201D
        he answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CDo not lay a hand on the boy or harm him,\u201D he said, \u201Cfor
        now, I know you are fully dedicated to me, [[COMMENT(0)]] since you did not
        withhold your son, your beloved son,  from me.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 22:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat you fear God.\u201D      As translated from the
          Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cyour only son.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "As Abraham looked up, his eyes fell upon a ram caught by its horns
        in a nearby thicket. Abraham took the ram and sacrificed it on the altar
        as a burnt offering in Isaac\u2019s place. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 22:13
        content: "  The ram caught in the thicket is a picture of Christ, who was
          \u201Ccaught in the thicket\u201D of our sins. Here we have the doctrine
          of substitution. Christ became our Substitute, just as the ram became a
          substitute for Isaac. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "So Abraham named that place <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> Appears.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps> Even to this day, it is said, \u201COn <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Mountain there is vision.\u201D <smallcaps>\u2019s mountain there is vision.\u201D
        On</smallcaps><smallcaps>\u2019s mountain (Golgotha) we see clearly the vision
        of God placing our sins upon his Son. Our salvation is already provided for
        us through the blood of Jesus\u2019 cross. Solomon\u2019s Temple was built
        on Moriah (see</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 22:14
        content: "  Or \u201CSees [to it]\u201D or \u201CProvides.\u201D However,
          the verb in the descriptive clause is pointed, or can be translated as
          a passive, reading \u201CAppears.\u201D Also, the Septuagint renders it
          \u201COn the mount the Lord appears.\u201D      Or \u201COn      ). This
          was also the site where David purchased Araunah\u2019s threshing floor
          (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s angel spoke a second time from
        heaven:"
      comments: []
    - name: '16-17: '
      title: 
      number: 16-17
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I solemnly promise you,by the glory of my own name,\u2019
        decrees <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,\u2018because you have obeyed my voiceand
        did not withhold from me your son\u2014your beloved son [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014I
        will greatly bless you!I will make sure your seed becomes as numerousas the
        stars of heaven and as the sand of the seashore.Your offspring will take
        possession of the city gates of their enemies. "
      comments:
      - number: "22:16\u201317"
        content: "  There is a hint in the test of Abraham offering his son that
          one day God would require a human sacrifice to take away the sins of the
          world. See  .      \u201CTak[ing] possession of the city gates of their
          enemies\u201D is a figurative expression that refers to conquering, defeating,
          and taking possession of the enemy\u2019s city. Here, it means simply that
          the seed of Abraham will have great authority to conquer cities.    "
    - name: '16-17: '
      title: 
      number: 16-17
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I solemnly promise you,by the glory of my own name,\u2019
        decrees <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,\u2018because you have obeyed my voiceand
        did not withhold from me your son\u2014your beloved son [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014I
        will greatly bless you!I will make sure your seed becomes as numerousas the
        stars of heaven and as the sand of the seashore.Your offspring will take
        possession of the city gates of their enemies. "
      comments:
      - number: "22:16\u201317"
        content: "  There is a hint in the test of Abraham offering his son that
          one day God would require a human sacrifice to take away the sins of the
          world. See  .      \u201CTak[ing] possession of the city gates of their
          enemies\u201D is a figurative expression that refers to conquering, defeating,
          and taking possession of the enemy\u2019s city. Here, it means simply that
          the seed of Abraham will have great authority to conquer cities.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Because you have obeyed me,the entire world will be blessed through
        your seed.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 22:18
        content: "  The \u201Cseed\u201D has his life, his life of faith.    "
    - name: '19: The Children of Nahor'
      title: The Children of Nahor
      number: 19
      content: So Abraham and Isaac returned to the waiting servants, and they departed
        for Beersheba, where Abraham had settled. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 22:19
        content: "  Behind the testing of Abraham lies the wisdom of God. Notice
          these four divine principles of God\u2019s tests: (1) When God tests us,
          his requirements of us often make no sense at the time. Therefore, faith
          is needed. Faith yields to God, even when it does not make sense. (2) Faith
          is never brought to maturity without a measure of suffering attached. Even
          Jesus was made perfect through sufferings (see  ;  ;  ). Faith will carry
          you through even the most severe trial. (3) We must obey the Holy Spirit
          even before we know all the details of what is involved. We must be willing
          to not know where God is taking us. Obedience is always one moment, one
          step at a time. (4) Others may not be permitted to know what God is doing
          with us. Abraham left the two servants behind, he left Sarah behind, and
          only he, Isaac, and God would see this test. Often, God will bring you
          to a lonely place where others cannot intrude; they wouldn\u2019t understand
          anyway!    "
    - name: '20-23: '
      title: 
      number: 20-23
      content: "Some time later Abraham heard the news, \u201CYou\u2019re an uncle!
        Milcah and your brother Nahor have eight sons: Uz, their firstborn, Buz [[COMMENT(0)]]
        his brother, Kemuel the father of Aram,  Chesed,  Hazo,  Phildash, Jidlaph,
        and Bethuel the father of Rebekah.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: "22:20\u201323"
        content: "    means \u201Ccontempt\u201D and is mentioned in  . Elihu, Job\u2019s
          fourth friend, was called a \u201CBuzite\u201D ().      Aram was the ancestor
          of the Syrians.        means \u201Cincrease\u201D and is thought to be
          the name from which his eponymous ancestors, the Chaldeans (Hb.  ), got
          their name.      The name    means \u201Cvision\u201D and was found in
          an ancient inscription. Hazo possibly represents the Hazu region in northern
          Arabia, known from the records of Esarhaddon\u2019s campaigns. Uz, Buz,
          and Hazo likely settled in the land north of Edom.      Rebekah was the
          wife-to-be of Isaac. Her name is derived from a Hebrew root meaning \u201Cto
          loop a cord over the head of a lamb or kid\u201D; thus, some etymologists
          define the meaning of her name as \u201Ccaptivating [beauty]\u201D or \u201Cbeauty
          that ensnares.\u201D    "
