    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Moreover, Nahor had another wife, [[COMMENT(0)]] Reumah, who also
        had four sons: Tebah, Gaham, Tahash, and Maacah.'
      comments:
      - number: 22:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cconcubine,\u201D a term referring to a wife with secondary
          status in the family. She may have been either taken as a captive in war
          or purchased. Wives taken as captives in war were given certain protection
          from exploitation (see  ). This list contains the names of twelve Aramaean
          tribes traced to Nahor, the same number associated with Ishmael (see  )
          and Jacob (see  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Death of Sarah'
      title: The Death of Sarah
      number: 1
      content: 'Sarah lived to be one hundred and twenty-seven. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 23:1
        content: "  This reference to Sarah is the only time that Scripture mentions
          a woman\u2019s age at death.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'She died in the land of Canaan at Kiriath Arba, [[COMMENT(0)]] now
        known as Hebron. There Abraham mourned and wept for her. '
      comments:
      - number: 23:2
        content: "    means \u201Cthe city of the four [giants].\u201D See  . Some
          Jewish scholars believe \u201Cthe city of the four\u201D refers to the
          four couples buried there: Adam and Eve, Abraham and Sarah, Isaac and Rebekah,
          Jacob and Leah. See also the first footnote on    on \u201CMachpelah.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'After his time of mourning was over, Abraham got up from where her
        body lay, and went to speak with the Hittites. He said to them, '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CI live as an alien and stranger among you. Sell me some of
        your property so I can use it as a burial site for my wife.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "\u201CHear us, my lord,\u201D the Hittites answered, \u201Cyou are
        a mighty prince of God  [[COMMENT(0)]] among us. You may bury your dead in
        the choicest of our tombs. None of us would withhold our burial ground from
        you.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "23:5\u20136"
        content: "  Or \u201Cking of God\u201D (LXX). The Hebrew reads \u201Ca mighty
          chief among us,\u201D with the generic term for \u201Cgod\u201D likely
          being used as the superlative for \u201Cmighty.\u201D    "
    - name: '5-6: '
      title: 
      number: 5-6
      content: "\u201CHear us, my lord,\u201D the Hittites answered, \u201Cyou are
        a mighty prince of God  [[COMMENT(0)]] among us. You may bury your dead in
        the choicest of our tombs. None of us would withhold our burial ground from
        you.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "23:5\u20136"
        content: "  Or \u201Cking of God\u201D (LXX). The Hebrew reads \u201Ca mighty
          chief among us,\u201D with the generic term for \u201Cgod\u201D likely
          being used as the superlative for \u201Cmighty.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then Abraham bowed respectfully before the Hittites, the people of
        the land '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "and he said to them, \u201CIf you are willing to allow my wife a
        proper burial, then please hear me out. On my behalf please persuade your
        countryman, Ephron the son of Zohar, "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "to sell me the cave he owns at Machpelah [[COMMENT(0)]] on the edge
        of his land. Let him sell it to me publicly  and at the full price, so that
        I may own it for a burial site.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 23:9
        content: "    means \u201Cdouble\u201D or \u201Cdoubling.\u201D Everyone
          buried in this cave would be as one of a couple: Abraham and Sarah, Isaac
          and Rebekah, Jacob and Leah (see  ;  ;  ;  ). Death for the patriarchs
          was a gateway into the resurrection. This cave was more like a bedroom
          to rest in than a tomb, more an altar than a grave. It was an altar to
          the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, who is not a God of the dead but
          of the living (see  ). According to Jewish tradition, Adam and Eve were
          also buried in this cave. See Jerusalem Talmud,    4:2; Babylonian Talmud,   
          53a;  , ch. 20; Midrash Rabba (), 28:3. According to the Midrash, the patriarchs
          were buried in this cave because this cave is the threshold to the garden
          of Eden. Some New Testament scholars believe that it could have been the
          patriarchs who were raised from the dead at the resurrection of Christ
          and were seen in Jerusalem. See  .      Or \u201Cin your presence\u201D
          or \u201Camong you.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Now Ephron the Hittite was sitting there among his countrymen. He
        spoke up so all the Hittites who sat at the gate as elders of the city [[COMMENT(0)]]
        could hear him, and said, '
      comments:
      - number: 23:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cwho came in at the gate of his city,\u201D a figure
          of speech for stating they had leadership in the city. See  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CNo, my lord, listen. I will give you not only the cave but
        also the entire field! In the presence of my people, I will give it to you
        to bury your dead.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Then Abraham bowed low before the people of the land, '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "and he said to Ephron in the hearing of all the people, \u201CNo,
        please listen, kind sir. I will pay whatever the field is worth. Take my
        money so that I can bury my dead there.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "\u201CIf you insist, my lord,\u201D answered Ephron. \u201CBut what
        is a piece of land worth only four hundred silver shekels to men of our standing?
        Go ahead and bury your dead.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '14-15: '
      title: 
      number: 14-15
      content: "\u201CIf you insist, my lord,\u201D answered Ephron. \u201CBut what
        is a piece of land worth only four hundred silver shekels to men of our standing?
        Go ahead and bury your dead.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So Abraham agreed to the amount, weighed out the four hundred silver
        shekels [[COMMENT(0)]] according to the merchant\u2019s standard of weight,
        and in the presence of the Hittites he gave the money to Ephron."
      comments:
      - number: 23:16
        content: '  The price was undoubtedly high. Jeremiah gave only seventeen
          shekels for land that was probably no less spacious than the field of Machpelah
          (see  ). Although difficult to estimate the cost, some have calculated
          four hundred shekels of silver to be approximately ten pounds of silver.  '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So Ephron\u2019s field of Machpelah, east of Mamre, along with the
        cave and all the trees within its borders, passed "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "to Abraham as his legal possession. The complete transaction was
        carried out in the presence of the Hittites\u2014those who sat as elders
        at the city gates. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'After this, Abraham buried his wife Sarah in the cave there in the
        field of Machpelah near Mamre (now Hebron) in the land of Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Both the field and the cave passed from the Hittites to Abraham\u2019s
        possession to be his family burial ground."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Abraham Seeks a Wife for Isaac'
      title: Abraham Seeks a Wife for Isaac
      number: 1
      content: 'Now, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had wonderfully blessed Abraham
        in every way, and he became a very old man, well advanced in years. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 24:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cgone in days,\u201D a figure of speech for saying Abraham
          was very old and had little time left. Perhaps the Hebrew phrase    is
          saying that Abraham \u201Clived every day to its fullest.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "One day, Abraham called for his trusted head servant, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who was in charge of all that he had, and said \u201CPlease, put your hand
        here under my thigh,   "
      comments:
      - number: 24:2
        content: "  Or \u201Coldest servant.\u201D Many scholars conclude this was
          Eliezer. See  . He becomes a type of the Holy Spirit, who finds and draws
          a bride for the Son of God by revealing him as Savior.      Abraham is
          euphemistically referring to his private parts, his \u201Cfamily jewels.\u201D
          The servant touching his private parts while making this oath was acknowledging
          that if he broke his solemn promise, Abraham\u2019s seed (offspring) had
          the right to avenge him of this sin. In Western society, we raise our right
          hand and swear, but in this episode, the servant put his hand on Abraham\u2019s
          reproductive power to give life.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'and I will make you swear by <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God
        of heaven and earth, that you will not acquire a wife for my son among the
        daughters of the Canaanites among whom I am living. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Promise me you will go instead to my relatives in my native land
        and find a wife among them for my son Isaac.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "The servant asked him, \u201CSuppose the woman is not willing to
        come back with me to this land. Should I then take your son back to your
        native land?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CAbsolutely not,\u201D Abraham answered, \u201Cmake sure that
        you do not take my son back there. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "For <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of heaven, took me from
        my father\u2019s house and from the land of my birth. He spoke to me and
        solemnly promised that he would give this land to my descendants. I know
        he will send his angel before you [[COMMENT(0)]] so that you can find a wife
        for my son from there. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:7
        content: "  That is, the angel of God would lead Abraham\u2019s servant to
          the right woman for his son. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "And if for any reason the woman is unwilling to come back with you,
        then you are released from this oath that you swear to me. But no matter
        what, do not take my son back there!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Woman at the Well'
      title: The Woman at the Well
      number: 9
      content: So, the servant put his hand under the thigh of his master Abraham
        and swore an oath to carry out his wishes. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 24:9
        content: "  We can see a picture here of the Father releasing the Holy Spirit
          to seek out a bride for his Son, Jesus Christ. It is the Father who brings
          the bride to Jesus as his love-gift to the Son (see  ). In picture form,
          the details of this chapter point us to the heavenly scene of gathering
          a bride for Jesus from the nations of the earth. The church is the bride,
          the Lamb\u2019s wife (see  ). His ministers are friends of the Bridegroom
          who are sent to awaken bridal love in the nations as they persuade souls
          to espouse their hearts to him (see  ;  ;  ). Only the trusted Servant,
          the Holy Spirit, is capable of drawing hearts to the Son, imparting endless
          love for him. Although unnamed here, the servant is elsewhere named Eliezer
          (see  ), which means \u201Cthe God of help\u201D or \u201Cthe God of comfort.\u201D
          Is not the Holy Spirit our Helper, our Comforter (see  )? He desires a
          willing bride for the heavenly \u201CIsaac.\u201D She will be willing to
          leave all to follow this Prince. She will be willing to follow the Holy
          Spirit as he leads her back to her Bridegroom.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So the servant took ten of his master\u2019s camels, loaded them
        with all sorts of gifts, some of the best things his master owned, and journeyed
        toward the distant land of Mesopotamia [[COMMENT(0)]] until he got to the
        village where Abraham\u2019s brother Nahor had lived.   "
      comments:
      - number: 24:10
        content: "  Or \u201CAram Naharaim,\u201D which means \u201Ctwo rivers\u201D
          and refers to the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers in modern Iraq.      From
          Canaan to Mesopotamia was a journey of at least five hundred miles (eight
          hundred kilometers).    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'He had his camels kneel by a well outside the village. It was evening,
        the time when the women came out to draw water. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "He prayed: \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, God of my master
        Abraham, let my journey here be a success and show your gracious love to
        my master Abraham. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'I am standing here by this well, and the young women of the village
        are coming out to draw water. Give me a sign. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "I will say to one of the girls, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u2018Please, lower
        your jar and give me a drink.\u2019 And if she is the right one, the girl
        whom you have chosen to be a wife for your servant Isaac, then let her say
        to me, \u2018Drink, and I will also draw water for your camels.\u2019 By
        this sign I will know that you have shown your gracious love to my master.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 24:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cvirgins\u201D (LXX).      Would the girl be willing
          to give ten thirsty camels water from the well? The woman\u2019s willingness
          to serve water showed that she had a true servant-spirit. What work to
          draw water for these thirsty camels! She had to lower her bucket down the
          well    times, for one camel can drink twenty gallons\u2014all for a stranger!
          It was evening, and it would have been dark after she was done. Only an
          exceptional woman would do something like this. She is a picture of the
          servant-bride of Jesus Christ.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Suddenly, before he had finished praying, there was Rebekah approaching
        the well with her jar on her shoulder. She was the daughter of Bethuel and
        the granddaughter of Milcah and Abraham\u2019s brother Nahor. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'The young woman was strikingly beautiful, unmarried, and still a
        virgin. She walked down to the well, filled her jar, and came back up. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Abraham\u2019s servant hurried over to meet her and said, \u201CPlease,
        lower your jar and give me a little drink.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "She responded, \u201CDrink, my lord.\u201D She then quickly lowered
        her jar to give him a drink. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then, after she had finished giving him a drink, she added, \u201CI
        will also draw water for your camels until they have finished drinking.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: She quickly emptied her jar into the watering trough and ran back
        to the well to draw more water, until she had watered all the camels. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 24:20
        content: "  This one act of service qualified Rebekah to be Isaac\u2019s
          bride and to be brought into the line of Christ and his inheritance. We
          often do not realize how one act of humble service will affect the world
          and bring promotion to our own life (see  ).    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Meanwhile, the servant stared at her, silently pondering whether
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> had indeed made his journey successful. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'After the camels had finished drinking, he took a costly gold nose
        ring weighing a half shekel [[COMMENT(0)]] and two solid gold bracelets weighing
        ten shekels,  and gave them to Rebekah. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:22
        content: "  That is, approximately \xBC ounce or 6 grams.      That is, approximately
          5 ounces or 110 grams.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then he asked her, \u201CTell me, who is your father? Is there room
        in your father\u2019s house for me and my men to stay tonight?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "She replied, \u201CMy father\u2019s name is Bethuel, and my grandparents
        are Milcah and Nahor.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 24:24
        content: "  Rebekah was Isaac\u2019s second cousin.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "She went on, \u201CThere is room for you to spend the night at our
        home, and plenty of straw and food for the camels.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Upon hearing this, the servant bowed down and worshiped <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, '
      comments: []
    - name: "27: Rebekah\u2019s Family Agrees to the Marriage Arrangement"
      title: "Rebekah\u2019s Family Agrees to the Marriage Arrangement"
      number: 27
      content: "saying, \u201CPraised be <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of
        Abraham, for you have faithfully kept your promise to my master and displayed
        your wonderful kindness and love. <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, you led
        me straight to the very place of my master\u2019s relatives!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Then the girl quickly ran [[COMMENT(0)]] to inform her mother and
        family about all that had happened. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:28
        content: '  What energy Rebekah had! After filling many buckets of water,
          she then ran home to tell her household what had taken place.    '
    - name: '29-30: '
      title: 
      number: 29-30
      content: "Now Rebekah had an older brother named Laban, [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        when he heard everything the man had told his sister and saw her gold nose
        ring and the costly bracelets dangling on her wrists, Laban ran out to meet
        the man waiting at the well\u2014and there he was standing beside his camels."
      comments:
      - number: "24:29\u201330"
        content: "  Rebekah\u2019s brother Laban saw her running home wearing gold
          jewelry and knew something good must have happened (see  ).    means \u201Cwhite.\u201D
          It is also used poetically for the moon. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '29-30: '
      title: 
      number: 29-30
      content: "Now Rebekah had an older brother named Laban, [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        when he heard everything the man had told his sister and saw her gold nose
        ring and the costly bracelets dangling on her wrists, Laban ran out to meet
        the man waiting at the well\u2014and there he was standing beside his camels."
      comments:
      - number: "24:29\u201330"
        content: "  Rebekah\u2019s brother Laban saw her running home wearing gold
          jewelry and knew something good must have happened (see  ).    means \u201Cwhite.\u201D
          It is also used poetically for the moon. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then Laban said to the man, \u201CFriend, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has wonderfully blessed you; please, come to my home. Why are you standing
        out here when I have prepared the house for you and a place for your camels?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "So the man came into the house, and his camels were unloaded and
        given straw and feed. The servants brought water to wash the man\u2019s feet
        and the feet of the men with him."
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "But when they set food before him, he said, \u201CI won\u2019t eat
        until I tell you why I\u2019m here.\u201D\u201CPlease, tell us,\u201D Laban
        said."
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CI am Abraham\u2019s servant,\u201D he began. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has wonderfully blessed my master,
        and he has become extremely wealthy. [[COMMENT(0)]]  <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has given him flocks and herds, camels and donkeys, a fortune in silver and
        gold, and many male and female servants. "
      comments:
      - number: 24:35
        content: "  Or \u201Cgreat\u201D or \u201Cpowerful.\u201D    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "And my master\u2019s wife, Sarah, has miraculously borne him a son
        in her old age, and my master\u2019s son is the sole heir of his fortune. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "My master has put me under an oath saying, \u2018Do not get a wife
        for my son from among the daughters of the Canaanites among whom I am living. "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Instead, go to my relatives in my native land and find a wife among
        them for my son.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "In reply I said to my master, \u2018Suppose the woman refuses to
        return with me.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "He answered me, \u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, in whose presence
        I have walked all these years, will send his angel with you and will make
        your mission successful. You will find a wife for my son from among my relatives,
        my father\u2019s family. "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "If you go to my relatives, and they will not give her to you, then
        and only then will you be released from this oath.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 24:41
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom my adjuration.\u201D The Hebrew implies that only
          if the girl\u2019s family refused to release her would the servant be absolved
          from the curse and penalty for breaking his oath.    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "So, when I arrived at the well today, I prayed, \u2018O&nbsp; <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        God of my master Abraham, make my mission a success. "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "I\u2019m here standing at this well. May the right girl for my master\u2019s
        son come out to draw water. And when she does, I will say to her \u201CPlease
        give me a little drink from your jar.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "And if she replies, saying, \u201CDrink, and I will also draw water
        for your camels,\u201D then I might know that she is the young woman <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has chosen for my master\u2019s son.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "\u201CBefore I had even finished my heartfelt prayer, there was Rebekah
        coming out with her water jar on her shoulder! After she went down to the
        well and filled her jar, I said to her, \u2018Please give me a drink.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "She quickly lowered her jar and said, \u2018Drink, and I will also
        draw water for your camels.\u2019 So, I drank, and she also watered the camels. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "Then I asked her, \u2018Tell me, who is your father?\u2019 She said,
        \u2018I\u2019m the daughter of Bethuel, son of Nahor, whom Milcah bore to
        him.\u2019 When I learned she was of my master\u2019s family, I put a gold
        ring in her nose and gold bracelets on her wrists, "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "and I bowed before <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> and worshiped him.
        I praised <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of my master Abraham, who
        led me perfectly on the right path to find the very daughter of my master\u2019s
        brother to marry his son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "Now, if you will show faithful love to my master and do what is right,
        then give me permission to take Rebekah back to his land. If not, tell me,
        and I will go on my way.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 24:49
        content: "  Or \u201CI will turn to the right or to the left,\u201D which
          suggests going elsewhere to look for a wife for his master\u2019s son.    "
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: "After hearing this, Laban and Bethuel said, \u201CThis was all planned
        by <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>! [[COMMENT(0)]] If this is his plan, what
        can we say?   "
      comments:
      - number: 24:50
        content: "  So many times we think the events of our life are happenstance,
          but they may be a \u201Cdivine setup\u201D to release the next phase of
          destiny in our lives.      Or \u201Cwe are not able to speak to you bad
          or good.\u201D It didn\u2019t matter to Laban and Bethuel what they could
          add, for they viewed all that happened as God\u2019s will.    "
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "Here stands our Rebekah before you. You may take her and go and let
        her marry your master\u2019s son and fulfill <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        plan for her.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "When Abraham\u2019s servant heard their words, he bowed his face
        down to the ground and worshiped <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: 'Then he brought expensive jewelry of silver and gold and exquisitely
        embroidered garments, and gave them all to Rebekah, and he gave costly gifts
        to her brother and her mother. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 24:53
        content: "  These \u201Ccostly gifts\u201D would likely serve as the bride
          price required by the culture of that day.    "
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: "Afterward, the servant and his men ate and drank, and they spent
        the night in Laban\u2019s home.First thing in the morning, he said to them,
        \u201CAllow me now to return to my master.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: "Her brother and mother replied, \u201CPlease let Rebekah remain with
        us a while\u2014for ten days or so, then she may go with you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: "He responded, \u201CPlease, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has made
        my mission successful. Send me off with her to my master, don\u2019t make
        me wait.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: "They answered him, \u201CWe will call for Rebekah and see what she
        wants to do.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '58: '
      title: 
      number: 58
      content: "So they called for Rebekah and asked her, \u201CWill you go with
        this man?\u201D\u201CI will gladly go with him,\u201D she answered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: "So they sent their sister Rebekah away with her servant girls to
        go with Abraham\u2019s servant and his men. "
      comments: []
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: "As she departed, they blessed her with these words:\u201COur dear
        sister,may you become thousands of ten thousands! [[COMMENT(0)]]May your
        descendants gain possessionof the city gates of their foes!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 24:60
        content: "  Or \u201Cmay you be [grow into] thousands of myriads!\u201D     
          Destiny hung over them that moment as the Spirit of Prophecy fell. The
          prophetic blessing was this: The seed (descendants) of Rebekah received
          the same blessing as the seed of Abraham: they would possess the city gates
          of their enemies. They would take cities! They would possess the places
          once held by God\u2019s enemies. This is a prophetic promise of a coming
          anointing that would reach cities. This city-reaching power comes when
          God\u2019s people walk with a heart like Rebekah. We must become Rebekah\u2019s
          spiritual seed, so that we may enter into the gate-taking anointing for
          our cities.    "
    - name: '61: Isaac Meets Rebekah'
      title: Isaac Meets Rebekah
      number: 61
      content: Then Rebekah and her servant girls mounted the camels and followed
        the servant and his men. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 24:61
        content: "  Their journey to Isaac\u2019s home would have lasted at least
          a month.    "
    - name: '62: '
      title: 
      number: 62
      content: 'Meanwhile, Isaac, who was living in the southern desert of Canaan,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] had just come back to his camp from the Well of the Living
        One Who Watches Over Me.   '
      comments:
      - number: 24:62
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe land of the Negev.\u201D      Or \u201CBeer-Lahai-Roi.\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '63: '
      title: 
      number: 63
      content: 'Isaac went out in the evening into the field to meditate. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He looked up, and saw camels coming in the distance. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:63
        content: "  Or possibly \u201Cto mourn [the loss of his mother].\u201D The
          Hebrew is uncertain. Some translations have \u201CIsaac went out into the
          field to take a walk.\u201D    "
    - name: '64: '
      title: 
      number: 64
      content: 'As Rebekah got closer, she raised her eyes, and when she saw Isaac,
        she nearly fell off her camel! [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 24:64
        content: "  The Hebrew phrase is literally \u201Cshe fell off her camel\u201D
          or \u201Cshe collapsed.\u201D One can imagine their eyes met, they locked
          eyes with each other, and something sparked between them. Some interpretations
          suggest that Isaac was simply glowing with God\u2019s light and shining
          with God\u2019s glory from spending time with God. Rashi (a well-known
          Torah commentator) writes about Rebekah and this initial meeting: \u201CShe
          saw his [Isaac\u2019s] majestic appearance, and she was astounded by him.\u201D    "
    - name: '65: '
      title: 
      number: 65
      content: "She whispered to the servant, \u201CWho is that man walking in the
        field toward us?\u201D\u201CWhy, he\u2019s the one about whom I told you,
        that\u2019s my young master!\u201D the servant said. So Rebekah quickly took
        her veil and covered her face. "
      comments: []
    - name: '66: '
      title: 
      number: 66
      content: 'Then the servant began to explain to Isaac in detail all the amazing
        things that had happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '67: '
      title: 
      number: 67
      content: "Isaac fell in love [[COMMENT(0)]] with Rebekah. He took her to be
        his wife, and they were married, and he brought her into his mother Sarah\u2019s
        tent.  In this way, Isaac was greatly comforted after his mother\u2019s death."
      comments:
      - number: 24:67
        content: "  Isaac\u2019s love for Rebekah is the second time in the Bible
          that love is mentioned between people. The first is Abraham\u2019s love
          for his son, Isaac. And now we have a man who loves his wife. This speaks
          of the two most loving bonds among humanity: the love of parents for their
          children and the love bond between husband and wife.      With Rebekah
          coming into Sarah\u2019s tent, we see the matriarchal continuity from Sarah
          to Rebekah, a fitting successor.  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Abraham and Keturah\u2019s Descendants"
      title: "Abraham and Keturah\u2019s Descendants"
      number: 1
      content: 'Now Abraham had taken another wife, whose name was Keturah. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 25:1
        content: "  It is not clear when Abraham took Keturah to be his wife. It
          is possible this happened after the death of Sarah. This would mean that
          he married her when he was more than one hundred and thirty-seven years
          old. (Sarah died at age one hundred and twenty-seven, and Abraham was ten
          years older than Sarah.) The six sons would have been born when Abraham
          was between the ages of one hundred and thirty-seven and one hundred and
          seventy-five. Another possibility is that Abraham had taken Keturah while
          Sarah was still living. The name Keturah may be a variant of a word referring
          to the smoke from a sacrifice or from incense (\u201Csweet smelling smoke\u201D
          or \u201Csweet incense\u201D). Jewish tradition states that Keturah was
          actually Hagar who returned from her exile and married Abraham, who changed
          her name to Keturah.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'She and Abraham had sons named Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak,
        and Shuah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Dedan\u2019s sons were the Ashurites, the Letushites, and the Leummites.
        Midian\u2019s sons were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, [[COMMENT(0)]] Abida, and Eldaah.
        All these were the descendants of Keturah. "
      comments:
      - number: 25:4
        content: "  Or \u201CEnoch.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Abraham gave all that he possessed to Isaac, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: The Death of Abraham'
      title: The Death of Abraham
      number: 6
      content: but to his sons by his concubines he gave gifts while he was still
        living. [[COMMENT(0)]] He sent them all away eastward, separating them from
        his son Isaac.
      comments:
      - number: 25:6
        content: '  These gifts may have included jewels, precious metals, animals,
          slaves, or combinations of these. It is unlikely that he gave them land,
          for he wanted these sons to have a legal settlement that would enable them
          to begin life on their own, away from Isaac.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Abraham lived a total of one hundred and seventy-five years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Abraham took his final breath, dying at a good old age. After having
        lived a full, content life, he joined his ancestors. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'His sons, Isaac and Ishmael, buried him in the cave of Machpelah,
        in the field which had belonged to Ephron, the son of Zohar the Hittite,
        east of Mamre. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'They buried him next to his wife Sarah, in the same field that Abraham
        purchased from the Hittites. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Descendants of Ishmael'
      title: The Descendants of Ishmael
      number: 11
      content: After Abraham had passed, God greatly blessed his son Isaac, and Isaac
        settled near the well named the Well of the Living One Who Watches Over Me.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 25:11
        content: "  Isaac was a man of the well (see  ). Isaac lived near Beer-Lahai-Roi,
          which means \u201CThe Well of the Living One Who Watches Over Me.\u201D
          This is where Hagar once cried out for deliverance and God heard her. In
          a time of desperation Ishmael drank from this well of grace. It is the
          place where God sees our problems and provides a well of mercy and satisfaction.
          Isaac did not visit there; he lived there, making the all-seeing God his
          source of supply. He saw a realm where the Living One sees all things.
          It was a well of perpetual revelation and grace.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "This is the account of the descendants of Abraham\u2019s son Ishmael,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] whom Sarah\u2019s servant, Hagar the Egyptian, bore to Abraham."
      comments:
      - number: 25:12
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "The names of Ishmael\u2019s sons in their birth order are: Nebaioth
        the firstborn; and Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Mishma, Dumah, Massa, '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'These twelve sons of Ishmael became princes [[COMMENT(0)]] of twelve
        tribes that were named after them, listed by the places they settled and
        camped. '
      comments:
      - number: 25:16
        content: "  Or \u201Ctribal chieftains.\u201D    "
    - name: '17-18: The Birth of Jacob and Esau'
      title: The Birth of Jacob and Esau
      number: 17-18
      content: They occupied the land from Havilah to Shur, which is east of Egypt,
        in the direction of Assyria. And Ishmael lived in hostility toward all of
        his people. At the age of one hundred and thirty-seven, Ishmael breathed
        his last and died [[COMMENT(0)]] and was joined to his ancestors.
      comments:
      - number: "25:17\u201318"
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cdied\u201D is  , the word commonly
          used for the death of a righteous person. The Semitic origin of the word   
          is \u201Cto hunger,\u201D \u201Cto be empty,\u201D or \u201Cto have a longing
          to be filled with something.\u201D The famed Jewish sage, Rashi, translated
          this as \u201CIshmael died [as a righteous man] still hungering for righteousness.\u201D    "
    - name: '17-18: The Birth of Jacob and Esau'
      title: The Birth of Jacob and Esau
      number: 17-18
      content: They occupied the land from Havilah to Shur, which is east of Egypt,
        in the direction of Assyria. And Ishmael lived in hostility toward all of
        his people. At the age of one hundred and thirty-seven, Ishmael breathed
        his last and died [[COMMENT(0)]] and was joined to his ancestors.
      comments:
      - number: "25:17\u201318"
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cdied\u201D is  , the word commonly
          used for the death of a righteous person. The Semitic origin of the word   
          is \u201Cto hunger,\u201D \u201Cto be empty,\u201D or \u201Cto have a longing
          to be filled with something.\u201D The famed Jewish sage, Rashi, translated
          this as \u201CIshmael died [as a righteous man] still hungering for righteousness.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "This is how the story of Isaac begins. He was the beloved son of
        Abraham [[COMMENT(0)]]  and the successor of Abraham\u2019s blessing."
      comments:
      - number: 25:19
        content: "  Or \u201CAbraham became the father of Isaac.\u201D The redundancy
          of Abraham in this verse is a literary device for showing the promise given
          to Abraham was passed on to his son.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'When he was forty, he married Rebekah. She was the daughter of Bethuel
        and the sister of Laban. Both her father and brother were Arameans from Paddan-Aram.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 25:20
        content: "  Paddan-Aram is also called \u201CAram Naharaim,\u201D which means
          \u201CAram of the two rivers\u201D (see  ). It is another name for Mesopotamia,
          the area between the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers in modern Iraq.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Now, Rebekah was unable to have children, but Isaac pleaded with
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> on behalf of his wife because she was barren\u2014and
        she did get pregnant, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> responded to Isaac\u2019s
        prayer. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 25:21
        content: '  During their twenty-year wait for children, there is no mention
          that Isaac fathered children with his handmaiden, as his father Abraham
          did. Isaac loved Rebekah and was patient and prayerful until the miracle
          happened.    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "During her pregnancy, Rebekah could feel twins thrashing and struggling
        [[COMMENT(0)]] with each other inside her womb. So she went to inquire of
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, saying, \u201CWhy do I have to live with this?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 25:22
        content: "  The Hebrew is literally \u201Cthey crushed each other.\u201D
          It was an intense struggle going on inside of Rebekah.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> answered her, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying,\u201CThe
        two sons in your womb will become two nations,and the two peoples within
        you will become rivals. One people will become stronger than the other,and
        the older will serve the younger.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 25:23
        content: "  We do not know how God answered her. It could have been by an
          audible voice or in a dream.      Or \u201Cdivided,\u201D a Hebrew word
          used for a river dividing into branches (see  ).    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'And when the time came for Rebekah to give birth, sure enough, she
        had twins! '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The first one came out reddish and covered with hair like a hairy
        garment; [[COMMENT(0)]] so they named him Esau.   '
      comments:
      - number: 25:25
        content: "  Or \u201Ca mantle.\u201D        is a wordplay on the Hebrew word   
          meaning \u201Chairy.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: Esau Sells His Birthright'
      title: Esau Sells His Birthright
      number: 26
      content: "And his brother came out with his hand grasping Esau\u2019s heel;
        so, they named him Jacob. [[COMMENT(0)]] Isaac was sixty when the twins were
        born. "
      comments:
      - number: 25:26
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201CJacob\u201D sounds like the words for
          \u201Cheel\u201D and \u201Ccheat\u201D (see  ).    can be translated \u201Cheel
          grabber\u201D or \u201Csupplanter.\u201D Even in the womb, Jacob was jostling
          for the right of the firstborn.      Isaac waited twenty years for God
          to fulfill the promise of a child. God\u2019s promises are worth waiting
          for.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When the boys grew up, Esau became a rugged outdoorsman and a hardy
        hunter, but Jacob was more contemplative, [[COMMENT(0)]] content to stay
        close to home. '
      comments:
      - number: 25:27
        content: "  Although the Hebrew word    can mean \u201Cblameless\u201D (see 
          ), it is better translated \u201Cmeditative,\u201D \u201Ctranquil,\u201D
          \u201Cquiet,\u201D or \u201Ccontemplative.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: Isaac loved Esau because he was fond of eating wild game, but Rebekah
        dearly loved Jacob.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'One day, when Jacob was cooking a stew, [[COMMENT(0)]] Esau returned
        from hunting,  and he was famished. '
      comments:
      - number: 25:29
        content: "  Jewish sages state that Abraham, Jacob and Esau\u2019s grandfather,
          had just died, and the stew Jacob was cooking was fulfilling a cultural
          obligation to cook and was related to the prescribed season of mourning.
          See    16b.      Or \u201Cfrom the field.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Smelling the aroma of food, Esau said to Jacob, \u201CI\u2019m starving!
        Let me eat some of that red stuff you\u2019re cooking.\u201D (This is why
        he is also called Edom.) [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 25:30
        content: "    sounds like the Hebrew word for \u201Cred.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CYes, but first you must trade me your birthright,\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Jacob replied."
      comments:
      - number: 25:31
        content: "  The birthright refers to the right of the firstborn to inherit
          from the father a double portion\u2014twice as much as the younger siblings
          inherit. Jacob now rightfully possessed the rights and blessings of the
          firstborn, which included authority, headship, a double portion of the
          inheritance, and the right to be the priest of the family. God identifies
          himself as the \u201CGod of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob\u201D (). The God
          of Abraham is God of Promises Fulfilled. The God of Isaac is the God of
          Inheritance and Miracles. The God of Jacob is the God of Transformation,
          for Jacob would become Israel, a prince with God. God gives us the promise,
          but the promise requires a miracle to perform it. This miracle-promise
          releases true transformation within the heart of man. This is the revelation
          of the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CCan\u2019t you see I\u2019m dying of hunger?\u201D Esau said.
        \u201CWhat good is the birthright if I\u2019m dead?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "But Jacob insisted, \u201CFirst, swear to me that you\u2019ll give
        it to me.\u201D So, Esau swore an oath and surrendered his birthright to
        Jacob."
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: Then Jacob gave Esau some lentil stew and bread. When Esau had finished
        eating and drinking, he just got up and walked away. Esau cared nothing about
        his own birthright. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 25:34
        content: '  See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Adventures of Isaac in Gerar'
      title: The Adventures of Isaac in Gerar
      number: 1
      content: "Now, another famine struck the land, like the one in Abraham\u2019s
        time. Isaac traveled to Gerar [[COMMENT(0)]] where Abimelech was the Philistine
        king. "
      comments:
      - number: 26:1
        content: "    means \u201Clodging place\u201D and was directly on the route
          to Egypt. Isaac and Rebekah were apparently on their way down to Egypt.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> appeared before Isaac and said, \u201CDo
        not go down to Egypt. Stay in the land that I will reveal to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Live there as a foreigner, and my presence will be with you. I promise
        to bless you, [[COMMENT(0)]] for I will give all these lands to you and your
        descendants. I will fulfill the oath I swore to your father Abraham. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:3
        content: '  God blessed Isaac even in a time of famine. See vv.  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I will make your descendants as numerous as the stars of heaven,
        and I will one day give them all these lands. I will bless all the nations
        of the earth through your offspring '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "because Abraham was faithful to me. He listened to my voice and yielded
        his heart to follow my direction. He kept my commandments, my instructions,
        and my teachings.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s voice and followed
        his revelation in all its forms.</smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 26:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cmy laws.\u201D The laws of Moses for Israel had not
          yet been given. Abraham had no Bible; therefore, he depended on hearing   
          commends Abraham for his faithfulness. The Hebrew word for \u201Cteachings\u201D
          is a plural form of  . Many years later,  revealed the Torah to Moses,
          who set it down in the books we know as Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers,
          and Deuteronomy (see  ). The universe of meaning for the Hebrew word   
          includes direction, instruction, rules, etc.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So Isaac settled in Gerar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The men of the land noticed Rebekah\u2019s beauty and asked Isaac
        about her. \u201COh, she\u2019s just my sister,\u201D he replied. Rebekah
        was indeed very beautiful, and he was afraid to tell them, \u201CShe\u2019s
        my wife,\u201D for he thought that the men of the land would kill him and
        take his wife."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'One day, after Isaac had lived there awhile, the Philistine king
        Abimelech looked out his window and saw Isaac affectionately caressing [[COMMENT(0)]]
        his wife Rebekah. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cfondling.\u201D Perhaps we would say, \u201CThey were
          making out.\u201D This Hebrew word in its consonantal form is a play on
          words with the name Isaac.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "So Abimelech summoned Isaac and said, \u201CSo, this woman is your
        wife! Why did you say that she was your sister?\u201D\u201CBecause I thought
        the men of the land would kill me and take her,\u201D Isaac said."
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t you realize what you\u2019ve done to us?\u201D Abimelech
        asked. \u201COne of our men might have slept with your wife, and you would
        have brought guilt and punishment upon us!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Isaac Becomes Very Wealthy'
      title: Isaac Becomes Very Wealthy
      number: 11
      content: "So Abimelech issued a stern warning to all the people, saying, \u201CWhoever
        lays a hand on this man or his wife shall be put to death!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Isaac planted crops in that land, and in the same year [[COMMENT(0)]]
        reaped a hundred-fold harvest, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> greatly
        blessed him!   '
      comments:
      - number: 26:12
        content: "  Isaac did not hoard his seed in a time of famine but sowed it
          in the enemy\u2019s land and reaped great blessing. See  .      God transformed
          a land of famine into a land of abundant harvest. If you sow your seed
          in the day of famine, watch God multiply it into an abundant harvest. See 
          ;  .    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Isaac grew richer and richer [[COMMENT(0)]] until he was extremely
        wealthy. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cgreater and greater.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'He acquired so many flocks and herds and so many servants that the
        Philistines grew jealous, '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "so the Philistines stopped up all of Isaac\u2019s wells and filled
        them with dirt\u2014the same wells his father\u2019s servants had dug in
        the time of Abraham. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:15
        content: '  In the culture of the day, to dig a well on unclaimed land was
          a proof of title to the land. To stop the wells of someone else was considered
          an act of war. Isaac refused to war against the people and chose instead
          to move away.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Eventually Abimelech\u2019s jealousy got the better of him, and he
        said to Isaac, \u201CYou must leave us! You have become too rich and powerful
        for us!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: Isaac Digs New Wells'
      title: Isaac Digs New Wells
      number: 17
      content: "So Isaac departed from Abimelech\u2019s domain and camped near the
        Wadi of Gerar, where he settled."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Isaac reopened and restored the wells his father Abraham had originally
        dug\u2014the wells the Philistines had stopped up after Abraham\u2019s death.
        And Isaac gave these wells the same names that his father had given them."
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "One day, when Isaac\u2019s servants dug in the valley, they uncovered
        a spring-fed well. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cliving water,\u201D that is, an unfailing spring of
          water flowing beneath the surface. Isaac not only reopened ancient wells
          but also went on to open his own. God\u2019s spiritual \u201CIsaacs\u201D
          will always be those who not only respect the wisdom of the elders but
          also go on to dig their own wells.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "But the herdsmen of Gerar picked a fight [[COMMENT(0)]] with Isaac\u2019s
        herdsmen, saying, \u201CThat\u2019s our well!\u201D So Isaac named the well
        Argument  because of the sharp contention. "
      comments:
      - number: 26:20
        content: "  There is an implication of physical violence over the well, for
          the same Hebrew word is found in    concerning a fistfight.      Or \u201CEsek,\u201D
          which means \u201Ccontention,\u201D \u201Cdispute,\u201D \u201Cquarrel,\u201D
          or \u201Cargument.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'They dug a second well, and it also caused a quarrel, so Isaac named
        that well Hostility. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 26:21
        content: "  Or \u201CSitnah,\u201D which means \u201Caccusation,\u201D \u201Chostility,\u201D
          or \u201Cenmity.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then he pulled up stakes from there and dug a third well, but this
        one was dug without any quarreling, so Isaac named it Spacious, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        saying, \u201CFinally, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has made ample room
        for us and we will become prosperous  in the land!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 26:22
        content: "  Or \u201CRehoboth,\u201D which means \u201Cbroad places,\u201D
          \u201Croom [roomy],\u201D or \u201Cspacious places.\u201D This place was
          later known as Wadi Ruhebe and is located about twenty miles (thirty kilometers)
          southwest of Beersheba.      Or \u201Cfruitful.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'From there, Isaac moved his camp to Beersheba. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "That very night, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> appeared before him
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and said:\u201CI am the God of Abraham your father.You will
        never need to fear a thing for I am with youand I will greatly bless you.Your
        children will flourish and succeedbecause of the promises I gave my servant
        Abraham.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 26:24
        content: '  In Beersheba, God dug a well in Isaac. The strife with others
          had taken its toll on Isaac, leaving him hungry for a fresh encounter with
          God. When others were jealous, continually harassing him, faithful Isaac
          was visited by God.    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'So Isaac built an altar, [[COMMENT(0)]] prayed, and worshiped <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        there. He pitched his tent there, and his servants started digging another
        well. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:25
        content: "  That Isaac built an altar implies that he offered sacrifices
          upon this altar, remembering the altar he once was placed upon by his father
          (see  ).      The altar, the tent, and the well\u2014each one points to
          an aspect of the lives of the patriarchs: the altar of worship, the tent
          of temporary sojourn, and the deep well of satisfaction in God.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'Then King Abimelech came to Isaac from Gerar with his adviser [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Ahuzzath and his army commander Phicol. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:26
        content: "  Although the Hebrew word can be translated \u201Cfriend,\u201D
          Ahuzzah was a counselor who had the ear of the king. The names Abimelech
          and Abraham are both found seven times in this chapter.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Isaac asked them, \u201CWhy have you come to me now, since you hated
        me and sent me away?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "They answered, \u201CWe have witnessed firsthand how powerfully 
        <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s favor has been with you, so we say,
        let there be a peace treaty among us. Let us make a covenant "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "to do each other no harm. Swear to us that you will not trouble us,
        just as we have not troubled you and have always treated you well and sent
        you away in peace. Now look at how <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has blessed
        you!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'So Isaac prepared a wonderful feast for them, and they all ate and
        drank together. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: Then the next morning, they got up early and exchanged oaths. Isaac
        said goodbye to them, and they left Isaac in peace.
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Later that same day, Isaac\u2019s servants came with wonderful news
        about the well they had dug, saying, \u201CWe\u2019ve just found water!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:32
        content: '  truly smiled on what Isaac had done in forgiving and feeding
          his enemies, for on the same day he made this covenant with Abimelech,
          his servants brought him the news of a fresh well of water they found.
          Since Isaac had remained silent over the offense of losing wells, God honored
          him with a new one.    '
    - name: '33: The Hittite Wives of Esau'
      title: The Hittite Wives of Esau
      number: 33
      content: So he named it Oath. [[COMMENT(0)]] This is why the city where they
        dug the well is called Beersheba  to this day.
      comments:
      - number: 26:33
        content: "  Or \u201CShibah,\u201D which means \u201Coath\u201D or \u201Cseven.\u201D
          The triliteral Hebrew root can also be interpreted as \u201Cabundance\u201D
          and is translated in this way by Syriac, Vulgate, Aquila, and Symmachus.
          The preferred translation is \u201Coath\u201D (LXX) or \u201Cvow.\u201D     
          Or \u201CWell of the Oath.\u201D Isaac\u2019s name is associated with wells
          seven times in Genesis.    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'When Esau was forty, he married two Hittite women, Judith [[COMMENT(0)]]
        the daughter of Beeri  and Basemath  the daughter of Elon. '
      comments:
      - number: 26:34
        content: "    means \u201Cpraised.\u201D        means \u201Cmy well.\u201D       
          means \u201Cfragrance\u201D or \u201Cspice.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: They made life miserable for Isaac and Rebekah. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 26:35
        content: "  Isaac failed to deal with Esau concerning his Hittite wives.
          Remember how much care Abraham gave to finding a wife for Isaac (see  )?
          Why didn\u2019t Isaac now give great attention to finding the proper wife
          for his son? The Targums say that Esau and his wives rebelled against Isaac
          and Rebekah\u2019s instruction.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jacob Defrauds Esau'
      title: Jacob Defrauds Esau
      number: 1
      content: "When Isaac was very old and blind, he called for his oldest son,
        Esau, and asked him, \u201CMy son?\u201D\u201CI am here, father,\u201D Esau
        answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CAs you can see, I am now an old man,\u201D Isaac said. \u201CAnd
        I may die any day now. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "So please take your hunting gear\u2014your bow and arrows\u2014and
        go out into the field and hunt some wild game for me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then prepare me a savory meal, the food I love, and bring it to me.
        After I eat it, I will bless you from my innermost being before I die.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:4
        content: "  Or \u201CAfter I eat, my soul will bless you before I die.\u201D
          The repeated mention of this meal (vv.  ,  ,  ,  ) implies that it was
          a ceremonial meal closely connected with the act of blessing.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Now, Rebekah was eavesdropping on their conversation. So, when Esau
        left for the field to hunt for game to cook for Isaac, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "she found Jacob and said to him, \u201CI just overheard your father
        say to your brother Esau, "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u2018Bring me some wild game and prepare a savory meal for me. Afterward
        I will bless you in the presence of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> before
        I die.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Listen carefully, my son, and do everything I tell you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Go out to the flock and bring me two of the best young goats. I\u2019ll
        cook them for your father and prepare a delicious meal, the way he loves
        it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then, you take it to him to eat and your father will bless you before
        he dies.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u2019s promise of the older son
        serving the younger. She could not stand to see Esau, who had broken her
        heart by taking foreign wives (see</smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: 27:10
        content: "  Rebekah thought she was pursuing the best course, for she remembered   
          ), receive Isaac\u2019s blessing. This entire episode attests to the conniving
          nature of man and the overriding purposes of God that cannot be thwarted
          by our sin.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Jacob objected, \u201CBut my brother Esau is covered with hair, and
        I\u2019m smooth skinned. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "If my father feels my hairless skin, he\u2019ll know I\u2019m not
        Esau. He\u2019ll think I\u2019m a trickster, and I\u2019ll end up bringing
        a curse upon myself rather than a blessing!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CMy son,\u201D his mother said, \u201Clet any curse against
        you fall on me alone! Just do what I say and go and get the goats for me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So he went and got the goats and brought them to his mother. She
        prepared a delicious meal, just the way his father loved it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then Rebekah picked out the best clothes [[COMMENT(0)]] of her older
        son Esau and put them on her younger son Jacob.   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:15
        content: "  These were probably Esau\u2019s dress-up clothes reserved for
          celebrating feasts or ceremonial occasions. The Hebrew word for \u201Cclothes\u201D
          is  , which can also be translated \u201Ctreachery\u201D or \u201Cdeceit.\u201D
          This is a play on words, for Jacob used Esau\u2019s clothes to deceive.
          The Midrash Rabbah teaches that Esau ambushed Nimrod in the field, killed
          him, and took his garments. Jacob wore Nimrod\u2019s garments and deceived
          his father. According to the apocryphal Book of Jasher, the clothing that
          God robed Adam with was passed down to Noah, who gave it to his son Ham,
          and was eventually acquired by Nimrod.      Jacob was about to pull the
          wool over his father\u2019s eyes. Jacob would do anything just to get his
          father\u2019s blessing!    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "She covered Jacob\u2019s hands and the soft part of his neck with
        goatskins. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then she handed Jacob the tasty dish and the bread that she had prepared '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "and he took them to Isaac.\u201CFather?\u201D Jacob said.Isaac replied,
        \u201CWhich one of my sons are you?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Jacob answered, \u201CIt\u2019s I\u2014Esau\u2014your firstborn.
        I have done as you asked. Please, sit up. Eat some of this delicious game
        you love so that you may give me your innermost blessing.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cso that your soul may bless me.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Isaac asked his son, \u201CHow in the world did you find game so
        quickly, my son?\u201D\u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, your God, caused
        it to come right to me,\u201D he replied."
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Isaac said to Jacob, \u201CPlease, please, come closer that
        I may touch you, my son. I need to really know for certain that you are Esau.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "So Jacob inched closer to his father Isaac, who felt his skin and
        said, \u201CYou sound like Jacob, but your hands are Esau\u2019s.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Because his hands were hairy like his brother Esau\u2019s, Isaac
        was tricked and did not recognize that it was really Jacob. As he was about
        to give him his blessing, "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Isaac asked him again, \u201CAre you really my son Esau?\u201DJacob
        answered, \u201CI am.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CThen bring the food to me,\u201D Isaac said, \u201Cand let
        me eat my son\u2019s game. Then I will give you my blessing.\u201D So, Jacob
        gave his father the food and he ate it. He brought him wine and he drank
        it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then Isaac said to him, \u201CMy son, come near and kiss me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "So he came near and kissed him. Isaac recognized the smell of his
        son\u2019s clothes and blessed him, saying,\u201CAh, the smell of my sonis
        like the smell of a lush field that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has blessed!"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "May God give you heaven\u2019s dew, [[COMMENT(0)]]the fatness of
        earth, and an abundance of grain and new wine!"
      comments:
      - number: 27:28
        content: "  Dew is a frequent biblical metaphor for God\u2019s anointing,
          favor, abundance, revelation-truth, renewal, and unity. In  , Gideon\u2019s
          fleece, saturated with dew, was a sign to him that God was with him. He
          wrung out a bowl full of dew. We are bowls, vessels of honor, full of heaven\u2019s
          dew. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .      The fatness of the earth means not only its
          finest produce (grain and wine) but also abundant prosperity. The earth\u2019s
          finest blessings were promised to Jacob and his seed.    "
    - name: "29: Esau\u2019s Lost Blessing"
      title: "Esau\u2019s Lost Blessing"
      number: 29
      content: "Let peoples serve youand nations bow down to you!May you be master
        [[COMMENT(0)]] over your brothersand may your mother\u2019s sons bow down
        to you!Those who curse you will be cursedand those who bless you will be
        blessed!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 27:29
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cmaster\u201D is  , used for the first
          time in Genesis here. The word is closely related to  , which means \u201Cstrong,\u201D
          \u201Cmighty,\u201D \u201Cvaliant,\u201D or \u201Cone who does acts of
          bravery.\u201D      The Hall of Faith (see  ) reveals a remarkable insight
          into this account. God commended Isaac in  , saying, \u201CThe power of
          faith prompted Isaac to impart a blessing to his sons, Jacob and Esau,
          concerning their prophetic destinies.\u201D At first glance, it does not
          appear to be an act of faith but rather a blunder for Isaac to bless Jacob
          instead of Esau. But God called it faith. All of this was contrary to Isaac\u2019s
          natural inclination. Instead of doubt or unbelief, he acted by faith. It
          is the nature of faith to give priority to God\u2019s will rather than
          our own. This is what Abraham had to do in giving up his son Isaac. Now
          Isaac had to give up Esau and his opinion of how God was to accomplish
          his purposes.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'No sooner had Jacob left from receiving the blessing of his father
        Isaac, than his brother Esau arrived home from hunting. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He too prepared a savory meal for his father and took it to him.
        He said to Isaac, \u201CSit up my father; eat some of your son\u2019s wild
        game so that you can give me your innermost blessing.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:31
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat your soul may bless me.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "His father Isaac asked him, \u201CWho are you?\u201D\u201CI\u2019m
        Esau, your firstborn son,\u201D he answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "When Isaac realized what had happened, he began to tremble and shake
        violently. He asked, \u201CWho was it then that hunted wild game and brought
        it to me? I\u2019ve already eaten it all before you came, and I gave him
        the blessing\u2014yes, and he will be blessed indeed!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "When Esau heard his father\u2019s words, he burst into bitter weeping
        and uncontrollable sobbing. He said to his father, \u201CBless me! Bless
        me too, father!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Isaac answered, \u201CYour brother was here and deceived me. He has
        taken away your blessing.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Esau exclaimed, \u201CJacob, that heel grabber  [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014the
        name fits him perfectly! Now he has tricked me twice! He stole my birthright,
        and now he\u2019s robbed me of my blessing!\u201D Then he asked, \u201CFather,
        haven\u2019t you reserved a blessing for me?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 27:36
        content: "  Jacob\u2019s name comes from the Hebrew word for \u201Cheel\u201D
          and can be translated \u201Ctrickster,\u201D \u201Cheel grabber,\u201D
          or \u201Ccheater.\u201D    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Isaac replied, \u201CYou don\u2019t understand. My blessing will
        empower him to be master over you. [[COMMENT(0)]] I have already given him
        all his brothers and relatives as servants. My blessing will richly provide
        him with grain and new wine. What more is left for me to do for you, my son?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 27:37
        content: "  This demonstrates the power of a father\u2019s prophetic blessing.
          It can shape the futures of his children. The words we speak over our children
          can make them or mar them. Be sure to speak life and blessing over your
          children!    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Esau pleaded with his father, \u201CIs that the only blessing you
        have to give? Bless me too, my father!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] Esau could not
        hold back his tears and he wept loudly. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:38
        content: "  The Septuagint adds, \u201CBut Isaac remained silent.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Then Isaac his father spoke these words:\u201CYou will live far from
        earth\u2019s bountyand far from heaven\u2019s dew on high."
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "You will live by the sword and serve your brother;but when you grow
        restless,you will break free from his control.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:40
        content: "  Esau would be given all the provisions he would need in life.
          Notice that Isaac reverses the order of the blessing. The fatness of the
          earth was given first because Esau would be a man with his heart attached
          to the world. He would live by the sword-principle, always retaliating
          and unable to forgive. How many believers today have enough of God to get
          by but live with unresolved anger and unforgiveness like Esau? Hebrews
          describes Esau as careless about God\u2019s blessing (see  ). The descendants
          of Esau were known as Edomites. They were a violent people who raided caravans
          and pillaged cities. During David\u2019s reign, the united monarchy dominated
          the Edomites, but they later revolted under the reign of Jehoram (849\u2013842
          BC).    "
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "Esau hated Jacob because he stole his blessing. He said to himself,
        \u201CIn a short time my father will be gone. After the time for mourning
        his death has passed, I will kill my brother Jacob!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:41
        content: "  Isaac sealed Jacob\u2019s blessing with a kiss but not Esau\u2019s.
          All of this caused Esau to hate his brother. Following in the way of Cain,
          Esau made an inner vow to murder his brother as soon as his father died.
          His jealousy turned to hatred and hatred to murder, all because his younger
          brother received a blessing that he did not.    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "But when Rebekah found out about her older son Esau\u2019s plan,
        she quickly sent for her younger son Jacob, [[COMMENT(0)]] and said to him,
        \u201CListen, your brother Esau is planning to exact revenge by killing you.   "
      comments:
      - number: 27:42
        content: "  Jacob may have been in hiding for fear of Esau.      Or \u201Cis
          consoling himself [over what you did to him] by planning to kill you.\u201D    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'My son, you must do what I say. Run away at once to my brother Laban
        in Haran. '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'You can live with him for a while until your brother calms down. '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "After your brother\u2019s anger has died down and he has forgotten
        what you\u2019ve done to him, I will send a messenger to bring you back from
        there. Why should I lose both my sons in one day?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:45
        content: '  This would be the last time Rebekah saw her son before she died.  '
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Later, Rebekah said to Isaac, \u201CI\u2019m so disgusted with our
        Hittite daughters-in-law. I\u2019d rather die than see Jacob marry one of
        these local girls\u2014these Hittite women!\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jacob Flees to Laban'
      title: Jacob Flees to Laban
      number: 1
      content: "Before Jacob left, Isaac called for him, blessed him, and gave him
        these instructions: \u201CI forbid you to marry any Canaanite woman. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Leave at once for the land of your grandfather Bethuel in Paddan-Aram
        and find one of the young women there to marry, one of your uncle Laban\u2019s
        daughters. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 28:2
        content: '  Marriage with a cousin was acceptable in that day and continues
          to be common among people in the Near East today.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'May the God who is always more than enough [[COMMENT(0)]] bless you
        abundantly. May he make you fruitful and multiply your descendants until
        you become many tribes! '
      comments:
      - number: 28:3
        content: "  Or \u201CEl Shaddai.\u201D See second footnote on  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "May he impart to you and your seed the blessing of Abraham so that
        you may possess the land where you now live as a foreigner\u2014the land
        God gave to Abraham.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: Esau Takes Another Wife'
      title: Esau Takes Another Wife
      number: 5
      content: "Then Isaac sent Jacob on his way [[COMMENT(0)]] to Paddan-Aram, the
        land of his grandfather Bethuel the Aramean, to the home of Laban, Bethuel\u2019s
        son and the brother of Rebekah, the mother of Jacob and Esau."
      comments:
      - number: 28:5
        content: '  Jacob was in his seventies when he fled from his brother Esau,
          and the journey was about five hundred miles.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Esau had learned that Isaac had blessed Jacob and had sent him away
        to Paddan-Aram to find a wife there, and that while blessing him, Isaac had
        instructed him, \u201CDon\u2019t marry a Canaanite woman.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Furthermore, Esau found out that Jacob had obeyed his parents and
        fled to Paddan-Aram. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Esau, knowing that his father Isaac disapproved of Canaanite women, '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Stairway of Eternity'
      title: The Stairway of Eternity
      number: 9
      content: "went to Ishmael\u2019s clan and chose a woman named Mahalath to be
        one of his wives. She was the daughter of Ishmael, Abraham\u2019s son, and
        sister of Nebaioth. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 28:9
        content: '  Nebaioth was the firstborn of Ishmael (see  ) and is identified
          with Nabaiti, the possible ancestor of the later Nabateans.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Jacob left Beersheba and journeyed toward Haran. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'He encountered a certain place [[COMMENT(0)]] at sunset and camped
        there for the night. He took a stone  from there, made it his pillow, and
        lay down to sleep. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:11
        content: "  In the twilight, Jacob set up camp at Bethel. The Hebrew implies
          that it is \u201Cthe Place,\u201D a special place, or holy place. Indeed,
          it was, for God had also manifested himself there to Abraham (see  ). In
          Jacob\u2019s helpless, lonely condition, a new revelation would be given
          to him.      Perhaps this was one of the stones of the altar erected by
          Jacob\u2019s grandfather, Abraham. Jesus is the anointed Stone on whom
          we lay our heads. To lay your head (thoughts and dreams) on him is to discover
          the beauty of God (see  ). When the anointing of Jesus fills our heads
          (minds), we will see heaven opened with fresh revelation and perceive the
          visions of God. Jesus is the Chief Cornerstone, the Stone that killed Goliath,
          and the Stone of Daniel that conquers kingdoms (see  ,  ).    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'He had a dream [[COMMENT(0)]] of a stairway securely fixed on the
        earth and reaching into heaven. And there were messengers of God ascending
        and descending on the stairway.   '
      comments:
      - number: 28:12
        content: "  Dreams are a valid form of divine communication in the Bible.
          God frequently spoke to people through dreams. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  ;  . On
          the Day of Pentecost, Peter quoted the promise of Joel that those who received
          the Spirit would \u201Cexperience dreams\u201D (; see  ).      The steps
          of this stairway go up into the heavenly realm where our true riches are
          found. Each step is a progressive revelation of God\u2019s purpose for
          our lives found in Jesus Christ. The stairway goes both ways, touching
          heaven and touching earth. Jesus Christ can be thought of as the Stairway
          that reaches from earth (his human nature) to heaven (his heavenly nature).
          Jesus spoke to Nathanael using the same terminology (see  ). Jesus is the
          only valid entry into the spirit-realm, the true way into the heavenly
          realm. By him, we ascend and leave our lower life. This Jesus-Stairway
          was filled with messengers ascending and descending. Who are these messengers?
          Note the order: they ascended first. It does not say they were descending
          and ascending, which would be true if they were the angels in heaven. If
          they ascended first, they were leaving earth to go to heaven. These messengers
          might have been people or divine beings. If people, they were intercessors
          and promise-claimers. The Hebrew word translated \u201Cangel\u201D is 
          , which can also be translated \u201Cambassador,\u201D \u201Cdeputy,\u201D
          \u201Cmessenger,\u201D or \u201Cprophet.\u201D The Greek word used in the
          New Testament for \u201Cangel\u201D is    or \u201Cmessenger.\u201D It
          can refer either to a person or to a heavenly being. Paul wrote to the
          Galatians that they had welcomed him in their midst as if he were an \u201Cangel
          [messenger]\u201D from God (). In  , John was instructed to write to the
          seven churches and to the seven    of those churches. The angels were the
          human overseers of those churches. In  , three angels came to Abraham and
          are described as \u201Cthree men\u201D (cf.  ). We are like angel-ambassadors
          who ascend and descend upon the Jesus-Stairway. See  ;  ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> stood beside him [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and said to him, \u201CI am <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, the God of your
        father Abraham and the God of Isaac. You are lying on the very ground that
        I will give to you and your descendants. "
      comments:
      - number: 28:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cabove it [the stairway].\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'They will become as numerous as the specks of dust on the earth,
        and they will extend their territory in all directions. Through you and your
        descendants, I will bless the whole world. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 28:14
        content: '  See  ;  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Never forget\u2014I am always with you and will protect you wherever
        you go. And one day I will bring you back to this land, for I will neither
        leave you nor fail to fulfill every word I have promised you.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 28:15
        content: "  What did God tell Jacob? Did he scold him for being a crafty
          deceiver? Did he rebuke him for his lack of faith? Not at all. He revealed
          himself to Jacob as the One who would never leave or forsake him. This
          revelation of grace was a steady stream of assurances that washed over
          wayward Jacob! The Lord gave these promises to Jacob while he still was
          unbroken, unreliable, and a deceiver. Our God is a confident, capable God
          who can subdue and conquer the most difficult of men. Our future blessing
          and usefulness depend on God\u2019s strength, not ours. When God brought
          Jacob back to Bethel twenty years later, he was changed. God will change
          you. Your transformation may take more than a year, even more than ten
          or twenty, but your God will finish the work of changing you into the image
          of his Son (see  ). You will be his look-alike. You will carry the blessings
          of God to the next generation!    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When Jacob awoke from his dream, he was overcome with awe and said,
        \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> is here! He is in this place and I didn\u2019t
        realize it!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 28:16
        content: "  How many times have we been led to an uncomfortable place in
          life, only to encounter the Lord? Have you said, looking back over your
          life, \u201CTruly, the Lord really was in all I went through, and I didn\u2019t
          even know it!\u201D We often discover that he is where we did not think
          he would be. You may have a divine visitation anywhere! Ordinary places
          can become holy places.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Terrified and overwhelmed, he said, \u201CHow awesome is this place!
        I have stumbled right into the House of God! This place is a portal, the
        very gate of heaven!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Early in the morning, Jacob took the stone he had under his head,
        set it up as a pillar and anointed it by pouring oil over the top of it.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 28:18
        content: "  Jacob built a pillar from his pillow. The church is described
          by Paul as the \u201Cpillar and firm foundation of the truth\u201D ().
          By pouring oil on the stone, Jacob consecrated the pillar as a memorial
          to God. See  .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'He named that place Bethel; [[COMMENT(0)]] though the city was once
        called Luz. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:19
        content: "    means \u201CHouse of God.\u201D Jacob could see in a heap of
          stones the House of God that would arise. This is the first mention of
          God\u2019s house in the Scriptures. The House of God was filled with his
          presence, a gateway to heaven, a stairway with angels, and revelation.
          One day, the House of God would be born among us, born of a virgin. Jesus
          came to be an example of the House of God, the dwelling place of God and
          men under one roof, living in one body. Jesus is the God-Man, the House
          of God. As the House, he invites us to dwell as one with the Father. But
          Jesus was the initial fulfillment of the House of God, not the ultimate
          fulfillment, which would include others incorporated into Jesus. Today,
          the House of God, the gate to heaven, is also a description of the church.
          We are God\u2019s house (see  ), for the Lord dwells among us as his people.
          And we become a gateway for others to come to God through our message of
          new life in Christ.        means \u201Cseparation\u201D or \u201Cdeparture.\u201D
          God calls us to separate ourselves to himself, and when we do, we become
          the House of God.  "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then Jacob committed himself to God, saying, \u201CIf you will always
        be with me and protect me on this long journey, and if you give me bread
        to eat and clothing to wear, "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "and if I return safely to my father\u2019s house, then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>,
        you will be my God! "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "See! I have set up this sacred stone pillar and it will be your house,
        God. I promise to set aside a tenth of all that you give me as my gift to
        you.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jacob Meets a Woman at the Well'
      title: Jacob Meets a Woman at the Well
      number: 1
      content: 'Jacob resumed his journey [[COMMENT(0)]] and entered the land east
        of Canaan.   '
      comments:
      - number: 29:1
        content: "  Or \u201CJacob lifted up his feet.\u201D This unusual Hebrew
          expression could be double entendre, telling us that Jacob lifted up his
          feet not only to go on his journey but also to go up the Stairway he had
          just seen in his dream. To move forward is always to move higher up with
          God.      Or \u201Cthe land of the sons of the east,\u201D that is, east
          of Canaan. Jacob arrived at Paddan-Aram in Mesopotamia.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'One day, Jacob came to a well out in the open country where the shepherds
        watered their animals. Three flocks of sheep and goats were lying near the
        well, which had a large, heavy stone covering the opening. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Whenever all the flocks gathered there, the shepherds would roll away
        the stone from the mouth of the well, water their sheep, and then roll the
        stone back over the top of the well.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Jacob approached them and said, \u201CGood day, friends; where are
        you from?\u201D\u201CWe\u2019re from Haran,\u201D they answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CDo you happen to know Laban, [[COMMENT(0)]] a grandson of Nahor?\u201D
        Jacob said.\u201CWe do,\u201D they replied."
      comments:
      - number: 29:5
        content: "  Laban was the son of Bethuel and the grandson of Nahor, Abraham\u2019s
          brother.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Jacob asked, \u201CHow\u2019s he doing?\u201D\u201CHe\u2019s doing
        well,\u201D they answered. \u201CAs a matter of fact, here comes his daughter
        Rachel [[COMMENT(0)]] right now with her flock.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 29:6
        content: "    means \u201Cewe lamb.\u201D      It is obvious that God led
          Jacob supernaturally to the very well where Rachel would appear, and she
          came at an unusual time of day to water her father\u2019s flocks. This
          was a divine appointment for Jacob. And you can be assured that God has
          his hands of guidance upon you also.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Jacob said to them, \u201CLook, it\u2019s not time for the animals
        to gather together here; it\u2019s now the hottest hour of the day. Let\u2019s
        go ahead and water the sheep, then you can go and pasture them.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "They replied, \u201CFirst, we have to wait until all the flocks are
        gathered. After that, the stone needs to be rolled away from the mouth of
        the well, then we\u2019ll water the animals.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "While they were still speaking, Rachel, the shepherdess, drew near
        to the well with her father\u2019s sheep. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'As soon as Jacob took one good look at Rachel, the beautiful daughter
        of his uncle Laban, he quickly went over to the mouth of the well and single-handedly
        rolled away the stone and watered all the flock of his uncle Laban! [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 29:10
        content: "  At the sight of the lovely Rachel, Jacob\u2019s soul was so moved
          that he gained the strength to roll away the stone all by himself. \u201COne
          flash of [her] eyes\u201D () made him a momentary \u201Csuperman.\u201D
          After he moved the heavy stone, Jacob drew gallons and gallons of water
          for her flocks.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Immediately, he walked up to Rachel and kissed her! Unable to hold
        back his tears, Jacob wept aloud. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 29:11
        content: "  This entire scene is filled with emotion. Jacob saw the girl
          of his dreams and became supercharged to move the heavy stone and water
          her flock. Then he kissed her and lifted up his voice with passionate tears.
          You can almost hear the tender music playing in the background as this
          \u201Cguy meets girl\u201D scene unfolds. As you read it over again, think
          of Jesus who also rolled away a heavy stone so that he could come meet
          you to romance your soul (see  ). He drew you to faith in him, then offered
          you a drink from the well of life.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "After he composed himself, he explained to Rachel, \u201CI\u2019m
        your father\u2019s nephew, your aunt Rebekah\u2019s son.\u201D Upon hearing
        this, Rachel ran to tell her father. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When Laban heard the news that his nephew Jacob had arrived at the
        well, he ran to greet him. Laban hugged and kissed Jacob and welcomed him
        into his home. After Jacob told him the story of all that happened, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Jacob Marries Leah and Rachel'
      title: Jacob Marries Leah and Rachel
      number: 14
      content: "Laban said to him, \u201CCertainly, you are my own flesh and blood!\u201D
        Jacob stayed with him for an entire month and worked for him."
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Afterward, Laban said to Jacob, \u201CJust because you\u2019re my
        relative doesn\u2019t mean I expect you to work for nothing. Tell me, what
        do you want your wages to be?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: '(Now, Laban had two daughters; the older was Leah, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and the younger was Rachel. '
      comments:
      - number: 29:16
        content: "  The etymology of the name Leah is somewhat ambiguous. Some Hebrew
          scholars equate the name Leah with \u201Cweak,\u201D \u201Csluggish,\u201D
          or \u201Cweary.\u201D Tradition has it that Leah was cross-eyed, or perhaps
          partly blind. Her vision was impaired; seeing dimly. A \u201CLeah\u201D
          church does not function with clear vision. Leah represents those with
          limited vision who cannot discern the timing and ways of God. Like the
          lukewarm Laodiceans, the church is instructed to \u201Cpurchase eye salve\u201D
          so that it can see clearly (). A vision-impaired church will live by principles,
          laws, traditions, and customs. It was the \u201Ccustom\u201D for Leah to
          marry Jacob (v.  ). Like many today, she was unable to see clearly, felt
          unloved, and was unable to perceive God\u2019s greater purpose. The fruit
          of Leah (and her handmaiden, called \u201Cthe slave girl\u201D in  ) was
          only bondage. Jacob had to \u201Cwork\u201D after getting her!    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Rachel had a lovely figure and was gorgeous, [[COMMENT(0)]] but Leah\u2019s
        eyes were weak. )"
      comments:
      - number: 29:17
        content: "  Or \u201CRachel was beautiful of form and beautiful in appearance.\u201D
          Rachel becomes a picture of the radiant bride of the last days who makes
          herself ready for her Bridegroom. See  ;  .      Or \u201Cher eyes were
          sickly\u201D (LXX). The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Jacob had fallen in love with Rachel, so he answered Laban, \u201CI
        will serve you for seven years for the hand of your younger daughter, Rachel!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Laban replied, \u201CI\u2019d rather give her to you than to some
        other man. Stay and work for me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: So Jacob served Laban for seven years in exchange for Rachel, but
        because he loved her so deeply, the seven years seemed like only a few days.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 29:20
        content: '  Love can make long, hard service short and easy. This is why
          the Scriptures speak of a labor of love (;  ). In  , we learn that Jacob
          tended sheep for those seven years in order to get the bride he loved.
          There is another who has now waited for nearly seven thousand years for
          his bride that he dearly loves! And what has he been doing for all those
          years? He has been carrying his lambs close to his heart and tending his
          flock like a Shepherd (see  ).    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "After the seven years, Jacob said to Laban, \u201CMy time is fulfilled;
        give me your daughter so that I may marry her and sleep with her.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So Laban prepared a wedding feast [[COMMENT(0)]] and invited all
        the people of the surrounding area. '
      comments:
      - number: 29:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cdrinking party.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "That night, Laban tricked Jacob by bringing his older daughter Leah
        to Jacob\u2019s tent, and he slept with her on his wedding night! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 29:23
        content: '  Perhaps Jacob was drunk on wine, and Leah was wearing a bridal
          veil.    '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "(Laban assigned Zilpah [[COMMENT(0)]] to be Leah\u2019s servant.)"
      comments:
      - number: 29:24
        content: "    means \u201Csmall\u201D or \u201Ca trickling.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "When Jacob woke up the next morning, he was shocked to find Leah
        lying next to him! So he confronted Laban and said, \u201CWhat have you done
        to me? Didn\u2019t I serve you these seven years for Rachel? Why have you
        tricked me?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Laban answered, \u201CIt\u2019s not our custom here to give the younger
        daughter in marriage before the older daughter is married. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Wait until this bridal week of festivities is over, then I\u2019ll
        give you Rachel, but you must serve me for another seven years.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 29:27
        content: "  For those seven years, God was teaching Jacob submission to the
          rights of the firstborn. It was not right to marry the younger before the
          older. All that Jacob had circumvented in stealing the blessing from Esau
          he must now learn by serving for another seven years and learn the timing
          of God. After the first seven years were over, Laban tricked Jacob by giving
          him Leah, not Rachel, on his wedding night. Jacob was fooled by the veil
          over the bride\u2019s face, thinking she was Rachel, even as he had fooled
          his father with a hairy skin over his arms, confusing him with Esau. Every
          \u201CJacob\u201D will one day meet his \u201CLaban.\u201D    "
    - name: "28-30: Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      title: "Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      number: 28-30
      content: "Jacob complied with Laban\u2019s request. After he completed the
        prescribed week of Leah\u2019s wedding feast, Laban gave his daughter Rachel
        to be his wife, and he slept with her. Rachel was his true love, not Leah.
        (Laban assigned Bilhah [[COMMENT(0)]] as his daughter Rachel\u2019s servant.)
        And Jacob remained there serving Laban for another seven years."
      comments:
      - number: "29:28\u201330"
        content: "  The name Bilhah may come from an Arabic word for \u201Cstupid\u201D
          or \u201Cunconcerned.\u201D If it comes from Hebrew, it means \u201Ctroubled.\u201D    "
    - name: "28-30: Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      title: "Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      number: 28-30
      content: "Jacob complied with Laban\u2019s request. After he completed the
        prescribed week of Leah\u2019s wedding feast, Laban gave his daughter Rachel
        to be his wife, and he slept with her. Rachel was his true love, not Leah.
        (Laban assigned Bilhah [[COMMENT(0)]] as his daughter Rachel\u2019s servant.)
        And Jacob remained there serving Laban for another seven years."
      comments:
      - number: "29:28\u201330"
        content: "  The name Bilhah may come from an Arabic word for \u201Cstupid\u201D
          or \u201Cunconcerned.\u201D If it comes from Hebrew, it means \u201Ctroubled.\u201D    "
    - name: "28-30: Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      title: "Leah\u2019s Four Sons"
      number: 28-30
      content: "Jacob complied with Laban\u2019s request. After he completed the
        prescribed week of Leah\u2019s wedding feast, Laban gave his daughter Rachel
        to be his wife, and he slept with her. Rachel was his true love, not Leah.
        (Laban assigned Bilhah [[COMMENT(0)]] as his daughter Rachel\u2019s servant.)
        And Jacob remained there serving Laban for another seven years."
      comments:
      - number: "29:28\u201330"
        content: "  The name Bilhah may come from an Arabic word for \u201Cstupid\u201D
          or \u201Cunconcerned.\u201D If it comes from Hebrew, it means \u201Ctroubled.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'When <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> saw that Leah was unloved, he
        opened her womb, but Rachel remained childless. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Leah conceived, gave birth to a son, and named him Reuben, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        saying, \u201CBecause <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> looked upon me with compassion
        in my misery, surely, my husband will love me now!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 29:32
        content: "    means \u201CSee! A son!\u201D Leah defined fulfillment by how
          much Jacob loved her. Envy can often be traced back to an inward struggle
          to gain identity. Leah and Rachel competed for Jacob\u2019s heart. Leah
          called her firstborn Reuben, which in Hebrew sounds like \u201Che has seen
          my misery.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "She conceived again, gave birth to a son, and named him Simeon, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        saying, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> has heard that I am despised,
        and in his mercy, he has given me this son also.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 29:33
        content: "  Simeon\u2019s name comes from the Hebrew verb meaning \u201Cto
          hear.\u201D God saw Leah\u2019s pain and heard her cry. She named her first
          two children after God\u2019s mercy and compassion for the downcast and
          rejected. There is a mercy-chord in God\u2019s heart that is touched by
          the broken, poor, and rejected. God gives greater honor to dishonored ones
          (see  ). It is the nature of God to be drawn to those who hurt. God saw
          her pain, her loneliness, and her heartache. If only she had understood
          how greatly the Lord loved her.    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Leah conceived the third time, gave birth to a son, and named him
        Levi, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CThis time my husband will be joined to
        me, because now I\u2019ve given him three sons!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 29:34
        content: "  The name Levi sounds like the Hebrew word meaning \u201Cto join,\u201D
          \u201Cbind,\u201D or \u201Cattach.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Once again, Leah conceived and gave birth to a son. She named him
        Judah, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CThis time I will praise the Lord!\u201D
        Then she stopped bearing children for a while."
      comments:
      - number: 29:35
        content: "  The name Judah sounds like the Hebrew verb meaning \u201Cto praise.\u201D
          Over the years of struggling with the pain of being unloved, Leah finally
          opened her heart to the Lord, and grace touched her. God was tenderly wooing
          her to himself through her disappointment in her marriage. At last, she
          gave birth to her fourth son and resolved to praise the Lord no matter
          what. Leah had now become a worshiper of the Almighty. She found her fulfillment
          in God, so she named her son Judah and declared, \u201CThis time I will
          praise the Lord!\u201D Leah, not Rachel, became the mother of Judah and
          the ancestor of Jesus.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Battle of the Brides'
      title: Battle of the Brides
      number: 1
      content: "When Rachel saw that she could not give Jacob children, her jealousy
        toward her sister simmered. So, she said to Jacob, \u201CGive me sons, or
        I\u2019ll die!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 30:1
        content: '  Ironically, Rachel died while giving birth to her second son
          (see  ).    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Jacob became furious with Rachel and said, \u201CAm I God? He\u2019s
        the one keeping you from bearing children!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "She replied, \u201CHere\u2019s my servant Bilhah. Sleep with her.
        She can be my surrogate; then I can have children through her [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and build a family.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 30:3
        content: "  Literally, \u201Cthat she may bear upon my knees,\u201D a Hebrew
          figurative expression that refers to the practice of obtaining children
          through the service of another woman and legally adopting the child as
          one\u2019s own. See    and footnote;  .      Or \u201CI will be built up
          through her.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'So Rachel gave her servant Bilhah to Jacob as another wife, and Jacob
        slept with her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'And Bilhah conceived and bore Jacob a son, '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "and Rachel named him Dan, saying, \u201CGod has vindicated me. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He heard my voice and gave me a son.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 30:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cjudged me [decided in my favor].\u201D The name Dan
          sounds like the Hebrew verb meaning \u201Cto judge.\u201D The Hebrew contains
          a wordplay on his name\u2014\u201CGod has vindicated [] me.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then her servant Bilhah conceived again and bore Jacob a second son. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Rachel named him Naphtali, saying, \u201CI have wrestled mightily
        [[COMMENT(0)]] with my sister, and I won!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:8
        content: "  The name Naphtali means \u201Cwrestle,\u201D \u201Ccontest,\u201D
          \u201Cstruggle,\u201D or \u201Cfight.\u201D The Hebrew reads \u201Cwith
          wrestling of  ,\u201D posing an interpretive problem. There are three ways
          to understand this phrase: (1) Many scholars see    as a descriptive term
          of intensity meaning \u201Cgreat\u201D or \u201Cmight.\u201D (2) Some interpret
          this statement as Rachel wrestling with God for his favor. (3) Some see
          it as describing a mysterious struggle or \u201Cfateful contest [of God]\u201D
          or \u201Cplaying a trick on her sister.\u201D In any case, this was one
          troubled home. As Jacob had struggled with his older brother, Rachel now
          struggled with her older sister.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Meanwhile, when Leah saw that she had ceased bearing children, she
        took her servant Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as another wife. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10-11: '
      title: 
      number: 10-11
      content: "Zilpah bore Jacob a son, and Leah named him Gad, saying, \u201CWhat
        good fortune!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: "30:10\u201311"
        content: "  The name Gad means \u201Cgood fortune\u201D or \u201Cgood luck
          has come.\u201D    "
    - name: '10-11: '
      title: 
      number: 10-11
      content: "Zilpah bore Jacob a son, and Leah named him Gad, saying, \u201CWhat
        good fortune!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: "30:10\u201311"
        content: "  The name Gad means \u201Cgood fortune\u201D or \u201Cgood luck
          has come.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Zilpah bore Jacob a second son, '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "and Leah named him Asher, saying, \u201COh happy day! [[COMMENT(0)]]
        All the women will say, \u2018She\u2019s happy now!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:13
        content: "  The name Asher means \u201Chappy.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "One day, during wheat harvest, Reuben found some mandrake plants
        [[COMMENT(0)]] in the field and brought them to his mother Leah. Rachel said
        to Leah, \u201CPlease give me some of your son\u2019s mandrakes.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:14
        content: "  Mandrakes, or \u201Clove apples,\u201D had an erotic connotation
          and were considered in that culture to have aphrodisiac properties. Aphrodite,
          the Greek goddess of love, beauty, and sex, was known as the \u201CLady
          of the Mandrake.\u201D The Hebrew root for \u201Cmandrake\u201D is similar
          to the word for \u201Clove.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Leah replied, \u201CYou already took away the affection of my husband,
        so now you\u2019re going to take my son\u2019s mandrakes, too?\u201DRachel
        said, \u201CAll right then, I\u2019ll let him sleep with you tonight in exchange
        for some of your son\u2019s mandrakes.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "That evening, when Jacob was coming home from the field, Leah went
        out to meet him and said, \u201CYou must sleep with me tonight, for I\u2019ve
        paid for your services with my son\u2019s mandrakes.\u201D So Jacob slept
        with Leah that night. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "God listened compassionately to Leah\u2019s cry, she became pregnant,
        and bore Jacob a fifth son, "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "whom she named Issachar, saying, \u201CGod rewarded [[COMMENT(0)]]
        me for giving my maidservant to my husband.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:18
        content: "  The name Issachar comes from the Hebrew word for \u201Creward.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Once again, Leah conceived and bore Jacob a sixth son, '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "whom she named Zebulun, saying, \u201CGod has given me good gifts
        for my husband! Now he will accept [[COMMENT(0)]] me, for I\u2019ve given
        him six sons.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 30:20
        content: "  The name Zebulun sounds like the Hebrew word for \u201Chonor,\u201D
          \u201Craise up,\u201D or \u201Caccept.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: Lastly, Leah gave birth to a daughter and named her Dinah. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 30:21
        content: "    means \u201Cjudgment\u201D or \u201Cvindication.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "God listened to Rachel\u2019s heart-cry, and had compassion [[COMMENT(0)]]
        on her, and made her fertile."
      comments:
      - number: 30:22
        content: "  Or \u201CGod remembered.\u201D    "
    - name: '23-24: Jacob Makes a Deal with Laban'
      title: Jacob Makes a Deal with Laban
      number: 23-24
      content: "She conceived, and bore a son, and named him Joseph, saying, \u201CGod
        has taken away my disgrace. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> add [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to me another son.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "30:23\u201324"
        content: "  The name Joseph means \u201Che adds [another].\u201D    "
    - name: '23-24: Jacob Makes a Deal with Laban'
      title: Jacob Makes a Deal with Laban
      number: 23-24
      content: "She conceived, and bore a son, and named him Joseph, saying, \u201CGod
        has taken away my disgrace. May <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> add [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to me another son.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "30:23\u201324"
        content: "  The name Joseph means \u201Che adds [another].\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "After Rachel gave birth to Joseph, Jacob said to Laban, \u201CRelease
        me to go back home to my homeland. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "You know how hard I\u2019ve worked for you these many years to finish
        paying for my two wives. Give them to me along with my children, and I\u2019ll
        be on my way.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Laban countered, \u201CIf you please, I have learned by divine inquiry
        [[COMMENT(0)]] that I have become prosperous because of you and the blessing
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  that\u2019s on your life. "
      comments:
      - number: 30:27
        content: "  Or \u201Cby divination [omens, astrology, fortune-tellers].\u201D
          God forbid divination among his people (see  ;  ,  .)    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Just name your price, and I\u2019ll give it to you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Jacob replied, \u201CYou know how hard I\u2019ve worked for you and
        how your livestock has increased under my care. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "The little you had before I came has multiplied greatly, for <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        has blessed you wonderfully because I am here. [[COMMENT(0)]] But now, I
        need to provide for my own family, too.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 30:30
        content: "  Literally, \u201Caccording to my foot,\u201D a figure of speech
          for \u201Cbecause I am here [working for you].\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "So Laban asked, \u201CWhat should I give you?\u201D\u201CNothing,\u201D
        Jacob replied, \u201CYou don\u2019t need to give me a thing. If you will
        do but one thing for me, I will continue to care for your flocks: "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Just let me pass through all your flocks today and take out every
        speckled and spotted sheep or goat, and every black lamb. That\u2019s all
        the payment I ask. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "And in the future, when you review my wages, the integrity of my
        dealings with you will be obvious. If you find any animal among mine that
        is not speckled, spotted, or black, then you will know that I stole it.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CAgreed!\u201D Laban said. \u201CWe\u2019ll do what you\u2019ve
        suggested.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'But that same day, Laban secretly removed all the male and female
        goats that were speckled or spotted (all that had white on them) and all
        the black lambs and left them under the care of his sons. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "He set a distance of a three-day journey between himself and Jacob,
        while Jacob continued to tend the rest of Laban\u2019s flocks."
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Jacob, however, cut green branches of poplar, almond, and plane trees
        and peeled back part of their bark, to expose the white inner wood of the
        branches. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'Then he set the partially peeled branches inside the water troughs
        where the goats would see them when they came to drink. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'For they mated when they came to the water troughs, and as they lowered
        their heads to drink, they saw the stripped branches in front of their eyes.
        Miraculously  [[COMMENT(0)]] they gave birth to streaked, speckled, and spotted
        young. '
      comments:
      - number: 30:39
        content: '  These were not simply principles of animal husbandry, but a divine
          miracle revealed to Jacob through a dream (see  ). God always uses unique
          and puzzling methods to perform a miracle. He may require bathing seven
          times in the Jordan River (see  ), parting the Red Sea (see  ), or having
          the sun stand still (see  ). God displayed his creative power through the
          birth of these multicolored young goats. Perhaps the miracle teaches us
          that what we see or gaze upon can impregnate us with the object of our
          vision, for you can determine what you conceive by what you behold. What
          you set your gaze upon is what you will give birth to.  '
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "But with the mating ewes, on the other hand, he made them face the
        streaked or completely black animals in Laban\u2019s flock. By doing this,
        he produced his own special flocks, which he didn\u2019t allow to mingle
        with Laban\u2019s. "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'Moreover, every time the stronger females were in heat, Jacob laid
        the partially peeled branches in the water troughs in front of the flock,
        so that they would mate among the branches. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "But he didn\u2019t place the branches in front of the scrawny goats
        when they mated, leaving the feeble animals for Laban and the stronger for
        himself. "
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: In this way, Jacob quickly grew very wealthy and owned large flocks,
        a great number of camels and donkeys, and many male and female servants.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jacob Escapes from Laban'
      title: Jacob Escapes from Laban
      number: 1
      content: "Now Jacob heard that the sons of Laban were complaining, \u201CEverything
        Jacob owns he has taken from our father! He gained all his wealth from what
        our father owned.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'And Jacob saw that Laban no longer viewed him favorably as he once
        did. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said to Jacob, \u201CReturn to
        the land of your ancestors where you were born; and remember, I will be with
        you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'So Jacob sent a message for Leah and Rachel to meet him in the field
        where his flocks were grazing. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When they arrived, he said to them, \u201CI can see that your father\u2019s
        attitude toward me has changed, but the God of my father has been with me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You both know I have worked for your father as hard as I could, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'although he has cheated me and reduced [[COMMENT(0)]] my wages over
        and over. Yet God has not allowed him to harm me. '
      comments:
      - number: 31:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cchanged.\u201D The implication is that Laban did not
          give him raises, but reduced his salary literally in the Hebrew \u201Cten
          times\u201D (a term not meant to define how many times, but a figure of
          speech for \u201Cmany, many times\u201D).    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "If he said, \u2018The speckled ones will be your wages,\u2019 then
        all the flock bore speckled. If he said, \u2018The striped ones will be your
        wages,\u2019 then all the flock bore striped. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Because of these miracles, God has taken away your father\u2019s
        livestock and given them to me!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Jacob continued, \u201COnce during the breeding season, I had a dream.
        I saw that the male goats who were mating were all speckled, streaked, or
        spotted. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "In the dream, the angel of God called me by my name, \u2018Jacob.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D\u201C&nbsp;\u2018I
        am here,\u2019 I answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CThen he said, \u2018Observe and note that all the male goats
        that are mating are speckled, streaked, or spotted, for I have seen all that
        Laban is doing to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "I am the God who appeared to you at Bethel, [[COMMENT(0)]] where
        you anointed a pillar and made a vow to me. Now leave this land at once and
        return to the land of your birth.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 31:13
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint and ancient Targums. The Hebrew
          is \u201CI am the God of Bethel.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then Rachel and Leah answered him, \u201COur father doesn\u2019t
        want us to inherit a portion from his estate. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Hasn\u2019t he treated us as outsiders and not as members of his
        family? Not only did he sell us like property, but he has also spent our
        purchase price! "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Our father\u2019s wealth that God has given you was legally ours
        and our children to begin with! So, go ahead and do whatever God has told
        you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Jacob immediately put his wives and children on camels '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: and took with him all the livestock and everything he had amassed
        in Paddan-Aram. He set out to return to his father Isaac in the land of Canaan.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "One day, when Laban had gone to his fields to shear his sheep, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Rachel stole her father\u2019s household idols.   "
      comments:
      - number: 31:19
        content: "  Sheep shearing was done in the spring, and it was a time of celebration
          and festivities that could have lasted a week (see  ,  ,  ;  ). Laban was
          preoccupied with the festivities and didn\u2019t realize that his household
          gods had been stolen and that Jacob was secretly taking off with his daughters.     
          This is the Hebrew word  ; they can be described as small, carved figurines
          passed down within the family or clan.    is taken from an Aramaic root
          word meaning \u201Cto inquire.\u201D Apparently, Laban used these images
          for guidance by divination. Rachel\u2019s taking her father\u2019s gods
          meant she took his ability to discover where they had gone (see  ;  ; 
          ). Other scholars believe that the teraphim guaranteed the right of inheritance
          to whoever possessed them. According to ancient Akkadian writings, the
          possession of these family idols (gods) could verify legal title to the
          family estate. This was perhaps the reason for Laban\u2019s angry accusation
          of Jacob (v.  ).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Jacob had outwitted Laban the Aramean by secretly departing without
        telling him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'He fled with all that he had, and after crossing the Euphrates, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        he headed for the hill country of Gilead. '
      comments:
      - number: 31:21
        content: "  The Euphrates was known to the Hebrews simply as \u201Cthe River.\u201D
          It was about fifty miles from Laban\u2019s home to the Euphrates.    "
    - name: '22: Laban Pursues Jacob'
      title: Laban Pursues Jacob
      number: 22
      content: "And it wasn\u2019t until three days later that Laban discovered Jacob
        had left."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Laban, along with some of his relatives, took off in pursuit and
        chased after Jacob for seven days. He had almost caught up with him in the
        hill country of Gilead, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "when God appeared to Laban the Aramean in a dream and warned him,
        \u201CBe careful that you neither harm nor threaten Jacob.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 31:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat you speak not to Jacob a word either good or evil.\u201D
          This is a merism, for God was not telling Laban to remain silent, but rather
          to neither harm nor threaten Jacob with his words.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Now Jacob had set up his camp with his flocks on a hill, and Laban
        had him in his sights. Laban and his companions set up their camp nearby. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Laban approached Jacob and said, \u201CNephew, what have you done?
        You\u2019ve deceived me and carried away my daughters like captives on a
        battlefield. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Why did you trick me and run away in secret without telling me? I
        would have sent you off joyously, celebrating with singing and dancing to
        the tambourine and stringed instruments. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'And why did you not even let me kiss my daughters and grandchildren
        goodbye? What you have done is foolish! '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "I could harm you, but the God of your father spoke to me in a dream
        last night, saying, \u2018Be careful that you neither harm nor threaten Jacob.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Now I realize you ran away because you desperately long to return
        to your father\u2019s house, but why did you steal my gods?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CI left in a hurry because I was afraid,\u201D Jacob answered,
        \u201Cand I thought you would take your daughters from me by force. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Whoever has taken your gods will be put to death! So here, in the
        presence of our relatives, if you can find among our possessions anything
        that is yours, take it.\u201D Now Jacob had no clue that Rachel had stolen
        the gods."
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Laban went immediately into Jacob\u2019s tent to search. Then he
        went into the tents of Zilpah and Bilhah but found nothing. After searching
        Leah\u2019s tent, he went into Rachel\u2019s. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Now Rachel had taken the family gods and put them in her camel\u2019s
        cushion and sat on them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "She said to her father, \u201CPlease my father, [[COMMENT(0)]] don\u2019t
        be angry if I don\u2019t rise before you, for I\u2019m having my period.\u201D
        When he rummaged through her tent, he did not find them."
      comments:
      - number: 31:35
        content: "  Or \u201Cmy lord.\u201D    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Then Jacob became angry and complained to Laban, \u201CWhat have
        I done wrong? What sin have I committed that you would hotly pursue me as
        if you were chasing a criminal? "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "You have rummaged through all my things, and did you find anything
        of your own property? If you did, set them here in front of your relatives
        and mine. Let them decide between the two of us.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Jacob continued, \u201CFor the last twenty years I have served you,
        and the whole time your sheep and goats did not miscarry, nor did I feast
        on any of your rams. "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "If one from your flock was mauled by a wild beast, I didn\u2019t
        bring it to you; I absorbed the loss myself. And you always made me pay for
        any missing animal, whether snatched by day or by night. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'Many times, scorching heat consumed me by day and hard frost by night;
        I endured sleepless nights. '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "For these twenty years that I\u2019ve lived among you, I slaved away
        fourteen years for your two daughters, and six years for your flocks. And
        besides all that, you\u2019ve reduced my wages over and over. "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: Laban and Jacob Make a Covenant'
      title: Laban and Jacob Make a Covenant
      number: 42
      content: "If the God of my father, the God of Abraham, and the Awesome One
        of Isaac [[COMMENT(0)]], had not been on my side, you certainly would have
        sent me away empty-handed! But God in his mercy took notice of how much I\u2019ve
        suffered and how hard I\u2019ve worked\u2014and that\u2019s why he rebuked
        you last night in your dream!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 31:42
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe One whom Isaac worships\u201D or \u201Cthe Fear
          of Isaac.\u201D The Hebrew is uncertain.    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Laban replied to Jacob, \u201CThese women are my daughters, these
        children are my grandchildren; and the flocks are mine. In fact, everything
        you see belongs to me. But from today I will not be able to do anything more
        for my daughters and grandchildren. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 31:43
        content: "  Or \u201CWhat can I do today about these daughters of mine and
          these children they have borne?\u201D    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "Come now, let\u2019s form a covenant between you and me. Let it endure
        as a witness between us.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 31:44
        content: '  This covenant (treaty), memorialized by the heap of stones and
          their covenant meal, was an agreement to never harm each other.    '
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'So Jacob took a stone, set it up as a pillar, '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "and in the presence of his relatives, he said to them, \u201CEveryone
        gather stones, and place them here in a pile.\u201D And they did so, and
        afterward, they ate together next to the heap of stones. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: 'Laban and Jacob named the place in both languages, Aramaic  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        and Hebrew,  calling it Witness Heap. '
      comments:
      - number: 31:47
        content: "  Or \u201CJegar Sahadutha,\u201D Aramaic for \u201CHeap of Witness.\u201D     
          Or \u201CGaleed,\u201D Hebrew for \u201CHeap of Witness.\u201D    "
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "And Laban said, \u201CToday, this heap of stones will be a witness
        between you and me of our enduring friendship.\u201D He called it Witness
        Heap "
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "and Watchpost, [[COMMENT(0)]] for Laban declared, \u201CMay <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        keep his eyes on us when we are absent from each other. "
      comments:
      - number: 31:49
        content: "  Or \u201CMizpah,\u201D which means \u201CWatchpost [Lookout].\u201D
          Jesus is our Mizpah.    states that Jesus made the Jew and the gentile
          one, breaking down the middle wall between them. Jacob, the father of the
          Israelites, and Laban, a gentile, found peace at Mizpah.    "
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'If you mistreat my daughters or marry other women besides my daughters,
        remember that even though no one else is with us, God is watching us. '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: 'Here is the heap of stones and here is the memorial pillar that stands
        between us. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 31:51
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat I have set up between us.\u201D    "
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: 'This heap and this pillar stand as witnesses that I will never pass
        beyond them to harm you and that you will never pass beyond them to harm
        me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: "Now may the God of Abraham and the god of Nahor judge between us!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>, the God of Abraham, was not the god of Nahor.</smallcaps><smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>Jacob made his vow by the Awesome One of his father Isaac.   "
      comments:
      - number: 31:53
        content: "  As translated from some Hebrew manuscripts and the Septuagint.
          Other Hebrew manuscripts add \u201Cthe gods of their fathers.\u201D   
          called Abraham out of Haran (see  ) and away from idol worship (see  ).     
          Or \u201Cby [in the name of] the Fear of Isaac [the One whom Isaac feared].\u201D  "
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: Then Jacob offered a sacrifice on the mountain and called everyone
        together for a meal, and they remained there all night on the mountain.
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: Early the next morning, Laban kissed his daughters and grandchildren,
        blessed them, and then he returned home.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Divine Encounter'
      title: A Divine Encounter
      number: 1
      content: 'As Jacob continued toward Canaan, the angels of God came to meet
        him! '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "When he saw them, he exclaimed, \u201CThis is God\u2019s military
        camp!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] So he named that place Two Camps of Angels."
      comments:
      - number: 32:2
        content: "  Or \u201CThis is God\u2019s camp,\u201D \u201CThis is God\u2019s
          army,\u201D or \u201CMahanaim.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jacob sent messengers ahead to his brother Esau who was living in
        the land of Seir, the country of Edom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He instructed them, \u201CGive this message from me to my master
        Esau, \u2018I am your servant. I have lived with our uncle Laban all these
        years "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "and have acquired sheep, cattle, donkeys, and both male and female
        servants. I send this message to you, my master, in the hope of finding favor
        in your eyes.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When the messengers returned to Jacob, they informed him, \u201CWe
        gave your brother Esau your message, and he himself is coming here to meet
        you. In fact, he\u2019s on his way now with four hundred men!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Gripped with fear [[COMMENT(0)]] to the point of panic, Jacob split
        all the people who were with him into two camps, and also the flocks, herds,
        and camels. '
      comments:
      - number: 32:7
        content: "  Or \u201CBound,\u201D \u201CTied-up,\u201D \u201CRestricted,\u201D
          implying that Jacob was immobilized by his anxiety.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "He said to himself, \u201CIf Esau attacks the first camp and destroys
        them, at least the other camp will escape.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then Jacob prayed, \u201C<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, God of my
        father Abraham and God of my father Isaac, you said to me, \u2018Return to
        your country and to your family, and I will make you prosper.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'I am so unworthy of all the loving-kindness and faithfulness that
        you have showered upon me, your servant. When I crossed this river Jordan
        years ago, all I had to my name was a staff in my hand, and now I have increased
        to become two camps! '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Save me, I pray, from the hand of my brother Esau, for I\u2019m afraid
        he will come and kill all of us, including the women and children. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "You said to me, \u2018I will certainly prosper you and make your
        offspring as innumerable as the sand of the sea.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'So he spent the night there.From what he had with him, Jacob sent
        a gift [[COMMENT(0)]] to his brother Esau: '
      comments:
      - number: 32:13
        content: "  Or \u201CJacob sent from what he had in his hand.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'two hundred female goats and twenty male goats, two hundred ewes
        and twenty rams, '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'thirty female camels and their calves, forty cows and ten bulls,
        twenty female donkeys and ten male donkeys. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 32:15
        content: '  This was at least 550 animals, a substantial gift indeed. Perhaps
          Jacob was attempting to return a portion of the stolen birthright.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "He placed them in the care of his servants, each herd by itself.
        He told them, \u201CGo on ahead of me, and put some space between each herd.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He gave these instructions to the one in the lead, \u201CWhen my
        brother Esau meets you, and asks, \u2018Who is your master? [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Where are you going? Who owns these herds you are driving?\u2019   "
      comments:
      - number: 32:17
        content: "  Or \u201CTo whom are you?\u201D      Or \u201CWhose are these
          ahead of you?\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "then you are to say, \u2018They belong to your servant Jacob. He\u2019s
        sent them as a gift to you, my lord Esau, and he is coming behind us.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He likewise instructed the leaders of the second and the third herds
        and all those following them, \u201CYou must say the same thing when you
        meet Esau. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "And be sure to say, \u2018Your servant Jacob is coming behind us,\u2019&nbsp;\u201D
        because he reasoned, \u201CIf I can appease Esau with these gifts before
        I have to meet him face-to-face, he may accept me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: A Midnight Wrestling Match'
      title: A Midnight Wrestling Match
      number: 21
      content: So he sent the gifts on ahead of him, while he spent that night in
        the camp.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'During the night, Jacob arose, woke up his two wives, his two maidservants,
        and eleven sons, and had them cross the ford of the Jabbok River. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 32:22
        content: "  The name of this river was a prophecy of what God was doing in
          his servant.    means \u201Cemptying.\u201D The Jabbok is known today in
          Arabic as the Wadi Zerga, which empties into the Jordan twenty-five miles
          north of the Dead Sea.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'He sent them across along with everything he had, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'and Jacob was left all alone. [[COMMENT(0)]] Suddenly, out of nowhere,
        a man appeared and wrestled  with him until daybreak. '
      comments:
      - number: 32:24
        content: "  To be left alone with God is the only true way of coming to self-discovery.
          This was the turning point for Jacob. His schemes had all failed, and now
          he faced God alone.      The Hebrew word for \u201Cwrestle\u201D is related
          to a word for \u201Cdust\u201D or \u201Cget dusty,\u201D as two people
          do when wrestling on the ground. There is an amazing play on words in the
          Hebrew between the words \u201Che wrestled\u201D (), \u201CJabbok\u201D
          (), and \u201CJacob\u201D (). The eyes of Jacob could not discern who was
          coming out of the shadows, just as Jacob\u2019s father, Isaac, could not
          discern who it was that received his blessing. It was not Jacob wrestling
          a man, but a Man wrestling with Jacob. The One whom Jacob saw at the top
          of the stairway at Bethel had come down to wrestle with him\u2014and roll
          in the mud of Jacob\u2019s mistakes.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "When the man saw that he was not winning the match, he struck Jacob\u2019s
        hip and knocked it out of joint, leaving it wrenched as he continued to wrestle
        with him. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 32:25
        content: "  Jacob grabbed a heel; God grabbed his hip! Through these private
          encounters with the Lord, we become those whose names have been changed
          (see  ;  ,  ;  ;  ); we are changed into humbled, transformed ones who
          are subdued by the power of God (see  ). Jacob had at least two night encounters
          with the Lord: one while he rested (see  ) and the other while he wrestled.
          When he rested, the region got a new name\u2014Luz became Bethel. When
          he wrestled, he got a new name\u2014Jacob became Israel.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Eventually, the man said to him, \u201CLet me go, for the day is
        breaking.\u201DBut Jacob refused. \u201CNo! Not until you bless me!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 32:26
        content: '  Jacob might have initially thought it was Esau who had come at
          midnight to wrestle him. But as the night wore on, he realized the Man
          was a divine being (see  ). Perceiving this was a supernatural Man who
          had the power to bless or to curse, Jacob refused to release him until
          he pronounced a blessing over him.    '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CWhat is your name?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] asked the man.\u201CJacob,\u201D
        he replied."
      comments:
      - number: 32:27
        content: "  This was a strange question because God knew his name. God touched
          not only his hip but also his slumbering conscience. When asked this question,
          Jacob\u2019s imagination took him back over twenty years to the dark tent
          where his blind, aged father had faced him with the same question and he
          had answered, \u201CIt\u2019s I\u2014Esau\u201D\u2014and got away with
          it (see  )! Now the Lord had come to Jacob insisting he acknowledge that
          he was the one who took advantage of his father and his brother.    means
          \u201Cheel grabber\u201D or \u201Csupplanter.\u201D The Lord was insisting
          that his blessings would only begin when Jacob realized the true need of
          his heart. By speaking out his name, Jacob confessed his true nature: \u201CI
          am a deceiver, a cheat. My name is heel grabber.\u201D This confession
          liberated Jacob and opened the way for inner transformation (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CNot anymore,\u201D the man said to him. \u201CYour new name
        is Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]] for you have struggled both with God and with people
        and have overcome.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 32:28
        content: "    means \u201Cone who struggled with God and prevailed,\u201D
          \u201Cmay God [El] preserve,\u201D or \u201Cprince with God.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Jacob said, \u201CPlease, tell me your name.\u201D\u201CWhy ask my
        name?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] the man replied, then he spoke a blessing  over
        Jacob."
      comments:
      - number: 32:29
        content: "  If this is a rhetorical question, it may mean \u201CYou should
          not ask my name.\u201D      This blessing empowered Jacob to succeed and
          prosper.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "So Jacob named the place Penuel, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CI have
        seen God face-to-face, yet my life has been spared!\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 32:30
        content: "  Or \u201CPeniel [face of God].\u201D Eight times in the Old Testament
          this word is spelled \u201CPenuel,\u201D and only once \u201CPeniel.\u201D
          Since both spellings are in vv.    and  , the translator has chosen to
          make them identical.      Once you have seen the face of God, the faces
          of those who oppose you will no longer intimidate you. Jacob could now
          look Esau in the eyes.  "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'The sun rose upon him as he crossed the Jabbok River from Penuel,
        limping because of his hip. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "To this day, the Israelites do not eat the thigh muscle attached
        to the hip socket, because the man struck Jacob\u2019s hip socket at the
        thigh muscle."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Brothers Reconcile'
      title: Brothers Reconcile
      number: 1
      content: 'When Jacob [[COMMENT(0)]] looked up, he saw Esau approaching with
        four hundred men.  So he quickly divided the children among Leah, Rachel,
        and the two maidservants. '
      comments:
      - number: 33:1
        content: "  Jacob\u2019s name had been changed, but like us, he was slow
          to realize his new identity. It was not until Rachel died that Israel journeyed
          onward (see  ). Jacob entered his promised inheritance with a limp. When
          he walked toward Esau and bowed down, he was limping. Esau did not see
          a whole Jacob; he saw a crippled Jacob.      Esau came with four hundred
          men; Jacob came with four women and his children. Jacob divided his children
          by their mothers and sent them to Esau one group at a time. The most loved
          of all to Jacob were Rachel and Joseph, so he reserved them for last, just
          in case the anger of Esau broke out against him and his family. Jacob was
          a clever, thoughtful man, but he was still walking in man\u2019s wisdom.
          Because he anticipated vengeance from the hand of Esau, he exposed those
          whom he cared about the least to the first stroke of that vengeance.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He lined up the maidservants and their children in front, then Leah
        and her children, then Rachel and Joseph last of all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Then Jacob went ahead of them to face Esau. As he approached his brother,
        he bowed down to the ground seven times [[COMMENT(0)]] before reaching him.
      comments:
      - number: 33:3
        content: "  It is hard to miss the irony here, for Isaac\u2019s prophecy
          was that Esau would be ruled by Jacob and bow down to him (see  ), but
          here we see Jacob bowing down before his estranged brother.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But Esau ran to Jacob and hugged him! He threw his arms around Jacob\u2019s
        neck, he kissed him, and they wept in each other\u2019s arms. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 33:4
        content: '  Imagine the sense of emotional release Jacob (Israel) must have
          felt as he stood there hugging Esau. Jacob had deceitfully kissed his father,
          pretending to be Esau (see  ). Now the two brothers shared the kiss of
          restoration. Their tears released and washed away the emotional pain of
          their past! Reconciliation between brothers always pleases God (see  ).
          Remember that, in a moment, God can turn enemies into friends. Remember
          that God turned Saul into Paul (see  )! Our hearts must always be postured
          to reconcile with others who have distanced themselves from us.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When Esau looked up and saw the women and the children, he said to
        Jacob, \u201CWho are all these coming behind you?\u201DJacob replied, \u201CThese
        are the children, your niece and nephews, whom God has so graciously given
        [[COMMENT(0)]] your servant.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 33:5
        content: "  This word comes from a Hebrew verb meaning to \u201Cbe gracious,\u201D
          \u201Cshow favor,\u201D or \u201Cbe kind to.\u201D Indeed, children are
          a gracious gift from God. See  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Then the maidservants came forward with their children and bowed
        low before Esau. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Leah likewise came forward with her children and bowed down. Finally,
        Rachel and Joseph came forward and they bowed down to the ground before Esau.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Esau asked Jacob, \u201CWhy did you send all these animals to me?\u201D\u201CI
        was hoping to find favor with you, my lord,\u201D Jacob replied."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CBut my brother,\u201D Esau laughed, \u201CI have plenty. Keep
        what you have for yourself.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Jacob replied, \u201CNo, please. If I have found favor in your eyes,
        please take the gifts. For truly, seeing your face after all these years,
        it\u2019s like looking upon the face of God! [[COMMENT(0)]] Since you have
        received me so warmly, "
      comments:
      - number: 33:10
        content: '  Jacob again saw that same glorious face of God (see  ) through
          the mending of his relationship with his brother. How sweet is forgiveness,
          how pleasant to the soul when we are made one again with those we love!
          It is like gazing on the face of God. We see God most clearly as we touch
          mercy and forgiveness. Are there some in your life that need to see the
          face of God in your countenance?    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "please accept the blessing I have brought to you, for God has poured
        his grace over me, and I have everything I want!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] So
        with these words Jacob urged him, and Esau accepted the gifts."
      comments:
      - number: 33:11
        content: '  Jacob was offering to share the blessing he took away from Esau
          many years earlier.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then Esau said, \u201CLet\u2019s start out on our journey, and I\u2019ll
        walk alongside you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "But Jacob replied, \u201CMy lord, you can see how tired the children
        are, and all our flocks and herds are nursing their young. If we drive them
        too hard for even a day, they will die. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Please, my lord, go ahead of your servant. Let me move along slowly
        with my flocks and herds, to give them a chance to graze. I must think of
        my children, too, so go ahead of me, my lord, until I catch up with you in
        Seir.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Esau said, \u201CWell, at least let me leave you with some of my
        men.\u201D\u201CYou\u2019re so kind,\u201D Jacob replied, \u201Cbut there\u2019s
        no need to do so.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So that very day Esau and his men left to return to Seir, '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: Jacob Builds an Altar at Shechem'
      title: Jacob Builds an Altar at Shechem
      number: 17
      content: but Jacob went the opposite direction to Succoth instead, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and built himself a house there. He also built shelters for his livestock,
        and that is why Jacob named the place Succoth.
      comments:
      - number: 33:17
        content: "    means \u201Cbooths,\u201D \u201Cshelter,\u201D \u201Chuts,\u201D
          or \u201Cstalls.\u201D There is a large tell, or archeological mound, called
          Deir \u2019Allah located in the center of the Jordan Valley that is now
          identified as Succoth.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Jacob\u2019s journey home from Paddan-Aram finally brought him safe
        and sound to the Canaanite city of Shechem, [[COMMENT(0)]] where he camped
        just outside of the city. "
      comments:
      - number: 33:18
        content: "  Shechem lies about forty miles north of Jerusalem and is the
          site where Abram first built an altar in the promised land (see  ). Joseph
          was eventually buried on this parcel of land (see  ). In    Jesus encountered
          a woman of Samaria in the vicinity of Sychar (Shechem). The well was on
          a piece of land which was bought by Jacob and given to his son Joseph (see 
          ). The well mentioned in    was Jacob\u2019s well. Jesus sat on top of
          the very place where Jacob dwelt at Shechem. At that time, Jacob had no
          clue that his seed would indeed sit upon that well someday. There, the
          long-awaited Messiah patiently won the soul of a sinful woman. The Mighty
          God of Israel visited Jacob\u2019s well at Shechem!    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "He purchased the field where he pitched his tent from the clan of
        Hamor, [[COMMENT(0)]] Shechem\u2019s father, for one hundred pieces of silver.   "
      comments:
      - number: 33:19
        content: "    means \u201Cdonkey.\u201D      Some ancient manuscripts have
          \u201Cone hundred sheep\u201D as the purchase price.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'There he set up an altar [[COMMENT(0)]] and named it To the True
        God, the God of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: 33:20
        content: "  Or \u201Ca pillar.\u201D      Or \u201CEl-Elohe-Israel\u201D
          or \u201CMighty is the God of Israel.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Dinah Raped by Shechem'
      title: Dinah Raped by Shechem
      number: 1
      content: "One day, Jacob and Leah\u2019s daughter, Dinah, went out to visit
        the neighborhood girls. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 34:1
        content: '  Perhaps the local women introduced her to Shechem, the prince
          of the city named for him. Dinah was likely fifteen or sixteen years old.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Now Hamor, the tribal chief of the Hivites, had a son named Shechem,
        who was the prince. When he saw how attractive Dinah was, he seized her and
        sexually assaulted her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "His heart was drawn to Dinah, Jacob\u2019s daughter, so he sought
        to win her affection and spoke tenderly to her. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Shechem went to his father Hamor and said, \u201CGet me this girl
        to be my wife.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Now Jacob heard that Shechem had violated his daughter Dinah; but
        his sons were in the fields with his livestock, so he waited to act until
        his sons returned home. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Shechem\u2019s father Hamor brought his son  [[COMMENT(0)]] to speak
        with Jacob about marriage arrangements. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:6
        content: '  From v.    we learn that Shechem was present during this conversation.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "During their conversation, Jacob\u2019s sons came in from the field,
        and they heard the report of what Shechem had done to their sister Dinah.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] They were shocked and furious over the shameful act Shechem
        committed against Israel \u2014a criminal act of sexual assault that never
        should have happened."
      comments:
      - number: 34:7
        content: "  Apparently, Dinah was still being held in Hamor\u2019s house
          within the city (see vv.  ,  ).      Or \u201Cin Israel.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But Hamor tried to defuse the situation, saying, \u201CListen, my
        son Shechem is in love with your daughter. Please, give her to him in marriage. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Let\u2019s allow our people to intermarry. [[COMMENT(0)]] Let your
        daughters marry our sons, and we will let our daughters marry your sons. "
      comments:
      - number: 34:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cpartner [with us],\u201D that is, become our brothers-in-law.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "You may settle here among us, live anywhere you wish, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        move about  freely, and acquire property.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 34:10
        content: "  Or \u201CThe land is before your faces.\u201D This could be an
          idiom meaning \u201CMake yourselves at home here.\u201D      Or \u201Ctrade\u201D
          (LXX, Vulgate, Targums).      The basic meaning of the Hebrew verb used
          here is \u201Ctake possession of land.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then Shechem spoke up and said to Dinah\u2019s family, \u201CPlease,
        let me find favor in your eyes. Whatever you require of me, I\u2019ll pay. "
      comments: []
    - name: "12: Jacob\u2019s Sons Exact Revenge"
      title: "Jacob\u2019s Sons Exact Revenge"
      number: 12
      content: "Set the bride-price as high as you wish, no matter how expensive
        it is; I\u2019ll pay whatever you ask. Only give me the young woman to be
        my wife.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The sons of Jacob concocted a devious plan. Because of the rape of
        their sister Dinah, they answered Shechem and Hamor deceitfully, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "saying, \u201COur culture will not allow us to consent to our sister
        Dinah marrying someone who is uncircumcised, for that would be a disgrace
        to us. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'We would only approve of the marriage on one condition: you must
        circumcise every male among you and become as we are. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Then we will allow our daughters to marry your sons and your daughters
        to marry our sons. And we will live among you and become one people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But if you refuse to be circumcised, then we will take our sister
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and be gone.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 34:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cdaughter.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The offer pleased Hamor and his son Shechem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "And the young man lost no time in doing what they asked, because
        Shechem really wanted to marry Jacob\u2019s daughter!Now Shechem was the
        most honored [[COMMENT(0)]] in all his family, "
      comments:
      - number: 34:19
        content: "  Or, possibly, \u201Cthe most important.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'so Hamor and his son went to the gate of the city and spoke to the
        men, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThese people are our friends. Let them settle in our land and
        make themselves at home; there\u2019s plenty of room in the country for them.
        And, let\u2019s agree to exchange our daughters in marriage to them and to
        unite us as one people. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'They only have one condition in order to live among us and to unite
        with us as one people: every male among us must be circumcised as they are
        circumcised. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Won\u2019t all of their livestock and property become ours? Let us
        agree to their request, so they will live among us.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: So all the townsmen agreed with Hamor and his son Shechem, and every
        male of the city was circumcised.
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Three days later, while all the men were still suffering in pain,
        two of Jacob\u2019s sons, Simeon and Levi, Dinah\u2019s brothers, took their
        swords and attacked the unsuspecting city. They slaughtered every male of
        the city. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "They even killed Hamor and his son Shechem, and took Dinah from Shechem\u2019s
        house, and left. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Later, Jacob\u2019s other sons came upon the dead bodies, and they
        looted the city as retribution for the violation of their sister. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They seized the flocks, herds, and donkeys, and all that was in the
        city and in the field. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: They plundered all their wealth and their household goods and took
        their wives and children as captives.
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "When Jacob found out, he said to Simeon and Levi, \u201CWhat have
        you done? You have ruined my name, [[COMMENT(0)]] and now the Canaanites
        and Perizzites and all the people of this land will hate me! My men are so
        few that if they unite against me and attack, I and all my household will
        be destroyed!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 34:30
        content: "  Or \u201CYou have muddied the waters\u201D or \u201CYou have
          made a stink.\u201D That is, they had brought trouble upon Jacob.  "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "But they answered him, \u201CWhy should they treat our sister like
        a whore?\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jacob Returns to Bethel'
      title: Jacob Returns to Bethel
      number: 1
      content: "God said to Jacob, \u201CArise, go at once to Bethel, and settle
        there. Build an altar there to God, who appeared to you when you were fleeing
        from your brother Esau.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 35:1
        content: '  Jacob fulfilled the vow he had made to God thirty years previously.
          See  .    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So Jacob said to his household and to all who were with him, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        \u201CGet rid of every foreign god you have, purify yourselves, and change
        your clothes.   "
      comments:
      - number: 35:2
        content: "  Those \u201Cwith him\u201D included the captives he took at Shechem.     
          Our old clothes symbolize the old life that must be laid aside as we put
          on Christ (see  ;  ). To change our garments is to change our manner of
          life and put on a new man (see  ).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then come with me; let us go up to Bethel. I will build an altar
        there to God who answered my prayer when I was in distress [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and whose presence has been with me wherever I have gone.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 35:3
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Then they surrendered all the foreign gods they had as well as their
        earrings. [[COMMENT(0)]] Jacob buried them under the oak tree near Shechem.
      comments:
      - number: 35:4
        content: '  Most scholars consider these earrings to have been religious
          objects, perhaps amulets or magical charms.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'As they made their way to Bethel, a tremendous fear of God fell upon
        all the cities around them, and no one dared pursue them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Jacob and all the people who were with him arrived in the land of
        Canaan at Luz, [[COMMENT(0)]] now known as Bethel. '
      comments:
      - number: 35:6
        content: "    means \u201Cdeparture\u201D or \u201Calmond tree.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'He built an altar there and named it El-Bethel, [[COMMENT(0)]] because
        it was the place that God had unveiled himself when Jacob was running from
        his brother. '
      comments:
      - number: 35:7
        content: "  That is, \u201CGod of the House of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "During that time, Rebekah\u2019s nurse Deborah died. They buried
        her under an oak tree near [[COMMENT(0)]] Bethel, and they named the place
        Weeping Oak. "
      comments:
      - number: 35:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cbelow.\u201D      Or \u201CAllon-Bacuth.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'After Jacob returned from Paddan-Aram, God appeared to him once again
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and blessed him, '
      comments:
      - number: 35:9
        content: "  \u201COnce again\u201D may refer to either Jacob\u2019s earlier
          encounter with God at Mahanaim (see  ) or the one at Penuel (see  ), but
          more likely it refers to a new experience. God revealed himself many times
          to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and he will reveal himself to this generation
          also.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "saying, \u201CYour name was once Jacob, but no longer. Your new name
        is Israel!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] God named him Israel "
      comments:
      - number: 35:10
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "and said to him, \u201CI am the God who is more than enough. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Go and have many children, and they will multiply. A nation and a gathering
        of many nations will come from you; and you will be the ancestor of kings. "
      comments:
      - number: 35:11
        content: "  Or \u201CEl Shaddai.\u201D Some translate    as \u201CAlmighty
          God\u201D or \u201CSovereign God.\u201D However, in this context, God blessed
          Jacob and gave him the power of life and multiplication. See  ;  . See
          also T. N. D. Mettinger,  , 69\u201372; R. Gordis, \u201CThe Biblical Root 
          ,\u201D  , 54 (1935): 173\u2013210.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "I will give you the land which I gave to Abraham and to Isaac, and
        after you are gone, to your descendants.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then God ascended [[COMMENT(0)]]  into heaven from the place where
        he had spoken to him. '
      comments:
      - number: 35:13
        content: "  Or \u201CElohim ascended from upon him.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Jacob set up a stone pillar to memorialize the place where he had
        met [[COMMENT(0)]] with God. He poured over it a drink offering  and anointed
        the pillar with oil. '
      comments:
      - number: 35:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cwhere God had spoken to him [Jacob].\u201D      Literally
          \u201Che poured a pouring.\u201D One may assume that it was a drink offering
          of wine. Jacob poured an offering once again over the pillar at Bethel,
          the House of God, as he had in  . See  ;  ;  ;  ;  . The drink offering
          was a unique offering that was offered by a priest in gratitude for the
          firstfruits of harvest (see  ). Often, it was poured out upon other offerings.
          Jacob himself was the drink offering that was poured out to God. The pillar
          becomes a picture of the victorious life (see  ).    "
    - name: '15: Rachel Dies in Childbirth'
      title: Rachel Dies in Childbirth
      number: 15
      content: Jacob called the place where God had spoken with him Bethel.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'From Bethel, they journeyed on, and as they were approaching Ephrath,
        Rachel went into very hard and painful labor. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "As she was having great difficulty in giving birth, the midwife said
        to her, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid, for you\u2019re having another son!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "With her dying breath, Rachel said, \u201CHis name is Son of My Sorrow,\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]] but his father called him Son of My Right Hand.   "
      comments:
      - number: 35:18
        content: "  Or, in Hebrew, \u201CBen-oni,\u201D which means \u201Cson of
          my sorrow\u201D or possibly \u201Cson of my strength.\u201D      Or, in
          Hebrew, \u201CBen-yamin\u201D [Benjamin], which means \u201Cson of my right
          hand\u201D or possibly \u201Cson of the south.\u201D In the entire universe,
          there is only one Son that is both the \u201CSon of Sorrow\u201D and the
          \u201CSon of the Right Hand\u201D! Jesus is his name! Christ is a wonderful
          person with these two aspects to his name.    describes him as the \u201Cman
          of deep sorrows,\u201D and    tells us that \u201CGod exalted him to his
          right hand.\u201D His mother Mary, like Rachel, experienced pain as Simeon
          prophesied: \u201Ca painful sword will one day pierce your inner being\u201D
          (). When her Son was raised from the dead, he rose to be at God\u2019s
          right hand (see  ).    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Rachel died and was buried on the road to Ephrath (now Bethlehem).
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 35:19
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Jacob set up a pillar to mark her burial site, and it is known as
        The Marker of Rachel\u2019s Tomb to this day. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 35:20
        content: '  This was the fourth pillar Jacob set up. The first was at Bethel
          to symbolize the end of his fleshly self-confidence, which was replaced
          with a new revelation of God and his faithfulness (see  ,  ). The second
          was a pillar at Mizpah to symbolize that God was watching over Jacob and
          could be trusted (see  ). The third was at Bethel as a pillar of his confidence
          in the Living God (see  ).    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Israel journeyed on and pitched his tent beyond Migdal Eder. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 35:21
        content: "  Or \u201CWatchtower of the Flock.\u201D This was the place where
          shepherds watched over the sacred flocks meant for temple sacrifice and
          where the Passover lamb was selected. Migdal Eder is mentioned in    as
          the possible birthplace of Jesus, Israel\u2019s Messiah. See also  .    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "While Israel was living in that land, Reuben went and slept with
        Bilhah, [[COMMENT(0)]] his father\u2019s concubine, and Israel found out.Jacob
        had twelve sons."
      comments:
      - number: 35:22
        content: "  Why would Reuben have slept with Rachel\u2019s servant girl,
          his father\u2019s concubine? Since Rachel had been Jacob\u2019s favorite
          wife before her death, Reuben hoped that by having sex with Bilhah, he
          would prevent her from taking Rachel\u2019s place. Reuben wanted his mother
          Leah to be the favored wife of Jacob and take over the leadership of his
          clan. That this episode happened immediately following Rachel\u2019s death
          seems to imply that this was at least part of Reuben\u2019s motivation
          for lying with Bilhah.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Leah\u2019s sons were Reuben (Jacob\u2019s firstborn), Simeon, Levi,
        Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun."
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Rachel\u2019s sons were Joseph and Benjamin."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "The sons of Rachel\u2019s maidservant Bilhah were Dan and Naphtali."
      comments: []
    - name: '26: The Death of Isaac'
      title: The Death of Isaac
      number: 26
      content: "The sons of Leah\u2019s maidservant Zilpah were Gad and Asher.These
        were the sons of Jacob born to him in Paddan-Aram."
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Jacob came home to his father Isaac in Mamre, near Kiriath Arba (that
        is, Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had lived as foreigners. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Isaac was one hundred and eighty when he breathed his last and died.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 35:28
        content: '  Isaac died years after Joseph was sold into Egypt as a slave.
          Isaac lived the longest of all the patriarchs.  '
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: He died an old man and had lived a full life when he joined his ancestors.
        And his sons Esau and Jacob buried him there.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Descendants of Esau'
      title: The Descendants of Esau
      number: 1
      content: 'Here are the descendants of Esau, also known as Edom:'
      comments: []
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: "Esau chose three wives from among Canaanite women: Adah (daughter
        of Elon the Hittite), Oholibamah [[COMMENT(0)]] (daughter of Anah son of
        Zibeon the Hivite ), and Basemath (Ishmael\u2019s daughter, sister of Nebaioth)."
      comments:
      - number: "36:2\u20133"
        content: "    means \u201Ca [cultic] tent-shrine.\u201D      Or \u201CHorite\u201D
          (see vv.  ).    "
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: "Esau chose three wives from among Canaanite women: Adah (daughter
        of Elon the Hittite), Oholibamah [[COMMENT(0)]] (daughter of Anah son of
        Zibeon the Hivite ), and Basemath (Ishmael\u2019s daughter, sister of Nebaioth)."
      comments:
      - number: "36:2\u20133"
        content: "    means \u201Ca [cultic] tent-shrine.\u201D      Or \u201CHorite\u201D
          (see vv.  ).    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Adah bore Eliphaz to Esau; Basemath bore Reuel; '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: and Oholibamah bore Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These are the sons who
        were born to Esau in the land of Canaan.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Esau took his wives, his sons, his daughters, and his entire household,
        and the cattle, livestock, and possessions he had acquired in the land of
        Canaan, and migrated to the land of Seir [[COMMENT(0)]] some distance from
        his brother Jacob. '
      comments:
      - number: 36:6
        content: "  As translated from the Syriac and explicitly stated in v.  .
          The Hebrew is \u201Cto a land.\u201D The Septuagint is \u201Cfrom the land
          of Canaan.\u201D See  ;  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Since the land where Jacob was living could not support their combined
        possessions and livestock, '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: Esau (also known as Edom), settled in the hill country of Seir.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'This is the account of Esau, ancestor of the Edomites in the hill
        country of Seir:'
      comments: []
    - name: '10-13: '
      title: 
      number: 10-13
      content: "Esau\u2019s wife Adah bore him one son Eliphaz, and Eliphaz had five
        sons: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz. Eliphaz also had a son with his
        concubine Timna, named Amelek.Esau\u2019s wife Basemath bore him one son
        Reuel, and Reuel had four sons: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah."
      comments: []
    - name: '10-13: '
      title: 
      number: 10-13
      content: "Esau\u2019s wife Adah bore him one son Eliphaz, and Eliphaz had five
        sons: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz. Eliphaz also had a son with his
        concubine Timna, named Amelek.Esau\u2019s wife Basemath bore him one son
        Reuel, and Reuel had four sons: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah."
      comments: []
    - name: '10-13: '
      title: 
      number: 10-13
      content: "Esau\u2019s wife Adah bore him one son Eliphaz, and Eliphaz had five
        sons: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz. Eliphaz also had a son with his
        concubine Timna, named Amelek.Esau\u2019s wife Basemath bore him one son
        Reuel, and Reuel had four sons: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah."
      comments: []
    - name: '10-13: '
      title: 
      number: 10-13
      content: "Esau\u2019s wife Adah bore him one son Eliphaz, and Eliphaz had five
        sons: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz. Eliphaz also had a son with his
        concubine Timna, named Amelek.Esau\u2019s wife Basemath bore him one son
        Reuel, and Reuel had four sons: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah."
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Esau\u2019s wife Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah and granddaughter
        of Zibeon, bore Esau three sons: Jeush, Jalam, and Korah."
      comments: []
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: "These are the tribes [[COMMENT(0)]] descended from Esau\u2019s firstborn
        son Eliphaz whom Adah bore, and who lived in Edom: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz,
        Korah, Gatam, and Amalek."
      comments:
      - number: "36:15\u201316"
        content: "  Or \u201Cclans\u201D or \u201Cchiefs,\u201D a Hebrew word related
          to \u201Cthousand.\u201D    "
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: "These are the tribes [[COMMENT(0)]] descended from Esau\u2019s firstborn
        son Eliphaz whom Adah bore, and who lived in Edom: Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz,
        Korah, Gatam, and Amalek."
      comments:
      - number: "36:15\u201316"
        content: "  Or \u201Cclans\u201D or \u201Cchiefs,\u201D a Hebrew word related
          to \u201Cthousand.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "These are the tribes descended from Esau and Basemath\u2019s son
        Reuel, who lived in Edom: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "These are the tribes descended from Esau\u2019s wife Oholibamah,
        the daughter of Anah: Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: The Descendants of Seir'
      title: The Descendants of Seir
      number: 19
      content: This concludes the list of the descendants of Esau (also known as
        Edom) and their respective tribes.
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: 'These are the tribes descended from Seir the Horite, of the original
        inhabitants of Edom: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan.
        All of these were the descendants of Seir.'
      comments: []
    - name: '20-21: '
      title: 
      number: 20-21
      content: 'These are the tribes descended from Seir the Horite, of the original
        inhabitants of Edom: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan.
        All of these were the descendants of Seir.'
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Lotan\u2019s sons were Hori and Heman, and Lotan\u2019s sister was
        Timna."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Shobal\u2019s sons were Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and Onam."
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Zibeon\u2019s sons were Aiah and Anah. This is the Anah who discovered
        the springs in the wilderness while he was grazing the donkeys of his father
        Zibeon."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Anah\u2019s son was Dishon, and Anah\u2019s daughter was Oholibamah."
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Dishon\u2019s sons were Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Keran."
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Ezer\u2019s sons were Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan."
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Dishan\u2019s sons were Uz and Aran. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29-30: The Kings of Edom'
      title: The Kings of Edom
      number: 29-30
      content: 'This concludes the list of the Horite tribes in the land of Seir:
        Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan.'
      comments: []
    - name: '29-30: The Kings of Edom'
      title: The Kings of Edom
      number: 29-30
      content: 'This concludes the list of the Horite tribes in the land of Seir:
        Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan.'
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Long before the Israelites had kings, there were eight kings who
        reigned in Edom, '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'beginning with Bela [[COMMENT(0)]] son of Beor  from the city of
        Dinhabah.   '
      comments:
      - number: 36:32
        content: "  Some etymologists link Bela to Balaam, whose father was Beor.   
          means \u201Cswallowing up\u201D or \u201Cgluttony.\u201D        means \u201Cstupid,\u201D
          \u201Cdull-hearted,\u201D \u201Cunreceptive,\u201D \u201Ccruel,\u201D \u201Cinhuman,\u201D
          or \u201Cbarbarous.\u201D        means \u201Cgiven over to judgment.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: When Bela died, Jobab [[COMMENT(0)]] son of Zerah from the city of
        Bozrah  succeeded.
      comments:
      - number: 36:33
        content: '  There is an ancient Jewish tradition that equates Jobab with
          the biblical figure of Job.      Bozrah is identified as modern Buseirah.
          See  ;  .    '
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: When Jobab died, Husham from the land of Teman succeeded him.
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: When Husham died, Hadad from the city of Avith, who was the son of
        Bedad, succeeded him. Hadad defeated the Midianites in the land of Moab.
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: When Hadad died, Samlah of Masrekah succeeded him.
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: When Samlah died, Shaul of Rehoboth-on-the-River [[COMMENT(0)]] succeeded
        him.
      comments:
      - number: 36:37
        content: '  This river is possibly Wadi el-Hesa, which formed the boundary
          of Edom and Moab, or possibly the Euphrates.    '
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: When Shaul died, Baal-Hanan son of Achbor succeeded him.
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "When Baal-Hanan son of Achbor died, Hadar [[COMMENT(0)]] from the
        city of Pau succeeded him. (His wife was Mehetabel the daughter of Matred,
        Me-Zahab\u2019s granddaughter.)"
      comments:
      - number: 36:39
        content: "  Or \u201CHadad.\u201D  "
    - name: '40-42: '
      title: 
      number: 40-42
      content: 'These are the tribes of Esau according to their clans and regions:
        Timna, Alvah, Jetheth, Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon, Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar, '
      comments: []
    - name: '40-42: '
      title: 
      number: 40-42
      content: 'These are the tribes of Esau according to their clans and regions:
        Timna, Alvah, Jetheth, Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon, Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar, '
      comments: []
    - name: '40-42: '
      title: 
      number: 40-42
      content: 'These are the tribes of Esau according to their clans and regions:
        Timna, Alvah, Jetheth, Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon, Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar, '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: Magdiel, and Iram. This concludes the list of the Edomite tribes who
        settled and possessed land in different regions of their country. All the
        Edomites descended from Esau.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: The Story of Joseph'
      title: The Story of Joseph
      number: 1-2
      content: "This is the story of the family of Jacob, who had settled in the
        land of Canaan, where his father Isaac had lived as an immigrant. [[COMMENT(0)]]Jacob\u2019s
        son Joseph was seventeen, and he served his older half brothers, the sons
        of his father\u2019s wives Bilhah and Zilpah, helping them watch over the
        flocks. One day Joseph went to his father with a bad report about their behavior. "
      comments:
      - number: "37:1\u20132"
        content: "  According to the Genesis chronologies, Isaac was alive during
          the events of this chapter and would have been one hundred and sixty-eight.
          Jacob was one hundred and eight when Joseph was sold into slavery. See
          JPS Torah Commentary:  , Nahum Sarna.      Although we are not told exactly
          what the \u201Cbad report\u201D contained, Joseph\u2019s brothers saw him
          as a tattle-tale and trouble maker. He may have exaggerated or slandered
          his brothers to his father.    "
    - name: '1-2: The Story of Joseph'
      title: The Story of Joseph
      number: 1-2
      content: "This is the story of the family of Jacob, who had settled in the
        land of Canaan, where his father Isaac had lived as an immigrant. [[COMMENT(0)]]Jacob\u2019s
        son Joseph was seventeen, and he served his older half brothers, the sons
        of his father\u2019s wives Bilhah and Zilpah, helping them watch over the
        flocks. One day Joseph went to his father with a bad report about their behavior. "
      comments:
      - number: "37:1\u20132"
        content: "  According to the Genesis chronologies, Isaac was alive during
          the events of this chapter and would have been one hundred and sixty-eight.
          Jacob was one hundred and eight when Joseph was sold into slavery. See
          JPS Torah Commentary:  , Nahum Sarna.      Although we are not told exactly
          what the \u201Cbad report\u201D contained, Joseph\u2019s brothers saw him
          as a tattle-tale and trouble maker. He may have exaggerated or slandered
          his brothers to his father.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Now Israel\u2019s love for Joseph surpassed that for his other sons
        because he was born to him in his old age. [[COMMENT(0)]] So Israel had made
        him a richly ornamented robe.   "
      comments:
      - number: 37:3
        content: "  Jacob was ninety-one when Joseph was born. Joseph and his baby
          brother Benjamin were the only two sons Jacob had with his beloved Rachel.     
          Or \u201Ca coat of many colors\u201D (LXX, Vulgate), a long-sleeved tunic
          that went down to his feet. Most tunics worn by men would only go down
          to the knees and were often made without sleeves. This robe was not something
          one would wear at work but was considered to be a robe of special significance
          for a prince. The same Hebrew word is found in    referring to the robe
          of a princess. Fully aware of what happened with parental favoritism between
          him and his brother Esau, Jacob still lavished preference upon Joseph.
          It is possible that Jacob was designating Joseph as the royal priest of
          his family, thus bypassing Reuben, the firstborn, and planting seeds of
          angry jealousy in the hearts of all his half brothers.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "When Joseph\u2019s brothers saw that their father loved him more
        than he loved them, they hated him and would not speak a kind word to him.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 37:4
        content: "  Or possibly, \u201Cthey pushed aside every attempt by Joseph
          to be friendly.\u201D See Shadal; cf. Tanh. B. Gen. 180.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'One night Joseph had a dream, and when he shared it with his brothers,
        they hated him even more! '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CListen to this dream I had,\u201D he told them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CThere we were, binding sheaves of grain in the field. Suddenly,
        my sheaf rose up and stood upright. Then your sheaves gathered around mine
        and bowed down to mine!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "His brothers asked him, \u201COh, so you think you\u2019re going
        to be our king? Do you actually think you\u2019re destined to rule over us?\u201D
        So, the dream that he told them about made them hate him even more."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then another night he had a dream, and he shared it with his brothers,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CListen, I had another dream. This time, the
        sun and moon and eleven stars were bowing down to me.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 37:9
        content: "  The Septuagint adds \u201Cand he shared it with his father.\u201D     
          These dreams had a major influence on Joseph\u2019s life from that day
          forward. If you had a dream about the stars of heaven bowing down to you,
          do you not think it would affect you? Joseph behaved with excellence because
          he saw himself as a \u201Cstar.\u201D When you understand what motivated
          young Joseph, you will understand the true significance of the following
          chapters.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "When his father and brothers heard it, his father scolded him, \u201CWhat
        kind of dream is that? Do you really think that I, and your mother, and your
        brothers are going to come and bow to the ground before you?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Joseph Sold by His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Sold by His Brothers
      number: 11
      content: "So his brothers grew more jealous of him, but his father kept pondering
        Joseph\u2019s dream. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 37:11
        content: "  Even though the sheaves, stars, sun, and moon would all bow down
          to Joseph, his family missed it! They were \u201Csheaves\u201D and \u201Cstars,\u201D
          not thorns and snakes. Everyone in the family would be favored. The sheaves
          of grain were Jacob\u2019s sons. They were God\u2019s crop on the earth\u2014a
          ripened, harvested crop. They were stars, bright lights shining in the
          heavens. Instead of provoking his brothers to jealousy, this dream could
          have brought them joy over God\u2019s mercy to them as a family. The second
          dream spoke of government. God informed Joseph through the symbols of the
          sun, moon, and stars that the government would be given to Joseph one day.
          In    the lights of the sky were to \u201Crule\u201D the day and \u201Crule\u201D
          the night. These governing bodies bowing down to Joseph spoke of the great
          authority he would one day be given over his brothers. This second dream
          is much like the vision in  . The woman clothed with the sun signifies
          God\u2019s people (bride), with the moon under her feet and the crown of
          twelve stars on her head. We must see God\u2019s church as ready to give
          birth to a corporate expression of Christ as his Body on the earth. From
          the standpoint of eternity, God sees us all as sheaves full of life and
          stars full of light. Although the sons of Jacob sinned, Christ still came
          through them (see  ;  ). The jealous brothers had no faith in Joseph\u2019s
          dreams, but Jacob, having been broken by God, kept the matter in his heart,
          for even Jacob had received messages from God in dreams.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "One day, when his brothers had gone to Shechem to care for their
        father\u2019s flock, "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Israel called for Joseph and said to him, \u201CYour brothers are
        grazing the flocks near Shechem. I want you to go join them.\u201D\u201CYes,
        Father, I\u2019ll go.\u201D Joseph replied."
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Jacob added, \u201CGo find out how your brothers are doing with the
        flocks and bring word back to me.\u201D So, his father sent him off from
        the valley of Hebron. [[COMMENT(0)]]When Joseph arrived at Shechem "
      comments:
      - number: 37:14
        content: "  Shechem is at least a four-day walk from the valley of Hebron.
          Joseph left Hebron (which means \u201Cfellowship\u201D) to visit his brothers.
          Jesus left the fellowship of heaven to reveal his Father\u2019s love to
          those who killed him out of jealousy. Joseph\u2019s life story is a vivid
          preview of the life of Christ.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "and began to roam the countryside looking for his brothers, a man
        approached him and asked, \u201CWhat are you looking for?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CI\u2019m looking for my brothers, who are taking care of their
        flock,\u201D he answered. \u201CPlease tell me, do you know where they are?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "The man replied, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CThey\u2019ve left here already.
        I overheard them mention that they were going to Dothan.\u201D So, Joseph
        took off to catch up with his brothers and found them at Dothan. "
      comments:
      - number: 37:17
        content: "  Who was this man who directed Joseph to Dothan? Was it an angel?
          Perhaps. It was God\u2019s hand that led Joseph into this encounter with
          his angry brothers. God began the process of exalting Joseph through this
          encounter. God would send him ahead of his brothers into Egypt (see  ).     
          , the home of Elisha, means \u201Ctwo wells.\u201D Dothan is about a day\u2019s
          walk from Shechem.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'As he was still a long distance away, the brothers recognized him
        by his robe, and by the time he reached them, they had plotted together to
        kill him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "They said to each other, \u201CHere comes this dream expert. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 37:19
        content: "  Or \u201Clord dreamer\u201D or \u201Cmaster dreamer.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Let\u2019s kill him [[COMMENT(0)]] and throw his body into one of
        these dry wells. We can say that a wild animal ate him. Then we\u2019ll see
        how his dreams turn out!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 37:20
        content: '  His brothers scorned him for his gift and hated him for his dreams.
          They could not endure the thought of bowing down to a younger brother that
          was more favored than they were. Rather than bow down to Joseph, they sought
          to kill him. See  .    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "When Reuben heard of this, he tried to save Joseph\u2019s life. \u201CDon\u2019t
        take his life,\u201D he said. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CNo bloodshed! Let\u2019s throw him into this pit in the middle
        of nowhere, but don\u2019t hurt him.\u201D Reuben said these things because
        he planned to return later to rescue Joseph and take him back to his father.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 37:22
        content: "  Reuben was Jacob\u2019s firstborn and would have had the responsibility
          of representing his father\u2019s interests.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'When Joseph finally caught up with his brothers, they seized him,
        stripped him of his ornamented robe, his beautiful full-length robe, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: and threw him into the dry, empty pit. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 37:24
        content: "  If we will remain faithful in a time of betrayal, we will be
          restored and wear the favor-garment once again. Joseph\u2019s life was
          really a series of three robes: the \u201Crobe of favor\u201D given to
          him by Jacob and taken by his jealous brothers, the \u201Cstolen robe\u201D
          that Potiphar\u2019s wife ripped from him to falsely accuse him, and the
          \u201Croyal robe\u201D of reigning in Egypt as God\u2019s savior for Israel.
          That coat of many colors had to go before God could use young Joseph. What
          is there in your life that must be taken from you before you can be set
          free to be God\u2019s instrument?    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Afterward, the brothers sat down to eat their food. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        When they looked up, they saw a caravan of Ishmaelite merchants coming from
        Gilead on their way to Egypt. They had many camels loaded with myrrh, spices,
        and perfumes. '
      comments:
      - number: 37:25
        content: "  What callous indifference Joseph\u2019s brothers demonstrated
          as they sat near the well, eating a meal! No doubt they were within earshot
          of Joseph\u2019s cries, asking them for help.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Judah spoke up and said to his brothers, \u201CWhat will we gain
        by murdering our brother and covering up his blood? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 37:26
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "I have an idea! Let\u2019s sell Joseph to these Ishmaelites and not
        lay a hand on him, for he is our brother, our own flesh and blood.\u201D
        His brothers agreed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "And when the Midianites (also known as Ishmaelites)  [[COMMENT(0)]]
        came by, Joseph\u2019s brothers lifted him out of the pit, and sold him to
        the Ishmaelites for twenty pieces of silver,  and the merchants took Joseph
        far away to Egypt."
      comments:
      - number: 37:28
        content: "  See  ; see also \u201CMidianites\u201D in  , page 634.      In
          that day, twenty silver shekels was the going price to purchase a young
          male slave. See the Laws of Hammurabi, pars. 116, 214, 252; see also  .
          Isn\u2019t it amazing how the Lord sent the merchants from Midian at just
          the right time for Joseph? The Lord has ways to deliver us that are beyond
          our comprehension. It is ridiculous to even try to figure out how God will
          pull it off\u2014he just will! Judah sold Joseph for twenty pieces of silver;
          Judas (Judah) sold Jesus for thirty (see  ). Whenever we devalue one another,
          we are selling one another, \u201Cshortchanging\u201D one another, failing
          to understand a person\u2019s true value. How could a life be sold for
          mere silver? If Joseph\u2019s brothers had valued him as a sheaf or a star,
          they would not have sold him.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Later, Reuben went to the pit, and saw that Joseph was gone. He was
        overcome with grief and tore his clothes. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "He went to his brothers and said, \u201CThe boy is gone! What am
        I going to do now?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then they took Joseph\u2019s colorful robe, killed a goat, and dipped
        the robe in its blood. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 37:31
        content: '  This account contains significant irony, for it was    hair that
          Jacob used to deceive his father Isaac. Now it was    blood that was used
          to deceive the deceiver. See  ,  .    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "They took the blood-stained robe back to their father and said, \u201CWe
        found this. Look it over\u2014doesn\u2019t it belong to your son?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Jacob recognized it instantly and cried out, \u201CIt\u2019s my son\u2019s
        robe! Some wild animal must have killed him. My son Joseph has been torn
        to pieces!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 37:33
        content: '  The Hebrew text contains a powerful lament in these three words
          with alliteration:  .    '
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Overcome with grief, Jacob tore his clothes, put on sackcloth, and
        mourned for his son a long time. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "All his sons and daughters [[COMMENT(0)]] came and tried to comfort
        him, but he refused to be comforted. He told them, \u201CNo, I will mourn
        for him the rest of my life, until I join my son in the realm of the dead.\u201D 
        Joseph\u2019s father wept and wept for his son."
      comments:
      - number: 37:35
        content: "  \u201CDaughters\u201D refers to Dinah and Jacob\u2019s daughters-in-law.     
          Or \u201CSheol\u201D or \u201Cthe underworld.\u201D This is the first reference
          to Sheol in the Bible, which refers to a place believed to be beneath the
          earth where departed souls exist in the gloom of death, darkness, and silence.    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Meanwhile, the Midianites took Joseph to Egypt and sold him to Potiphar,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] one of Pharaoh\u2019s officials, the captain of the guard. "
      comments:
      - number: 37:36
        content: "    means \u201Cgiven by the sun-god Ra\u201D or \u201Cone who
          belongs to the sun-god Ra.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe chief executioner.\u201D
          He was the warden over the Egyptian penal system and, perhaps, the chief
          steward over Pharaoh\u2019s affairs.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Story of Judah and Tamar'
      title: The Story of Judah and Tamar
      number: 1
      content: 'Around that time, Judah left his brothers at Hebron and went to Adullam
        [[COMMENT(0)]] to stay with a man named Hirah.   '
      comments:
      - number: 38:1
        content: "  From Hebron to Adullam was a day\u2019s journey of about twelve
          miles.        means \u201Cfading\u201D or \u201Cto turn pale.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'There he met and married a Canaanite girl, the daughter of Shua.
        He slept with her and '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'she became pregnant and gave birth to a son, and Judah [[COMMENT(0)]]
        named him Er. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:3
        content: "  Some Hebrew manuscripts, the Samaritan Pentateuch, and one ancient
          Targum have \u201Cshe [Bath-Shua] named him.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'She conceived again and gave birth to another son and named him Onan.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 38:4
        content: "    means \u201Cstrong\u201D or \u201Cvigorous.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'While they [[COMMENT(0)]] were staying in Chezib,  she gave birth
        to a third son and named him Shelah. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:5
        content: "  Or \u201Che\u201D or \u201Cshe\u201D (LXX).      Chezib was a
          village about three miles south of Adullam and is likely the \u201CAchzib\u201D
          mentioned in  .    means \u201Cfalse.\u201D        means \u201Ca request\u201D
          or \u201Csomething asked for.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When their sons were grown, Judah arranged for Er, his oldest son,
        to marry a girl named Tamar. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 38:6
        content: "    means \u201Cdate palm.\u201D The Midrash states that Tamar
          was the daughter of Noah\u2019s son, Shem. See    85:10. This conjecture
          would mean that Tamar was not Canaanite (since Canaan was the cursed son
          of Ham), but was a descendant of Shem, just like the sons of Israel.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'But Er had become so wicked in the sight of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> ended his life. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then Judah said to Er\u2019s brother Onan, \u201CYour duty [[COMMENT(0)]]
        is to join yourself to her. Go perform your duty as a brother-in-law and
        provide an heir for your brother.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 38:8
        content: "  This custom, called \u201Clevirate marriage,\u201D was later
          adopted into Hebrew law (see  ). It was a disgrace for a dead man\u2019s
          living brothers to fail to have children with the widow of the deceased.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Onan, however, did not want to produce a child that would not be
        his own rightful heir, [[COMMENT(0)]] so whenever he and Tamar had intercourse,
        he purposely spilled his semen onto the ground to keep her from getting pregnant
        and having a child that would belong to his dead brother. '
      comments:
      - number: 38:9
        content: "  Since Onan\u2019s brother Er, the firstborn, died, Onan stood
          in line to receive a great inheritance from his father Judah. But if he
          fathered a child with Er\u2019s widow, that inheritance would be greatly
          diminished.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But what he did was wicked in <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, so he took Onan\u2019s life also."
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then Judah said to his daughter-in-law Tamar, \u201CLive as a widow
        in your father\u2019s house until my youngest son Shelah grows up.\u201D
        So Tamar went home to her parents, but Judah worried that Shelah would end
        up dead like his brothers. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 38:11
        content: '  In other words, since Judah lost two of his sons already, he
          had no intention of ever giving Shelah to Tamar, fearing he would lose
          him too.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "After some time passed, Judah\u2019s wife, the daughter of Shua,
        died. When his time of mourning was over, he and his friend Hirah the Adullamite
        went to Timnah [[COMMENT(0)]]  to enjoy the festivities at the sheep-shearing.   "
      comments:
      - number: 38:12
        content: '  Timnah is about four miles northeast of Adullam.      The time
          of shearing the sheep was a time of celebration and festivities. See  , 
          ;  ,  .    '
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Meanwhile, Tamar had learned that Shelah had grown up, but Judah
        had still not given him to her to father a child for her deceased husband.
        So, when Tamar found out her father-in-law was coming to Timnah for the sheep-shearing,
        she removed her widow\u2019s clothes and covered herself with a veil to disguise
        herself. And she sat waiting at the crossroads [[COMMENT(0)]] where Judah
        would have to pass by."
      comments:
      - number: "38:13\u201314"
        content: "  Or \u201CShe sat at the entrance to Enaim.\u201D    means \u201Ccrossroads\u201D
          or \u201Cintersection.\u201D    "
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Meanwhile, Tamar had learned that Shelah had grown up, but Judah
        had still not given him to her to father a child for her deceased husband.
        So, when Tamar found out her father-in-law was coming to Timnah for the sheep-shearing,
        she removed her widow\u2019s clothes and covered herself with a veil to disguise
        herself. And she sat waiting at the crossroads [[COMMENT(0)]] where Judah
        would have to pass by."
      comments:
      - number: "38:13\u201314"
        content: "  Or \u201CShe sat at the entrance to Enaim.\u201D    means \u201Ccrossroads\u201D
          or \u201Cintersection.\u201D    "
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: "When Judah saw her, she was wearing a veil over her face, so he thought
        she was a prostitute. He had no clue that she was his own daughter-in-law.
        So he approached her and said, \u201CCome sleep with me.\u201D\u201CWhat
        will you give me if I do?\u201D she answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '15-16: '
      title: 
      number: 15-16
      content: "When Judah saw her, she was wearing a veil over her face, so he thought
        she was a prostitute. He had no clue that she was his own daughter-in-law.
        So he approached her and said, \u201CCome sleep with me.\u201D\u201CWhat
        will you give me if I do?\u201D she answered."
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He responded, \u201CI will send you a young goat from the flock.\u201D\u201CWhat
        guarantee can you give me that you will really send it?\u201D she asked."
      comments: []
    - name: '18-19: '
      title: 
      number: 18-19
      content: "\u201CWell, what pledge do you want?\u201D Judah asked.Tamar answered,
        \u201CGive me your necklace with your personal signet [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        the staff  you\u2019re holding.\u201D So, he gave them to her, and he went
        and slept with her. When she got up and went home, she removed her veil and
        put her widow\u2019s garment back on. Later, she discovered she was pregnant."
      comments:
      - number: "38:18\u201319"
        content: "  This \u201Csignet\u201D refers to an engraved cylinder seal.
          \u201CThe center was hollowed out and a cord passed through so that the
          seal could be worn around the neck. When the cylinder was rolled over soft
          clay, the resultant impression served as a means of identifying personal
          possessions and of sealing and legitimating clay documents. It was a highly
          personal object that performed the function of the signature in modern
          society\u201D (JPS Torah Commentary:  , Nahum M. Sarna).      Or \u201C[tribal]
          scepter.\u201D The leaders of the twelve tribes of Israel each had scepters
          (see  ).    "
    - name: '18-19: '
      title: 
      number: 18-19
      content: "\u201CWell, what pledge do you want?\u201D Judah asked.Tamar answered,
        \u201CGive me your necklace with your personal signet [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        the staff  you\u2019re holding.\u201D So, he gave them to her, and he went
        and slept with her. When she got up and went home, she removed her veil and
        put her widow\u2019s garment back on. Later, she discovered she was pregnant."
      comments:
      - number: "38:18\u201319"
        content: "  This \u201Csignet\u201D refers to an engraved cylinder seal.
          \u201CThe center was hollowed out and a cord passed through so that the
          seal could be worn around the neck. When the cylinder was rolled over soft
          clay, the resultant impression served as a means of identifying personal
          possessions and of sealing and legitimating clay documents. It was a highly
          personal object that performed the function of the signature in modern
          society\u201D (JPS Torah Commentary:  , Nahum M. Sarna).      Or \u201C[tribal]
          scepter.\u201D The leaders of the twelve tribes of Israel each had scepters
          (see  ).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Soon afterward, Judah sent the young goat by his friend Hirah the
        Adullamite to recover his items from the prostitute, but she was nowhere
        to be found. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "So he asked the townspeople, \u201CWhere is the temple prostitute
        that sits by the crossroads?\u201DThey answered, \u201CNo prostitute has
        been there.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "So he returned to Judah and informed him, \u201CI couldn\u2019t find
        her, and besides that, the townspeople said that no prostitute has been there.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Judah replied, \u201CLet her keep my pledge. If we try to go get
        it now, we\u2019ll become a laughingstock. [[COMMENT(0)]] After all, I did
        send you with the payment I promised her, and you couldn\u2019t find her.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 38:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cwe\u2019ll appear contemptible [dishonest].\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "About three months later, Judah was told, \u201CYour daughter-in-law
        Tamar has been promiscuous, and now she is pregnant!\u201D Indignant, Judah
        said, \u201CBring her out, and let her be burned!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 38:24
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "As she was being brought out, she sent word to her father-in-law,
        \u201CLook, the one who owns these things got me pregnant! See, whose signet
        and staff are these?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Judah recognized them as his and said, \u201CShe is more righteous
        than I, for I never gave my son Shelah to marry her.\u201D And he let her
        go free and never slept with her again. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 38:26
        content: "  Or \u201Che did not know her again.\u201D \u201CTo know her\u201D
          is a Hebrew figure of speech for having sex with her. In chs.    and   
          we have two contrasting accounts of lust and the evil it spawns. Why this
          abrupt interruption of the incredible story of Joseph? Why did God include
          this chapter in his inspired Word? One reason is that God wanted to paint
          a contrast between Judah\u2019s unwise choices and immorality and Joseph\u2019s
          righteous character, which is revealed in the following chapter.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When it was time for her to give birth, there were twins in her womb! '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "While she was in labor, one hand popped out, so the midwife wrapped
        a crimson thread around its wrist, saying, \u201CThis one came out first.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "But immediately, he drew his hand back, and out came his brother;
        and she said, \u201CLook how you have broken out of the womb!\u201D So, he
        was named Perez, the one who breaks through. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 38:29
        content: "    means \u201Cbreach\u201D or \u201Cbreaking through.\u201D Perez
          was an ancestor of King David (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Afterward, his brother came out, the one with the crimson thread
        on his wrist. That\u2019s why they named him Zerah [[COMMENT(0)]] (\u201Cthe
        crimson one\u201D)."
      comments:
      - number: 38:30
        content: "    comes from a word that sounds like \u201C[dawn\u2019s] crimson
          brightness.\u201D Or, it could be taken from an Aramaic root for \u201Ccrimson
          [thread].\u201D Achan (see  ) was a descendant of Zerah (see  ).  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joseph Serves Potiphar'
      title: Joseph Serves Potiphar
      number: 1
      content: 'After the Ishmaelite traders brought Joseph down to Egypt, he was
        purchased by an Egyptian officer [[COMMENT(0)]] of Pharaoh, the captain of
        the guard, whose name was Potiphar.   '
      comments:
      - number: 39:1
        content: "  This is actually the Hebrew word for \u201Ceunuch.\u201D In Egyptian
          culture, the key officials surrounding the king were made eunuchs to prevent
          them from having sons that would compete for the throne. This may help
          the reader understand why Potiphar\u2019s wife chased after Joseph later
          in the chapter.        means \u201Cgiven by the sun-god Ra\u201D or \u201Cone
          who belongs to the sun-god Ra.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s presence was with Joseph and
        he became successful [[COMMENT(0)]] while living in the house of his Egyptian
        master. "
      comments:
      - number: 39:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cprosperous.\u201D The implication is that Joseph excelled
          in everything. God\u2019s presence and favor do more for us than our skill,
          intelligence, and cleverness could achieve. God had his hand in everything
          that happened to Joseph, and he has his hand in everything that happens
          to you (see  ).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "When his master realized that <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence was with Joseph [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps> and caused
        everything he did to prosper, "
      comments:
      - number: 39:3
        content: "  The Talmud teaches that the Hebrew text should be translated
          as \u201Cwas continually on Joseph\u2019s lips\u201D; in other words, Potiphar
          noted that Joseph did everything as unto God and gave him the glory. There
          is something trustworthy about a person with no agenda other than to give
          God glory in everything.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Joseph found favor with Potiphar. He was quickly promoted to become
        the overseer of Potiphar\u2019s house and was put in charge of all that he
        had. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "From the moment Potiphar appointed Joseph over his household, <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        blessed the Egyptian\u2019s affairs for Joseph\u2019s sake. The blessing
        of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> was upon everything Potiphar owned; his
        finances increased, his crops flourished, and his flocks and herds multiplied.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 39:5
        content: "  Or \u201Ceverything Potiphar owned, at home and in the field.\u201D    "
    - name: "6: Joseph and Potiphar\u2019s Wife"
      title: "Joseph and Potiphar\u2019s Wife"
      number: 6
      content: "So Potiphar placed all that he owned under Joseph\u2019s oversight.
        And with Joseph in charge, Potiphar had nothing to worry about, except deciding
        on what to eat! [[COMMENT(0)]]Now Joseph was strikingly handsome, very good-looking,
        and well-built.   "
      comments:
      - number: 39:6
        content: "  Or possibly a figure of speech for \u201Chis private affairs,\u201D
          or euphemistically for \u201Chis wife.\u201D      No other man is described
          in these terms in the Bible; however the Hebrew phrase is nearly identical
          to the description of Rachel (see  ).    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "It wasn\u2019t long before his master\u2019s wife [[COMMENT(0)]]
        noticed Joseph. She demanded: \u201CCome make love to me.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 39:7
        content: "  Although unnamed, Hebrew tradition identifies Potiphar\u2019s
          wife as Zuleika. As an Egyptian aristocrat, she was no doubt a beautiful
          woman.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CNever!\u201D Joseph replied. \u201CDon\u2019t you realize that
        my master has nothing to worry about with me in charge, for he has put everything
        he has under my care? "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "There is no one greater in his household than me, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        nor has he kept anything back from me except you, because you\u2019re his
        wife. Why would I want to do such an immoral thing and sin against God?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 39:9
        content: "  Joseph understood the great favor shown to him and could not
          violate the trust of his master. He valued Potiphar\u2019s trust in him.
          Joseph knew that he was elevated to a place of honor; nothing was held
          back from him. Joseph had self-respect and respected Potiphar\u2019s wife.
          Though she was evil, he was honorable toward her.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Yet day after day, she was determined to seduce him. But Joseph continually
        refused her advances and would not even go near her. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Then one day, when he had to go into the house to do his work and
        no one else was there, '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "she grabbed him by his robe and said, \u201CCome on, sleep with me!\u201D
        But he abruptly ran out of the house, leaving his robe in her hands! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 39:12
        content: "  Interestingly, the triliteral Hebrew root for \u201Crobe,\u201D 
          , has a homonym meaning \u201Cmarital fidelity.\u201D There are times when
          running is the mark of a coward, and there are times when running is the
          mark of courage. Joseph would rather run in embarrassment than linger,
          falling into the trap of sexual promiscuity (see  ). Self-control is a
          true sign of integrity. It is better to lose a good coat than a good conscience!
          He may have lost his coat, but Joseph kept his character. If the Lord has
          destined you for greatness, if God has a work for you to do, there should
          be no surprise when this kind of temptation comes to you.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Realizing he had fled, and she was holding his robe in her hands, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "she called for her household servants and said to them, \u201CSee!
        My husband brings this Hebrew foreigner here to make fools of us! [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He barged into my house and tried to have sex with me, and I screamed; "
      comments:
      - number: 39:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cto play with us,\u201D a possible euphemism for having
          sex with them.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "and when he heard me scream for help, he ran out of the house and
        left his robe!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'She kept the robe beside her until his master came home '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "and she told him the same story: \u201CThis Hebrew foreigner you
        brought among us barged into the house and tried to violate me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: Joseph Goes to Prison'
      title: Joseph Goes to Prison
      number: 18
      content: "As soon as I screamed out for help, he ran outside and left his robe
        here beside me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "When his master heard his wife\u2019s account about how his servant
        had treated her, he became furious. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 39:19
        content: "  The text does not say with whom Potiphar was furious. Perhaps
          he knew his wife\u2019s promiscuous ways. He had Joseph only thrown into
          prison when a man with his authority could have had him killed. Perhaps
          he doubted the truth of her story, but to save face, he had Joseph imprisoned.
          According to the  , Asenath, the daughter of Potiphar, did her best to
          convince her father of Joseph\u2019s innocence and what really happened.
          Later, when Joseph was freed from prison, Asenath became Joseph\u2019s
          wife.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "So Joseph\u2019s master took him and threw him into prison, the place
        where the king\u2019s prisoners are confined, and he was left there. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 39:20
        content: "  In    we learn that Joseph\u2019s feet were in chains and an
          iron collar was placed on his neck (or \u201Chis soul\u201D). It would
          be hard to imagine a lower point in Joseph\u2019s life. Betrayed by his
          brothers, sold as slave, and falsely accused, he suffered for a season
          until his time of deliverance arrived. As hard as it may seem, God may
          allow others to take advantage of us in order to carry out his secret will
          for our life. He will let us look like a fool in order to perfect our character.
          This is \u201Cthe place where [our King\u2019s] prisoners are confined\u201D
          (; see  )!    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'But <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> was with Joseph and demonstrated
        to him his faithful love by giving him great favor in the sight of the warden. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The warden put all the prisoners under Joseph\u2019s care; he was
        placed in charge of all the prisoners and everything in the prison. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "The warden had no worries about the prison with Joseph in charge,
        because <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>\u2019s presence was with Joseph and
        caused everything Joseph did to prosper. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 39:23
        content: "  Joseph had a God-favored life. A study of the life of Joseph
          is a study of the favor of God. He was faithful as a son, a shepherd, and
          a servant. He was diligent in all that he did. Wisdom guided him, even
          in a strange land, and everything he did prospered (see  )! He not only
          adjusted to living in Egypt but also flourished and became the personal
          attendant (administrator) of Potiphar\u2019s affairs and eventually the
          supervisor of the penal system. Joseph would never have been given such
          an honor if he had not demonstrated a high degree of integrity and faithfulness.
          Everyone could see that God was with Joseph. He that was faithful over
          a few things was now being made a ruler over much. See  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Cupbearer and the Baker and Their Dreams'
      title: The Cupbearer and the Baker and Their Dreams
      number: 1
      content: "Some time later, [[COMMENT(0)]] both Pharaoh\u2019s chief steward 
        and chief baker deeply offended their master, the king of Egypt.   "
      comments:
      - number: 40:1
        content: "  Eleven years had passed since the time Joseph was sold into slavery.
          He was about twenty-eight at this time.      Or \u201Ccupbearer\u201D (lit.
          \u201Cdrink-giver\u201D). He was the king\u2019s trusted official and had
          a position to influence Pharaoh.      Jewish tradition states that a fly
          had fallen into Pharaoh\u2019s cup of wine, and a pebble was found in his
          bread, thus causing this \u201Coffense.\u201D See Midrash: by Rashi.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Pharaoh was angry with his two officers, the chief steward and the
        chief baker, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'so he incarcerated them in the palace of Potiphar, the captain of
        the guard, in the same prison where Joseph was bound. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The captain of the guard placed them under Joseph\u2019s charge,
        and they remained in custody for some time. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 40:4
        content: "  Jesus was falsely accused, maligned, and crucified between two
          thieves. At Calvary, the one thief was released (to enter paradise), and
          the other killed. So it was with the two men imprisoned with Joseph, three
          days after they were released! Christ was rejected by his brothers (see 
          ), sold by one of his own (see  ), and eventually cast into the prison
          of death (see  ).    gives us additional information about Joseph\u2019s
          time in prison: \u201CHis feet were bruised by strong shackles and his
          soul was held by iron.\u201D The last phrase can be translated \u201Chis
          soul entered into iron.\u201D The inner strength of loving and serving
          in painful circumstances made Joseph\u2019s soul as strong as iron. He
          learned to serve and to rule over himself first, before God released him
          to rule over others.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then one night, they both dreamed\u2014the steward and the baker,
        officials of the king of Egypt. They each had a prophetic dream with different
        interpretations."
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When Joseph came to them in the morning, he saw they looked miserable, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "so he asked Pharaoh\u2019s two officials who were under his custody,
        \u201CWhat\u2019s wrong? Why the sad faces?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CWe had dreams last night,\u201D they answered, \u201Cand we
        have no one to interpret them.\u201DAnd Joseph said to them, \u201CGod can
        interpret your dreams! Please, tell them to me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "So the chief steward shared his dream with Joseph first. He said,
        \u201CIn my dream, I saw a vine with three branches in front of me. I watched
        as it budded, then immediately it blossomed, and its clusters ripened into
        grapes. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9-10: '
      title: 
      number: 9-10
      content: "So the chief steward shared his dream with Joseph first. He said,
        \u201CIn my dream, I saw a vine with three branches in front of me. I watched
        as it budded, then immediately it blossomed, and its clusters ripened into
        grapes. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "I was holding Pharaoh\u2019s cup, so I took the grapes, squeezed
        them into his cup, and handed the cup to the king.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Joseph said to him, \u201CGod has given me the interpretation of
        your dream: The three branches are three days. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "In three days, Pharaoh will pardon you and restore you to your post.
        You will once again hand Pharaoh\u2019s cup to him as you used to do as his
        steward. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When things start to go well for you, remember me, and please be
        kind and mention me to Pharaoh so that he might release me from here. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 40:14
        content: '  Joseph could prophesy the release of another, but not his own.
          Often, prophetic gifts and words of revelation over other people simply
          do not come for the prophet. They are gifts to be used to bless others,
          not for self-consumption. We need others to come with a word for our need.
          This keeps us dependent not only upon God but also upon others.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "For I was kidnapped from the land of the Hebrews, and I have done
        nothing here to deserve being thrown into this dungeon.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 40:15
        content: "  Joseph felt forgotten. He had been forgotten a long, long time.
          He became a slave when he was seventeen years old, and soon afterward,
          Potiphar cast him into prison. Not until he was thirty did Pharaoh release
          him from prison. Thirteen years is a long time to be forgotten. His faith
          in God and the fulfillment of his dreams kept Joseph faithfully waiting
          for his day of promotion. Perhaps, like Joseph, you have been let down
          by others who promised to be a help to you but did not follow through on
          their pledge. Don\u2019t despair, for God will never forget the plans he
          has for his children (see  ). Even if others let us down, God is always
          faithful and will bring his plans to pass at the appointed time.  "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When the chief baker saw how favorably Joseph interpreted the dream,
        he said to him, \u201CLet me tell you my dream. I saw three wicker breadbaskets
        stacked on my head one above the other. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "In the top basket, I saw all kinds of bread and pastries for Pharaoh
        to enjoy, but the birds came and ate out of the basket above my head.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Joseph said, \u201CGod has given me the interpretation of your dream:
        The three baskets are three days. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "In three days, Pharaoh will behead you and impale you on a pole,
        and birds will eat the flesh off your corpse.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Three days later, it was Pharaoh\u2019s birthday, and he threw a
        huge feast for all his household. He singled out among his servants the chief
        steward and the chief baker. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'He pardoned the chief steward and restored him to his post, and the
        steward handed Pharaoh his drink. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But he had the chief baker beheaded and impaled on a pole. So, Joseph
        had accurately interpreted both their dreams, '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: but the chief steward completely forgot about Joseph and never remembered
        him.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: From the Pit to the Palace'
      title: From the Pit to the Palace
      number: 1
      content: 'After two full years, Pharaoh dreamed that he was standing by the
        Nile, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'and up from the river emerged seven healthy, fat cows, and they began
        grazing in the marshland. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then he saw seven other cows come up out of the Nile right behind
        them. They were ugly and thin, and they stood beside the fat cows on the
        riverbank. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The seven ugly, thin cows ate up the seven healthy, fat cows.After
        Pharaoh\u2019s dream he awoke "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'and fell back to sleep. He dreamed a second time. In his dream, he
        saw seven ears of grain, plump, ripe, and growing on a single stalk. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Close behind them sprouted seven ears of grain, thin and shriveled
        by the east wind. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: And the seven thin ears swallowed up the seven plump and full ears.
        Then Pharaoh awoke from his vivid and disturbing dream!
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: The next morning, his spirit was agitated, so he called for all the
        magicians [[COMMENT(0)]] and wise men in Egypt. Pharaoh recounted his dreams
        to them, but no one could give him the interpretation.
      comments:
      - number: 41:8
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cmagicians\u201D is    and is used exclusively
          in connection with Egypt and Babylon.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "When the chief steward heard about the dreams he remembered Joseph
        and said to Pharaoh, \u201CPlease, your dream reminds me today of my failures. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Once, when Pharaoh was angry with his servants, he incarcerated me
        and the chief baker in the prison of Potiphar, the captain of the guard. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'We both had dreams on the same night but with different meanings. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'There was a young Hebrew man imprisoned with us who had been the
        personal servant to the captain of the guard. And when we told him our dreams,
        he interpreted them and told each of us their meaning. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And it happened just as he said. Pharaoh restored me to my post,
        but he had the baker impaled.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'After hearing this, Pharaoh immediately sent for Joseph. They rushed
        him out of the dungeon to prepare him to meet with the king. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        When he had shaved and changed his clothes, he came and stood before Pharaoh. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:14
        content: "  Joseph\u2019s dreams landed him in a pit and later in a prison.
          It was Joseph\u2019s gift for interpreting dreams that brought him out
          from the prison to stand before Pharaoh (see  ).      Joseph did not immediately
          beg to be released from prison. He approached the mighty Pharaoh with dignity
          and respect. Joseph quickly acknowledged that only God has the power to
          interpret dreams, for he is the One who gives them. Like the Lord Jesus,
          Joseph did only what the Father revealed to him (see  ,  ).    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CI have had two dreams that no one can
        explain. I have heard that you are able to interpret a dream the moment you
        hear it.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CI cannot do it alone,\u201D Joseph replied, \u201Cbut God will
        help me to give Pharaoh the proper interpretation for Pharaoh\u2019s welfare.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then Pharaoh told Joseph, \u201CIn my dream I was standing on the
        bank of the Nile, "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'and up from the river emerged seven healthy, fat cows, and they began
        to graze in the marshland. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Right behind them followed seven other scrawny and emaciated cows.
        Never have I seen such ugly cows in all the land of Egypt! '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The seven ugly, scrawny cows ate up the healthy, fat cows, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'but after consuming them, no one could tell that they had eaten them,
        for they looked just as bad as before. I awoke with a start, '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'but immediately went back to sleep and had another dream. I saw seven
        ears of grain, full and ripe, growing on a single stalk. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Right behind them sprouted seven thin, shriveled ears, scorched by
        the east wind. '
      comments: []
    - name: "24: Joseph Interprets Pharaoh\u2019s Dreams"
      title: "Joseph Interprets Pharaoh\u2019s Dreams"
      number: 24
      content: "The seven shriveled ears swallowed up the seven healthy ears. I have
        shared my dreams with my magicians, but no one can give me an interpretation.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then Joseph said to Pharaoh, \u201CBoth your dreams tell the same
        story, for God has prophetically told Pharaoh what he is about to do. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Both the seven healthy cows and the seven healthy ears represent
        seven good years; it\u2019s the same dream. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'The seven ugly and scrawny cows that followed and the seven shriveled
        ears scorched by the east wind are seven years also. They represent seven
        years of famine. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'It is just as I have told Pharaoh; God has divinely revealed what
        he is about to do. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'There will come seven years of great abundance throughout all the
        land of Egypt, '
      comments: []
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: 'followed by seven years of intense famine. All of Egypt will forget
        the former abundance, for all the land will be ravaged by a famine, a very
        severe famine. They will not even remember their former abundance. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: 'followed by seven years of intense famine. All of Egypt will forget
        the former abundance, for all the land will be ravaged by a famine, a very
        severe famine. They will not even remember their former abundance. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "The reason that Pharaoh\u2019s dream was repeated is that God has
        determined that it will surely happen, [[COMMENT(0)]] and that he will soon
        carry it out.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 41:32
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Joseph continued, \u201CLet Pharaoh select a very wise and discerning
        man and set him over the land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Let Pharaoh appoint other officials throughout the land to collect
        one-fifth of all the crops each year during the seven plentiful years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Have them gather all the food of these abundant years that are coming,
        and under Pharaoh\u2019s authority, have the grain stored in the cities for
        food. "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: Joseph Promoted to Power'
      title: Joseph Promoted to Power
      number: 36
      content: "Store it all as food reserve for the people during the seven years
        of famine coming upon Egypt, so that the land will survive the famine.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Joseph\u2019s proposal pleased Pharaoh and all his advisers. "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "He said to them, \u201CWhere can we find anyone else like this one,
        for he has the Spirit of God in him!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 41:38
        content: "  How true this is of Jesus as well. There is simply no one like
          our Lord Jesus Christ. He walked in the fullness of the Spirit without
          limitation (see  ). Joseph was a forerunner of our Lord Jesus. His wisdom
          and understanding for interpreting dreams flowed out of a relationship
          with God\u2019s Spirit. True wisdom comes from the Spirit of Christ (see 
          ). This is the first time that Scripture mentions that someone has the
          Spirit of God in them. Later in the Old Testament, Bezalel, the craftsman
          of the tabernacle, is similarly described (see  ;  ), as well as Daniel
          (see  ).    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "So Pharaoh turned to Joseph and said, \u201CSince God has divinely
        revealed this to you, there is no one as wise and full of insight as you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: I hereby place you in charge of all my affairs, and all my people
        will obey your commands. [[COMMENT(0)]] Only I, the king,  will be greater
        than you!
      comments:
      - number: 41:40
        content: "  The Hebrew text is literally \u201Con your mouth all my people
          will kiss.\u201D See also  , where a kiss demonstrates serving and worshiping
          God.      Or \u201COnly the throne,\u201D a metonymy for the king and his
          authority.    "
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "\u201CListen to me, Joseph,\u201D Pharaoh continued. \u201CI am placing
        you in charge of all of Egypt.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "Then he removed his signet ring, [[COMMENT(0)]] placed it on Joseph\u2019s
        finger, and had him clothed with fine linen robes!  He adorned him with a
        golden collar around his neck. "
      comments:
      - number: 41:42
        content: "  Pharaoh validated Joseph\u2019s authority by giving him his signet
          ring, which had the royal seal of Egypt engraved upon it.      Instead
          of prison garments, Joseph was given the finest of clothing (the linen
          garments of a priest). Joseph had lost a robe twice; now he received a
          new one! He who had been dragging fetters of iron was now adorned with
          a chain of gold. Pharaoh gave Joseph an  , a broad collar made of gold.
          The Egyptians placed these collars on their deities or officials. Pharaoh
          recognized that God was with Joseph, and the Egyptians would recognize
          Joseph\u2019s authority. See  ;  . Instead of sitting in a dingy dungeon,
          Joseph was free. He was even given the keys to his own chariot! Joseph
          was now thirty years old (see  ). This is the age at which Jewish men could
          enter priestly service at the temple and the age at which Jesus began his
          earthly ministry. Nevertheless, it is a very young age to be awarded the
          highest governmental position in a powerful nation with the responsibility
          of running the affairs of the country. This testifies to Joseph\u2019s
          God-given wisdom and grace.    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Pharaoh had him ride in the chariot reserved for the second-in-command
        and sent runners going before him, crying out, \u201CKneel!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]
        In this way, Pharaoh placed Joseph over all the land of Egypt."
      comments:
      - number: 41:43
        content: "  Joseph, once accused of rape, was now made prime minister, head
          of all the people, chief justice, and general of the armed forces in all
          of Egypt\u2014all as a foreigner! He went from a prison to the highest
          office in the land in one day! Joseph had the strange experience of having
          what others dream about, but not what he dreamed about. His gifts were
          finally recognized, but not by his brothers. A million people shouting
          \u201CKneel!\u201D would not do for Joseph as much as eleven brothers doing
          the same. This exaltation, as glorious as it was, still fell short of what
          God had promised Joseph in his dreams.    "
    - name: '44: A New Identity and a Bride'
      title: A New Identity and a Bride
      number: 44
      content: "Pharaoh also said to Joseph, \u201CI am Pharaoh. No one in all of
        Egypt will lift a finger [[COMMENT(0)]] without your permission!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 41:44
        content: "  Or \u201Cno one will lift a hand or foot.\u201D    "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Pharaoh gave Joseph a new name: Revealer of Secrets. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He also arranged for him to marry the daughter of Potiphera,  the priest
        of Heliopolis.  Her name was Asenath.  And Joseph took charge over all the
        land of Egypt.   '
      comments:
      - number: 41:45
        content: "  Or \u201CZaphenath-Paneah.\u201D The root word for \u201CZaphenath\u201D
          means \u201Cto hide,\u201D and the root word for \u201CPaneah\u201D means
          \u201Cto disclose [explain].\u201D The Greek of the Septuagint can be translated
          \u201Csavior of the world [sustainer of life].\u201D Other scholars believe
          it could be translated \u201CGod has said, \u2018he will live.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D
          Each of these possible translations can point us to Jesus Christ, the true
          Revealer of Mysteries, the Savior of the world, and the One God raised
          from the dead.      Potiphera is the longer form of the name Potiphar.
          Some of oldest traditions of Rabbinical Judaism state that Potiphera was
          the same Potiphar that had Joseph imprisoned (see Rashi, Rashbam, Alshich).
          This would have been Joseph\u2019s final vindication of innocence, to marry
          the daughter of the one who accused him. However, more contemporary scholars
          believe Potiphera was a different individual than the captain of the guard.     
          Or \u201COn [strength, vigor],\u201D which is also recognized as Heliopolis,
          a modern suburb of Cairo. It is one of the most ancient Egyptian cities
          and was the seat of worship of the sun god Ra. Heliopolis is the home of
          the oldest obelisk on earth, the Obelisk of Sesostris I. Joseph was marrying
          the daughter of one of the most respected men in Egypt.      , the daughter
          of the Egyptian priest of On, means \u201Cbelonging to (the goddess) Neith.\u201D
          Joseph was given a bride while rejected by his brothers. Joseph is a type
          of Christ who finds a bride during this church age. See  ;  .      Or \u201CJoseph
          went out throughout the land of Egypt.\u201D    "
    - name: '46: Seven Years of Abundance'
      title: Seven Years of Abundance
      number: 46
      content: "Joseph was thirty years old [[COMMENT(0)]] when he entered the service
        of Pharaoh, king of Egypt.  Leaving Pharaoh\u2019s presence, Joseph traveled
        throughout the entire land of Egypt. "
      comments:
      - number: 41:46
        content: "  Jesus, too, was thirty when he began his public ministry. Ezekiel
          was thirty when he was visited by God. Thirty is the number of maturity
          and the priesthood, for a priest had to be thirty before he could serve
          in temple worship.      Joseph had lived thirteen years in captivity.     
          Think of this as Joseph\u2019s royal tour, inspecting the kingdom he was
          to rule over.    "
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: 'During the seven years of abundance, the land produced bumper crops. '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Joseph supervised the gathering up of all the great stores of food
        of the seven years of abundance and strategically placed them in various
        walled cities near where the harvest was gathered. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 41:48
        content: '  One can see the wisdom of Joseph in storing the grain near where
          it would be needed, versus keeping it all in one central storage place.    '
    - name: "49: Joseph\u2019s Two Sons"
      title: "Joseph\u2019s Two Sons"
      number: 49
      content: He gathered such massive quantities of produce that he gave up trying
        to measure it all, for it was like counting the sand on the seashore.
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'Prior to the famine, Joseph and Asenath, daughter of Potiphera, priest
        of Heliopolis, had two sons. '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "Joseph named the firstborn Manasseh, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CGod
        has made me forget all my troubles and my parental home.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 41:51
        content: "    sounds like the Hebrew words for \u201Che causes to forget.\u201D    "
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "The second he named Ephraim, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CGod has
        made me fruitful in the land of my suffering.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 41:52
        content: "    comes from the Hebrew word for \u201Cbeing fruitful,\u201D
          with an implication of \u201Cdouble fruitfulness.\u201D This is God\u2019s
          order: Manasseh then Ephraim. God must cause us to forget our prisons of
          the past before we can become fruitful. The \u201CKing\u2019s prison\u201D
          is the place where we forget our pain so we can move on into the fruitfulness
          of becoming like Christ, one who forgives others. Instead of seeking revenge
          toward our brothers who have harmed us, we must give birth to a \u201CManasseh.\u201D
          To call your afflictions \u201Cblessings\u201D is to become fruitful and
          give birth to an \u201CEphraim.\u201D In all of these things, we acknowledge
          that they are the glorious work of God (see  )!    "
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: "Eventually, Egypt\u2019s seven years of abundance came to an end. "
      comments: []
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: 'Then began the seven years of famine, just as Joseph prophesied.
        Although there was a severe famine everywhere else, food was available throughout
        the land of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: "When the Egyptians grew hungry, the people cried out to Pharaoh for
        food. Then Pharaoh said to all his people, \u201CGo to Joseph and do whatever
        he tells you.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 41:55
        content: '  Joseph, in effect, became the Minister of Agriculture over the
          land. His first dream of bundles of wheat bowing before him was a prophetic
          hint of his future responsibilities.    '
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: 'As the famine worsened over all the land, Joseph opened all the storehouses
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and sold grain to the Egyptians, for the famine was severe
        everywhere. '
      comments:
      - number: 41:56
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint, Vulgate, and Syriac. The Hebrew
          is \u201Che opened all that was among them.\u201D Joseph opened the door
          for others to be fed. He was an exceptional administrator and a wise manager
          of Egypt\u2019s resources. Because he had passed each previous test and
          grown in character, he was ready when the Lord promoted him to a place
          of such power. He handled all this prestige without pride or arrogance.
          Joseph was a man prepared to rule in wisdom and to use his position of
          authority to provide for others. God now had a man he could use as a deliverer.  "
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: So because of the severity of the worldwide famine, people from all
        over the world had to come and buy grain from Joseph.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joseph\u2019s Brothers Go to Egypt"
      title: "Joseph\u2019s Brothers Go to Egypt"
      number: 1
      content: "When Jacob learned there was food in Egypt, he said to his sons,
        \u201CWhy are you standing around here staring at each other? "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "I hear there is grain in Egypt; go there and buy some for us so we
        don\u2019t all starve to death.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "So Joseph\u2019s ten half brothers went down to buy grain in Egypt, "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "but Jacob did not send Joseph\u2019s full brother Benjamin with them,
        because he feared something might happen to him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So Israel\u2019s sons were among those who went to Egypt to buy grain,
        for the famine in the land of Canaan was severe. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 42:5
        content: "  Joseph\u2019s ten brothers left for Egypt on a journey of eight
          to ten days to buy food for their very large families (see  ).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Now Joseph was the governor of the land of Egypt, which meant he
        supervised the sale of grain to all the people. One day, Joseph\u2019s ten
        brothers came and bowed down before him with their faces on the ground. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 42:6
        content: "  Joseph was seventeen when he had his dreams. At the age of thirty,
          he was exalted over Egypt. About nine years later his brothers come to
          buy grain from him. After he had waited twenty-two years for the fulfillment
          of his prophetic dreams, here were his brothers bowing down before him.
          What a feeling that must have been! When his ten brothers came before him,
          he knew who they were, even though they didn\u2019t recognize him. His
          dream was being fulfilled right before his eyes\u2014almost. As they were
          bowing down before him, he counted them; there were only ten, not eleven.
          Where was the eleventh? Joseph needed a plan.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "As soon as Joseph saw them, he realized that they were his brothers!
        But he pretended he didn\u2019t know them and spoke to them harshly: \u201CWhere
        do you come from?\u201D\u201CFrom the land of Canaan,\u201D they answered,
        \u201Cand we\u2019re here to buy food.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Although Joseph recognized his brothers, they had no clue that it
        was Joseph speaking to them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Then at once, Joseph remembered the dreams he had about them bowing
        down before him! [[COMMENT(0)]]  Pausing, he said to them, \u201CYou are
        spies! You\u2019ve come to see where our land is weak!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 42:9
        content: "  At that moment, Joseph had the choice of revealing his identity
          to his brothers or remaining in disguise. He chose the latter, for the
          wisdom of God was in him. He wanted to test them to see if they were repentant
          of their betrayal. From a human standpoint, Joseph would have been happy
          for an instant reconciliation with them, but Joseph was a man broken by
          God and was now prepared to deliver others. Joseph spoke and acted in such
          a way that their hearts would be revealed and exposed. Did Joseph wonder
          if they had done to Benjamin what they had done to him? It was not a spirit
          of revenge driving Joseph, but a true love for his brothers and for the
          ways of God. The tests Joseph took them through were designed by God to
          see what they had done and if they had come to repentance. See  .     
          Or \u201Cto see the nakedness of the land.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "His brothers replied, \u201CNo, master; we\u2019ve come to buy food. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "We, your servants, are honest men; we\u2019d never think of spying!
        We\u2019re blood brothers, sons of one father.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Joseph interrupted, \u201CNo! You are spies who have come here to
        find our weakness!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CWe are your servants,\u201D they insisted. \u201CWe were twelve
        brothers, our youngest brother remained behind with our father, and one brother\u2014well,
        he is no more.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Joseph said to them, \u201CIt\u2019s just as I said; you are spies! "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "And here is how I\u2019ll test you: unless your younger brother comes
        and presents himself here before me, then as surely as Pharaoh lives, you
        shall not depart from here! "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "One of you must go and bring me your brother, while the rest of you
        will remain here in confinement. This way I will test your words to see if
        the story you have told me is true. If not, as surely as Pharaoh lives, you
        are spies!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: Joseph Tests His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Tests His Brothers
      number: 17
      content: He placed them all in prison together for three days. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 42:17
        content: "  Joseph put his brothers in confinement for three days, perhaps
          to let them know how he had suffered in prison for those many years\u2014not
          to punish, but to prepare them. They could only conclude that God had confined
          them because of what they had done to Joseph.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "On the third day, Joseph said to them, \u201CDo as I say and you
        will live. I am a man who respects God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'If you are as honest as you say you are, then I will keep just one
        of your brothers here in confinement while the rest of you carry grain home
        for your starving families. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "You must return with your youngest brother so that I may verify your
        story, and that you may not die.\u201D So they agreed to do so."
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "With Joseph standing there, they began to speak among themselves,
        saying, \u201CLook what\u2019s happened to us! We\u2019re being punished
        for what we did to Joseph long ago. We heard his cries of anguish and saw
        the agony of his soul when he begged us for mercy, but we turned a deaf ear.
        That\u2019s why all this trouble has come upon us!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Then Reuben spoke up, \u201CDidn\u2019t I tell you not to sin against
        the boy? But you wouldn\u2019t listen! So now we\u2019re paying the price
        for his murder!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 42:22
        content: "  Or \u201CNow comes the reckoning for his blood!\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: They had no clue that Joseph understood every word, for he had been
        speaking to them through an interpreter.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Deeply affected by what he heard, Joseph began to weep and hurriedly
        left their presence. After he had composed himself, he returned to them,
        and pointing to Simeon, said, \u201CThis one will remain here.\u201D  [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then he had him tied and bound while they all watched. "
      comments:
      - number: 42:24
        content: "  Joseph wanted to be sure they would return to Egypt. Simeon\u2019s
          name means \u201Che who hears.\u201D By keeping Simeon, Joseph was showing
          them that they had \u201Clost their hearing.\u201D Also, Joseph was testing
          them to see if they would abandon Simeon as they had him. While in prison,
          Simeon would have lots of time on his hands to listen\u2014and discern.
          Simeon was known for his cruelty (see  ;  ), and he might have been the
          one that led the way in their persecution of Joseph.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Joseph then gave orders to have their bags filled with grain, to
        hide each man\u2019s money back inside his sack, [[COMMENT(0)]] and to give
        them provisions for their journey home. After this was done for them, "
      comments:
      - number: 42:25
        content: "  As the nine brothers left for Canaan, Joseph gave them sacks
          of grain for their journey. At his orders, his brothers\u2019 money was
          replaced in their sacks of grain. Joseph paid for the grain himself, for
          he loved his brothers. His secret love paid their debt (see  ). They deserved
          no grain, they deserved no money, but mercy prevailed. The money in the
          sacks was also a part of Joseph\u2019s wise plan to test his brothers.    "
    - name: "26: Joseph\u2019s Brothers Return to Canaan"
      title: "Joseph\u2019s Brothers Return to Canaan"
      number: 26
      content: they loaded their donkeys with the bags of grain and departed.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Later, they camped for the night, and as one of them [[COMMENT(0)]]
        opened his sack of grain to feed his donkey, he discovered that his money
        was there right on top of the grain! '
      comments:
      - number: 42:27
        content: '  The Midrash identifies him as Levi. See  .    '
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "He shouted to his brothers, \u201CMy money! Look, someone put my
        money back in my sack!\u201D Troubled and trembling, they said to each other,
        \u201CWhat in the world has God done to us?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'When they came to their father Jacob in Canaan, they told him the
        story of all that happened to them, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CThe governor of Egypt spoke harshly to us and accused us of
        being spies. "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "We told him, \u2018We are not spies but honest men. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "We\u2019re twelve brothers, sons of our father. Our youngest remained
        with our father in the land of Canaan, and one is no more.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Then the man, the governor of Egypt, demanded, \u2018By this test,
        I will discern if you are honest men: Leave one of your brothers with me,
        take the grain you need for your families, and be on your way. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Return to me with your youngest brother, then I\u2019ll know you
        are not spies, but men of integrity. Then I\u2019ll release your brother
        back to you, and you\u2019ll be free to trade in the land.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'As they each emptied their sacks of grain, each man found his money
        inside his sack! When they and their father saw their money returned to them,
        they were frightened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Their father Jacob said to his sons, \u201CYou have taken away my
        children! First, Joseph is gone, and now, Simeon! And now, you want to take
        Benjamin from me! Everything is against me!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 42:36
        content: '  And how many times have we said that everything is against us
          when, in fact, everything and every event is being woven together for our
          good because we love God (see  )? See also  ;  ,  .    '
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Then Reuben said, \u201CFather, you may put my two sons [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to death if I fail to bring Benjamin back to you! Trust me\u2014I will bring
        him back!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 42:37
        content: "  Reuben had four sons, so the Hebrew implies \u201Ctwo of my sons.\u201D    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "But Jacob replied, \u201CI can\u2019t let my son Benjamin go with
        you. For his brother is dead, and of Rachel\u2019s sons, he alone is left.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] If he were to meet with disaster on your journey, I would
        die of grief! You will send my white hair and broken heart sorrowing down
        to the grave!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 42:38
        content: "  Jacob could not see how insensitive his remarks were. Reuben
          was a son, Judah was a son, Levi was a son, and so were all the others.
          Jacob spoke as if the other sons did not matter; Jacob continued to show
          favoritism.      Or, in Hebrew, \u201CSheol.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Joseph\u2019s Brothers Return to Egypt with Benjamin"
      title: "Joseph\u2019s Brothers Return to Egypt with Benjamin"
      number: 1
      content: 'Now the famine in the land continued to grow more severe. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "When all the grain they had brought from Egypt was almost gone, their
        father said to them, \u201CGo back and buy us more food.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Judah objected, \u201CThe Egyptian warned us repeatedly, \u2018You
        will not see my face again, unless Benjamin is with you!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "We\u2019ll only go if you\u2019ll let our brother come with us. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "If you insist he remains here, we won\u2019t go, for the man solemnly
        told us, \u2018You will not see my face again, unless your brother is with
        you!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 43:5
        content: "  Jacob\u2019s sons told him, essentially, \u201CWe won\u2019t
          see Joseph\u2019s face until he sees Benjamin.\u201D The name Benjamin
          means \u201Cson of my right hand.\u201D There is One greater than Joseph
          who is now waiting until he sees \u201Cthe sons of his right hand,\u201D
          an overcoming company of sons and daughters who will sit and reign with
          him in victory (see  ). When the church matures into the full measure of
          sonship, we will see him whom our soul loves.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Israel [[COMMENT(0)]] demanded, \u201CWhy did you make it so hard
        for me by telling the man you had another brother?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 43:6
        content: '  Israel is the name God gave to Jacob.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "They answered him, \u201CThe man interrogated us about ourselves
        and our family, saying, \u2018Is your father still living? Do you have another
        brother?\u2019 We had to answer his questions! We had no idea he would say,
        \u2018You must bring your brother here to me.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: "Then Judah spoke up and said to Israel, \u201CFather, I promise to
        guarantee his safety with my life. [[COMMENT(0)]] You can hold me personally
        responsible if I don\u2019t return with him. I\u2019ll bear the blame before
        you for the rest of my life if I fail to bring him safely back to you! You
        have my promise. Entrust him to my care, and let us be on our way, so that
        we all don\u2019t die of starvation\u2014we and you and all our children\u2014we
        will live and not die! "
      comments:
      - number: "43:8\u20139"
        content: '  This was an amazing statement of sacrificial love from Judah.
          One day a son of Judah would come, a Lion from the tribe of Judah, Jesus,
          who would offer his life as a ransom for many. Only a father can understand
          the loss of two of his children, and Judah had experienced that loss. See 
          ,  .    '
    - name: '8-9: '
      title: 
      number: 8-9
      content: "Then Judah spoke up and said to Israel, \u201CFather, I promise to
        guarantee his safety with my life. [[COMMENT(0)]] You can hold me personally
        responsible if I don\u2019t return with him. I\u2019ll bear the blame before
        you for the rest of my life if I fail to bring him safely back to you! You
        have my promise. Entrust him to my care, and let us be on our way, so that
        we all don\u2019t die of starvation\u2014we and you and all our children\u2014we
        will live and not die! "
      comments:
      - number: "43:8\u20139"
        content: '  This was an amazing statement of sacrificial love from Judah.
          One day a son of Judah would come, a Lion from the tribe of Judah, Jesus,
          who would offer his life as a ransom for many. Only a father can understand
          the loss of two of his children, and Judah had experienced that loss. See 
          ,  .    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And besides, if we hadn\u2019t delayed so long, we could have gone
        and returned twice by now!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "After considering their words, their father Israel said to them,
        \u201CIf that\u2019s the way it has to be, then do this: Load your donkeys
        with the very best gifts you can find, choice products of the land, and offer
        them to the man. Take some balm and some honey, spices, and myrrh, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        pistachio nuts and almonds. "
      comments:
      - number: 43:11
        content: '  Ironically, these items were the same things carried in the caravan
          that took Joseph away as a slave (see  ). Now they carry the same items
          to Joseph as tribute.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Take double the money with you. Give him back the money that was
        returned in the top of your sacks, for it may have been a mistake. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Take your brother, too, and be off! Go back to the man at once. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "May the God who is more than enough [[COMMENT(0)]] grant you mercy
        and favor before the man, so that he may send back both Simeon and Benjamin.
        As for me, if I suffer loss, then let it be so.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 43:14
        content: "  Or \u201CEl Shaddai.\u201D See second footnote on  .    "
    - name: '15: Joseph Prepares a Feast for His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Prepares a Feast for His Brothers
      number: 15
      content: So the brothers set off for Egypt and took double the money, the many
        gifts, and Benjamin. Once they arrived, they presented themselves before
        Joseph.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When Joseph saw his brother Benjamin with them, he said to his chief
        servant, \u201CBring the men to my house and make them feel at home. Butcher
        an animal and prepare a meal, for these men are to dine with me at noon.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Joseph\u2019s chief servant did as he was told and brought the men
        to Joseph\u2019s house."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Now the brothers were very apprehensive as they were being led inside,
        and said to each other, \u201CHe brought us here because of the money that
        was put back in our sacks the first time we came to Egypt! He\u2019s looking
        for an opportunity to arrest us, turn us into his slaves, and take away our
        donkeys!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'So they approached the chief servant and spoke to him at the entrance
        of the house. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CIf you please, my lord,\u201D they said, \u201Cwe came here
        once before to buy food, "
      comments: []
    - name: '21-22: '
      title: 
      number: 21-22
      content: "but on our way home, when we camped for the night and opened our
        sacks, we found each one\u2019s money in the top of his bag. All our money
        was there in our bags! We know it must have been an oversight of some kind,
        and we have no clue who put it there, so we have brought it all back with
        us. Plus, we have additional money to buy more food.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21-22: '
      title: 
      number: 21-22
      content: "but on our way home, when we camped for the night and opened our
        sacks, we found each one\u2019s money in the top of his bag. All our money
        was there in our bags! We know it must have been an oversight of some kind,
        and we have no clue who put it there, so we have brought it all back with
        us. Plus, we have additional money to buy more food.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CRelax,\u201D he replied, \u201Cdon\u2019t be afraid. Your God,
        the God of your father, must have been the one who put treasure in your bags.
        I have received your money; it\u2019s all accounted for.\u201D Then the chief
        servant brought Simeon out to them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Then he gave feed to their donkeys and brought the brothers into
        the house. He gave them water to drink and washed their feet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: The men laid out their gifts to present to Joseph, for they were told
        he would appear before them at noon and would dine with them.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'When Joseph came home, they presented to him the gifts they had brought
        with them into the house. They each bowed low before him with their faces
        to the ground. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "He asked them how the family was doing, saying, \u201CYou mentioned
        your aging father; is he still alive? Is he doing well?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D they replied, \u201Cour father, your servant, is
        still alive and doing well.\u201D And they bowed low before Joseph in respect."
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Looking them over, he saw his brother Benjamin, his mother\u2019s
        son, and said to them, \u201CSo, I see you have returned with your youngest
        brother, of whom you spoke. God be gracious to you, my son.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Joseph hastily left the room, for he was overwhelmed with feelings
        of love [[COMMENT(0)]] for his brother and on the verge of tears. He went
        into a private room and sobbed, as tears ran down his cheeks.   '
      comments:
      - number: 43:30
        content: "  This is the Hebrew word  . It is used ninety times in the Bible
          and almost always refers to God\u2019s compassionate, merciful love for
          us.    is also the word for \u201Cwomb.\u201D    is best described as nurturing
          love, the love a mother would have for her children.      All of a sudden,
          this world leader, this captain over millions, collapsed inside. It was
          beginning to make sense to him\u2014all the loneliness, those dark days
          in prison, the misunderstanding, and the pain of rejection. A family shattered
          for over two decades was being reunited. It took great discipline for Joseph
          to keep his secret from them. Joseph\u2019s heart moved him to tears\u2014tears
          of tenderness and affection for his younger brother and his long-lost family.
          Like a little boy again, Joseph missed his daddy.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "When he finally composed himself, he washed his face, reappeared,
        and ordered: \u201CServe the meal.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'First, they served Joseph who was seated apart from his brothers,
        then the brothers by themselves, and the Egyptians by themselves. (It would
        have been utterly offensive for the Egyptians to eat at the same table with
        the Hebrews.) '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Now, the brothers had been seated before Joseph in their birth order,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] from the firstborn at one end of the table to the youngest
        at the other end. They were all stunned when they realized the seating arrangement
        and looked at each other in astonishment. '
      comments:
      - number: 43:33
        content: '  What a feast was before them! They had not eaten like this for
          months, maybe years. As they noticed the order of seating, the brothers
          were amazed but still had no clue. There are 39,916,800 different orders
          in which eleven individuals could be seated. Did they believe he had supernatural
          wisdom to know their birth order?    '
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Eleven plates of food were taken from Joseph\u2019s table and set
        in front of each of them, but Benjamin\u2019s portion was five times more
        than any of theirs! [[COMMENT(0)]] They feasted and drank their fill with
        Joseph until they all became drunk."
      comments:
      - number: 43:34
        content: "  Joseph let them understand that Benjamin was his favorite, giving
          him a portion five times larger than the others. Five times more meat,
          five times more vegetables, five times more of everything! Why would Joseph
          have given more to Benjamin? Was he merely following the steps of his father\u2019s
          favoritism that brought all of this on? No. Joseph was testing them to
          see if they would be jealous again. Were they truly broken? Could they
          endure seeing one brother favored over the others and still rejoice? Or,
          would they get rid of Benjamin as they had him?  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joseph Tests His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Tests His Brothers
      number: 1
      content: "Joseph ordered his chief servant, \u201CFill the men\u2019s sacks
        with grain, with as much as they can hold, and put each one\u2019s money
        back in the mouth of his bag. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "As for the youngest one, place my silver goblet in the mouth of his
        sack, along with the money he paid for his grain.\u201D And he did as Joseph
        said."
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'At dawn, the men loaded their donkeys and set off for home. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "They hadn\u2019t gone far outside of the city when Joseph said to
        his chief servant, \u201CNow, go at once and pursue the men! And when you
        catch up to them, say to them, \u2018Why did you repay good with evil? "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Why have you stolen the silver goblet  [[COMMENT(0)]] from which
        my master drinks, and the one he uses to discover secrets hidden from men? 
        You have done an evil thing!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 44:5
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint and Vulgate and implied in
          the Hebrew.      Or \u201Cfor divination.\u201D Some historians tell that
          water was poured into a certain vessel, and then pieces of gold, silver,
          or precious stones were added, and then, by the shape of the designs that
          appeared at the surface of the water, the diviner could interpret events.
          Joseph did not say that he used the goblet for divination but wanted his
          brothers to think he did.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When the chief servant caught up with them, he repeated his master\u2019s
        words to them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "They answered him, \u201CWhy does my lord accuse us of such things?
        Far be it from your servants to do anything of the kind! "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Didn\u2019t we return from Canaan with the money we found in our
        grain sacks? Why then would we steal silver or gold from the house of your
        lord? "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Look for yourself. If any of your servants is found to have it, then
        he will die, and the rest of us will become your master\u2019s slaves!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CVery well then,\u201D Joseph\u2019s servant replied, \u201Cas
        you have said. But I will show you leniency. The one who has it will be my
        slave, but the rest of you will go free.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Each one quickly lowered his bag to the ground and opened it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then the chief servant searched each bag, beginning with oldest and
        ending with the youngest\u2014and he found the silver goblet in Benjamin\u2019s
        bag! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 44:12
        content: "  They had not stolen Joseph\u2019s silver goblet, but they had
          stolen Joseph\u2019s dignity and threw him into a pit. They were responsible
          for all of Joseph\u2019s afflictions. God was seeking to reveal their hearts
          through how they endured this false accusation. Joseph\u2019s    goblet,
          hidden in Benjamin\u2019s bag, was a picture of the years of suffering
          Joseph went through as a slave sold for \u201Csilver.\u201D Joseph was
          testing their loyalty. Would they stand with Benjamin and love him, or
          would they sacrifice Benjamin as they had Joseph? Would they be loyal brothers
          now? Joseph gave them a chance to do away with Benjamin as they had done
          away with him.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: Aghast, the brothers ripped their clothes in despair. They all loaded
        their donkeys again and returned to the city.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Joseph was waiting in his house when Judah and his brothers arrived.
        When they saw Joseph, they all fell to the ground before him. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 44:14
        content: "  For the third time, Joseph\u2019s brothers bowed before him.
          What a sight for Joseph to see them all return. He had to know if they
          had really changed. Joseph was truly doing them a kindness. He was giving
          them a chance to pass a test they once had failed! Their guilt could be
          removed not only by the mercy of Joseph but also by proving their \u201Crepentance
          by a changed life\u201D ().    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Joseph said to them, \u201CWhat have you done? Don\u2019t you know
        that divination would have given insight to a man like me?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Judah replied, \u201CWhat can we say, my lord? How can we plead our
        case? How can we prove our innocence? God has revealed the guilt of your
        servants, [[COMMENT(0)]] and here we are\u2014our lord\u2019s slaves, both
        we and the one in whose sack the silver goblet was found.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 44:16
        content: '  Their long-suppressed feelings of guilt surfaced. God was awakening
          their consciences to what they had done to Joseph.    '
    - name: '17: Judah Pleads for Benjamin'
      title: Judah Pleads for Benjamin
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D Joseph commanded. \u201COnly the one who stole my
        silver goblet will be my slave; the rest of you will go on home in peace
        to your father.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then Judah stepped forward and offered, \u201CMy lord, please, may
        I have a word with you? You are the equal of Pharaoh. Please don\u2019t be
        angry with me, your servant. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "My lord asked his servants, \u2018Do you have a father or another
        brother?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "We answered my lord, \u2018We have an aged father and our youngest
        brother, who is a child of his old age. The child\u2019s full brother is
        dead, so now he is the only child left of his mother, and his father loves
        him very much.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then you said to your servants, \u2018Bring him here to me so that
        I might see him myself.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "We said to my lord, \u2018But he cannot leave his father; if he were
        to leave him, his father would die.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then you said to your servants, \u2018You will not see my face again
        if I do not see your youngest brother.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: When we arrived home to your servant, my father, we told him every
        word you had spoken to us.
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CSometime later, our father said to us, \u2018Go back and buy
        some more food for us.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "We answered, \u2018We can only return to Egypt if we take our youngest
        brother with us. We won\u2019t see the man\u2019s face again, if he doesn\u2019t
        see our youngest brother.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then, your servant, my father, said to us, \u2018You know that my
        wife Rachel only gave me two sons. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "One is gone from me\u2014torn by a beast! I haven\u2019t seen him
        since. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "If you take this one also from me, and something happens to him,
        you will send my gray hairs in grief down to the grave.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: "Judah continued, \u201CMy lord, if I went to your servant, my father,
        without the boy, and he saw that the boy was not with us, he would die! His
        very life is wrapped up with the life of the boy. [[COMMENT(0)]] Now he is
        so old that the grief of his loss would kill him. "
      comments:
      - number: "44:30\u201331"
        content: '  As father and son, the souls of Jacob and Benjamin were bound
          together in the bundle of life.    '
    - name: '30-31: '
      title: 
      number: 30-31
      content: "Judah continued, \u201CMy lord, if I went to your servant, my father,
        without the boy, and he saw that the boy was not with us, he would die! His
        very life is wrapped up with the life of the boy. [[COMMENT(0)]] Now he is
        so old that the grief of his loss would kill him. "
      comments:
      - number: "44:30\u201331"
        content: '  As father and son, the souls of Jacob and Benjamin were bound
          together in the bundle of life.    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Furthermore, I, your servant, have guaranteed the boy\u2019s safety
        to my father. I told him, \u2018If I don\u2019t return the boy back to you,
        I will bear the blame before you, my father, for the rest of my life!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '33-34: '
      title: 
      number: 33-34
      content: "\u201CSo, please let me take the place of the boy, and I will remain
        here as a slave to you, my lord. Please let the boy go back with his brothers.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] How could I return to my father without the boy? I don\u2019t
        want to witness the woe and grief that would overtake my father.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "44:33\u201334"
        content: '  As Judah spoke for his brothers, he did not attempt to justify
          himself or pass the blame off onto Benjamin. Unlike in the past, they did
          not turn on Benjamin as they had turned on Joseph. Judah stood as a savior
          for his brother. He had changed greatly from the one who conspired to sell
          his brother into slavery (see  ) and now offered himself to be a slave
          as a substitute for his brother Benjamin. Jewish historians note that for
          many long years after this event, the tribe of Benjamin walked in faithful
          love toward the tribe of Judah even when the other ten tribes deserted
          them.  '
    - name: '33-34: '
      title: 
      number: 33-34
      content: "\u201CSo, please let me take the place of the boy, and I will remain
        here as a slave to you, my lord. Please let the boy go back with his brothers.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] How could I return to my father without the boy? I don\u2019t
        want to witness the woe and grief that would overtake my father.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "44:33\u201334"
        content: '  As Judah spoke for his brothers, he did not attempt to justify
          himself or pass the blame off onto Benjamin. Unlike in the past, they did
          not turn on Benjamin as they had turned on Joseph. Judah stood as a savior
          for his brother. He had changed greatly from the one who conspired to sell
          his brother into slavery (see  ) and now offered himself to be a slave
          as a substitute for his brother Benjamin. Jewish historians note that for
          many long years after this event, the tribe of Benjamin walked in faithful
          love toward the tribe of Judah even when the other ten tribes deserted
          them.  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Joseph Reveals Himself to His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Reveals Himself to His Brothers
      number: 1
      content: "Joseph could no longer contain his pent-up feelings, so he cried
        out to his attendants, \u201CLeave the room!\u201D So no one was there when
        Joseph revealed his identity to his brothers. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 45:1
        content: '  The family secret was a secret no more! Having held this secret
          for nearly a year, Joseph could contain himself no longer. He had to reveal
          himself to those he loved. All the Egyptians and the interpreter were ordered
          to leave. Joseph waited for the last Egyptian to file out of the room,
          then his long-buried emotions surfaced.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He began to weep so loudly that the Egyptians heard it\u2014even
        as far away as Pharaoh\u2019s house! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 45:2
        content: "  Or \u201C[word] reached Pharaoh\u2019s house.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Joseph, through his tears, said to his brothers in Hebrew: \u201CI
        am Joseph! Is father still alive?\u201D His brothers stood there stunned,
        scared, and speechless."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Joseph said to his brothers, \u201CPlease, come close to me.\u201D
        Inching forward, they came close to him. Then Joseph said, \u201CIt\u2019s
        me\u2014your brother\u2014whom you sold into slavery in Egypt. I am Joseph! "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Now don\u2019t be grieved. Don\u2019t blame yourselves because you
        sold me here. It was God who sent me ahead of you in order to save lives. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The famine has now endured for two years, and the land will not bear
        fruit for five more years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'God sent me ahead of you to ensure that you would live [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        and have descendants. He has saved your lives through this marvelous act
        of deliverance. '
      comments:
      - number: 45:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cto preserve you for a remnant on earth.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: So it was God, not you, who sent me here. [[COMMENT(0)]] God has made
        me a father to Pharaoh, the master of his entire household, and the ruler
        over all of Egypt.
      comments:
      - number: 45:8
        content: "  Joseph\u2019s compassion for his brothers ran deep. For the third
          time, he told them that it was God, not they, who orchestrated all the
          events to bring him to the throne. Once painfully betrayed by them, Joseph
          now began to encourage his brothers. His words flowed from a loving, forgiving
          heart, and Joseph\u2019s kindness washed over them. Their guilt was overruled
          by Joseph\u2019s mercy. Through his tears, he convinced them not to dwell
          on their sin but on how God had worked through it all. Joseph had been
          sent by God ahead of them to preserve their lives. Though they did not
          realize it, Joseph\u2019s brothers were helping the Lord fulfill his promise
          to Abraham (see  ). Today, we must learn to see that even those who hurt
          us the most may be those who move us toward the throne. If you see yourself
          in the hands of a loving God, not of others, you will not be offended.
          If Joseph\u2019s brothers had not sold him into slavery, how would his
          dreams have been fulfilled? Some of your dreams will never come true until
          you can handle both mistreatment and betrayal with forgiving love (see 
          ;  ).    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CHurry back to my father and tell him that you have found me
        alive. Tell him, \u2018This is what your son Joseph says, \u201CGod has made
        me ruler [[COMMENT(0)]] of all Egypt. Come to me without delay. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:9
        content: "  The brothers once asked in  , \u201CDo you actually think you\u2019re
          destined to rule over us?\u201D Joseph\u2019s words, no doubt, would have
          reminded them of their question.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "You will settle in the land of Goshen, [[COMMENT(0)]] where you will
        be near me\u2014you and all your children and your grandchildren, your flocks
        and herds and all that you possess. "
      comments:
      - number: 45:10
        content: "    means \u201Cdrawing near.\u201D It was a fertile area in the
          eastern part of the Nile delta that today is called Wadi Tumilat. It was
          known as a place for grazing livestock (see  ;  ,  ). Joseph\u2019s palace
          was apparently near Goshen.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "For there will be five more years of famine, but I will provide all
        that you need to live in Goshen. You, your household, and all that you have
        will not live in poverty.\u201D&nbsp;\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CMy brothers, you each can see for yourselves, and Benjamin
        can too, that I really am Joseph, for I\u2019m speaking to you face-to-face
        in our own language. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 45:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat it is my mouth that speaks with you.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "You must tell father everything you have seen here and how greatly
        I am honored in Egypt. But hurry and bring my father here to me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then Joseph threw his arms around Benjamin\u2019s neck, sobbing,
        and Benjamin wept on Joseph\u2019s neck. "
      comments: []
    - name: "15: Pharaoh\u2019s Invitation"
      title: "Pharaoh\u2019s Invitation"
      number: 15
      content: With tears streaming down his face, Joseph kissed each brother, one
        by one. After their tearful, emotional embrace, they took time to speak brother-to-brother.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 45:15
        content: "  All that transpired that amazing day was a prophetic portrayal
          of the glorious reconciliation that one day will occur between Jesus and
          his alienated Jewish brothers (see  ;  ). Through the last two thousand
          years, he has been unrecognizable to many of the Jewish people in his \u201Cgentile
          garb,\u201D as it were. But one day the time will come when hearts will
          soften in repentance toward the Father and Jesus will reveal his full identity
          as their long-lost Jewish brother and Messiah. See  .    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "The news reached Pharaoh\u2019s house: \u201CJoseph\u2019s brothers
        have come.\u201D Pharaoh and his officials were greatly pleased when they
        heard it."
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CTell your brothers: \u2018Load your
        donkeys and return to Canaan. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Get your father and your families and come back to me. I will give
        you the best of the land in Egypt, and you will enjoy the fat of the land.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Tell them also: \u2018Take Egyptian wagons with you for your wives
        and little ones and bring their father with them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Give no thought to leaving your possessions behind; the best of all
        the land of Egypt will be yours.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Israel\u2019s sons did as they were instructed. Joseph gave them
        wagons, as the king had ordered, and provided food for their journey. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'He gave each of them a set of garments, and to Benjamin he also gave
        three hundred pieces of silver and five sets of garments. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'He sent his father ten donkeys loaded with the best Egyptian goods
        and ten female donkeys loaded with grain, bread, and other provisions for
        the journey. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then he sent his brothers off, admonishing them, \u201CDon\u2019t
        quarrel [[COMMENT(0)]] along the way.\u201D And they departed."
      comments:
      - number: 45:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cbe trembling [with anxiety].\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'They left Egypt and went back home to their father Jacob in Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "When they arrived, they ran to their father and announced, \u201CJoseph
        is still alive! Not only that, he is the ruler of all Egypt!\u201D The news
        so stunned Jacob that he nearly fainted. [[COMMENT(0)]] He could not believe
        his ears! "
      comments:
      - number: 45:26
        content: "  Or \u201Chis heart was numb.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'But when they told him all that Joseph had said to them, and when
        he saw the wagons Joseph had sent to take him to Egypt, he recovered from
        the shock. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CMy son Joseph is still alive!\u201D Israel said. \u201CNow
        I\u2019m convinced! I must go to see him before I die.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 45:28
        content: "  Why did Joseph wait for nine years before he sent for his father
          Jacob? He could have sent chariots to Canaan before now, bringing his father
          to Egypt to share his wealth and power. Why did he wait so many years until
          now? Was it because he did not care? No, Joseph cared deeply for his family;
          something else kept him back. Joseph was a man who chose to bear the pain
          of separation from his father rather than run ahead of God. He was an enthroned
          prince, yet he placed God\u2019s interests over his. He knew that the plan
          of God must be fulfilled, not just his own desires. So he waited and waited
          again. Instead of initiating contact with his father and brothers, he stayed
          within the timing of the Lord. Even when it was in his power, Joseph waited
          nine years before his loneliness was removed. The dreams of his youth included
          Jacob, his father, bowing before him also. More than anything else, Joseph
          longed to see his father, but for nine years he did nothing. Even when
          the time came, he himself did not go; he waited until the others brought
          Jacob back. He was restricted to the will of God. This is why Joseph was
          a ruler and a prince. If you are unable to rule yourself, you will not
          be a good ruler over others.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Israel and His Family Go to Egypt'
      title: Israel and His Family Go to Egypt
      number: 1
      content: 'Israel packed up all he had and went to Beersheba, where he offered
        sacrifices to the God of his father Isaac. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "God spoke to him in visions of the night, and called, \u201CJacob,
        Jacob!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CYes, I\u2019m here,\u201D he answered."
      comments:
      - number: 46:2
        content: '  For the first time in twenty-two years, God appeared to Jacob.
          He was now one hundred and thirty years old. See  .    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CI am God, the God of your father. Do not be afraid to go to
        Egypt; for I will make your descendants a great nation there. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I will go with you to Egypt, and I will bring your descendants back
        to this land. And the hand of Joseph will be there to close your eyes when
        you die.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 46:4
        content: '  Within Jewish culture, even to this day, the nearest relative
          or oldest son would gently close the eyes of a loved one at death. Indeed,
          Joseph did as God had promised Jacob. See  .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Then Jacob set out from Beersheba. His sons put him, their little
        ones, and their wives in the wagons that Pharaoh had sent. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: The Family of Jacob'
      title: The Family of Jacob
      number: 6-7
      content: 'They took their livestock and the possessions they had acquired in
        Canaan and went to Egypt. Jacob took all his descendants with him: his sons,
        his grandsons, his daughters, his granddaughters.'
      comments: []
    - name: '6-7: The Family of Jacob'
      title: The Family of Jacob
      number: 6-7
      content: 'They took their livestock and the possessions they had acquired in
        Canaan and went to Egypt. Jacob took all his descendants with him: his sons,
        his grandsons, his daughters, his granddaughters.'
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Now these are the names of Jacob\u2019s descendants, the Israelites
        who went to Egypt with him:Reuben, Jacob\u2019s firstborn, "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'and his sons: Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.'
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Simeon and his sons: Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jachin, Zohar, and Shaul
        (the son of a Canaanite woman).'
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Levi and his sons: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.'
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Judah and his sons: Shelah, Perez, and Zerah. (Judah\u2019s other
        sons, Er and Onan, had died in Canaan.) Perez\u2019s sons were Hezron and
        Hamul."
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Issachar and his sons: Tola, Puah, [[COMMENT(0)]] Jashub,  and Shimron.'
      comments:
      - number: 46:13
        content: "  The Masoretic text reads \u201CPuvah.\u201D This translation
          follows the Samaritan Pentateuch and Syriac (see  ).      The Masoretic
          text reads \u201CJob.\u201D This translation follows the Samaritan Pentateuch
          and some Septuagint manuscripts which read \u201CJashub,\u201D following   
          and  .    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Zebulun and his sons: Sered, Elon, and Jahleel.'
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: These thirty-three were the sons that Jacob and Leah had while in
        Paddan-Aram, besides his daughter Dinah.
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Gad and his sons: Zephon, [[COMMENT(0)]] Haggi, Shuni, Ezbon, Eri,
        Arodi, and Areli.'
      comments:
      - number: 46:16
        content: "  The Masoretic text reads \u201CZiphion.\u201D This translation
          follows the Samaritan Pentateuch and the Septuagint which read \u201CZephon,\u201D
          following  .    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Asher and his sons: Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, Beriah, and their sister
        Serah. Beriah\u2019s sons were Heber and Malchiel."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: These sixteen were the descendants of Jacob and Zilpah (the slave
        woman whom Laban gave to his daughter Leah).
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Jacob\u2019s sons with Rachel were Joseph and Benjamin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'In Egypt, Joseph had two sons, Manasseh and Ephraim, by Asenath (the
        daughter of Potiphera, a priest of On). '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Benjamin\u2019s sons were Bela, Becher, Ashbel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi,
        Rosh, Muppim, Huppim, and Ard. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: These fourteen were the descendants of Jacob by Rachel.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Dan and his son: Hushim.'
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Naphtali and his sons: Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, and Shillem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: These seven are the descendants of Jacob and Bilhah (the slave woman
        Laban gave to his daughter Rachel).
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The total number of the direct descendants of Jacob who went to Egypt
        was sixty-six, not including his sons\u2019 wives. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: Joseph and His Father Jacob'
      title: Joseph and His Father Jacob
      number: 27
      content: "Two sons were born to Joseph in Egypt, bringing the total number
        of Jacob\u2019s family who went there to seventy."
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Jacob sent Judah ahead to ask Joseph to lead them in Goshen. When
        they arrived, '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Joseph got in his chariot and rode to Goshen to meet his father,
        Israel. As soon as Joseph saw his father, he threw his arms around his father\u2019s
        neck and wept for a long time. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 46:29
        content: '  Words completely fail to describe the emotion of this scene as
          father and son embraced! The great Egyptian lord was once more only a boy
          needing his father. After two decades, Jacob saw the son he had given up
          for dead. The two men stood holding each other and weeping. What a family
          reunion this was!  '
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Israel said to Joseph, \u201CI am ready to die, now that I have seen
        you and know that you are still alive.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Then Joseph said to his brothers and all his father\u2019s family,
        \u201CI must go and tell the king that my brothers and all my father\u2019s
        family have come to me from Canaan. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'I will tell him that you are shepherds and take care of livestock
        and that you have brought with you your flocks and herds and all you own. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'When the king calls for you and asks what your occupation is, '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "be sure to tell him that you and your fathers before you have herded
        livestock all your lives. Then he will let you live in the region of Goshen.\u201D
        Joseph said this because Egyptians despise shepherds."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: Jacob Blesses Pharaoh'
      title: Jacob Blesses Pharaoh
      number: 1-2
      content: "Joseph took five of his brothers with him to Pharaoh and presented
        them to the king. Joseph said to Pharaoh, \u201CMy father and my brothers
        have come from Canaan with their flocks, their herds, and all that they own.
        They have made their camp in the region of Goshen.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '1-2: Jacob Blesses Pharaoh'
      title: Jacob Blesses Pharaoh
      number: 1-2
      content: "Joseph took five of his brothers with him to Pharaoh and presented
        them to the king. Joseph said to Pharaoh, \u201CMy father and my brothers
        have come from Canaan with their flocks, their herds, and all that they own.
        They have made their camp in the region of Goshen.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Pharaoh asked the men, \u201CWhat is your occupation?\u201D\u201CWe,
        your servants, are shepherds, just as our fathers were,\u201D they answered. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CWe have come to stay as temporary residents in this country,
        because in the land of Canaan, the famine is so severe that there is no pasture
        for your servants\u2019 flocks. Please give us permission to settle in the
        land of Goshen.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CNow that your father and your brothers
        have arrived, "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "the land of Egypt is theirs. Let them settle in the best part of
        the land, in the region of Goshen. And if there are any competent men among
        them, put them in charge of my own livestock.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 47:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cplace them as princes over my livestock,\u201D thus
          making them officers of the crown and granting them legal protection. Ancient
          Egyptian inscriptions tell of Pharaoh owning huge herds of royal livestock
          with superintendents watching over them.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Later, Joseph brought Jacob into the house and presented him before
        Pharaoh. And Jacob gave Pharaoh a blessing. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 47:7
        content: "  Or \u201CJacob greeted Pharaoh with great respect.\u201D Jacob
          blessed Pharaoh, not the other way around! Although he was the most powerful
          person on earth, Pharaoh came under the blessing of Jacob. A refugee from
          Canaan became the \u201Cblesser\u201D of Pharaoh! With the authority of
          a prophet, Jacob blessed Egypt\u2019s ruler. The fact that Jacob blessed
          Pharaoh proves that he was greater than Pharaoh (see  ).    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Pharaoh asked Jacob, \u201CHow old are you?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Jacob answered, \u201CMy earthly journey has been one hundred and
        thirty years. My years have been few and hard, but it doesn\u2019t compare
        to the length of the earthly journeys of my fathers.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: Then Jacob blessed Pharaoh again and departed.
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'So Joseph settled his father and brothers in the choicest part of
        the land of Egypt, in the district of Rameses, [[COMMENT(0)]] as Pharaoh
        had commanded. '
      comments:
      - number: 47:11
        content: '    was another name for Goshen.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Joseph also provided his father and brothers and their families, down
        to their little ones, with all the food they needed.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Now there was no food anywhere, for the famine was very severe. Both
        the land of Egypt and the land of Canaan languished because of the famine. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "And the people of Egypt and Canaan spent all their money to buy grain.
        Joseph gathered all the money from the sale of grain and deposited the wealth
        into Pharaoh\u2019s treasury. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When the money ran out in Egypt and Canaan, all the Egyptians came
        to Joseph and pleaded with him, \u201CAll our money is gone; give us food!
        Why would you let us die in front of your eyes?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Joseph answered, \u201CIf your money is gone, then give me your livestock.
        I will give you food in exchange for your livestock.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So in that year, they brought their livestock to Joseph\u2014their
        horses, sheep, cattle, and donkeys\u2014and he supplied them with food in
        exchange for their livestock. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "The next year, they came to him and said, \u201CMaster, it\u2019s
        no secret to you that we are broke. All our silver and livestock are now
        yours. We have nothing left but ourselves and our lands. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Why would you let us die in front of your eyes, leaving all our lands
        uninhabited? Buy us and our lands in exchange for food. We\u2019ll become
        Pharaoh\u2019s slaves and give up our land. Only give us seed so that we
        may live and not die and so that the land will not become a desert.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'So Joseph gained possession of all the farmland in Egypt for Pharaoh.
        Every Egyptian sold his land in exchange for food, for the famine was that
        severe. Eventually, the Egyptians had transferred all the land to Pharaoh.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 47:20
        content: "  This was perhaps one of the greatest transfers of wealth in human
          history! This was important, for when the Israelites left Egypt, this was
          the wealth they would take with them (see  ). God used Joseph to make Egypt
          rich; in time, Egypt gave its riches back to God\u2019s people\u2014with
          interest.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Everyone became a slave to Pharaoh, [[COMMENT(0)]] from one end of
        Egypt to the other. '
      comments:
      - number: 47:21
        content: "  As translated from the Samaritan Pentateuch and the Septuagint.
          The Hebrew reads \u201CHe removed the people to the cities.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: However, he did not take over the land of the priests, for they received
        royal subsidies from Pharaoh. They lived on the food he provided for them,
        and that is why they did not have to sell their land.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Joseph said to the people, \u201CToday I have acquired for Pharaoh
        you and all your land. Here is seed for you to sow in the land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "But when harvest comes, you must pay one-fifth to Pharaoh, and you
        may keep the rest for planting your fields and for food for yourselves and
        your families to nourish your household and your little ones.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CYou have saved our lives!\u201D they said. \u201CMay we find
        your favor, our lord, and we will be slaves to Pharaoh.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: "26: Jacob\u2019s Last Request"
      title: "Jacob\u2019s Last Request"
      number: 26
      content: "Thus, Joseph established the law of the land in Egypt, which is still
        in effect, \u201CA fifth will go to Pharaoh.\u201D Only the land of the priests
        did not become Pharaoh\u2019s."
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Israel and his descendants settled in Egypt in the land of Goshen.
        They had many children and multiplied, and they acquired property.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Jacob lived in Egypt for seventeen years and lived a total of one
        hundred and forty-seven years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "When the time of Israel\u2019s death was near, he summoned his beloved
        son Joseph and said to him, \u201CSon, do me this favor before I die: Place
        your hand under my thigh as a pledge that you will show me kindness and loyal
        love. Do not bury me in Egypt, "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'but when I go to rest with my fathers, I want you to carry me out
        of Egypt and bury me where they are buried. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 47:30
        content: "  This refers to the cave of Machpelah purchased by Abraham from
          the Hittites in ch.  . Why did Jacob\u2019s burial place matter so much
          to him? He was looking forward to the time of resurrection! Abraham, Isaac,
          and Jacob were all buried near the ancient site of Jerusalem, where many
          centuries later Jesus would be crucified, buried, and raised from the dead.
          On the day Jesus was nailed to the cross, tombs nearby opened, and many
          holy people arose in resurrection life and were seen walking about the
          city ()! In faith, Jacob asked to be buried near the spot where the Messiah
          would be crucified. God honored that faith and raised many holy people
          to life to glimpse the city they had only dreamed of! Jacob knew the fulfillment
          of the promise would be in Canaan, not Egypt.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Swear that you will do this.\u201DSo Joseph took the oath and said,
        \u201CI will do as you say.\u201DThen Israel worshiped and leaned on the
        top of his staff. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 47:31
        content: "  Or \u201Cby the head of his bed.\u201D See  .  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Jacob Blesses Joseph\u2019s Sons"
      title: "Jacob Blesses Joseph\u2019s Sons"
      number: 1
      content: "Not long afterward, Joseph received the news that his father\u2019s
        health was failing, so he took his two sons Manasseh and Ephraim along with
        him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: When Jacob heard that they had come to see him, Israel rallied his
        strength and sat up in bed.
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CThe God who is more than enough appeared
        to me at Bethel [[COMMENT(0)]] in the land of Canaan where he blessed me! "
      comments:
      - number: 48:3
        content: "  Or \u201CLuz,\u201D the ancient name of Bethel. Jacob was referring
          to the appearance of the heavenly stairway reaching into heaven. See  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "He said to me, \u2018I will make you fruitful and multiply your descendants
        until I have made you a company of nations. And I will give this land to
        your descendants for an everlasting possession.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Furthermore, I will adopt as my very own your two sons who were born
        in the land of Egypt before I came here. Yes, I claim Ephraim and Manasseh
        as mine, no less than my two oldest, Reuben and Simeon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'As for any children born after them, they will be considered yours.
        They will receive their portion of the inheritance in the same territory
        as their brothers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "For when I was returning from Paddan-Aram, my beloved Rachel died,
        to my sorrow, in the land of Canaan while we were still on our way, not far
        from Ephrath. So I buried her there beside the road to Ephrath (that is,
        Bethlehem).\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "When Israel noticed Joseph\u2019s two sons, he said, \u201CWho are
        these?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CThey are the sons that God has graciously given me here,\u201D
        Joseph said to his father.\u201CPlease bring them closer,\u201D he said,
        \u201Cso that I may bless them.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Now Israel could barely see, for his eyes were failing because of
        old age. So, Joseph brought his sons closer to him, and Joseph\u2019s father,
        their grandfather, hugged and kissed them."
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Jacob Blesses His Grandchildren'
      title: Jacob Blesses His Grandchildren
      number: 11
      content: "Tearfully, Israel said to Joseph, \u201CI never thought I\u2019d
        see your face again, and now, God has let me see my grandchildren as well!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Joseph then removed them from his father\u2019s knees and bowed low
        in respect before his father with his face to the ground. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And Joseph took his sons and had them stand facing their grandfather
        Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]] Ephraim at Israel\u2019s left hand, and Manasseh at
        Israel\u2019s right hand.   "
      comments:
      - number: 48:13
        content: "  By placing them before him like this, Israel recognized Joseph\u2019s
          sons as his own by adoption. By adopting Joseph\u2019s sons, Jacob removed
          the firstborn blessing from Reuben and gave it to Joseph\u2019s sons.     
          Joseph positioned his sons so that Jacob\u2019s right hand would rest on
          the firstborn, Manasseh.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'But Israel crossed his arms, and stretched out his right hand on
        the head of the younger son, Ephraim, and his left hand on the head of the
        firstborn son, Manasseh. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "He spoke this blessing over them: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CMay the God
        of my fathers, Abraham and Isaac, who lived devoted to him,the God who has
        been my Shepherd from my birth until this day,"
      comments:
      - number: 48:15
        content: "  Or \u201CJoseph.\u201D The Septuagint reads \u201Cthem.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "the Angel who has delivered me from all harm, [[COMMENT(0)]]may he
        bless these boys!May their lives echo my name,and the names of my fathers
        Abraham and Isaac.May they multiply into teeming multitudes throughout the
        earth!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 48:16
        content: "  The Lord had visited Jacob as an Angel, the midnight wrestling
          Man, his true Friend. At the end of Jacob\u2019s life, he could say that
          his Shepherd-Friend had delivered him from all harm. Instead of moaning
          and complaining about his hardships, this servant of God declared the mercy
          that had preserved him. Christ, the Angel of the Covenant, redeems us from
          all evil.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "When Joseph saw his father place his right hand on Ephraim\u2019s
        head, he was not happy, so he tried to move his father\u2019s hand from Ephraim
        to Manasseh\u2019s head. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CNot that way,\u201D Joseph said to his father, \u201CHere,
        father, put your right hand on the firstborn\u2019s head.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But his father refused and said, \u201CI know, my son, I know. Manasseh\u2019s
        descendants will also multiply and become a great people. His younger brother
        will become even greater than he, and his tribe will one day give rise to
        many nations.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 48:19
        content: "  As the Spirit of Prophecy fell upon Jacob, he knew that it was
          God\u2019s will to bless and honor Ephraim above his brother Manasseh.
          Once again, the younger was set above the older and was given a greater
          blessing and a greater work. Maneuvering is our choosing, our selecting.
          Blessing is God\u2019s choice. It had taken Jacob a lifetime to learn this
          lesson: It is far better to wait until the blessing of God is seen and
          give up our maneuvering to have our own way.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "So Jacob blessed them that day, saying,\u201CIsrael will use your
        names when they pronounce blessings!They will say, \u2018May God make you
        like Ephraim and like Manasseh!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]So the crossing
        of his arms during Jacob\u2019s blessing put Ephraim ahead of Manasseh. "
      comments:
      - number: 48:20
        content: "  Ephraim and Manasseh became strong leaders in Israel. Their descendants
          multiplied and grew mighty. Joshua was of the tribe of Ephraim, and so
          was Jeroboam. The tribe of Manasseh was divided after the conquest with
          one half on one side of the Jordan and the other half on the other side
          of the river. Jacob, foreseeing this division would weaken the tribe, \u201Ccrossed\u201D
          his arms! This blessing spoken by Jacob endured and still endures. When
          the Lord blesses, no one can revoke it (see  ,  ). Jacob\u2019s hands that
          had deceived and grasped what was not his now became the hands that blessed
          out of an overflow of life. The \u201Cheel grabber\u201D became the \u201Cblessing
          giver.\u201D The day will come when this transformation will take place
          in you as well.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Then Israel said to Joseph, \u201CSon, I will die soon, but God\u2019s
        presence will go with you, and one day, he will take you back to the land
        of your ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "I give you one mountain slope more than your brothers, the mountain
        slope of Shechem, the fertile region I took from the Amorites with my own
        sword and my own bow.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 48:22
        content: "  The Hebrew text is somewhat ambiguous, for the word for \u201Cmountain
          slope\u201D can also mean \u201CShechem.\u201D The translator has chosen
          to leave both possibilities in the text. Additionally, it may be a reference
          to Mt. Gerizim, which stands above Shechem. The implication is that because
          Joseph was raised up, he would inherit the higher ground.  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Jacob\u2019s Last Words"
      title: "Jacob\u2019s Last Words"
      number: 1
      content: "Jacob called all his sons together and gathered them around his bedside.
        He said to them, \u201CLet me prophesy to you about your future destinies:
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:1
        content: "  The struggle between flesh and spirit had been fierce and protracted
          in Jacob, but as the end drew near, he ministered from a deep well as the
          Spirit of Prophecy fell upon him. Jacob became a shaper of destiny for
          his children as God revealed to him the futures of his sons. His prophecies
          were based both on their characters and on their actions. He spoke into
          their destinies and described God\u2019s plan for each one. The prophecies
          of    also apply to the day in which we live. The rest of the Old Testament
          and all the New Testament are the development of  . These verses require
          the whole Bible for their understanding. How profound were the prophecies
          of Jacob!    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CCome together and listen to me, O&nbsp;sons of Jacob,Listen
        to your father Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:2
        content: "  The order of the blessings given by Jacob corresponds to the
          sons of Leah, then the sons of Bilhah, the sons of Zilpah, two more sons
          of Leah, and finally the two sons of Rachel (Joseph and Benjamin). In the
          book of Numbers, the order of Jacob\u2019s sons is given by where their
          camps were situated in relation to the tabernacle. In Exodus, they are
          represented by the twelve gemstones on the breastplate of the high priest.
          In Revelation, they are the twelve gates of the New Jerusalem. One of the
          surprising things in the Bible is that the names of Jacob\u2019s sons are
          inscribed on the gates of pearls through which God\u2019s people must pass.
          The names of the gates of pearl are Jacob\u2019s sons. This shows that
          God is the one who transforms the worst of us and makes us his pearls for
          eternity. All who enter the New Jerusalem will enter by the gates of the
          tribes. As Jacob\u2019s spiritual sons, we can see our lives in the history
          and transformation of Jacob\u2019s sons.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CReuben, my firstborn, you are my strengthand the firstfruits
        of my manhood.You are preeminent in prideand surpassing others in power."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "You are unstable\u2014as turbulent as floodwaters;you will no longer
        excel,for you have slept with my concubine [[COMMENT(0)]]and defiled yourself
        in your father\u2019s bed! "
      comments:
      - number: 49:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cyou went up to your father\u2019s bed,\u201D a euphemism
          for sleeping with his father\u2019s concubine.      See  . Joseph received
          Reuben\u2019s birthright because he fled from the very defilement Reuben
          indulged in (see  ). Joseph did not lie with Potiphar\u2019s wife, even
          though she begged him. Joseph gained by purity what Reuben lost by defilement.
          This birthright was the inheritance not only of a double portion of land
          and possessions but also the privileges of headship and priesthood. Reuben
          lost it all, even though he likely repented and was pardoned. You may be
          first in line for the blessing, but it is how you finish that counts. Sinful
          acts can disqualify you for spiritual privilege and leadership.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CSimeon and Levi, you are two of a kind and brothers in crime,for
        your swords have committed violent acts."
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'O&nbsp;my soul, let me not join in their secret plans. [[COMMENT(0)]]O&nbsp;my
        heart, never let me be counted in their assembly,for they killed men in fits
        of rage,and for pleasure, they maimed an ox. '
      comments:
      - number: 49:6
        content: '  See  .      Figuratively, Joseph was the ox they tried to hurt
          (see  ).    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Cursed be their anger, for it is fierce,and their wrath so relentless.I
        will divide your descendants throughout Jacob\u2019s territoryand scatter
        them throughout Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:7
        content: "  Jacob chose neither Simeon nor Levi to replace Reuben as the
          firstborn, and they received no blessing because they were men of anarchy,
          not righteousness. Both Simeon and Levi had a disposition to kill others.
          Instead of using their swords for self-defense, they wielded their weapons
          in cruel rage to slaughter and plunder the city of Shechem (see  ). Simeon
          and Levi themselves were not cursed, only their anger. By all accounts,
          Simeon became the fiercest tribe among all of Israel. When Ezekiel described
          the final division of the land, he included a portion for Simeon (see 
          ). His is one of the sealed tribes mentioned in  . There is also a gate
          in the eternal city on which the name Simeon is inscribed (). In the New
          Testament another \u201CSimeon\u201D is named (  Peter), who once used
          a sword to cut off an ear. Even so, this Simeon\u2019s destiny was to be
          \u201Cone who hears\u201D from God (see    and footnote) and who blessed
          others with God\u2019s Word by writing the books of 1 and 2&nbsp;Peter.
          Concerning Levi, because his natural ways were transformed, he was privileged
          to carry God\u2019s Urim and Thummim as a priest (see  ). The Levites had
          the wonderful privilege of serving God in his presence. Their inheritance
          was not a piece of land (see  ) but the privilege of intimate worship.
          From the story of the Levites, we learn that God can redeem and transform
          us, even if we have lost our blessing because of past failures. Moses,
          the author of Genesis, was from the tribe of Levi!    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CO&nbsp;Judah, your brothers will praise you. [[COMMENT(0)]]You
        will conquer your foes in battle, And your father\u2019s sons will bow down
        before you."
      comments:
      - number: 49:8
        content: "  Judah eventually became the source of leadership in Israel, the
          father of the Davidic dynasty, and ancestor of the Messiah, Jesus Christ.
          Even the word \u201CJew\u201D is derived from the word    (\u201CJudahite\u201D).
          In the Spirit, Jacob saw the blessing of honor and power descending upon
          his son Judah. He would be a strong and courageous leader, with others
          showing him great honor. Remember, Judah became a changed man and displayed
          his true character by offering himself as a substitute for Benjamin (see 
          ). The tribe of Judah produced many kings, and some were quite notable
          in their exploits for God. A conquering, ruling tribe, Judah remained somewhat
          faithful when the nation divided. Judah was to have the leadership among
          his brothers. See  .      Or \u201CYour hand will be upon the neck of your
          enemies.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Judah, my son, you are like a young lionwho has devoured its prey
        and departed.Like a lion, he crouches and lies down,and like a lioness\u2014who
        dares to awaken him? [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:9
        content: "  Judah is a wonderful picture of the One who is seen as the mighty
          Lion of Judah. Jesus Christ is the One who places his omnipotent hand on
          the neck of his enemies and delivers us. The lion, the king of beasts,
          terrifies its prey with his roar. When he seizes his prey, no one can resist
          him. After he has seized his prey, no one pursues him or seeks revenge,
          for the lion is a conqueror. Jacob compared Judah to three kinds of lions:
          a young lion, a mature hunting lion, and a lioness. This is more than a
          prophecy about the tribe of Judah becoming strong and mighty; it is a prophecy
          of One who will come from Judah to devour his prey. Jesus is not a raging
          Lion; he is a resting Lion who has conquered every foe. He crouched and
          took his cross but now lies down in perfect peace. His victory is total
          and secure. Who would dare rouse a lion when he is lying down after his
          kill, and who would rouse a lioness while she is guarding her cubs? These
          three phrases to describe the lion are truly descriptive of what our Savior-King
          has done for us! Jesus came as our Savior: \u201Ca young lion who has devoured
          its prey&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. and departed.\u201D He laid down his life
          on the cross to destroy the one who held us in fear of death. He was raised
          again to be seated at God\u2019s right hand: \u201Clike a lion, he crouches
          and lies down.\u201D Today, he guards us with tender love and compassion
          \u201Clike a lioness.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The scepter of rulership will not be taken from Judah,nor the ruler\u2019s
        staff from his descendants,until the Shiloh comes [[COMMENT(0)]]and takes
        what is due him,for the obedience of nations belongs to him."
      comments:
      - number: 49:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cuntil he comes to Shiloh.\u201D The Messiah is the One
          given the name \u201CShiloh\u201D or \u201Cthe One whose right it is [to
          take the throne]\u201D (). When Jesus stood before Pilate, the people willingly
          allowed the staff, or authority to rule, to depart from Judah (see  ).
          They gave up the power to rule and handed it over to foreigners (the Romans).
          The departing of the staff was a sign that Shiloh, the One whose right
          it was to rule, had come! He has taken the staff as the emblem of his authority
          to rule over nations. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: He will tether his donkey to the vineand his purebred colt to the
        choicest branch.He will wash his garments in wineand his robe in the blood
        of grapes. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 49:11
        content: "  In this poetic prophecy, we are given wonderful descriptions
          of the fruit of Christ\u2019s righteous rule over us. There will be great
          prosperity and fullness. He will impart his servant nature (the \u201Cdonkey\u201D
          tethered to a vine, the church) and the display of his splendor (the \u201Cpurebred
          colt\u201D; Jesus rode into Jerusalem riding on a colt) to the church (the
          \u201Cchoicest branch\u201D; we are the branches of his life, see  ). His
          garments (gifts) will be washed in wine (soaked in the anointing of the
          Holy Spirit), and his robes (righteous life) in the blood of grapes (in
          the power of the Spirit and the blood, see  ).    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'His eyes are more exhilarating than wine [[COMMENT(0)]]and his teeth
        whiter than milk. '
      comments:
      - number: 49:12
        content: "  As translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is \u201Cred with
          wine\u201D or \u201Cdarker than wine.\u201D      Judah\u2019s dark eyes
          and white teeth point to the coming One, who will bring an abundance of
          wine and milk. His eyes are darker than wine\u2014not in outward coloring,
          but from the inward, energizing wine of God\u2019s Spirit. The redness
          of his eyes speaks of the fires of holy passion (see  ). His white teeth
          speak of the vigor and healthy power of his person. He is rich in love
          and rich in power! He has drunk deeply of the Holy Spirit and without measure
          from the milk of God\u2019s loving heart.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CZebulun [[COMMENT(0)]] will settle along the seashoreand become
        a safe harbor for ships,and his borders will extend to Sidon. "
      comments:
      - number: 49:13
        content: '  Having spoken of the tribe from which Jesus was born (Judah),
          Jacob now prophesied about Zebulun, the tribe in whose territory he lived.
          Jesus began his ministry in the area settled by Zebulun. The people of
          Zebulun were the first to see this great Light dawning (see  ). The disciples
          of Galilee were like a fleet of ships carrying the light of the gospel
          to the nations. It was from a mountaintop in Galilee that Jesus sent out
          his disciples to the nations like ships of mercy (see  ). As the disciples
          went out with the glad tidings, they became havens of refuge and a blessing
          to many. The descendants of Zebulun were known as merchants dwelling near
          the sea who traded goods with others. Deborah praised their bravery for
          rallying to the cause and fighting against Sisera (see  ). Elon, one of
          the mighty deliverers mentioned in Judges, was a valiant man from this
          tribe (see  ). They were men of undivided loyalty to the king ().     
          Sidon is often a metonymy for Phoenicia, or southern Lebanon.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CIssachar is a strong donkey [[COMMENT(0)]]lying down between
        its saddlebags. "
      comments:
      - number: 49:14
        content: "  The sons of Issachar were donkeys; they were meant to be burden
          bearers. A horse loves speed; a donkey is made for carrying burdens. A
          donkey is focused and sure-footed when it walks on mountain heights. A
          horse needs blinders or things will easily distract it; but a donkey keeps
          its attention on the trail ahead. As a donkey can endure weeks of hard
          conditions with little rest, so true intercessors don\u2019t stop until
          they get their answer. The men of Issachar were noted in Scripture as those
          who understood the times and knew what Israel should do (). They represent
          the intercessor of today.      The Hebrew word    is a homonym for \u201Csheepfolds.\u201D
          Some scholars render it \u201Ccampfires.\u201D It implies that the burdened
          donkey found a resting place near the sheep, near the campfire, and between
          saddlebags, ready to carry afresh the burden of the Lord.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'When he sees that his resting place is good,and his portion [[COMMENT(0)]]
        is so pleasant,then he will bend his shoulder to the burdenand labor for
        his master. '
      comments:
      - number: 49:15
        content: "  Or \u201Chis land.\u201D      Issachar is truly a picture of
          the intercessor. There is an anointing of rest for those who give their
          lives in intercession. Nothing will shake their confidence, for they have
          entered the Spirit\u2019s rest (see  ). Issachar, the donkey, saw that
          rest was good. Nobody else did. He saw the anointing of rest. Burdens must
          be carried, but carried within the pleasant land of resting in God\u2019s
          sweet presence. We must bend our shoulders to the burden of the Lord. God
          has a burden to share, but he waits for intercessors to find the resting
          place and bend their shoulders to his burden. True sons of Issachar will
          submit to voluntary labor and become slaves to prayer! Issachar bore the
          burden because he could see by the Spirit what God wanted to do in the
          land. God offers his intercessors, his friends, the opportunity to partner
          with him to bring his will to pass. Remember, it was a donkey that carried
          Jesus into Jerusalem. Could it be that intercessors are those whom God
          has chosen to carry his presence into the nations? We are to release the
          intercessors, for the Master needs them.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CDan will provide justice [[COMMENT(0)]] for his peopleas one
        of the tribes of Israel."
      comments:
      - number: 49:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cjudge.\u201D This is a wordplay on the name Dan. See   
          and footnote.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Dan will be a snake waiting by the roadside,like a snake in the grass.He
        bites the horse\u2019s heels,making its rider fall backward. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:17
        content: "  The destiny of the tribe of Dan was to provide justice. As the
          conscience of the nation, they were to excel in helping against the suppression
          of an enemy. Just as a snake can strike at the legs of a horse and overthrow
          a mightier animal, so God would anoint Dan to administer justice when the
          Israelites oppressed by others. Like a crafty serpent, this tribe would
          attack their enemies suddenly. Samson, one of the judges, was a Danite.
          Like a cunning serpent, Samson pulled down the house on the heads of the
          Philistines (see  ). Although the descendants of Dan won the victory, they
          became more independent and more proud. Soon, the tribe established a center
          of worship among them, with an idol made by Micah (see  ). The idolatry
          of the tribe of Dan became one of the greatest stumbling blocks for the
          nation of Israel. Dan also bit the heels of God\u2019s people and made
          them stumble backwards! What potential we each have to bless or hinder
          God\u2019s people. The genealogies of 1 and 2&nbsp;Chronicles omit the
          tribe of Dan altogether. During Joshua\u2019s conquest and allotment of
          the land, he gave the Danites no specific borders. Dan is not listed among
          the sealed tribes in  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CI wait in hope for your salvation, O&nbsp; <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>!
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:18
        content: "  Jacob interrupted his prophecy with a prayer. See  . The Hebrew
          word for \u201Csalvation\u201D is similar to  , the Hebrew name for Jesus.
          Jacob, looking to the end of the ages, saw the coming of Jesus! Jesus is
          the true Judge of all the earth, who alone will provide justice for his
          people. Where Dan failed, Jesus will succeed in leading us into the salvation
          of the Lord.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CGad will be raided by raiders,but he will raid at their heels
        and overcome them at last. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:19
        content: "  Or literally, \u201CA troop will troop upon Gad, but he will
          troop on their heels and overcome the troop at last.\u201D Gad symbolizes
          the beginning of the victorious life of an overcomer breaking forth. Throughout
          Israel\u2019s history, the Gadites were tremendous warriors. See  ;  ; 
          .    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CAsher\u2019s food will be rich,and he will provide delicacies
        fit for a king. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 49:20
        content: "  Moses said of the tribe of Asher in    that their feet would
          be bathed in oil.    speaks of walking in the anointing and richness of
          the Holy Spirit. Asher\u2019s footprints would be in oil. He would be anointed
          with the oil of gladness. Everywhere he walked he would leave the anointing
          and blessing of the Holy Spirit. The tribe of Asher settled in one of the
          most fertile places in Canaan and became exporters of oil and crops. In
          Christ, we feast on food fit for kings, for we are in his royal family.
          Truly, we are blessed in grace\u2014we have both a kingly family and royal
          dining! How would you like a prophetic word like this spoken over you?
          Asher\u2019s portion would be blessed with royal delicacies. In the victory
          of Christ, Asher\u2019s portion is yours!    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CNaphtali is a doe set free, [[COMMENT(0)]]who bestows beauty
        on his offspring. "
      comments:
      - number: 49:21
        content: "  The Hebrew root word for \u201Cdoe\u201D can be translated \u201Cmighty
          man.\u201D What a wonderful word picture this is.    has in its inscription,
          \u201CTo the tune of \u2018The Deer at the Dawning of the Day.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D   
          prophesied the death and resurrection of our Lord. Jesus is the \u201CDoe
          set free.\u201D In Naphtali, we see Christ not only as the victorious Lion
          but also as the resurrected Doe skipping on the mountaintops in freedom.
          He is the Resurrected Doe of the Morning Glory! The name    means \u201Cwrestling.\u201D
          What freedom we experience when we get up from our \u201Cwrestling match\u201D
          a changed person and run to the mountains with Christ in victory (). He
          has paid the price for our freedom; he has loosed us from our sins that
          we may run with him in resurrection life. We are his beautiful fawns.     
          Or \u201Cspeaks beautiful words\u201D or \u201Cspeaks words that glisten.\u201D
          How lovely and powerful are the words of our resurrected Doe. This could
          refer to the Great Commission of    when Jesus gathered his disciples together
          on a mountaintop and sent them out with beautiful words, good news to preach
          to all peoples. When we have tasted the resurrection, we have beautiful
          words to give others.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CJoseph is a fruitful vine,a fruitful vine growing by a spring,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]whose branches  run over a wall. "
      comments:
      - number: 49:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cnear a spring\u201D or \u201Cby a fountain.\u201D Joseph,
          the clearest type of Christ in the Old Testament, is seen as a fruitful
          vine. The Lord Jesus called himself the Vine and us his branches (see 
          ). When the Fruitful Vine lives through us, the fruit of the Spirit begins
          to be seen in our personalities (see  ). Jesus \u201Cbranches out\u201D
          through us, just as he branches out from the Father. Joseph, as a fruitful
          vine, dwelt near God. Joseph was God\u2019s \u201Cbranching out\u201D in
          a man (see  ;  ). The \u201Cspring\u201D or \u201Cfountain\u201D is the
          life of the Father (see  ;  ;  ). The source of his life and purity is
          from the spring of eternal life dwelling in him (see  ). All Joseph\u2019s
          fruitfulness came from the water of that divine Spring.      Or \u201Cdaughters.\u201D     
          Joseph, as a fruitful vine, has branches that run over the wall. The life
          of Christ in the believer will climb over a wall. Nothing will limit the
          branching forth of Christ in us when we walk in the Joseph anointing. We
          have many branches that climb over the walls around us. No matter how high
          the wall, our branches will run over it. Even if we are taken into captivity
          in Egypt\u2019s dungeon, the springing well will cause our branches to
          climb over the walls. Nothing can hem you in if you dwell by the Fountain.
          We are branches connected to a fruitful Vine who will bear his likeness
          and the fruit of his life in us. The enemy will always try to erect walls
          to restrict our fruitfulness, but in the Vine will still climb over them
          all.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'Persecutors [[COMMENT(0)]] fiercely attacked him;they pursued him
        with their bow and arrows. '
      comments:
      - number: 49:23
        content: "  Or \u201CWarriors [enemies].\u201D      Arrows were often used
          metaphorically for slander and false accusation. Joseph was a victim of
          both. See  . The slander and abuse of others could not keep Joseph from
          his destined promotion, nor can the words of others hold you back when
          you set your heart on pleasing God.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "But Joseph\u2019s bow remained steady,because the power of the Mighty
        One of Jacob strengthened him, [[COMMENT(0)]]by the name of the loving Shepherd,
        the Rock of Israel. "
      comments:
      - number: 49:24
        content: "  The Hebrew text literally reads \u201Cthe arms of his hands were
          made strong by the hands of the Mighty One of Jacob.\u201D God is pictured
          as putting his hands on Joseph\u2019s hands, placing his arms on Joseph\u2019s
          arms. The mighty God laid his hand upon Joseph\u2019s hand, stretched his
          arm upon the arm of Joseph, and strengthened him! And God will do this
          for you!      See  ;  . The Hebrew is \u201Cthe Stone of Israel,\u201D
          which may refer to the stone Jacob used as a pillow when he saw the stairway
          of the sky (see  ,  ).    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: The God of your father will help and protect you;the God who is more
        than enough will bless you.He will bless you with the blessings of heaven,blessings
        of the deep that lie beneath,and blessings of the breast and womb.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The blessings of your father will be greaterthan the blessings of
        the eternal mountains,surpassing the blessings of my ancestors! [[COMMENT(0)]]May
        Joseph\u2019s blessings crown his headand rest on the brow of the one set
        apart, prince among his brothers."
      comments:
      - number: 49:26
        content: "  The Hebrew is uncertain.      The Hebrew implies Joseph was \u201Cseparated
          like a Nazarite [for God].\u201D It looked as if Joseph had been in exile
          for thirteen years when, in fact, he was being prepared by God and set
          apart for his true destiny.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CBenjamin is a ferocious wolf. [[COMMENT(0)]]He devours his
        prey;in the evening, he divides the spoil.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 49:27
        content: "  Or possibly \u201CBenjamin shall tear a wolf in pieces.\u201D
          This would mean that Benjamin goes after the \u201Cwolf (nature),\u201D
          tearing it into pieces and turning it into food for the hungry. This is
          all accomplished in the \u201Cmorning\u201D of a new day.      The men
          of Benjamin were warlike and known as fearless soldiers. See  ;  ;  , 
          ,  ;  . King Saul was a Benjamite. In the New Testament, Saul of Tarsus,
          a Benjamite, became the apostle Paul, who fought the excellent fight of
          faith (see  ;  ).    "
    - name: '28: The Death of Jacob'
      title: The Death of Jacob
      number: 28
      content: All these men became the twelve tribes of Israel. [[COMMENT(0)]] These
        were prophetic words their father spoke to them when he blessed them, blessing
        each son with a parting word appropriate to him.
      comments:
      - number: 49:28
        content: "  This is the first of many biblical references to the \u201Ctwelve
          tribes of Israel.\u201D  "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Afterward, Jacob sat on the side of his bed and instructed his sons
        with these words: \u201CI am about to join my people in death. Bury me with
        my ancestors in the cave of the field of Ephron the Hittite\u2014"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'the cave in the field of Machpelah, near Mamre, in the land of Canaan.
        My grandfather Abraham purchased that field as a burial site from Ephron
        the Hittite. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'My grandfather Abraham and my grandmother Sarah are buried there.
        My father Isaac and my mother Rebekah were buried there also. And it is the
        place I buried my wife Leah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "So, bury me there, in that cave, in the field that was purchased
        from the Hittites.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: When Jacob finished his final words of instruction to his sons, he
        lifted his feet onto the bed, breathed his last, and was gathered to his
        people.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Jacob\u2019s Funeral"
      title: "Jacob\u2019s Funeral"
      number: 1
      content: "Joseph flung himself over Jacob, kissing him and weeping. And his
        tears fell on his father\u2019s face. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: 'When he was able to compose himself, he ordered the royal physicians
        to embalm his father. So, they began the required forty-day process. The
        Egyptians mourned for Israel for seventy days, '
      comments: []
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: 'When he was able to compose himself, he ordered the royal physicians
        to embalm his father. So, they began the required forty-day process. The
        Egyptians mourned for Israel for seventy days, '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "and when the weeping period was over, Joseph approached Pharaoh\u2019s
        officials and said to them, \u201CPlease, may I ask a personal favor? Bring
        my appeal before Pharaoh and tell him: [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 50:4
        content: "  A mourner was considered unclean and unable to come directly
          to Pharaoh, so Joseph made his appeal to Pharaoh\u2019s officials. See 
          .    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u2018My dying father made me promise that I would bury him in the
        land of Canaan\u2014in a tomb he had hewn with his own hands. Please give
        me permission to go and bury my father; then I will return.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CGo to Canaan, bury your father, and
        keep your promise to him.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "So Joseph went to Canaan to bury his father, and all the officials
        of Pharaoh, the elite members of his court, and all of Egypt\u2019s dignitaries
        accompanied him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "All of Joseph\u2019s household and all his brothers and their father\u2019s
        household went, too. Only the children and livestock remained behind in Goshen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Many chariots and horsemen\u2014a huge entourage\u2014accompanied
        Joseph to Canaan in a grand procession!"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'When they arrived at the threshing floor of Atad [[COMMENT(0)]] on
        the other side of the Jordan,  they mourned loudly with bitter sorrow for
        a long time. And Joseph spent seven days there in ceremonial mourning for
        his father.   '
      comments:
      - number: 50:10
        content: "    means \u201Cbrambles.\u201D      The phrase \u201Cthe other
          side of the Jordan\u201D usually refers to the Transjordan. It is possible
          that the funeral procession crossed over the Jordan near Jericho, the place
          where Joshua would later cross with Israel to take possession of Canaan.     
          A strict custom of a seven-day period of mourning remains in Judaism even
          to this day. See  ;  . For the first time, Joseph returned to what had
          been his boyhood home for thirty-nine years, sadly, for his father\u2019s
          funeral.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "When the people of Canaan saw the depth of mourning at the threshing
        floor of Atad, they said, \u201CThis is a solemn occasion of grief for the
        Egyptians,\u201D and named the place near the Jordan, The Mourning of the
        Egyptians. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 50:11
        content: "  Or, in Hebrew, \u201CAbel Mizraim.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "So Jacob\u2019s sons did as they were instructed "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'and carried his body to the land of Canaan. They buried him there
        in the cave in the field of Machpelah near Mamre, where Abraham had purchased
        a burial place from Ephron the Hittite. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Joseph Comforts His Brothers'
      title: Joseph Comforts His Brothers
      number: 14
      content: After burying his father, Joseph returned to Egypt with his brothers
        and all who had gone with him to bury his father.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "When the brothers realized they were now without their father, they
        said, \u201CWhat if Joseph still bears a grudge against us and decides to
        pay us back for all the trouble we brought on him?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So they sent this message to Joseph: \u201CBefore he died, your father
        left us this instruction: "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u2018Tell Joseph that I beg him to completely forgive the sin of
        his brothers who treated him so harshly.\u2019 Now, please forgive us, servants
        of the God of your father, of the horrible wrong we did to you.\u201D Joseph
        cried and wept as they read this message to him. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 50:17
        content: "  His brothers\u2019 shame brought Joseph to tears. Without hesitation,
          he offered them reassurance and forgiveness. Joseph spoke kindly to those
          who hurt him, and he comforted their hearts. He refused to harbor a grudge
          or treat them differently for what they had done.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then his brothers came and threw themselves down before Joseph\u2019s
        feet, saying, \u201CWe are here as your slaves!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But Joseph dried his tears and said, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid.
        How could I ever take the place of God? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 50:19
        content: '  Only God can judge, for he has perfect love and knows all things.
          Since we are not in his place, we only have the right to forgive. Many
          assume the role of a judge when they have someone cornered and vulnerable,
          but Joseph refused. He understood that God had turned the evil intentions
          of others into something good. God has power to transform pain into blessing
          when we love him through it all.    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Even though you intended to hurt me, God intended it for good. It
        was his plan all along, [[COMMENT(0)]] to ensure the survival of many people.
        So, don\u2019t worry. I myself will provide for you all that you need, both
        for you and your little ones.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 50:20
        content: '  See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '21: Joseph Dies in Egypt'
      title: Joseph Dies in Egypt
      number: 21
      content: Then with more kind, reassuring words, Joseph comforted his brothers.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Joseph lived in Egypt along with his father\u2019s family and lived
        to be one hundred and ten years old. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 50:22
        content: '  From ancient Egyptian writings we learn that Egyptians considered
          the age of one hundred and ten to be the ideal life span.    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "He lived to see the third generation of Ephraim\u2019s children.
        Joseph also lived to see the children of Makir, son of Manasseh; and Joseph
        gave Makir\u2019s children inheritance rights. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 50:23
        content: "  Or \u201CMakir\u2019s children were born on Joseph\u2019s knees,\u201D
          a figure of speech for being given inheritance rights.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Joseph declared to his brothers, \u201CI will die one day, but
        God will certainly come to you [[COMMENT(0)]] and fulfill his promises to
        bring you and your descendants from this land and lead you to the land he
        promised to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 50:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cvisit you.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "So Joseph had his brothers, the sons of Israel, make a solemn oath,
        saying, \u201CWhen God comes to you, you will carry my bones up from Egypt.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 50:25
        content: '  Even in death, Joseph fixed his eyes on eternity. Joseph foresaw
          life beyond the grave. By his astonishing declaration about his bones,
          Joseph proclaimed he lived for the promises rather than temporal concerns;
          he refused to be identified with his successes, accomplishments, or the
          blessings on his life, but only with the promises. He proclaimed that his
          home was not Egypt but the promised land. See  .    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: Joseph died at the age of one hundred and ten. He was embalmed and
        placed in a coffin in Egypt. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 50:26
        content: "  Genesis begins with God and ends with a coffin in Egypt. It begins
          with God\u2019s command for light to sparkle, thrusting its way throughout
          the universe, and it ends here with this sad moment as a family grieved
          over a loved one who had passed away. Genesis ends with the reader longing
          for the curse of sin and death to be broken. Exodus will bring us closer
          to seeing the Passover Lamb (see  ) who would one day be born to take away
          the sin of the world.  "
